<HEADLINE>
HOMERS 66 AND 66 ARE MINUTES APART 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This is a late add to page 1.)  
(lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a remarkable bit of long-distance theater, Sammy Sosa and
Mark McGwire exchanged home runs 45 minutes apart Friday night,
enhancing a home run duel that had already captivated the attention
of fans and nonfans everywhere. Sosa, who had led McGwire in their
dash to major-league baseball's home run record only once this
season, slugged his 66th home run in the fourth inning of the
Chicago Cubs' game in Houston. Then in the fifth inning in St.
Louis, McGwire countered by slamming his 66th against the Montreal
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's version of hand-to-hand combat came at the start of
the final weekend of the regular season. The final three-game
series were also critical for teams fighting for the final playoff
spots. The most heated of those races involved the Cubs, the Mets,
who were playing in Atlanta, and the San Francisco Giants, who were
playing the Colorado Rockies in Denver. The winner of that race
will gain the wild card, or fourth and final, spot in the National
League playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves edged the Mets, 6-5, and the Astros defeated the
Cubs, 6-2, maintaining their tie for the wild-card lead.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's home run tied the Cubs' game with the Astros, 2-2, but it
untied his personal duel with McGwire and broke the existing home
run record. McGwire on Sept. 8 broke the record of 61 Roger Maris
set in 1961 with the Yankees, when he eclipsed Babe Ruth's 60 in
1927. McGwire continued to hold his lead over Sosa until Sosa hit
his 64th and 65th last Wednesday in Milwaukee. Those blows made the
pair the running record-holders.
</P>
<P>
   Both players have said repeatedly that they would not mind if
the other finished with more home runs, but they also have said
that they would love to see themselves end the season in a tie.
``What he and I have done,'' McGwire said after his game,
``whoever's on top, nobody should be disappointed. Two guys have
done something that's never been done before, so how can you walk
away disappointed if you're one below or one above. Whatever
happens at the last out of the game Sunday, how can you think about
walking in here with your head down.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa struck first Friday night. Batting for the second time in
the game against his fellow Dominican and good friend, Jose Lima,
Sosa drove the second pitch an estimated 462 feet into fourth level
of the left-field stands at the Astrodome. He hit his 50th and 51st
home runs against Lima at Wrigley Field in Chicago on Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Four days earlier at Wrigley, Sosa and McGwire went into a game
between the Cubs and the Cardinals tied with 47 home runs each.
Sosa, who had never led McGwire, whacked his 48th in the fifth
inning. But in the eighth inning, only 57 minutes later, McGwire
swatted his 48th, and then in the 10th he hit another home run,
snatching the lead once again.
</P>
<P>
   This time McGwire waited only 45 minutes. Batting simultaneously
with Sosa, who hit a grounder to shortstop, McGwire, who had not
hit a home run since last Sunday, first hit a high fly toward the
left-field stands that just veered foul. He took the second pitch
from Shayne Bennett, a 26-year-old rookie from Australia, for a
ball, then swung and missed for a second strike.
</P>
<P>
   After fouling off another pitch, McGwire swung and, as Sosa had
with his earlier shot, instantly knew the ball was headed where no
outfielder could catch the ball. It descended into the left-field
stands an estimated 375 feet from where McGwire watched.
</P>
<P>
   The Astrodome crowd of 51,831, whose Astros have won the NL
Central championship, witnessed the McGwire home run on the
stadium's giant video screens and cheered, just as they had roared
for Sosa in calling him out of the visiting dugout for a curtain
call.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The home run race has created a new phenomenon in baseball: home
fans cheering for and saluting visiting players whose home runs
could help beat the home team. Home fans have also taken to booing
their own teams' pitchers if they walk Sosa and McGwire, or even
throw them pitches that are out of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire had his next turn at bat before Sosa had his, and he
lined a single on the first pitch to left field. Sosa went to the
plate as the leadoff batter in the ninth inning of a game the Cubs
were losing, 6-2. Chicago's share of the wild-card lead was at
stake, but Sosa was unable to reduce his team's deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Facing Billy Wagner, the Astros' flame-throwing closer, he took
two pitches for balls, then swung at and missed two pitches. The
fifth pitch was also a strike, and Sosa took it for the third
strike, maintaining his unwelcome position of never having ended a
day this season leading McGwire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
