<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE ANSWERS SOSA IN THE HOME RUN RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also BBN-HOMERUNS, BBN-METS-BRAVES, BBO-RHODEN-COLUMN,
BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN) 
(js) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The catch-me-if-you can home run race that has
stirred the nation required a split-screen to capture Friday night
as Mark McGwire of the Cardinals sent a 375-foot home run into the
left-field stands here 45 minutes after Sammy Sosa of the Cubs had
broken a homer tie with his 66th in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   A moment after Sosa grounded out in the at-bat that followed his
fourth-inning blast in Houston, McGwire tore into a 1-2 pitch by
Montreal's Shayne Bennett and sent the sellout crowd at Busch
Stadium into a frenzy in the fifth against the Expos.
</P>
<P>
   The red-clad fans, decked out in their McGwire wear, could
breathe again. The sight of a hand reaching out of the shadows and
pulling down No. 66 off the center-field scoreboard for Sosa had
sent a nervous stir through the fans. Instantly, they knew their
beloved icon had been passed by Sosa in a home run race that has
one last glorious weekend left.
</P>
<P>
   During the chase, McGwire has always met Sosa's challenge when
tied for the home run lead. Before Friday night, the most visible
evidence of this came on Aug. 19, when the two drew the nation's
undivided attention while playing against each other. Early in that
game, Sosa nudged ahead of McGwire by hitting his 48th. McGwire
then delivered a quick reply by hitting his 48th and 49th.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that Sosa brings out the muscle in McGwire, although
neither man claims to be in a race with the other. Before Friday's
game, McGwire sounded more philosophical than competitive about
closing out his unforgettable season this weekend. McGwire
telephoned his 10-year-old son Friday morning at his home in
California, and had a normal father-son conversation, a little
about baseball, a little about school.
</P>
<P>
   But the youngster who was hugged in half by his joyous father on
Sept. 8, the moment McGwire crossed the plate after breaking Roger
Maris' legendary record, will not be able to make a Busch Stadium
appearance when his dad's part in baseball's feel-good drama closes
on Sunday. Matt's team is playing baseball, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got things to do,'' McGwire said Friday. ``I'm not going
to take anything away from him being a child.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no home run request by Matt. ``He didn't talk about
that,'' McGwire said. ``I asked him what he wanted me to do
tonight. And all he said was, `Have fun.' And that's exactly what
I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never over until the last out, my last at-bat and Sammy's
last at-bat,'' McGwire added. ``We'll be playing at the same time
this weekend. And I wish him luck. I just want everyone to have
fun. So let's have fun.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There is something to be said for perspective. That is one thing
McGwire has gained in what he called ``the most mentally grueling
season of my life.'' But somewhere along this mind-wrenching chase,
McGwire fixed his Windex-blue eyes on those around him and
discovered the pied piper effect of his marvelous journey with
Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, he really took notice of how the country was
taking a coffee break from its troubles and following the magic
McGwire and Sosa were making.
</P>
<P>
   People were feeling good, and others were deeply touched by this
entrancing spectacle. McGwire could see this when a network news
broadcast led with the home run race before the grim details of
politics. He could see it when he sifted through the emotional
notes and letters to him, penned in ink and crayon, from old and
young.
</P>
<P>
   And he could hear it when a divorced father, like McGwire,
walked up to him and thanked him for being an inspiration, for
showing the country how a man and his ex-wife could amicably raise
a son. So it struck McGwire: This pursuit was not about the final
number, but the amount of impact he and Sosa have had on the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hits harder than any number,'' McGwire said before the
game Friday night. ``Whatever way the season ends, so be it. I'm
pretty damn proud of what I've done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a tie would be fantastic, but if I'm ahead or if he's
ahead, just look at what we've done. People have been saying for 37
years that this couldn't be done, and yet two guys have done it.
What I'll take away from this is the impact I've had on people's
lives. It's amazing that a guy who swings a bat can affect the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   But the season has not changed McGwire all that much. He has
sought more solitude, but the core of this regular guy still seems
to be the same. Whether or not his life will ever be normal again
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray it does,'' McGwire said. ``I am a normal person who
plays sports. I really hope people allow me to be who I am. People
have slowly changed around me, wanting to touch me, acting
differently. I'm asking that they not look at us differently. Sammy
and I go to the grocery store and take care of our children like
everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   And hit matching homers that thrill a nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
