<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CUBS-ASTROS-500&AMP;A     09-26 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-ASTROS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BBO-RHODEN-COLUMN, BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ill., Mo., N.Y., Calif.)  
 SOSA SWATS 66th BUT CUBS (AND METS) FAIL AGAIN  
(Eds: See also BBN-HOMERUNS, BBN-CARDS-EXPOS, BBN-METS-BRAVES,(mk) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Dewey defeats Truman. David knocks out Goliath. Sosa
beats McGwire? The underdog scenario has had two hours of life
during the Great Home Run Race of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For an hour on Aug. 19, the lead was held by Sammy Sosa of the
Chicago Cubs, 48 home runs to 47. Only three innings after Sosa had
hit No. 48 against St. Louis, Mark McGwire tied him at 48, and then
hit another in the same game, going ahead by 49-48.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night it happened again. Playing in Houston, Sosa hit his
66th home run, a long shot into the fourth level of the indoor
Astrodome. Fans in St. Louis groaned when Sosa's homer was posted
on the scoreboard. About 45 minutes later, in Busch Stadium,
McGwire tied the race with his 66th, against the Montreal Expos,
prompting fireworks in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   And another underdog, the San Francisco Giants, was flexing its
muscles Friday night on the last weekend of a magical baseball
season. The day began with the Mets and Cubs tied for the lead in
the consolation race for the last spot in the National League
playoffs, while the Giants trailed by only one game.
</P>
<P>
   The day ended with the Mets and Cubs tied, after both lost to
the teams that lead them by many lengths in the divisional races.
The Cubs lost to the Astros, 6-2. The Mets lost to the Braves in
Atlanta, 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, the Giants were playing a late game against the
Rockies. If the Giants won, the three teams would be tied in the
wild-card race, each with only two games to play.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's solo home run in Houston tied the Cubs, 2-2, in the
fourth inning of their game with the Astros. The Cubs would not
score again. The Astros went ahead in the bottom of the inning on a
run-scoring single by Moises Alou, and added single runs in each of
the next three innings. Jose Lima (16-8) defeated Kevin Tapani
(19-9), as the Cubs could manage only five hits.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa hit the home run off Lima, his longtime friend and fellow
Dominican. After Lima gave up two home runs (Nos. 50 and 51) to
Sosa on Aug. 23 in Chicago, both players reacted angrily to a
Chicago newspaper article suggesting that Lima might have been
trying to give Sosa a break. They were quick to point out that Lima
also gave up a home run to McGwire, on June 17 in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been out with him lately,'' Sosa said before Friday
night's game. ``Everybody knows we're friends. It doesn't mean he's
going to give me anything to hit right there.'' And he reminded
reporters: Remember, fellas, this isn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch Sosa hit was right there. It landed an estimated 462
feet away, in the loge level, not among the 10 longest home runs
ever in the Astrodome, but impressive nonetheless. In his first
at-bat, Sosa had flied out to first base. He later grounded out,
then struck out in his final at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   The 51,831 Astros fans (with a few Cubs fans mixed in) called
Sosa out for a curtain call, and also gave a cheer for McGwire when
his home run was shown on the giant video screens. Each time Sosa
batted, thousands of flashbulbs were wasted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sosa and McGwire were tied at 55 home runs after 138 games, tied
at 62, tied at 63, tied at 65, and are now tied at 66. Each has two
games remaining, Saturday and Sunday. From this homers-per-game
point of view, Sosa has never held the lead with the same amount of
the season played. At both points in which he led McGwire in home
runs, Sosa's team had played more games than McGwire's.
</P>
<P>
   Scoreboard watching was in vogue Friday night in Houston and
Atlanta. As the Cubs-Astros game began, the scoreboard already
showed the Mets losing, 2-0, in Atlanta. As the Cubs pulled to 2-1,
so did the Mets. When the Mets pulled even at 2-2, Sosa's homer did
the same for the Cubs. Then both the Mets and Cubs fell behind.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs players and coaches claimed to be fully recovered from
Wednesday's heartbreaking loss in Milwaukee, when left-fielder
Brant Brown's dropped fly ball allowed three runs to score and the
Brewers to win. The Cubs had blown a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs fans might not be so fully recovered. Agonizing through
another tantalizing year in a bad century, Cubs fans have been
gathering for therapy on the Internet, posting messages on a
bulletin board, not a Web page but a Usenet newsgroup, that serves
as a sort of 12-step program for Cubsaholics Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   The bulletin board overflowed with angst after Brown's three-run
error, which cost the Cubs a chance to pull ahead of the Mets. Here
is a sampler of subject lines from messages posted in
alt.sports.baseball.chicago-cubs within hours of Brown's error:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a nightmare.'' ``Dear God:'' ``I just wanna cry.''
``I'll be getting back to my real life now...'' ``Ouch!''
``NOOOOOOO!!!!!!'' ``The Long Dark Tea-Time of the Soul.'' ``Oh the
pain!!!!!!!!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stick a fork in them ...'' ``Do a Hillary and stand by the
Cubbies.'' ``poof!!!!!!!!!!'' ``Bring me the head of Brant Brown.''
``In defense of Brant Brown.'' ``Hath God any mercy?'' ``The
Giants? Say it ain't so!''
</P>
<P>
   At Friday night's game in Houston, the early entertainment was
provided by Brown's encounter with a pigeon in left field. Brown
had started the game, perhaps as a grant of grace from manager Jim
Riggleman. During the second inning, the pigeon tried to land on
his head. He chased it, but it lingered. Brown threw his cap at it,
and umpires stopped the game until the pigeon retreated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
