r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILD-KILLER-GETSMAX-     09-26 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-KILLER-GETSMAX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLER DAD GETS 21 TO LIFE FOR TODDLER'S 1995 MURDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- David Helms was sentenced to 21 years to life for
killing his 2-year-old son, in an apparent finish to a dramatic
case that turned mother against son and led to changes in
California's child-abuse laws.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the legal odyssey, Helms' former girlfriend was
jailed but later released and testified against him. The hourlong
hearing Friday included a statement by Helms' mother, Gail, urging
that her son receive the maximum sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully this is the end of a very terrible saga,'' Superior
Court Judge Sandy Kriegler said after handing down the maximum
punishment allowed by law.
</P>
<P>
   Helms was convicted of second-degree murder and assault on a
child causing death -- a crime that now can lead to a
25-years-to-life sentence because of changes the state Legislature
made in part because of the toddler's death.
</P>
<P>
   Finding that Lance Helms was ``particularly vulnerable'' and
that his father abused his ``position of trust,'' Kriegler
sentenced Helms to 15 years to life in prison for the slaying,
adding six years for a separate child-abuse charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no words a court can come up with to conclude a case
like this,'' Kriegler said.
</P>
<P>
   Helms kept a poker face during the hearing, which included a
montage of videotapes shot by Lance's grandmother before the child
died. Helms left the Van Nuys courtroom without looking back at an
audience filled with his mother, her friends and other relatives
who had gathered for the final stage in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Outside court, Gail Helms said she will probably never forgive
her son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still look at David and it hurts. It hurts a great deal,''
she said. ``But it's justice, and we needed that.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms watched the videotape intently, and his mother was
convinced her son was moved by the sight of her grandson playing
during bath time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't help but smile a little,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Helms was beaten to death in April 1995 in the suburban
North Hollywood apartment his father shared with a girlfriend, Eve
Wingfield.
</P>
<P>
   Wingfield initially was charged with the crime, pleaded guilty
to child abuse with the allegation of great bodily injury or death
and started to serve a 10-year prison term.
</P>
<P>
   But she was freed after a medical examiner found new evidence
re-estimating the time of death in the case, which pointed to
Helms, not Wingfield, as the only person who could have been
responsible for the fatal beating.
</P>
<P>
   She pleaded guilty against her lawyer's advice to a lesser
child-abuse charge and was released from prison. Wingfield, who did
not attend Helms' sentencing, testified against him during his
murder trial. A jury found him guilty Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Helms helped her daughter-in-law fight for custody of Lance
before he was killed, and has pushed for her son's prosecution
since her grandchild was beaten to death more than three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   County welfare officials had taken the boy away from his father
on a previous occasion, but then returned him.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Gail Helms said she kept faith that her son
would be punished for his crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believed in the system, don't ask me why,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Helms' attorney, Jack Stone, filed a notice of appeal on behalf
of his client at the end of the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was terribly emotionally involved at the end because I was
convinced that legally there was not enough evidence to convict
him,'' Stone said outside court.
</P>
<P>
   A medical examiner testified during trial that Lance Helms died
immediately after a severe blow that split his liver. He said the
injuries were so massive that it was ``like being hit by a car.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
