<HEADLINE>
SOSA OUT FRONT BRIEFLY WITH ASTRODOME LAUNCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ No matter how fast he speeds down Route 66 toward the
home-run finish line, Sosa Testarosa can't seem to pass the Big Mac
truck.
</P>
<P>
   After drafting behind St. Louis Cardinals slugger Mark McGwire
for 159 games, Chicago Cubs outfielder Sammy Sosa finally nosed
ahead last night by hitting historic homer No. 66 early in his
team's 6-2 loss to the Houston Astros at the Astrodome. Just 45
minutes later, however, McGwire matched the feat by hammering his
66th in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a feeling he would hit one; he's been doing it all
year,'' Sosa said. ``It's frustrating to lose the game, but not to
be tied with him. It's great. It was nice to have the lead, even
for a little while.''
</P>
<P>
   Down to approximately their last 10 at-bats, McGwire and Sosa
fittingly take their Greater Tater Race toward the most glamorous
record in American sports into the season's final two days. The
Cubs, too _ their loss coupled with a loss by the New York Mets _
will have their playoff fate decided today and tomorrow as they
enter the weekend in a wild-card dead heat at 88-72. A victory by
San Francisco last night would make it a three-way tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't ask for much more tension all around,'' Cubs
first baseman Mark Grace said. ``But, geez, we need to win a
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, who launched a 462-foot rocket off Jose Lima in the fourth
inning, has led McGwire only twice _ for three innings on Aug. 19
and for two more last night. Shortly after Sosa grounded out in the
sixth, McGwire's tying homer was shown to the near-sellout crowd of
51,831. As they did after Sosa's shot, the Astrodome rose in a
standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Leading off the fourth, Sosa took a first-pitch fastball at the
knees for a strike from co-Dominican Republic native Lima. With the
identical 0-1 pitch, Sosa went where no player in major-league
history had gone before by crushing No. 66 into left-center field's
fourth level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew at contact she was gone,'' said Sosa, who hit his third
this season off good friend Lima. ``And it went a long way, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   After snaring No. 66 off a carom with one hand and falling over
a chair, the fan who nabbed the historic and specially marked ball
left the stadium with the ball without giving his name to
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   As has become his trademark during his likely MVP season, Sosa
stutter-stepped around the bases, signaled love to his mother,
Lucretia, and then doused his face with a cup of water while flash
bulbs lit the dome, fans buzzed and Sosa eventually emerged from
the dugout for a curtain call.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible what he does,'' said Lima, who scoffed at the
suggestion he grooved pitches for his friend and countryman. ``You
make a mistake and boom, it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa may be hotter, with three homers in his last two games and
a 56-41 edge since May 24, but McGwire has proven flawlessly
resilient with homers in at-bats immediately after Sosa twice
taking the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being admittedly distracted by the devastation of
Hurricane Georges in his Dominican Republic homeland, Sosa laughed
and joked with teammates, media and fans before the game. As
admirers screamed ``Sammmmmeeeeee'' relentlessly, Sosa hit homers
on six of 22 swings in batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   He was jammed by a 1-1 fastball in the first, popping weakly to
second. In the sixth, he tried to pull a low sinker but grounded to
shortstop. Against closer Billy Wagner in the ninth, Sosa struck
out looking at a fastball down the middle to send fans to the exits
with two outs remaining.
</P>
<P>
   While teammates huddled around a television to watch the
conclusion of the Mets-Braves game, Sosa read a fax detailing the
destruction in the Dominican and talked with former Houston Rockets
center Kevin Willis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
