</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-TEX </SLUG>
 
McGWIRE SMASHES WAY TO HOME RUN NO. 66 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ For 45 minutes last night, Sammy Sosa stood alone as
baseball's single-season home-run king.
</P>
<P>
   Then, 780 miles away, Mark McGwire smashed another baseball into
the left-field seats at Busch Stadium and, in doing so, sent a
message back to Houston that the Great Home Run Chase could very
well go down to the last pitch of the last at-bat of the last game
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be an exciting weekend,'' McGwire prophesied
yesterday before hitting his 66th home run of the season in the
fifth inning of the Cardinals' 6-5 victory against the Montreal
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   So far he's right as yesterday's home run left McGwire tied with
archrival and bosom buddy Sammy Sosa, who hit his 66th for the Cubs
against the Houston Astros at the Astrodome. Both have two games
left, but Sosa could get extra chances if the Cubs are involved in
a playoff for the National League wild card.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned ... Mark McGwire and the home-run
chase is the most important thing the next two days,'' Cardinals
manager Tony La Russa said. ``That sounds like heresy, but he
deserves everything we can give him.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's 66th came off Expos rookie Shayne Bennett in his third
at-bat last night, just moments after Sosa had grounded out in his
third at-bat in the Astrodome. It came on a 1-2 pitch clocked at 79
mph, just after McGwire had hit another towering drive to left that
hooked foul into the upper deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hit a lot of foul balls down the line the last week,''
McGwire said. ``You see it and think, not again. But you have to
take a deep breath and get back in there. This time I was able to
get the head of the bat out there and center it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said La Russa: ``That was spectacular. That was almost as good
as 62.''
</P>
<P>
   La Russa conceded that it's unusual for a player to hit a home
run after the letdown of a near-miss but added, ``When has Mark
done anything usual or natural all year? He's been incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday marked only the second time this season Sosa has led
McGwire in home runs and the first time since they both surpassed
Roger Maris' record earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa took the lead briefly Aug. 19 when he hit his 48th home run
against the Cardinals. But McGwire came back and hit two in that
same game to regain the lead.
</P>
<P>
   This was also the 21st time this season McGwire and Sosa have
homered on the same day. McGwire said he heard from the crowd last
night that Sosa had hit a home run, but insisted he had no
emotional response to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought, he's hit another one,'' McGwire said. ``I've
said a thousand times this year, I can't control what he or anybody
else does. I can only control Mark McGwire swinging the bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is after what he and I have done, whoever ends on
top, nobody should feel bad. What we've done is something nobody
has ever done in the history of the game. Why should anybody walk
away disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's home run did set one record. It was his 34th home run
at home, tying Ted Kluszewski's National League mark for most in
one season. No telling what Kluszewski was doing on the road, since
he finished with just 49 total for the Reds in 1954. No word yet if
Major League Baseball will fly the late Kluszewski's family in for
the record-breaking ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   But even without them the finally thrilling chapter of a
yearlong epic is about to be written.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
