<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALONE: SHEFF WILL BE IN LEFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ New Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said
Friday he expects Gary Sheffield to be his starting left fielder
next season.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, who was lost for the season last month with a
sprained left ankle, took over in right field when he was acquired
May 15 from Florida. Raul Mondesi moved to center and played well
but wants to go back to right, where he won Gold Gloves the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield and Mondesi are the highest-paid players on the team
and are finishing the first season of long-term contracts.
Sheffield has a six-year deal worth $68.5 million; Mondesi has a
four-year contract for $36 million. He also has two years at the
club option that bumps the deal to $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield has said publicly he will do whatever it takes to win,
including a move to left. Privately he has told a few teammates he
wants to remain in right. Sheffield began his career as a shortstop
in Milwaukee and played third base with San Diego in 1992 when he
won the National League batting title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not spoken directly to Gary about left field, but he
told the manager (Glenn Hoffman) he was agreeable,'' Malone said.
``That is the way I see the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi made a successful shift to center, but began to
experience lower back pain in August. He traced it to the added
burden of covering so much ground and told Hoffman he wasn't going
back next season.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi missed his second consecutive game Friday with a
sprained index finger on his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Will Shaw want trade? Malone said he expects to head to the
Midwest and East Coast in the next two weeks to talk to several
players about their futures with the club. The biggest reason:
Dodgers closer Jeff Shaw is expected to demand a trade at the end
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Because Shaw, who has recorded 23 of his 46 saves since joining
the Dodgers at the All-Star break, was traded during a multi-year
contract, he has the leverage to get the Dodgers to move him,
preferably to a club closer to his home outside Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   But Malone, who helped revive Shaw's career in Montreal several
years ago, is confident he can get Shaw to remain with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he misses his family,'' Malone said. ``But I know he
also wants to win. And we can provide that. I didn't come here to
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, 32, earned $650,000 this season, but the big money starts
kicking in during 1999. Shaw will earn $2.8 million in each of the
next three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   That is a relative bargain for a top-flight closer on today's
market. Shaw is only the second reliever in history to have
consecutive 40-save seasons. The other was Lee Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Texas right-hander John Wetteland is the highest-paid closer at
$5.7 million. Randy Myers, now a setup man in San Diego, is earning
$4.4 million. Trevor Hoffman, the Padres closer who has 52 saves,
is making $2.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Malone knows it will take a considerable pay raise to keep Shaw
in Los Angeles, but he also knows how much Shaw enjoyed playing in
Cincinnati, just a half-hour from his hometown in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw also is in the position to veto trades to six teams. He
said he will make his decision at the end of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
