<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALMON SURGERY SET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ The Angels' Tim Salmon, who has played on a partially
torn ligament in his left foot since April, will have surgery
Monday. The ligament, which is 75 percent torn, will be severed
completely in a procedure performed by Dr. Phil Kwong.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon has served as the Angels' designated hitter since
injuring his foot while rounding the bases on a home run hit April
22 off the Orioles' Scott Erickson. He stayed on the disabled list
through May 9 and has played since then with the tear, which
worsened throughout the season.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon, though, has managed to put up numbers similar to his
career averages. Going into Friday's game, he was hitting .301 with
26 homers and 88 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been the most trying, difficult and frustrating year
I've ever had in baseball,'' Salmon said. ``I ran the gamut of
pain, dealing with the pain and having a reduced role. Any time you
have to persevere through something, you come out stronger. I try
to find the positives. But if it had to happen again, would I do it
the same? I don't think I would.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon had the option of avoiding surgery and trying to rehab
the injury through rest. But he decided to have the surgery
immediately and is expected to require three months of recovery
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor told me a month ago that the part (of the ligament)
that's still attached might never tear,'' Salmon said. ``But
there's still pain involved. I have a different appreciation for
the comments made by (Mark) McGwire (who had the same injury). When
he told me I should shut it down, I said, `What?!' Now, I have a
different appreciation for what he said.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Angels appreciate what Salmon has done for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed by it, impressed by it,'' manager Terry Collins
said. ``We don't know what kind of pain he's in. But we can rest
assured he's in a lot of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Velarde returns:Second baseman Randy Velarde returned to the
team Friday after spending Thursday with his family in Midland,
Texas. Velarde's grandfather, Elias, 92, has been diagnosed with
leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said Velarde had as much time off as he needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably the only guy in the ballpark where this
(baseball) is everything,'' Collins said. ``For other guys, there's
life outside this.''
</P>
<P>
   The right choice: Collins shook up the lineup for Friday's game,
trying to get as many right-handed hitters in the game against A's
left-hander Kenny Rogers as possible. Garret Anderson and Darin
Erstad were on the bench, replaced in right field and at first base
by Reggie Williams and Craig Shipley, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darin's not swinging like he can, and Garret's in a little bit
of a funk,'' Collins said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
