<SLUG> BC-NY-STATUTORY-RAPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKLYN TEACHER CONVICTED FOR AFFAIR WITH STUDENT, 16 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Brooklyn high school teacher was convicted Friday
of statutory rape and other charges for having a sexual
relationship with a student who was under 17, the legal age of
consent.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher, Joseph Rebecca, 36, of Canarsie, taught math at
Samuel J. Tilden High School. He was found to have engaged in
sexual activity with a student there from May to July of 1996, when
the girl was 16. The relationship continued into 1997,
investigators said, after the student turned 17 in July.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship ended when the student was told by schoolmates
that Rebecca was having an affair with a second student, a
law-enforcement official said. The girl became angry, the official
said, and told school authorities about her own relationship with
the teacher. The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said that the second student had at first confirmed having a
relationship with Rebecca but later recanted.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca's lawyer, Alan I. Stutman, said after the verdict Friday
that there had been no sexual activity between Rebecca and the
student whose complaint led to the criminal charges. He said that
the student had been obsessed with Rebecca. The relationship, he
said, ``went from puppy love to infatuation to obsession.''
</P>
<P>
   But the law-enforcement official said that the relationship had
``evolved out of a mutual attraction'' between the math teacher and
the student, who was in one of his classes and was also in the
school's Haitian Club, to which Rebecca was an adviser. The
official said that the student who filed a complaint has since
graduated from Tilden.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-week trial, a jury of six men and six women in state
Supreme Court in Brooklyn convicted Rebecca of charges that
included five counts of third-degree rape and eight counts of
third-degree sodomy. Each of these counts carries a sentence of
11/3 to four years in prison. Justice Norman George ordered Rebecca
jailed pending his sentencing on Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Stutman said his client would appeal his conviction. He said
Rebecca, who is not married, had been suspended from his teaching
post after his arrest and that he expected that the school system
would now dismiss him.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Stutman nor the Brooklyn district attorney's office
could say Friday how long Rebecca had been a teacher, and a
spokesman for the Board of Education, J.D. LaRock, said that
information could not be obtained late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a highly publicized 1995 case, Glenn Harris, then a
33-year-old Manhattan gym teacher, disappeared with a 15-year-old
student for two months on a cross-country trip. After turning
himself in to school investigators, he was charged with kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said that he fled with the girl to help her escape
abusive parents. He pleaded guilty to a charge of custodial
interference and was sentenced to three years of probation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
