<HEADLINE>
NHL TEAMS NOT SEEING RED (LINE)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The NHL stands guilty of tampering with its
own product this exhibition season as it explores ways to make its
product more appealing to TV sports junkies.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, for the exhibition game at the Forum between the
Kings and the Phoenix Coyotes, the league trotted out one of its
experimental rules, eliminating the center red line for offside
calls, though not for icing.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the rule should result in more scoring chances as
forwards hang out at the opposing blue line to cherry pick passes
from their defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   Asked before the game what he expected, Kings right wing Glen
Murray said: ``I have no idea. It could be 10-9.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. With the game early in the third period, neither team
had been able to capitalize on the experiment, and neither appeared
to have altered its game much to try to take advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings held a 3-1 lead with 18 minutes remaining. Russ
Courtnall (shorthanded), Murray and Philippe Boucher had the Kings'
goals, and Dallas Drake had the long score for the Coyotes. The
teams meet again tonight in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Jamie Storr practiced Friday morning for the
first time since signing his three-year contract worth a little
more than $3 million.... The angriest roar of the night was
reserved for referee Don Koharski, who called the fateful major
penalty on Sean O'Donnell during last spring's playoffs that turned
the tide against the Kings during Game 3 against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famer: Radio color commentator Cammi Granato will be
replaced in the broadcast booth for tonight's exhibition game at
Phoenix by former King Daryl Evans. Granato will be in Chicago,
where she will be inducted tonight into the Italian-American
Foundation Hall of Fame and honored as its athlete of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Granato led the U.S. women's hockey team to the gold medal
earlier this year at the Winter Olympics in Nagano, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets on sale: Individual game tickets go on sale at noon
Sunday at the Forum and all TicketMaster locations. The Kings'
annual open practice and skills competition is scheduled for 1 p.m.
at the Forum, with admission free for season-ticket holders and $5
for others wishing to attend. Proceeds will go to the Kings'
charitable foundation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
