<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO OUTSIDERS, ONLY ONE WORLD EXISTS IN NEBRASKA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. _ If there were any mistaking where one was, the
giant billboard on the highway entering town vaporized the
ambiguity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome,'' it said in 10-foot letters, ``to the football
center of the universe.''
</P>
<P>
   Subtle, these Nebraskans.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with three national championships in the last four years, no
one on the planet has a good counter-argument against the
University of Nebraska football team. And the morning line from
Vegas has the Cornhuskers favored by 10 over the Vulcans and two
over the Klingons.
</P>
<P>
   As for the University of Washington Huskies this afternoon, well
... they had their meteoric moment, in 1991, the last time the
Huskers lost at home, 44 games ago.
</P>
<P>
   The football universe is different now, filled by a red giant of
a star.
</P>
<P>
   If the billboard wasn't sufficient as a symbol, there is the
state capitol. A 14-story art-deco rocket ship of a building a few
blocks from campus, it looms alone above the prairie. By municipal
law, no building can be taller.
</P>
<P>
   Atop the dome of this incongruent obelisk is a 20-foot brass
statue. Political satirist Mark Russell once said it looked like a
woman bowling. But he doesn't know sports. To me, it appeared to be
a Husker tailback on an option dive.
</P>
<P>
   What else could better represent the state?
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, there is more to us than football,'' said a smiling E.
Benjamin Nelson, an affable Democrat finishing up his second and
final term as governor.
</P>
<P>
   The statue, it was pointed out, is called ``The Sower,'' a woman
spreading seed upon the fruited plain. Nelson too, is a sower,
trying to plant ideas in a skeptical Seattle sports columnist that
there is something going on in his state besides stone-faced talks
among the citizenry about squat lifts and zone blitzes.
</P>
<P>
   He certainly has convinced his fellow heartlanders that
something else is going on. Nelson's approval rating in statewide
opinion polls is more than 80 percent. Considering that Santa
Claus' career high rating in Nebraska was 87 percent _ he wears a
lot of red, you know? _ Nelson is on the frontier in ways more than
his address.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the firm-handshake, good-hair veneer of his profession,
Nelson is a big-time mover on international trade, since his
state's production of corn, soybeans, beef and feed grain in almost
as impressive as the football program's production of first downs
on the tailback pitch.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, trade was the topic of the fifth annual Diplomats
Weekend in Lincoln, in which Nelson invites business, political and
civic leaders from around the state, as well as national and
international guests, to talk about getting Nebraska's agriculture
and industry spread to the far corners.
</P>
<P>
   He likes to say things like ``we're local producers, but world
providers,'' and trots about impressive statistics about Nebraska's
substantial economy and impact.
</P>
<P>
   Friday at his CEO Roundtable panel at a downtown hotel, he had
the chief of Argentina's cabinet of ministers, Jorge Rodriguez,
tout the virtues of Nelson's trade initiatives as well as his
nation's eagerness to find Nebraska investors.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez also acquired his Master's and doctorate at the
University of Nebraska. He knows the local culture. So much so that
he taught Nelson the Spanish version of the state mantra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vamos rojo grande,'' said Nelson, beaming to his audience.
</P>
<P>
   Go Big Red.
</P>
<P>
   There is no escaping it, even in a room of serious suits talking
billions of dollars. Several of the panelists began their
presentation with football references, to make sure they were
connecting with the audience.
</P>
<P>
   The president of a big Minneapolis company, Ernie Micek,
immediately tossed out statistics guaranteed to win sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember these numbers _ 506 and 72,'' he said. ``That's the
cumulative score of the series between Nebraska and the University
of Minnesota.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't need to mention which was which.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a coincidence that Nelson marshaled the state's
leaders and out-of-state guests on a home football weekend. Nor was
it a coincidence that one of the eight panelists was Tom Osborne,
who retired as Nebraska's coach in December after 25 years of
achievement on and off the field. Osborne was there to promote his
``Teammates'' campaign, a new statewide mentoring program that
attempts to pair adults with at-risk kids. The endeavor sounded
very worthy, even if a little askew amid the talk of factories and
corn bushels.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are selling steak in Nebraska, there is only one kind
of sizzle that goes with it.
</P>
<P>
   As Scott Moore, the secretary of state, put it after the
roundtable, ``On ESPN, they don't talk about corn or soy futures.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN, along with the other networks and most newspapers and
magazines, don't much care about the ins and outs of world
agriculture. If you're talking the ins and outs of the Huskers'
quarterback spot, now we have meaning.
</P>
<P>
   If the world knows this place only through football, well,
that's OK with most Nebraskans. If they weren't known for football,
it's apparent that these folks might not have captured the
attention of anybody for anything.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the obvious circumstances of geographic isolation, small
population, an absence of major league activities as well as the
absence of another Division I football school in the state, there
is something else about the place of football in the culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about it, Nebraska is always a place that other
people went through,'' said Moore. ``The Pony Express, the Oregon
Trail, the Morman Trail, the Union Pacific railroad. These are all
important things in our history, but they were made by people going
somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nebraska football team gives people a reason to come back
here.''
</P>
<P>
   They are back here this weekend, a swirling ocean of red-clad
rooters who reconvene with their heritage via a big intersectional
football game. It is why, after hours of speechifying on important
world topics at the Roundtable, the first question to the panelists
from the audience went to Osborne:
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's gonna win (Saturday)?''
</P>
<P>
   They really don't expect outsiders to understand, especially
wise-guy sports columnists. Which is why Nelson, after bantering
with his Seattle visitor who a year ago irked him with
disparagements about about his state, unleashed the hospitality for
which Nebraskans may someday be known as much as football.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are,'' he said, ``granted immunity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, great,'' I said. Then I looked over his shoulder out the
window to the streets of Lincoln, knowing how deep they would run
red the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I have it in writing?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufednote &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
