<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS HOPE TO MAKE STATEMENT VS. STEELERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND _ Sam Adams is sorry, but the Seahawks' defensive
tackle is tired of feeling like has to say he's sorry.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks are 3-0 for the first time since 1986 and have a
realistic shot at the franchise's first 4-0 start in Sunday's game
against a struggling Pittsburgh Steelers team at Three Rivers
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But many still-skeptical fans are taking a who-have-they-beaten
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like we're supposed to apologize for our
schedule,'' Adams said. ``It's like, `Gee, sorry we've only beaten
the first three teams we've played.' We didn't schedule these
teams. But we did beat these teams.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just that those teams have been the Philadelphia Eagles,
Arizona Cardinals and Washington Redskins, who are a combined 1-8.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Sunday's game against the Steelers, next week's game
at Kansas City and the Oct. 11 game against the Denver Broncos at a
soldout Kingdome have become statement-making opportunities for the
Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   This three-game stretch provides a team that did serious damage
to a trio of lightweights from the NFC East a chance to show it is
a serious contender in the AFC.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big game because it's a better team and we're on the
road,'' quarterback Warren Moon said. ``But we're just taking the
attitude that it's another big game on our schedule. This is the
biggest game we've played because it's this week's game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks can beat the Steelers. Whether they will or not
hinges on their ability to:
</P>
<P>
   -- Run the ball. After leading the NFL in passing offense last
year, the Seahawks are running to set up the pass.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it has been an efficient if not overpowering formula.
They have had a 100-yard rusher in three straight games for the
first time in club history. Moon's quarterback rating of 101.2 ties
him for second-best in the AFC, and he has thrown six TD passes and
no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers allowed the Dolphins' Karim Abdul-Jabbar to rush
for 108 yards in last week's 21-0 loss at Miami, but it took him 33
carries. It broke the Steelers' string of 22 straight
regular-season games without allowing a 100-yard rusher.
</P>
<P>
   From 1993-1997, the Steelers allowed 3.43 yards per rush _ the
second-best average over a five-year span in league history to the
1971-75 Dallas Cowboys (3.40). The Steelers have not allowed a
100-yard rusher at Three Rivers since 1995, when then-Patriot
Curtis Martin went for 120.
</P>
<P>
   -- Stop the run. The Seahawks have been vulnerable to runs up
the middle. The Redskins' Terry Allen had a 92-yard effort last
week. The Eagles' Duce Staley ran for 95 yards in the opener. The
Cardinals' Adrian Murrell went for 79 yards in Week 2.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Jerome Bettis. The Bus didn't complete his route last
week, rushing for 48 yards on just 13 carries. But since joining
the Steelers in 1996, Bettis has never had sub-100 yard efforts in
back-to-back games he has started and finished. In fact, he has
rushed for triple digits in 21 of 32 full games _ sitting out the
season finale last year with an injury and being limited to six and
three carries in the final two games in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks will go light at linebacker for the second straight
week, with 230-pound Darrin Smith starting in the middle and
226-pound James Logan replacing Smith on the right side.
</P>
<P>
   -- Beat the Steelers at Three Rivers. The Steelers are 32-8
under coach Bill Cowher at home and have won eight straight.
</P>
<P>
   They were shut out last week for the first time since 1993 and
only the fourth time in the past 10 seasons. But they are 3-0 when
playing at home after those shutout losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Cowher is a fiery guy. He's going to challenge the team
this week,'' said linebacker Chad Brown, who signed with the
Seahawks last year after playing four seasons in Pittsburgh. ``It's
going to be up to us to No. 1, slow Jerome down, and then for our
offense to go out and prove we can move the ball against one of the
best defenses in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't begun to fire on all cylinders yet,'' he said.
``And this is a game where we need all cylinders to win.''
</P>
<P>
   HAWK TALK: LB Dean Wells will play Sunday, but won't start.
Wells has been sidelined with a pulled calf muscle for the first
three games. ... In Pittsburgh, DE Nolan Harrison was downgraded
from questionable to out with a strained hamstring. Orpheus Roye
will start for Harrison. ... FS Eric Stokes, TE Itula Mili, OT Todd
Weiner and DT Riddick Parker were named inactive by the Seahawks.
The Steelers' inactive list: Harrison, CB Deshea Townsend, OT Chris
Conrad and WR Jahine Arnold.
</P>
</TEXT>
