<DOCNO> NYT19980926.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5764 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI &LR;      09-26 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUARD, HUSKIES HEAD INTO BIG RED SEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. _ On an Indian-summer afternoon in the mid-80s
yesterday at Nebraska's Memorial Stadium, Jim Lambright, the
University of Washington football coach, showed up wearing a
long-sleeved black shirt, black vest and black pants.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the assumption by Lambright's Huskies is that they
don't get inundated by Nebraska's Blackshirts. That's what the
Huskers like to call their defense.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe subconsciously, Lambright can't get used to being here.
Remember, this Nebraska game wasn't his idea.
</P>
<P>
   When athletic director Barbara Hedges allowed Missouri out of a
contract a few years ago and took on the dreaded Huskers, Lambright
was OK with the 1997 game at Husky Stadium. But he wanted the road
rematch deferred so the '98 schedule wouldn't be so diabolical,
especially for a team relatively young.
</P>
<P>
   Valor prevailed over discretion, and here are the eighth-ranked
Huskies, about to take on the No. 2-rated team in the nation in
college football's feature game Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to go in without a conscience,'' said Brock Huard,
the UW quarterback. ``We went to ASU without a conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   The scheduling issue takes on focus because while the Huskies
have been judged in one rating to have the fourth-toughest in the
nation, Nebraska has again opened the season by punching out
no-counts and ne'er-do-wells disguised as Louisiana Tech,
Alabama-Birmingham and Cal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is their season opener,'' Huard said. ``They might not
admit to that, but we know it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to come at us in ways they haven't shown yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Nebraska comes at you _ as opposed to the way, say, New
Mexico State comes at you _ you can get beat up.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Nebraska's All-America end, Grant Wistrom, lunged at
Huard's shins after he threw a pass late in the first quarter.
Huard suffered a sprained ankle and the Huskies lost 27-14.
</P>
<P>
   Surely Nebraska will aim more such abuse Huard's way Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to come after me,'' Huard said. ``That's the way
the game's played. You look at the next level, and you've got to
hit the quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Count on it, says Chad Kelsay, who has been Nebraska's best
pass-rusher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he's coming in here, saying to himself last year was
a fluke or something,'' Kelsay said. ``I think if we can rattle his
cage a little at the beginning of the game, he's going to be
thinking about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the guys who are going to sit back there in the pocket
and throw the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Linehan, the UW offensive coordinator, can offer Huard
only a plan and some ``hot'' receivers to dump the ball to when it
gets dicey. His description of Nebraska's defense won't soothe
Huard much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Awesome,'' Linehan said. ``They've got the best pair of
speed-rushing ends (Kelsay and Mike Rucker) we'll see all season. I
see about eight, nine guys that are going to be in the NFL starting
on their defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Slotback Dane Looker's return _ albeit as he nurses a thigh
bruise _ should help Huard. Still, with Washington desperate to
establish a running game, the matchup Saturday is about as extreme
as it gets _ a team that has gravitated to the pass against the
ground-bound Huskers.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Washington was embarrassed by Nebraska's option
attack, allowing 384 yards rushing. Several factors seem to point
to better success against it this year: a rebuilt Husker offensive
line, a different backfield featuring quarterback Bobby Newcombe
and I-back DeAngelo Evans, and Washington's having experienced the
offense in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in shock that first series,'' Randy Hart, the UW
defensive coordinator, said about the speed of the attack. ``The
worst thing you can do is change the game plan then.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jabari Issa, the Husky defensive tackle: ``They have so
many ways of getting the ball up the middle or around the side.
When you tackle somebody, it's almost a gamble sometimes, because
you don't see the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   When it gets to the perimeter, one of the imponderables is the
Huskies' rover, Nigel Burton. The only Husky to have played in
Memorial Stadium, he has been gimpy with a sprained ankle, and _
undersized as he is at 180 pounds _ he is important to Washington's
defensive plan, because his backups lack experience.
</P>
<P>
   One such contingency is free safety Brendan Jones moving to
Burton's spot, and promising freshman free safety Hakim Akbar
supplanting Jones. But Burton will go as long as he can in the kind
of physical test he enjoys most.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's me and you,'' Burton says defiantly, ``and you might be
bigger than I am, but I don't give a damn.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton's ability to play a full game is in question, as is
linebacker Lester Towns'. The Huskies had Towns wear a boot
yesterday to protect his troublesome foot, and he didn't practice.
</P>
<P>
   Washington coaches have plotted an expanded role for backup
quarterback Marques Tuiasosopo, figuring that he's too good to keep
on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   They also know that no time is great to play Nebraska, but
perhaps this is as good as any. Not only are the Huskers retooling,
Washington is 2-0 and playing with house money after the surprise
victory at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us is thinking, `Let's make it respectable, let's make
it close,''' Huard insisted. ``We're thinking we're going to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
