<HEADLINE>
ACID TEST FOR COUGARS, BEARS IN PAC-10 OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ The Washington State Cougars finally leave
their backyard Saturday to face the California Golden Bears in the
Pac-10 Conference opener for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   After two home games and one at Boise State, Cal's Memorial
Stadium will be an altogether different place to play for the
Cougars. Rarely filled to half its 75,000-seat capacity, the
concrete confines can lull a team to sleep and the atmosphere could
have hallucinogenic effects on the unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a difficult place to play because of the uniqueness of
the stadium and their fans,'' Price said of the stadium built in
1923 to resemble the Colosseum in Rome. `` ... It's farther
removed, the crowd is a little quieter, a little more subdued. Even
though it's bigger, with more people, it's just a different feeling
when you go into that stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bears, who were thrashed 63-37 last year in Pullman, can't
wait to get the Cougars on their home turf. Cal is 24-9-3 against
WSU in games played in Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we play Washington State here,'' said Cal coach Tom
Holmoe, in his second year after going 3-8 in 1997. `` ... It is
good to be home and have this one ready to go because it is our
(conference) opener and it is a huge game.''
</P>
<P>
   Cal is 2-1 with victories over Oklahoma and Houston. The loss
was to Nebraska, a respectable 24-3 defeat at Memorial Stadium,
which was nearly filled to capacity for for a non-conference game
for the first time in four decades.
</P>
<P>
   For WSU, Cal expects a crowd of only 35,000.
</P>
<P>
   But at 3-0, the defending Pac-10 champion Cougars represent the
most important game to date to Holmoe and his Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is bigger than Nebraska, bigger than our opener
against Houston and bigger than Oklahoma on the road because it
counts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule works to Cal's advantage, too. The Bears get a bye
next weekend and can focus solely on the Cougars. WSU travels to
Pasadena next Saturday to face UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The schedule, the way it is now, benefits us in that we have a
very good team to play, the defending Pac-10 champs, and then we
have a bye,'' Holmoe said. ``It doesn't allow us to look down the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars, however, look at Cal as the first true test of
whether they can make it to consecutive bowl games for the first
time in school history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to bring our motivation, our inspiration and our
spirit with us. All those things have to come from within,'' said
Price, whose traveling squad includes 30 first-year players. ``We
aren't going to have the aid of the fog and the band and the town
cheering for you as you run out onto the field. Because it isn't
going to be like that.''
</P>
<P>
   And he doesn't expect anything like last year's offensive
donnybrook.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to be a little better than we were against Idaho,
and we just have to be little bit better than Cal, and we just have
to win by one point,'' Price said. ``I don't care how we do it.
Fumble recovery. Intercepted pass. Long touchdown pass. It doesn't
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA DREAMING: Playing in Berkeley gives the Cougars a
chance to showcase their program to potential Bay Area recruits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we have two top-notch prospects that are coming to the
game not only to evaluate the Cal Bears, but to look at the
Washington State Cougars, too,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   Current Cougars plucked from the Bay Area include free safety
Lamont Thompson and three junior college transfers from San
Francisco City College: running back Kevin Brown, defensive back
Chris Martin and receiver Jerry Roquemore.
</P>
<P>
   NOT SO FAB: With the exception of two seniors, wide receiver
Nian Taylor and tight end Love Jefferson, the rest of the receiving
corps has been getting fairly low marks from the coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to need work on just about everything,'' Price said.
``I wish I could say that wasn't the case. But from alignment,
assignment, running routes, blocking, catching, we just need to
improve.''
</P>
<P>
   The new group includes junior college transfers Leaford Hackett
and Roquemore, and redshirt freshmen Adam Davis and Jason White, as
well as junior Troy Woody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we have stunk it up by any means. I think we're
doing OK,'' Price said. ``But we just haven't made the plays that
they are capable of making.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
