<SLUG> BC-REUNION-TRAFFIC-STOP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAFFIC COP PULLS OVER LONG-LOST FATHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- For five blocks, LAPD patrol Officer Kelly
Benitez debated whether to stop a Ford Thunderbird for expired
registration tags.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most important decision he ever made.
</P>
<P>
   Against all odds, the driver turned out to be his long-lost
father -- the father he had never known, the father he had wanted
to meet for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at his eyes, and it seemed funny,'' Benitez said
Friday. ``I saw some similarities to myself, and that made me look
at the name on the license. It was Paul Benitez.''
</P>
<P>
   As Kelly Benitez knew, that was the name of his father, the man
who had walked out of his life when he was just 4 months old.
</P>
<P>
   With the expired tags forgotten, the two men quizzed each other
on family history and soon realized they were reunited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought: `Oh, my Lord. It can't be. What are the odds?' ''
said Paul Benitez Jr. ``So I just came flat-out and asked him, `Are
you Kelly?' and he said, `Yes,' and I said, `Oh, my God, I'm your
father.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, they live just five miles from each other in
suburban Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a dream. Every day I ask myself: `Is this really
happening? Did I really find him?' '' Paul Benitez Jr. said during
a news conference at which the two told their amazing tale.
</P>
<P>
   Both men say they had spent years looking for one another,
through professional search services and the Internet. Kelly
Benitez said he was forbidden by Los Angeles Police Department
rules from doing a personal search for his father through
Department of Motor Vehicles records or other government databases.
</P>
<P>
   Since they were reunited Sept. 18, the two men have spent a day
together, getting to know each other and discussing politics,
sports and the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very curious about each other, but we're really
different,'' said Paul Benitez Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The father is a Democrat, his son a Republican. Kelly Benitez
says he favors Sammy Sosa in the baseball home-run derby; his
father would prefer that Sosa and Mark McGwire end the season in a
tie.
</P>
<P>
   What they share is a desire to put their separation behind them
and jump-start their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of guilt, a lot of unfinished business,'' Paul
Benitez Jr. said. ``I just wish I could have been there earlier for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Benitez Jr. was 19, fresh from Bell Gardens High School in
East Los Angeles, when he had a child with a teen-ager named Debra.
He joined the Army, she moved away, and they drifted apart.
</P>
<P>
   On the only occasion he saw his son, Benitez was in uniform. A
photo was taken, one that Kelly Benitez has carried with him for
nearly three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Benitez was raised by his grandparents in Glendora and
also lost touch with his mom, who now lives in Northern California.
He did not want to reveal her last name since she has not yet been
notified of his reunion with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Benitez Jr. now teaches sixth grade at Bird Middle School
in suburban Sun Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In his three years as an LAPD officer, Kelly Benitez said he has
stopped several people with the surname Benitez and often had asked
them a few questions to see if they were relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Benitez Jr. concedes that when he saw that they shared the
same name, he had hoped to use that fact to bluff his way out of a
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   He told the officer he was heading to the DMV that very minute
to renew his car registration.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what they all say,'' Kelly Benitez recalled of the
traffic stop.
</P>
<P>
   When the officer later realized he had found his father, ``his
jaw dropped and he said, `Get out of the car,' '' Paul Benitez Jr.
said. ``We started hugging and people pulled over thinking I was
wrestling with this cop.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the expired tags, Benitez said his son gave him a
warning, and that the renewal check is in the mail to the DMV.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout their roadside reunion, Kelly Benitez said, he was
skeptical of the other man, so much so that he had his father
follow him back to the police station so they could talk.
</P>
<P>
   The snapshot proved to be the key piece of evidence. Paul
Benitez Jr. knew what and who was in the picture before he was
shown it by his son.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Benitez said he does not expect an apology from his mother
or father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what it's like to be 18 or 19,'' he said. ``I
understand the facts of being a young person and understand that
time, and I know no one's perfect. So as far as I'm concerned, it's
just water under the bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
