<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS NEED CLARK AND HIS HARDBALL WAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Broken toe and all, no one enjoyed last night's
Rangers division title clinching celebration more than Will Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of grit in this clubhouse,'' Clark said. ``A lot
of heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty four hours earlier, Clark's right's foot was stuck in a
bag of ice, his eyes were scanning the room like twin radar dishes
and his mouth was rattling off a steady stream of caustic
wisecracks like a machine gun on automatic fire.
</P>
<P>
   None of those three facts will elicit any news bulletins.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the first time, I was nailed in the crossfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're hovering,'' he barked in my direction. ``Why are you
hovering? It makes me nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd been standing a few feet away, trying to figure out a safe
approach to a man who'd drilled a five-ounce baseball off his right
big toe at about a hundred miles an hour some 90 minutes earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Now this would be painful under normal circumstances. The fact
that the toe had already been fractured less than two weeks ago
intensified the pain to an excruciating degree.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine slamming your finger in a car door. Now, just about the
time the purple bruises start yellowing, do it again. Get the idea?
</P>
<P>
   Clark had writhed in the dirt at home plate in the fourth inning
like a sunfish that had just been yanked onto a fishing dock. He
went down on his back, then spun over on his knees, his weight
forward, on his batting helmet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was as white as a sheet,'' manager Johnny Oates would say
after the Rangers' 9-3 victory Thursday in Game 1 of this series
had cut their magic number to clinching the AL West title to ``1.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every bit of blood had drained from his face and he was
incoherent.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark incoherent is not necessarily anything new, but normally
it's by choice. Not this time. Reluctantly he limped off to the
clubhouse for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   By the time reporters arrived in the clubhouse after the game,
he'd had _ to put it delicately _ several pain killers. Clark
feeling no pain can be even more daunting than when he's hurting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't come over here feeling sorry for me,'' he snapped. ``I
don't need your sympathy. It's just part of baseball. You do just
one thing; you suck it up and you go back out there again tomorrow
and you play.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it was that Clark was back in the lineup last night at
the Kingdome. His only concession to his injury was that he allowed
Oates to pencil him in at DH and not first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I despise DH'ing,'' Clark said. ``It drives me up the wall,
and I drive my teammates up the wall in the dugout. But it's better
than not playing at all.''
</P>
<P>
   I keep picturing a Clark poster I'd like to see. He'd be
standing there, leaning on his bat, with these arrows drawn in and
pointing to various body parts that have been battered and broken
over the years. His ribs, his knee, both elbows, his right leg,
from thigh to the tip of his toes, because of all the foul balls he
has ricocheted off it.
</P>
<P>
   He'd be wearing eye black, of course, and that sneer we've all
seen so often.
</P>
<P>
   There'd be a caption under it, too, something simple and to the
point.
</P>
<P>
   Hardball Player.
</P>
<P>
   This is my way of finally getting around to this conclusion:
Clark needs to be re-signed by the Rangers for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   I concede this somewhat reluctantly, because Clark and I have
had our ups and downs since he arrived in '94. At various times
he's stubborn, arrogant, insensitive and downright rude. He can be
impossible to talk to because he already thinks he knows everything
you've got to say. He should listen more and talk less.
</P>
<P>
   But he has had a remarkable renaissance of a season _ he'll
argue with that terminology, but it's true _ and the Rangers will
still need a first baseman next year.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, Clark, who enjoys living in the area and wants to
stay, will make it easy for Doug Melvin and the Rangers. Money, he
says, won't be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very flexible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds like he would be amenable to an incentive-laden
deal, maybe one-year with an option, allowing Melvin to concentrate
most of his resources on signing shortstop Royce Clayton and more
pitching. Randy Johnson and Todd Stottlemyre would be a good start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
