<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5775 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-MARINERS-     09-26 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-MARINERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS WIN AL WEST DESPITE BEING ROUTED BY MARINERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Eleven-run losses don't inspire hangovers.
</P>
<P>
   Champagne does, and it flowed and sprayed freely in The
Kingdome's visiting clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers _ despite last night's 15-4 loss to the Seattle
Mariners _ celebrated their second American League West title in
three seasons after the Anaheim Angels lost, 7-2, at Oakland,
eliminating themselves from contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the first champagne celebration we want to
have,'' Rangers second baseman Mark McLemore said. ``We want three
more just as good or better. We're going to enjoy this tonight and
then get back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is only step one,'' closer John Wetteland said. ``We'll
celebrate tonight, but there's a lot of unfinished business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers remain one game behind the Cleveland Indians, who
lost last night, for home-field advantage in one of the two
best-of-five, divisional playoff series. They would begin the
postseason Tuesday against the Yankees in New York based on the
league's standings entering today's games. If Texas ties or passes
Cleveland in the final two days, the Rangers will play Boston in
the divisional series, with the first two games in Arlington on
Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers players learned of the Angels' loss during the ninth
inning here last night. Several went to the clubhouse and began
celebrating while their teammates finished their last at-bat. The
scoreboard in the Kingdome stayed an inning or two behind the
Angels-Athletics game and did not reflect that it actually ended
with two innings remaining in the Rangers-Mariners game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was at my request,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
``Bucky (Dent) told me it was a final in the bottom of the seventh
or maybe the top of the eighth. But I wanted us to stay
professional right down to the end. I don't think it looks
professional to be high-fiving on the field in the middle of a
game, especially one we were losing big like that one.''
</P>
<P>
   As for any thought that the Rangers backed into the title,
McLemore said, ``We won the West in '98. That's all that counts. We
won more games than anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers won the West earlier this week with their three-game
sweep of the Angels in Anaheim. That gave the Rangers a three-game
lead in the AL West and reduced their magic number to two entering
this four-game series in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't a dry spot in the clubhouse last night when the
game did end. The players sprayed champagne all over the room and
all over each other. When the bubbly was gone, they did the same
with beer.
</P>
<P>
   Oates got it. General manager Doug Melvin got it. Club president
Tom Schieffer got it. Every player got it. Friends and strangers
got it.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Aaron Sele was trying to stay as dry as possible. Rick
Helling spotted him, grabbed him and doused him.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish-language broadcaster Luis Mayoral stayed on the outside,
hoping nobody would notice him. It didn't last. Someone grabbed him
with a bear hug, carried him to the middle of the clubhouse and he
was soaked.
</P>
<P>
   It many ways, it was a typical title-clinching celebration.
</P>
<P>
   In others, it was different.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, there was a sense of relief because it was the club's
first ever title. Last night, there might have been a slightly
different feel because of the way they won. The Rangers were tied
with the Angels on Monday, but they went into Anaheim and swept a
three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one feels pretty special because of the way we did it,''
first baseman Will Clark said. ``We won when we had to,
head-to-head with Anaheim. That's why it feels special.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners ensured that the Rangers would not clinch this
title with a victory at the Kingdome on the strength of their
four-run third and fourth innings.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Esteban Loaiza, who allowed six of those runs
during his three-inning appearance, likely will be banished to the
bullpen for the postseason after his fourth consecutive poor
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza surrendered a two-run double to center fielder Ken
Griffey Jr. _ who later hit his 56th home run this season off
left-hander Eric Gunderson during the sixth inning _ and
run-scoring base hits to second baseman David Bell and designated
hitter Edgar Martinez during the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Russ Davis and first baseman Raul Ibanez led off
the fourth inning with consecutive singles against Loaiza, and
manager Johnny Oates removed the right-hander and summoned
left-hander Greg Cadaret from the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Joe Oliver deposited Cadaret's third pitch into the
seats in right-center field for a three-run homer, and a
run-scoring single later in the inning by shortstop Alex Rodriguez
gave the Mariners an 8-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers did not experience such success against the
Mariners' Paul Abbott. The 30-year-old right-hander surrendered
four runs on two two-run homers during the seventh and ninth
innings by first baseman Lee Stevens. Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Todd Stottlemyre was removed as today's starter, with Eric
Gunderson to take his place. Rick Helling may or may not pitch an
inning or two over the next couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be ready to pitch in the first two games of the
playoffs, whether we're on the road against the Yankees or at home
against the Red Sox,'' Oates said. He said the Rangers will piece
their pitching tomorrow against the Mariners, and bring someone in,
probably Jonathan Johnson, to start Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
