<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS DRAW 3 MILLION _ FOR LAST TIME?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In good seasons and bad, there was one constant
with the Dodgers: Three million fans.
</P>
<P>
   They reached that number in Friday night's 3-2 victory over the
Milwaukee Brewers for a major-league record 13th time, but there is
a good chance it might also be the last.
</P>
<P>
   Next season, the club is nearly doubling its television coverage
for home games. The move is designed to generate revenue, but TV
traditionally hurts day-of-game sales and could jeopardize one of
baseball's more prestigious statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been concerns in the past whenever we've made
changes in our television package, but so far we're still at three
million,'' club president Bob Graziano said. ``We've considered
that this time. We used to use television at the start of a home
stand to boost interest. Now we will be televising more games and
think it will expand our fan base.''
</P>
<P>
   Next season, the Dodgers will show a whopping 80 games on Fox
Sports West 2, up from 41 this year. There also will be 50 games on
KTLA Channel 5 in 1999, including 15 home games.
</P>
<P>
   And there will be move next year to add more flexibility to the
club's ticket package that could influence season ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of buying season tickets for 81 games at a cost of
$4-5,000 per year for premium seats between the bases, fans can
pick and choose 10 or 20 games for far less.
</P>
<P>
   Among the packages being considered are a ``Home Run Derby''
theme that includes games with the Sammy Sosa's Chicago Cubs and
Mark McGwire's St. Louis Cardinals. Sosa and McGwire each set the
major league home run record this season.
</P>
<P>
   To make it more attractive, fans also can cancel games in those
packages and receive refunds, something they can't do with season
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Season ticket holder still have the No. 1 consideration on
location, and location is what we've found is the most important
thing to a season ticket holder'' Graziano said.
</P>
<P>
   There were 36,059 at Dodger Stadium on Friday and they saw
right-hander Ismael Valdes allow one unearned run and six hits in
eight innings to close out his season with an 11-10 record.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, who missed five weeks with a strained left-side muscle,
was coming off a terrible outing in San Francisco last Sunday. He
gave up seven runs and didn't get out of the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he got home runs from Mark Grudzielanek and rookie
Adrian Beltre after Brewers' left-hander Scott Woodall (7-9) took a
1-0 lead into the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek, who has just two homers in 49 games with the
Dodgers, hit Woodall's first pitch with two outs in the seventh. It
also scored rookie catcher Paul LoDuca, who opened the inning with
a single.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, playing the final week at third in place of Bobby
Bonilla, opened the eighth by hitting the first pitch from reliever
Al Reyes into the left-field pavilion for his seventh homer.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Shaw replaced Valdes to start the ninth and gave up three
hits, including an RBI single by Jeromy Burnitz. But Shaw recovered
to earn his 47th save, 24th with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Dodgers have not been part of the wild card race
for more than a month, fans still have been watching.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is the season ticket sales, which were at about
20,000 per game this year. The National League counts the number of
tickets sold rather than the number of persons who actually attend,
which often makes announced crowds sound much larger than they
really are.
</P>
<P>
   But the season ticket figure is down from 27,000 in the early
1990s. The Dodgers single season attendance record is 3,608,881,
set in 1982, the year after the club won the World Series. This
season they are fourth in the National League in attendance behind
Colorado, Arizona and Atlanta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
