<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX ATTACK WITH REINFORCEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn ripped his 39th home run early and bombed a double
late. Tim Wakefield earned his career-best 17th win. Mike Stanley
got some needed plate time. Trot Nixon had three hits, Keith
Mitchell a couple. Jimy Williams got to clear his bench in front of
the 34th Fenway Park sellout crowd of the year (32,644).
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yeah, the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox won that, too, beating up the Orioles, 8-3, Friday
night, 24 hours after they'd wrapped up the American League wild
card.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox picked up win No. 91 against 69 losses with their
fourth triumph in a row and fifth in six games on this homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra, John Valentin, Mike Benjamin, and several
others got the night off.
</P>
<P>
   With all wild-card challengers disposed of, the only thing left
to watch on the out-of-town scoreboard _ other than the
Sosa-McGwire updates, of course _ are the games in Minnesota and
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rangers, who played the Mariners in Seattle, tie
Cleveland, the Red Sox will open the playoffs in Texas Tuesday. If
Central champion Cleveland, which lost in Minnesota, can stay ahead
of the Rangers, the Red Sox open there.
</P>
<P>
   Got all that?
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Red Sox took advantage of errors by the
Orioles _ who came in playing highly touted defense _ and walks by
Baltimore pitchers, threw in a few timely hits, and now are
threatening to roll into the playoffs with some momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been playing good overall,'' Williams said, ``even when
at times the verdicts have not been in our favor. Basically, that's
what you're looking for, consistency. If we kept pitching good and
playing good defense and you put those three things together _
pitching, defense, and offense at the right time _ you have a very
good chance to win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield (17-8) took care of the bulk of the pitching, giving
up six hits over six innings, walking none, and striking out five
while exacting a little personal revenge from the Orioles. He had
lost his last three starts against them, most recently a 2-1
decision in July.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Davis led off the game with a single and Wakefield then
retired 11 straight _ mostly on high popups _ before Danny Clyburn
got to him for his first home run in the fourth. By then, the Red
Sox had scored four runs and were in control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The knuckleball felt very good, very consistent,'' Wakefield
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gotta love those popups.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very good sign,'' Wakefield said. ``They're not
hitting it solid.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Jason Varitek concurred: ``You can always tell when his
ball is moving well. You get a lot of popups and bad swings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles had plenty of both.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn homered in the first inning with Damon Buford on for a
2-0 lead and had a leadoff double in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit those balls hard,'' said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Both were deep to right-center.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn struck out twice in between his hits as his average rose
to .336 in his duel for the batting title with the Yankees' Bernie
Williams, who now leads with a .337 mark.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox brass, who met Friday and likely will confer through
the weekend to shape their playoff roster, may have a little more
to think about after Friday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon had the three hits, a career high, and scored a couple of
runs. Mitchell had a double, a single, and three RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just seeing it and swinging it, nothing big, nothing
major,'' Nixon said. ``We clinched it up last night and went out
there and had some fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley walked three times with little to swing at, reached on a
fielder's choice, and scored twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox followed Thursday's 18-hit effort with 11 against
five Oriole pitchers. The Orioles, who had committed 76 errors,
fewest in the majors, coming into the game, had four Friday night.
Their pitchers gave up eight walks.
</P>
<P>
   For Boston, Carlos Valdez, Carlos Reyes, and John Wasdin tossed
an inning apiece of relief. The only hit they allowed was Brady
Anderson's solo home run in the ninth off Wasdin.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox made quick work of Oriole newcomer Chris Fussell. He
was making the second start and third appearance of his career.
</P>
<P>
   It was a short one. He couldn't get out of the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox did most of their damage in the first. Quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Fussell struck out Donnie Sadler to start things off, and it
went downhill for him after that.
</P>
<P>
   Buford walked and Vaughn drilled a 3-1 pitch 420 feet deep to
right-center field, just over the Red Sox bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley walked and scored on Mitchell's grounder later in the
inning. The Sox got another run in the second when they knocked
Fussell out. After the Orioles had cut it to 4-2, Boston came up
with three runs in the fifth to pull away. Mitchell had a
run-scoring double, Varitek and Chris Snopek run-scoring singles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-98 0203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
