<DOCNO> NYT19980926.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5783 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DANSHAUGHNESSY-CO     09-26 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DANSHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 McGWIRE QUICKLY TIES UP SOSA  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ They are Coke and Pepsi, Russell and Chamberlain,
Lincoln and Douglas, Ali and Frazier, Burger King and McDonald's.
And with two games left (barring a playoff for the Cubs), Mark
McGwire and Sammy Sosa are tied, each with 66 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The best moment of Day 160 came at 8:37 CST Friday night when
both Sosa and McGwire were standing in their respective batter's
boxes at the same instant.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa had already homered at the Astrodome to take the lead in
the duel to see which of the two men (if not both) winds up owning
the all-time home run record. Now McGwire, trailing in the Great
Home Run Chase for all of 45 minutes, launched his 66th into the
left-field lower deck at Busch Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever winds up on top, nobody should be disappointed,''
McGwire said after the Cardinals' 6-5 victory over the Expos. ``You
can't. It's impossible. Whatever happens, after the last out on
Sunday, how can you ever think about walking with your head down?''
</P>
<P>
   Heads are high all across the Americas as even casual fans
strain to catch a video clip in an airport lounge or perhaps get
some news from the overhead ticker in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   It is 9 p.m. Has anyone homered yet?
</P>
<P>
   It is never going to get better than this, sports fans. The
greatest baseball season of them all is winding down in
near-perfect fashion. Two days remain _ maybe three for Sammy's
contending Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis manager Tony La Russa, never one given to gimmicks or
frivolity, finally came clean after Friday night's win and admitted
that the Cardinals are now playing with one thing in mind:
McGwire's home run chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taught that honesty is better,'' said the manager.
``Management may not like this, but as far as I'm concerned, Mark
McGwire and the home run chase is the most important thing in the
next two days.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire seemed embarrassed by the remark. He knows that Sosa _
locked in a wild wild-card chase, is playing for something
altogether different.
</P>
<P>
   There was some thought that McGwire might be done hitting homers
in 1998. He'd cranked No. 65 in Milwaukee Sunday, then was robbed
of No. 66 by a bad umpiring decision. When he spoke with the media
before playing the Expos, he sounded like a man who'd put his bat
in the rack for the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sosa cracked No. 66 in the fourth inning in the Astrodome
while McGwire was stalled at 65. The St. Louis crowd groaned when
the ``66'' went up next to Sosa's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look up there, but I knew,'' said McGwire. ``It's
pretty obvious from the crowd's reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Mac didn't stay second for long.
</P>
<P>
   It was the sixth inning in Houston and the fifth in St. Louis
when McGwire came up for his third plate appearance of the night,
his first against Expos righthander Shayne Bennett. A split screen
was needed. Standing in the press box in St. Louis, you didn't know
where to look. Sammy on TV or Mark live and in color?
</P>
<P>
   Happily, Sosa grounded out before McGwire saw his first pitch.
And McGwire didn't get cheated. He ripped at Bennett's first serve
and hit it high and far, into the third deck of Busch. Alas, it was
foul. Barely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was pretty close,'' said McGwire. ``I've had four
or five of those in the last week and I was thinking, `Not
again.'''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire ran the count to 1-2, then ripped another Bennett pitch,
this one fair, over the wall in left.
</P>
<P>
   There was a scramble in Section 282 (another Midwest homey gave
the ball back to McGwire in exchange for an autograph) and bedlam
throughout Busch. The Great Home Run Chase was tied. Again.
</P>
<P>
   How often does a man hit a foul home run, then follow it up with
a fair one? Almost never. Then again, no one ever hit 66 home runs
in a season before this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he hit that thing, I just wanted to stop right there,''
said La Russa. ``It was almost as good as 62'' _ the one that broke
Roger Maris's 37-year-old record.
</P>
<P>
   Truly, if Friday night had been the last night, it would have
been about perfect. But perhaps Saturday will be better than Friday
night. And perhaps Sunday will be better than Saturday. And maybe
Sosa will hit a Bobby Thomson playoff homer Monday to put the Cubs
in the Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   It just keeps getting better. To the finish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-98 0205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
