</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_TKACHUK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TKACHUK, COYOTES END FEUD  
 1-YEAR EXTENSION SETTLES HOLDOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB McMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Captain Coyote has something to howl about _ and this time, it's
of a positive nature.
</P>
<P>
   After months of on-again, off-again negotiations and some
unflattering name-calling on both sides, Keith Tkachuk and the
Coyotes finally agreed to end their summerlong feud. The team
announced late Friday that it had signed the power forward to a
one-year contract extension, effectively bringing to an end
Tkachuk's 14-day holdout.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms of the deal were not disclosed, but it is
believed the team significantly sweetened the final two years of
his current deal, worth $2.8 million this season and $3 million the
next, and then back-loaded the one-year extension with an enormous
salary, worth perhaps as much as $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk, the Coyotes' captain and leading scorer, had been
seeking a three-year extension worth more than $40 million. He told
``The Republic'' this week he would not report to the team unless a
new deal could be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased to sign Keith to a one-year contract,''
Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith said in a statement released by
the team. ``Keith is one of the premier power forwards in the game
today and we are excited about having him in the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal was done after Smith met for several hours in
Minneapolis with Tkachuk and his agent, Bob Murray. Coyotes Owner
Richard Burke also attended the day-long negotiating session.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk was still in Minneapolis and could not be reached for
comment, but the Coyotes released the following statement from him:
``I am extremely happy to be back with the team. I have always
stated that Phoenix is the city I love and want to play in. Now I
can put this behind me and concentrate on one thing, playing
hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so glad this is over with and we're coming back to
Phoenix,'' Tkachuk's wife, Chantal, said from the couple's summer
home near Boston. ``Yea! It's a great day! We're both so excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk, the first American-born player to ever record
back-to-back 50-goal seasons, which he accomplished in 1995-96 and
1996-97, is scheduled to practice with the Coyotes Monday morning
at the team's training facility in north Scottsdale. Afterward, he
will appear at a news conference with Smith to discuss the
extension and obviously, the acrimony that came beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the negotiating process, both Tkachuk and Smith
engaged in a war of words. Although it never got particularly
personal or nasty, there were bridges that almost were burned.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Smith infuriated Tkachuk with comments in The
Republic suggesting the Coyotes were a better team without Tkachuk.
``All we've been able to do with Keith Tkachuk is lose in the first
round of the playoffs,'' Smith was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk, who led the team with 40 goals and 66 points last
season, fired back with occasional salvos of his own. Among other
things, he inferred to Smith as a ``rookie GM'' who ``can't make up
his mind,'' and also called him ``a liar'' for not fulfilling what
Tkachuk said was a handshake promise to sign him to a new deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a bad relationship with the guy, but I don't know
if it will ever be the same with him again after some of this
(expletive),'' Tkachuk said last month, when talks broke off for
the umpteenth time.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming he reports to the team in decent shape _ Tkachuk has
said he's been working out daily in Boston _ he likely will
accompany the team to Minneapolis for the Coyotes' preseason game
there against the Dallas Stars on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
