</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SOSA-66HOMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA SEIZES LEAD WITH 66TH HOMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ For a guy who essentially conceded the race five days
ago, Sammy Sosa is still doing a pretty good impression of a home
run king.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs slugger temporarily seized the 1998 lead and all-time
record when he hit his 66th homer Friday night. But typical of this
historic duel that has evolved into a game of leapfrog, he soon had
company. Forty-five minutes later in St. Louis, Mark McGwire _ whom
Sosa had declared the likely champion Tuesday when he trailed the
Cardinals slugger by two and was in an 0-for-21 slump _ responded
with his 66th.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa did his damage in the fourth inning of a 6-2 loss to the
playoff-bound Houston Astros. It was the night's only comsolation
for the Cubs, who now find themselves in a three-way tie for the
National League wild card with the Mets and Giants entering the
final weekend of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more the merrier,'' quipped Cubs first baseman Mark Grace.
``We're still out there battling. We got our butts kicked tonight
by Houston. But we've still got a chance, so we'll be back there
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the wild-card race was incidental to the 51,831 fans who
showed up at the Astrodome Friday night. They came to see Sosa go
deep. And he obliged on his second trip to the plate, victimizing
Dominican countryman Jose Lima _ who has given up three of the 66 _
by sending an 0-1 pitch on a 462-foot ride into the third deck of
the left-center-field stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``He broke my bat the first time,'' said Sosa, who went 1 for 4
on the evening. ``But I vowed that I would be patient today. He
threw me an inside fastball and I got a good swing on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa was saluted with a standing ovation that lasted so long, he
finally came out of the dugout for a curtain call. But less than an
hour later, he had company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be still nice if we were tied,'' said Sosa after the
game. ``I feel great that (McGwire) hit 66 tonight. But you can't
say for sure. No matter what happens, Houston is not going to give
us anything.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the second time this season Sosa took over the home run
lead, only to see McGwire erase it before the day was out. On Aug.
19, Sosa hit No. 48. McGwire trumped him with his 48th and 49th.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't seem to bother Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see my face?'' he said, beaming, after Friday night's
game. ``I'm not here to chase anybody. I'm here to do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Some have wondered whether Lima, Sosa's close friend, is making
that job easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are friends,'' said Sosa before the game. ``But not on the
ball field.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he paid tribute to Lima, who wound up going seven
innings for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to give credit to Lima,'' said Sosa. ``I got him once.
He got me. He pitched a great game. I don't like losing. But it's a
great situation to be in _ to have a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubs manager Jim Riggleman applauded his right fielder for
trying to lead the charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough challenge for Sosa,'' he said. ``The team and
all the city of Chicago are indebted for what he's done. We're
happy he got another one. But as a team, we're really more focused
on the score of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In a pregame media session, Sosa had more than home runs on his
mind. He used the forum to plead for financial assistance for
victims of Hurricane Georges, which has ravaged Puerto Rico, Cuba,
and the Dominican. Sosa gave more than lip service to the cause. In
conjunction with the Cubs, he announced that donations would be
accepted for the Sammy Sosa Charity Foundation to help sponsor a
relief effort. Additionally, he announced that if he was able to
gain possession of home run ball No. 62, with which he became the
second man to break Roger Maris's 37-year-old record, he would put
it up for auction, with all the proceeds going to the victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
