<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5801 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-     09-26 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS ELIMINATED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Not many teams pop open the champagne bottles after a
15-4 defeat, but the Texas Rangers did Friday night. And they had
the Oakland A's to thank for it.
</P>
<P>
   Because the A's beat the Angels 7-2 before 22,861 at the Oakland
Coliseum, the Rangers were able to celebrate the AL West crown in
the eighth inning of their blowout loss to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who swept three from the Angels in Anaheim prior to
the season-ending four-game series, are three games up on the
Angels with two to play.
</P>
<P>
   It was exasperating for the Angels to watch the scoreboard as
the Mariners opened up a big lead on the Rangers. The Angels
couldn't do anything with A's starter Kenny Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers (16-8) pitched his seventh complete game of the season,
more than double that of the entire Angels staff (three). He gave
up seven hits, walked two and struck out six, improving to 11-0 at
home this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was taunting us,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said of the
scoreboard. ``The bigger lead (Seattle) got, the more frustrated we
got, certainly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there's any consolation in us winning and
Texas winning (instead). I don't think that helps the situation
out. We've had a remarkable year in a lot of ways. A lot of people
stepped up. The team did things nobody expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly people will say it was another year we couldn't get
it done at the end. I disagree with that. We got a lot of things
from a lot of people. We're disappointed, but we're professionals.
What we do now is regroup and take a look at what we need to do to
get better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels could manage only a two-run double by Troy Glaus in
the fifth inning off Rogers, frustrating them and leaving them
empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over and it's not a good feeling,'' said Darin Erstad,
who did not play Friday. ``We didn't get the job done. There are
two reasons why you play _ to play hard and to win. And if you
don't win, I don't consider that getting the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a somber moment,'' Tim Salmon said. ``The possibility (of
winning the division) was very real. We played hard for seven
months or whatever it was, and all of a sudden you aren't playing
for anything anymore. It's kind of sad now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels fell behind early, making their task at hand even
more difficult. The A's took a 4-0 lead after four innings against
Angels starter Omar Olivares (9-9).
</P>
<P>
   The Angels cut it to 4-2 in the fifth on Glaus' double, but that
was as close as they'd get. Ben Grieve doubled in two in the fifth
and A.J. Hinch singled in the A's final run in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers became the first pitcher to go 11-0 at home in a season
since Orel Hershiser did it for the Dodgers in 1985, and the first
American League pitcher ever to go undefeated at home with a
minimum of 11 decisions. The major-league record is 12-0 by Billy
Pierce of the Giants in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers has been tough on the Angels throughout his career. He's
2-0 this year and 11-5 in his career, including a perfect game
while he pitched for the Rangers in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything to be ashamed about,'' Olivares
said. ``We gave it our all for 160 games and came pretty close. In
our hearts we know we gave it all we had. I'm going to go home
feeling proud of what I did and what everyone in this room did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to some players today and one thing that was brought
up is it's not just the games this month that are important, it's
the games all year long,'' Collins said. ``You have to realize
games in April and May are just as important as September. As I was
walking around today I heard guys talking about different games
that got away early in the year. But I'm real proud of them. We'll
be back. I still think we've got good young players and we'll be in
it for a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
