<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMBING-NUKE-SUSPECT-     09-26 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBING-NUKE-SUSPECT-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIN LADEN GROUP TRIED TO DEVELOP NUCLEAR WEAPONS, U.S. SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs for additions and refinements.)   (See related: KENYA-BOMBING)  
(lh) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal authorities said Friday that a man they described as a
senior deputy to Osama bin Laden, the Saudi exile suspected in last
month's bombings of two U.S. embassies in Africa, tried on behalf
of the bin Laden group in 1993 to obtain materials that could be
used to develop nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the authorities cited a document that they related
to a proposed purchase of enriched uranium. But they did not say
whether the group ever obtained the uranium.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the nuclear allegation, the authorities asserted that
the bin Laden group had worked with Iran and with the Sudanese
ruling party to oppose the United States, and they suggested that
the United States had penetrated the bin Laden organization in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations are contained in court papers unsealed Friday
that accused Mamdouh Mahmud Salim of conspiracy to murder and to
use weapons of mass destruction against Americans stationed outside
the United States, in Saudi Arabia, Yemen and Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   Salim was arrested in Munich, Germany, about 10 days ago, after
flying there from Sudan, and Washington said Friday that it would
seek his extradition.
</P>
<P>
   In the court papers, the government also asserted for the first
time that there was a ``working agreement'' among bin Laden, Iran
and the National Islamic Front of Sudan to ``work together against
the United States, Israel and the West.'' The front is the ruling
party in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Members of bin Laden's organization, Al Qaeda, sent emissaries
to Iran and some of its members received explosives training in
Lebanon from Hezbollah, the terrorist group backed by Iran,
prosecutors said in court papers filed in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The government also said that during the time when the agreement
with Iran and Sudan was reportedly being negotiated, Salim _ who is
described in the document as one of the founders of Al Qaeda _ met
with an Iranian religious official in Khartoum and traveled with Al
Qaeda members to Teheran to arrange for training in the use of
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations against Iran come at a sensitive time because
Afghanistan has reportedly given bin Laden a safe haven, and Iran
and the Taliban rulers in Afghanistan are at loggerheads about
Iran's support for armed militias opposing the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint against Salim was signed by an FBI agent, Daniel
J. Coleman, and was approved by two federal prosecutors, Patrick J.
Fitzgerald and Kenneth M. Karas, and was signed by a federal
magistrate judge on Sept. 14. Any indictment based on the complaint
must be approved by a grand jury.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In unsealing the charges against Salim, who is being held in
Germany pending his extradition. U.S. authorities suggested that
the investigation of bin Laden and Al Qaeda continues on two
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   One is focused on the bombings of the U.S. embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania on Aug. 7, in which more than 250 people were killed,
including 12 Americans in Nairobi. Bin Laden's agents are suspected
in the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The other track is directed at bin Laden's organization itself
and its possible role in other acts of terrorism, like the attacks
on U.S. and U.N. forces in Somalia in 1993 and early 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities also said Friday that as early as 1996, the FBI
had won the cooperation of a person who described himself as a
terrorist in Al Qaeda and obtained extensive information from him
about the group.
</P>
<P>
   The source was not identified, but was described in court papers
as ``a member of Al Qaeda for a number of years'' and ``personally
familiar'' with bin Laden and Salim. The document said the person
``has admitted to participating in terrorist activity against
American interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that description, there was no information about whether
the Government had actually penetrated the group and won the
cooperation of an active member, or whether the source had left Al
Qaeda.
</P>
<P>
   The document says that information from this source was provided
to the FBI in 1996, raising questions about how much the government
knew about the bin Laden group before the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph A. Valiquette, a spokesman for the FBI in New York, said
he could not comment beyond what was in the court complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint indicates how much the authorities have learned
about Al Qaeda's history and command. The document says that bin
Laden's group is highly organized and includes a majlis al shura,
or consultation council, which discusses and approves all major
undertakings, including terrorist operations and fatwas, which are
death sentences against anyone who is found to have offended Islam.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities did not specify when bin Laden's group reached
its agreement with Iran and the Sudanese party, saying only that
the arrangement was made while Al Qaeda was based in Sudan, between
1991 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Citing information from the confidential source, the authorities
said that as early as 1992, bin Laden and other ranking members of
Al Qaeda decided that the group ``should put aside its differences
with Shiite Muslim terrorist organizations, including the
government of Iran and its affiliated terrorist group Hezbollah, to
cooperate against its perceived common enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Al Qaeda members also began to provide training to
Somali tribes opposed to the United Nation's role there, the
complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Friday night how the allegations of Iranian
involvement with bin Laden would affect U.S. policy toward Iran,
particularly as Iran moves to improve its relations with the West.
</P>
<P>
   It is evident that the United States has had the Iranian
information since 1996, when the confidential source first provided
the information to the bureau, the complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   Such allegations come at a time when Washington is rounding up
people associated with the suspected network of bin Laden, yet is
eager not to provoke new acts of terrorism. It is apprehensive
about retaliation after the missile strikes against bin Laden's
camps in Afghanistan and a suspected chemical weapons plant in
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are said to have named bin Laden in a sealed
indictment last spring on terrorist charges. The authorities
asserted Friday that bin Laden privately encouraged associates to
make specific attacks against U.S. military forces in Africa and
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first indication that bin Laden issued such orders
directly to his associates, rather than through widely publicized
fatwas against the United States. Prosecutors may be moving closer
to being able to show that he ordered the embassy attacks as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-98 0233EDT &QL; 
