<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5812 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      09-26 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 Griffey hits HR milestone in M's win, but Texas clinches  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Ken Griffey Jr. might appreciate you more than you
think.
</P>
<P>
   Draped along the facing of the right-field second deck on Fan
Appreciation Night at the Kingdome was a bull's-eye surrounded by
the words ``Hit It Here, Junior.''
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, Griffey did that one tier better, punishing
the first pitch from Texas Rangers reliever Eric Gunderson into the
third deck to make him the youngest player in major legue history
to reach 350 career home runs. The three-run blast was the
highlight for 39,325 fans who saw the M's beat Texas, 15-4.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night wasn't a total loss for the Rangers, though. They
clinched their second American League West title in three years
thanks to a 7-2 loss in Oakland by the second-place Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   At age 28 years and 308 days, Griffey put himself ahead of seven
Hall of Famers on the fastest-to-350 track. The second-youngest is
Jimmie Foxx (29 years, 216 days) and the next six are Eddie
Mathews, Mickey Mantle, Mel Ott, Hank Aaron, Frank Robinson and
Harmon Killebrew. The fewest career homers any of them hit was
Ott's 511.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are things you don't really think about doing,'' Griffey
said. ``You don't sit at home when you're a kid and say, `I want to
hit 350 faster than anybody.' You just want to go out there and
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thinking about hitting a home run in that situation,
because I knew Gar (Edgar Martinez) was behind me and he needed one
(run batted in to reach 100). I got to home plate, turned around,
looked at Gar and said, `I'm sorry. I didn't mean to do that.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been doing it all year,'' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez got that 100th RBI on a double in the eighth inning,
giving him at least 100 in each of the past four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks better than 99,'' Martinez said. ``So I wanted to get
it. It was important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   And though he didn't grow up dreaming of it, the 350th homer was
meaningful to Griffey, too. It bounced out of the stands and back
onto the field, and Griffey pointed for it during his trot.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to keep it, but said he probably would not hand it
over to the Hall of Fame if Cooperstown came calling. That's
4-year-old Trey Griffey's call.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family comes first,'' Griffey said. ``I'll probably end up
giving that one to Trey. I'll ask him tomorrow morning when he gets
up.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball will be a get-well gift for the junior Junior, who is
fine but still smarting after being hit in the head with a golf
club on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Family, after all, matters more to Griffey than his milestones.
Of all his September achievements, Griffey said the one that links
him with his father is the most important. His 54th homer on
Thursday, which gave him 500 combined with Ken Sr., ``stands out
the most.''
</P>
<P>
   But the other stuff isn't bad. Since Sept. 7, Griffey has become
the third player in history with consecutive 50-homer seasons, the
third to couple 50 homers with 20 stolen bases and the third with
three consecutive 140-RBI seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's homer also tied a record Griffey already shared with
fellow Donora, Pa., native Stan Musial. It was Griffey's 21st off a
left-handed pitcher, tying the season mark for a left-handed hitter
set by Musial in 1949 and equaled by Griffey in '96.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the family connection: Griffey hits left-handers so well
because he grew up taking batting practice off his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad's left-handed,'' Griffey said. ``So I had no idea there
was a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey also got his wish to have the Rangers celebrate a
division title in their clubhouse, not on his field.
</P>
<P>
   Winning by losing is a familiar thing for the Rangers, who also
did it in 1996. The Rangers were in the midst of a 15-inning loss
in '96 when they found out they had won the first title in their
25-year history courtesy of a loss by the second-place M's.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't stop the spirits from flowing in the visiting
clubhouse. The Rangers, who trailed the Angels for much of the
summer, won eight of their last 10 before Friday's clinching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perseverance of this ballclub,'' said Rangers manager
Johnny Oates, pointing to his team's greatest strength. ``It just
seemed like we never really got it going. We'd win two or three
games in a row, then we'd lose two or three. (But) here at the end,
we persevered and got close and finally got it going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
