A5846 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-TAXES-REVIEW     09-26 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TAXES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANGER: A TANGLED WEB OF TAXES 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(previously budgeted as INTERNET-REGULATE-REVIEW) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Michael Leavitt was visiting California from Utah a
few months back, and while staying at a beach house used his laptop
computer to shop over the Internet. He accessed a website, made his
selections and charged the bill _ $44.50 plus $2.49 for shipping _
to his credit card.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not pay sales tax. That bothered him because, as
governor of Utah, Leavitt is acutely aware of how reliant states
are on sales taxes. And he has given considerable thought to the
looming problems _ for states, the economy and consumers _ of
relying on traditional tax systems in a world in which Internet
commerce is starting to change the way people shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which states could logically and reasonably have argued that
they should receive the benefits of that tax?'' Leavitt asked about
his purchase. ``California? I was sitting in California when I made
the transaction. New York? New York was where the home page was
resident and where the company was located. But the goods were
packaged and shipped from a warehouse in New Jersey, and they were
shipped to Utah, where I used them.''
</P>
<P>
   Governments have long grappled with how, if at all, they should
regulate the global flow of images and information over the
Internet, seeking to balance concerns about free speech, for
example, with those about pornography. But only recently have
policy-makers in Washington, in state capitals and around the world
begun to confront the economic implications of a new retail
marketplace that recognizes no political or geographical
boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Almost by the day, the new medium is showing its potential for
rapid growth. At Amazon.com, the online bookseller, the latest
chapter in President Clinton's woes led to a surge of orders for
the book version of Kenneth Starr's report to Congress and then for
the video of Clinton's grand jury appearance (both briefly topped
Stephen King's latest on the company's best seller list). Catalog
companies are increasingly giving customers the option to place
orders over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a major economic force here,'' said Ira Magaziner,
who heads the Clinton administration's Internet policy team. ``It's
just beginning to reach the consumer, and it's going to be huge.
The question is, how do we create an environment that will allow it
to flourish and also will take care of all the side effects that
will arise?''
</P>
<P>
   The issues are sweeping. Where does a transaction take place
when buyer and seller can be defined to be in multiple locations?
Will the borderless nature of the Internet force governments
further down a road that has already led them to drop trade
barriers, harmonize tax policies and form currency unions?
</P>
<P>
   On a more immediate level, many governors and state legislatures
are convinced that such commerce will present in greatly magnified
form the same problem they have faced for years with the L.L. Beans
of the world that sell by phone and mail from catalogs: Although
consumers are technically liable for sales taxes, companies have to
collect taxes only in states where they keep a physical presence.
Although some merchants collect the tax even where they are not
required to do so, most do not.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble's barnesandnoble.com, another online bookseller,
automatically adds sales tax to orders being shipped to New York,
where it has its corporate headquarters; New Jersey, where it has
its distribution center, and Virginia, where its computer operation
is based. Orders elsewhere go untaxed.
</P>
<P>
   The lost revenue for states is relatively trivial now, but could
mount substantially in coming years as the volume of business on
the Internet grows. Though estimates vary widely, some analysts see
the electronic market growing to hundreds of billions of dollars
annually within the next decade, from next to nothing a few years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   By early in the next decade, states could be losing up to $12
billion a year, according to the National Governors' Association.
That would be a big chunk of state sales tax revenue, which last
year totaled $150 billion, and would be three times what states say
they lose each year because of out-of-state mail-order purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The states are also under pressure from traditional retailers,
who see their Internet competitors as operating in a tax-free zone
that will draw customers away from Main Street and the mall.
</P>
<P>
   From the perspective of technology companies and online service
providers, the issue is whether they will become a tempting target
for new taxes, or the object of discriminatory policies intended to
benefit traditional retailers. A tax free-for-all, they and their
supporters warn, will stifle the new marketplace and deny its
economic benefits to the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is incumbent upon us to get it right so that we do not
allow a feeding frenzy by state and local tax collectors across the
world to turn the information superhighway into an empty
21st-century toll road,'' said Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts suggested the problem can be solved by an agreement
among the states to levy taxes based on residence and then creating
software that would automatically add the appropriate amount to any
Internet purchase as part of the credit card billing process.
</P>
<P>
   Such a system could also automatically route the tax to the
proper state.
</P>
<P>
   But getting the balance right between nurturing the new medium
and not hurting states and traditional retailers is no easy
proposition.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, the Senate is debating a bill cosponsored by Wyden
that would establish a two-year moratorium on any new taxes that
would treat Internet commerce differently from traditional
retailing, while establishing a commission to sort out the sales
tax issue. A similar bill passed the House in June.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's increasing interest has made the states nervous.
Some governors fear that the growth of Internet commerce will
encourage the federal government to create and administer a
consistent sales tax system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRS will say, we'll collect it, and Congress will say,
we'll appropriate it,'' said Leavitt, a Republican. ``We'll have
taxes now collected and spent by local governments collected and
spent by the federal government. That's a massive shift in power.''
</P>
<P>
   Another concern in the technology industry and in Washington is
that other countries could slap duties, tariffs or other trade
barriers on international Internet transactions, either to raise
revenue or protect their domestic industries, and create new taxes
for transactions within their borders. The Clinton administration
has already raised the issue at the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governments around the world are beginning to understand the
power of this medium, and it's something a lot of people are
wrestling with,'' said Ben Boyd, a spokesman for
barnesandnoble.com. ``It's a new medium and you need to look at
everything through new lenses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
