<P>
   The Photo-Graphics editor is Steffen Kaplan
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 603-1036
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: steffen(at)nytimes.com
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TECHNICAL PROBLEMS: &LR;  Peter Trigg
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (212) 499-3332.
</P>
<P>
   Pager: (800) 946-4645 (PIN 599-4539).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: triggp(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KENYA-BOMB-SUSPECT (Nairobi, Kenya) _ His business card said he
was the director of Africa Help, a nongovernmental relief
organization, and he told friends that he supplemented his income
by trading in precious stones. That was the public face here of
Wahid el Hage. Out of the public eye, according to recent federal
indictments, el Hage was a leader in the Kenyan branch of a
terrorist organization, Al Queda, which is run by Osama bin Laden,
the man believed to be the mastermind behind last month's bombings
of the American Embassies here and in neighboring Tanzania. By
Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   BALKAN-PEACE-BRIGADE (Skopje, Macedonia) _ Seven southeastern
European countries agreed Saturday to create a multinational
military force that could be used for peacekeeping or aid
operations in the Balkans and elsewhere. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-CHANGE (Berlin) _ Change is not lightly accepted in a
country where stability is paramount, and as Germany prepares to
vote Sunday in national elections it appears gripped by last-minute
doubts over whether the time has come to end the era of Chancellor
Helmut Kohl. For months, Kohl has trailed his Social Democratic
challenger, Gerhard Schroeder But with a relentless conviction,
Kohl has closed the gap to the point where pollsters say any
outcome is possible. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BANKS (Tokyo) _ Japan's governing party and the opposition
patched up a basic agreement Saturday on legislation to revive the
banking system. The latest agreement, if it sticks, may dispel
concerns that Japan's political paralysis will continue to hobble
its economy. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-LESOTHO (Johannesburg, South Africa _ Probably the
biggest blunder South Africa made in invading the tiny kingdom of
Lesotho on Tuesday was a military one _ sending fewer than half the
soldiers it ultimately needed. But it is hard to say; the list of
blunders is so long. An analysis. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   MACAU-CHINA (Macau) _ For years, the looming reversion of this
Portuguese colony to China has been little remarked on and largely
forgotten _ a bit of colonial housekeeping lost in the wake of Hong
Kong's momentous handover from Britain. But now, this other
handover is suddenly generating some drama of its own. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-LOGGING-BAN (Lixian, China) _ Stunned by this summer's
devastating floods along the Yangtze River, which experts said were
intensified because slopes far upstream had been stripped bare,
China has banned cutting of the old-growth forests that once formed
a rich green carpet over these mountains. No trees were to be cut
after Sept. 1, and all logs must be trucked to timber yards by Oct.
31. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-KOSOVO (Urosevac, Yugoslavia) _ Human rights officials say
Serbian authorities are using arbitrary arrests and torture to warn
ethnic Albanian civilians to stop supporting a separatist guerrilla
force fighting for the independence of Serbia's Kosovo province. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   With YUGO-KOSOVO-WARN.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN-OPIUM _ Bad weather and tensions with neighboring
Iran have slashed the opium production of Afghanistan and hampered
its opium exports for European heroin markets, according to a new
U.N. survey. By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND-MERIWETHER _ Wall Street, often hard-nosed and
cynical, was utterly dazzled by John Meriwether. He was viewed as a
bond trader with a Midas touch, a mathematician of genius who saw
gold nuggets in markets where others saw only sand. So when
Long-Term Capital fell from grace last week, that the glittering
Meriwether image toppled with it. By Diana B. Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-INSURE-LAWSUIT (Washington) _ When Mark Covington drives
his 1992 Chevy Cavalier at night, the beam of the left headlight
wobbles across the road, and in daylight, the red paint on the hood
shows an odd ridge on the left side. He blames his insurance
company: After his wife crashed the car into the back of a pickup
in April, he said, he took the car to one of the best body shops in
Laurel, Miss., but the shop had to use generic parts. ``State Farm
just absolutely refused to put GM parts on it,'' Covington said.
Lawyers are seeking to add him to a large class-action suit against
State Farm. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   HEART-STUDY-GALA (Framingham, Mass.) _ If all the Americans who
owe some of the length or quality of their lives to the Framingham
Heart Study were to express their gratitude by attending its 50th
anniversary gala on Sunday afternoon, the auditorium would need
millions upon millions of folding chairs. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-HOUSE-RACE (Boulder, Colo.) _ Could Boulder, the liberal
lighthouse of the Rockies, send to Congress _ a Republican? For
nearly a quarter century, Colorado's Second District has been a
safe seat for Democrats. But now the Republicans have fielded
Robert D. Greenlee, a moderate who favors abortion rights and
enjoys a wide following as Boulder's first Republican Mayor since
1971. For the Democrats, Mark Udall, who is in his first term as a
state representative, is mounting what appears to be an equally
strong candidacy. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-STUDENTS _ American colleges and universities, long the
world leaders in attracting international students, are seeing the
decline of their dominance, government analysts and education
officials reported on Thursday at a conference in Washington. By
William H. Honan.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-COURTHOUSE (Boston) _ The new federal courthouse that
opened for business on a spectacular waterfront site here last week
is in many ways the first of its kind in modern judicial
architecture: a building designed to welcome rather than
intimidate, to invite the public to stop by for a meal, an art
exhibit, a film festival, a chamber music concert or a stroll
through the new two-acre ``harbor park'' that surrounds the
building. By Linda Greenhouse. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-UNION-FRAUD _ A court-appointed monitor has found
widespread financial wrongdoing in the Hotel Employees and
Restaurant Employees Union, one that has long been linked to
organized crime, attacking its former president in particular for
using union money for personal activities, like flying his wife to
Palm Springs, Calif. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS _ Short political items for around the nation.
By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TAXCUT-SHOWDOWN (Washington) _ Brushing aside a veto threat from
President Clinton, the House passed an $80 billion Republican tax
cut Saturday that would be paid for by projected federal budget
surpluses. The vote put Republicans a step closer to a politically
charged election-year showdown with the White House and
congressional Democrats over an issue that both sides believe will
play to their advantage. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE (Washington) _ Just three months before a new era in
the history of Medicare is to begin, members of Congress and health
policy experts are expressing alarm that the federal Medicare
agency cannot make many of the changes scheduled to take effect
over the next two years. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RELATIONSHIPS (Washington) _ To meet Bill Clinton is to
like him, even his enemies agree. But to know him is not
necessarily to love him, even his friends acknowledge. By Todd S.
Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-REPUBS (Washington) _ Republicans in Congress insist
that they will not be deterred in their investigation of President
Clinton by polls showing the public's disapproval. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN _ Bob Herbert examines the question of medical
privacy rights.
</P>
