<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Sept. 27, moved Saturday in the `a' category.
</P>
<P>
   This final budget adds FUND-BAILOUT-REVIEW and
CLINTON-STARR-REVIEW.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-REGULATE-REVIEW is now INTERNET-TAXES-REVIEW.
SEX-DEFINE-REVIEW is now BIBLE-ADULTERY-REVIEW.
</P>
<P>
   MORAL-REVIEW _ President Clinton's admitted immoral behavior has
thrust to the forefront a fundamental question about the meaning of
the American presidency: Should the president be a moral leader?
And if so, what is a moral leader? Contrasting themselves with
Clinton, candidates around the country are declaring that they are
virtue personified. They are emphasizing their families and the
values by which they live. They are making the point, in essence,
that moral leaders are role models. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-TAXES-REVIEW _ Only recently have policy-makers in
Washington, in state capitals and around the world begun to
confront the economic implications of a new retail marketplace that
recognizes no political or geographical boundaries. The issues are
sweeping. Where does a transaction take place when buyer and seller
can be defined to be in multiple locations? Will the borderless
nature of the Internet force governments further down a road that
has already led them to drop trade barriers, harmonize tax policies
and form currency unions? By Richard W. Stevenson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIBLE-ADULTERY-REVIEW _ President Clinton has tried to
distinguish between ``sexual relations'' and oral sex. That isn't a
distinction most Americans might make, and it certainly isn't one
the Bible focuses on in defining sexual sin. The Bible does single
out adultery for special attention in the 10 Commandments _ but
defines it in a way that might surprise many people. By Gustav
Niebuhr. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ENABLERS-REVIEW _ A nation of Clinton Enablers?'' a
headline in The New York Post queried. ``We have all been enablers
for Bill Clinton,'' declared Time magazine. Last week, an editorial
in this newspaper spoke of Clinton's ``documentably dysfunctional
personality'' and warned that ``we must not become a nation of
enablers.'' In a recent speech, the television evangelist (and
sometime Clinton counselor) Robert Schuller asserted that ``we all
share part of the shame'' for stubbornly high public approval
ratings that have enabled Clinton so far to avoid confronting the
problem of his sexual behavior. By Joe Sharkey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PUNISH-REVIEW _ By now, virtually no one in the capital
contends that President Clinton shouldn't be punished for his
deceptions in the Lewinsky affair. But what to call the punishment?
By Todd S. Purdum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SAFETY-REVIEW _ The American classroom today echoes with
dire warnings about dangers and evils that seemingly lurk
everywhere, from marijuana peddlers to child molesters. The old
notion of sticking to basic education, in the view of some safety
advocates, belongs in a dreamily outdated age of innocent, white
picket-fence childhoods. What good are the three Rs, after all, to
a child trapped in the trunk of an abductor's car, a scenario
actually discussed in some child safety programs around the nation.
By Dirk Johnson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KURDS-REVIEW _ The Kurdistan Workers' Party, which is fighting
to create a Kurdish homeland in southeastern Turkey, has offered a
cease-fire. The party leader, Abdullah Ocalan, said his forces
would not attack Turkish troops as long as troops did not attack
them. Ocalan's offer, like at least three others he has made in
recent years, fell on deaf ears. The Turkish military, which does
not take orders from civilians, refused to budge from its long-held
view that negotiating with ``separatist terrorists'' is
unthinkable. By Stephen Kinzer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXERCISE-REVIEW _ Exercise requires metabolism, and metabolism
generates free radicals, those harmful reactive chemicals that
vitamin pills and other supplements are said to combat. The notion
that vigorous sports may actually be bad for you is hardly new or
illogical. Every tale of a former football player with brain damage
or bad knees can reinforce a popular notion that a life committed
to strenuous athletics carries bodily stress to unhealthy levels.
But there is no evidence that exercise in itself reduces life span.
By Nicholas Wade. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUND-BAILOUT-REVIEW _ Since when does the Federal Reserve Bank
broker a bailout of an investment firm that was a victim of nothing
more than its own bad judgment? An excellent question and one that
policy-makers in troubled nations around the world may well be
scratching their heads over for some time. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR-REVIEW _ The banality of legal: boring in on a
scandal. Excerpts from raw documentary evidence submitted by Ken
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
