<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980926.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5863 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-ART-590-2TAK     09-26 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-ART-590-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K AND OTHER WOES HAMPER MEDICARE CHANGES MANDATED BY CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just three months before a new era in the history
of Medicare is to begin, members of Congress and health-policy
experts are expressing alarm that the federal Medicare agency
cannot make many of the changes scheduled to take effect over the
next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmed with new responsibilities, federal health officials
say they will miss statutory deadlines for some of the changes,
required by the 1997 budget law, which was adopted with bipartisan
support. The changes are intended to save money and to modernize
Medicare by opening the government program to a wider range of
private health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, members of a federal advisory commission studying how
to preserve Medicare for the baby boom generation say they worry
that some of the more attractive policy options under consideration
may prove unworkable for a similar reason: They cannot be carried
out in a timely way.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans complain that Medicare officials have been dragging
their feet, even though President Clinton himself proposed many of
the changes enacted. Administration officials say they have made
great efforts to carry out the law and have met most deadlines, but
now have more urgent tasks: fixing computers to cope with the year
2000. In computers that use two digits to indicate the year, 2000
is often indistinguishable from 1900.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, it is clear that Congress overestimated the
agency's ability to make hundreds of complex changes in a health
insurance program created 33 years ago on the model of Blue Cross
and Blue Shield plans.
</P>
<P>
   William Scanlon, director of health care studies at the General
Accounting Office, a nonpartisan investigative arm of Congress,
said the Medicare agency's new duties ``appear to be outstripping
its capacity to manage its existing workload.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency in question, the Health Care Financing
Administration, is swamped with work.
</P>
<P>
   In a report to be issued next month, the GAO says that Medicare
officials are ``severely behind schedule'' in fixing and testing
their computer systems. The draft report, requested by the Senate
Special Committee on Aging, says, ``It is highly unlikely that all
of the Medicare systems will be compliant in time to insure the
delivery of uninterrupted benefits and services into the year
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written response to the auditors, HCFA Administrator
Nancy-Ann Min DeParle said her agency ``got a late start'' on
renovating computers, but was making ``credible progress.''
Moreover, she said, the agency has ``postponed important projects,
including activities required by the Balanced Budget Act'' of 1997,
to avoid diverting resources from its year 2000 work.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare and Medicaid benefit payments have increased 44 percent
in the last five years, to $315 billion in 1998. But the agency's
budget for people and equipment to operate these programs has been
relatively flat, around $2.2 billion a year, and the number of
employees has actually declined, to 3,942 from 4,272. Medicare
officials say they can do more with less because the agency is more
productive.
</P>
<P>
   But the delays in carrying out the 1997 law will affect Medicare
beneficiaries. One of the provisions being delayed would reduce the
amounts, known as co-insurance, that elderly people pay for
hospital outpatient services like diagnostic tests, cataract
surgery and hernia operations. Other delays will prolong the use of
an interim payment system for home health care, which is prompting
many home health agencies to cut back services to the elderly.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A new Medicare benefit for people with diabetes has been partly
carried out; patients can get coverage for blood-testing supplies
and equipment and monitors, but expanded coverage for the education
and training of people with diabetes has been delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., chairman of the Health Subcommittee
of the House Ways and Means Committee, expressed the frustration of
many lawmakers when he told a Medicare official at a public hearing
the other day: ``You have added a new parameter. We come up with
what we believe is a proper policy, often based on your
recommendations. Then after it's enacted into law, you tell us you
can't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Roth, R-Del., chairman of the Finance Committee,
said he was ``very, very disappointed'' by the delays.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare officials have never had so many changes to make at
once. The 1997 budget law created a half-dozen new health insurance
options for the elderly, under an initiative known as
Medicare(plus)Choice, which is supposed to begin Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But the program is off to a slow start, with just a few private
health plans submitting applications to sell new products.
</P>
<P>
   The same law radically changed the formulas used to pay home
health care agencies, hospital outpatient departments, ambulance
companies, physical therapists, nursing homes, health maintenance
organizations and other health care providers under Medicare. Under
the law, these changes are supposed to take effect in the next two
years.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Congress created a major new health insurance
program for children, supervised by the HCFA. And the agency is
struggling to enforce a 1996 law, the Health Insurance Portability
and Accountability Act, which guaranteed coverage for millions of
Americans who lose or change their jobs. Under this law, the agency
has unexpectedly found itself with a new role: directly regulating
private health insurance in California and four other states that
have yet to adopt the federal standards.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., a co-author of the 1996 law,
said the agency ``lacks the institutional expertise to deal with
private insurance issues'' and needed more employees to combat
``price gouging'' by insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Epstein, co-founder of a law firm that specializes in
health care issues, said, ``The people at the Health Care Financing
Administration are dedicated, hard-working people, but they have
been overwhelmed with the tasks that have been given to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Another health care lawyer, Joel Hamme, said, ``It was naive for
Congress to think that it could load a huge number of tasks on this
agency and expect the work to be completed in a timely way.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare handles 900 million claims a year, double the number a
decade ago. Changes in payment policy all require changes in
computer systems because most claims are paid by computer. Medicare
officials must worry not only about their own computers, but also
about those run by its contractors _ more than 60 insurance
companies that pay claims for the government _ and by tens of
thousands of hospitals, doctors and other health care providers.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., said: ``It is incomprehensible to me
how this year 2000 problem has gotten so far out of hand. The
Health Care Financing Administration is in danger of missing
numerous statutory deadlines for modernizing Medicare because the
program's contractors have failed to aggressively prepare for the
year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn., said that other agencies like the
Social Security Administration had done a much better job of
preparing their computers.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare officials have said they might delay even routine
increases in payments to doctors and hospitals in 2000, because
they do not want to interfere with testing of their computers in
the final months of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Employees of the HCFA and those who deal with the agency listed
several reasons for its current difficulties:
</P>
<P>
   _ The agency recently completed a major reorganization, which
disrupted the work of many offices. Many senior and mid-level
managers and experienced technical employees have retired in the
last few years, causing a loss of institutional knowledge through
attrition.
</P>
<P>
   _ Medicare officials canceled a huge computer project, the
Medicare transaction system, which had been promoted as a way to
speed payment of claims, improve customer service, combat fraud and
prepare for the year 2000. Investigators said the project was
poorly designed, behind schedule, over budget and plagued with
problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ The agency has been slow to make the transition from simply
paying bills to promoting and managing a competitive market in
health care for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the transition, Bruce Fried, a lawyer who worked
on Clinton's 1992 campaign and then worked at the HCFA from 1994 to
1997, said: ``The agency has a tendency to be mistrustful of health
care providers, especially investor-owned organizations. Few people
at the agency have had experience in the private sector. Officials
do not fully appreciate the power of the market, and the innovation
that takes place in a market-driven economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Information about the delays has been disclosed piecemeal over
the last few months. Medicare officials said in June that they
would develop legislative proposals to change the deadlines in the
Balanced Budget Act, but so far they have not submitted such
proposals to Congress. The legal authority for the delays is thus
uncertain. Lawmakers, doctors, health care executives and advocates
for the elderly say they are confused.
</P>
<P>
   The government is ``an unpredictable and uncertain partner,''
said Thomas Miller, chief executive of the Lutheran Hospital of
Indiana, in Fort Wayne.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
