<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 12:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5865 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-CHANGE-ART-10     09-26 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-CHANGE-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GERMAN CHANCELLOR KOHL: A NEW CHAPTER, OR HISTORY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic explaining the German national election is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN, Germany _ Change is not lightly accepted in a country
where stability is paramount, and as Germany prepares to vote
Sunday in national elections it appears gripped by last-minute
doubts over whether the time has come to end the era of Chancellor
Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Kohl has trailed his Social Democratic challenger,
Gerhard Schroeder, and it long seemed that the burden of 16 years
in office was too much for even the chancellor who presided over
Germany's unification to overcome. But with a relentless
conviction, Kohl has closed the gap to the point where poll takers
say any outcome is possible.
</P>
<P>
   This in itself is extraordinary. A whole generation of young
Germans has never known anything but Kohl's leadership, and
Schroeder's slick campaign, bent above all on avoiding mistakes and
conveying an image of modernity, has struck a chord with the many
who yearn for a more self-confident Germany less burdened by its
past.
</P>
<P>
   The thirst for a new face, one unmarked by the experience of
World War II, which indelibly fashioned Kohl's outlook, may still
carry Schroeder, 54, to victory. He remains the favorite, with a
lead most opinion polls put at about 2 percent. But Europe's most
powerful nation appears agonizingly torn between an awareness that
new blood may be needed and a visceral distaste for risk.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's achievement has done much to diminish that risk. The
place of a unified Germany in NATO and at the heart of a European
Union that has adopted a single currency, the euro, is now
questioned only by small fringes of the left and neo-Nazi right.
Whatever the result, America's critical alliance with Germany will
not be rocked.
</P>
<P>
   But with a new century beckoning, a new global economy posing
challenges to Germany's long-cohesive social model and the return
to the new capital in Berlin about to be completed, Germans sense
that their vote is of decisive importance. What they see less
clearly is who should oversee the symbol-laden return to the
Reichstag in 1999, 44 years after the defeat of the Nazi regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't look at the face of Kohl any more,'' said Joachim
Jens Hesse, a political scientist. ``It's a physical thing, a
psychological thing, just as the British tired of Mrs. Thatcher.
But at the same time, this is such an awkward choice. I do not know
if I can trust the Social Democrats, especially in coalition with
the Greens.''
</P>
<P>
   Coalitions have always governed under Germany's parliamentary
system, but a ``Red-Green'' alliance is as yet untried. The idea
alarms some of the centrist voters to whom Schroeder has been
trying to appeal because the Greens have in the past called for
sharp increases in gasoline taxes and a review of Germany's NATO
membership.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative for Schroeder, if his Social Democratic Party
emerges victorious but does not have enough votes to govern with
the Greens, would be a so-called Grand Coalition with Kohl's
Christian Democrats _ a broad formula not tried for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Unwieldy, almost certainly condemned to be short-lived, such a
coalition might at least provide the heft to push through the
difficult reform of a welfare system that Germany is hard-pressed
to afford. As in much of the rest of Europe, an aging population
and high unemployment have strained public pension and social
security payments.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Democrats have not closed the door to a Grand
Coalition, but Kohl has said categorically that he would refuse to
lead it. So, if the Christian Democrats emerge with more votes than
the Social Democrats, but not enough to renew their current
center-right coalition, the possibility exists that Kohl's acerbic
deputy, Wolfgang Schauble, could emerge as the next chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   This outcome is not likely. But Schauble, 56, who has used a
wheelchair since he was shot by a deranged man while campaigning
eight years ago, has emerged in recent opinion polls as by far the
most popular politician in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   His suggestion that ``16 weeks of Mr. Schroeder will seem longer
than 16 years of Mr. Kohl'' has proved to be one of the more
memorable phrases of a campaign in which oratory has scarcely
soared. Schauble's popularity has in turn raised doubts about the
wisdom of Kohl in insisting on seeking an unprecedented fifth term.
</P>
<P>
   It is on Kohl's protracted rule that Schroeder, the premier of
the state of Lower Saxony, has hammered, insisting in every speech
that ``Germany cannot afford four more years of Kohl.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest _ Germany's 4.1 million unemployed, the
country's role in Europe, the current world financial crisis, the
replacement of Germany's beloved mark by the euro in 2002 _
Schroeder has been much more vague, or simply silent, relying on
images (like a meeting with Microsoft's Bill Gates), broad promises
and rugged good looks to carry the day.
</P>
<P>
   Four previous Social Democratic candidates have tried to take on
Kohl by more confrontational means: Hans-Jochen Vogel in 1983,
Johannes Rau in 1987, Oskar Lafontaine in 1990 and Rudolf Scharping
in 1994. They all looked good for a while; they all failed. Not for
nothing do Social Democratic posters insist, and insist again, that
``Wir Sind Bereit'' _ ``We are ready''.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they are. In the end, it may be the unification of
Germany, Kohl's crowning achievement, that proves his undoing.
</P>
<P>
   Unification has proved extraordinarily costly. Germany has been
transferring the equivalent of about 4.3 percent of its gross
national product, or total output, to the east since 1990,
straining public finances, transforming the area with new
enterprises and urban projects, but failing to resolve the problems
of the 16 million citizens of the former Communist state.
</P>
<P>
   About one in five people of working age in the east is
unemployed. The anger of these people, who once hailed Kohl for
unifying the country, has been directed at the Christian Democratic
Party, whose support in the area has plunged from close to 40
percent to under 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   These votes will not all go to the Social Democrats _ the Party
of Democratic Socialism (former Communists) and various neo-Nazi
groupings have both benefited _ but the damage to Kohl may prove
insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a free fall in Christian Democrat support in
the east,'' said Lutz Erbring, a political analyst. ``And I suspect
it is in the east that the outcome of this election will be
decided.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The other factor propelling Schroeder is a vaguer but equally
potent one. Germany has been in an assertive mood of late _ its big
corporations have been buying up the likes of Random House,
Chrysler and Rolls-Royce _ and the Social Democratic challenger has
contrived to symbolize this less cautious, less fettered spirit of
a nation that feels it has labored under the weight of its past for
long enough.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's call to rethink a planned Holocaust memorial in
Berlin _ a monument strongly supported by Kohl _ has provided one
of the few, clear policy conflicts between the two candidates and
captured their differing priorities and preoccupations.
</P>
<P>
   While Kohl dwells on the wounds of war, the glories of Germany's
reconstruction, the building of a united Europe and the precious
prize of peace, Schroeder wants to shift the focus unflinchingly to
the future.
</P>
<P>
   He has by no means convinced everyone. The large number of
undecided voters _ more than 20 percent, according to several polls
_ appears to reflect in part the hesitations of many Germans in
trusting a candidate who has shunned direct, declarative sentences
throughout the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that many of the so-called undecided are in fact
people who will end up not voting, so their importance may be
exaggerated. But if the hesitant opt in the end for Kohl's camp _
the reservoir of potential Christian Democratic voters is believed
to be larger than that of the Social Democrats _ they could still
swing the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am afraid that Kohl will still win it,'' said Andrea Zeller,
a 25-year-old student, as she watched the chancellor at a rally in
Munich this week. ``It's time for a change, but he always catches
up.'' She added that she would vote for the Greens, but without the
conviction that a ``Red-Green'' coalition could win.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week of campaigning, Kohl has been playing on the
fears of a conservative people, trying to portray Schroeder as the
gateway to a Communist presence in government. He has attacked
Schroeder's proposal to grant citizenship to some of Germany's 7
million foreign residents, and warned of instability.
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment falling _ it is expected to drop below 4
million this month after going as high as 4.8 million earlier this
year _ and the German economy enjoying a recovery, Kohl's
statements appear to have had an impact. His appearance as a rock
of stability at a moment of world uncertainty, when the U.S.
president, Bill Clinton, is clearly distracted, has also helped his
cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``A company that is doing well does not change its chief
executive just because he has been there for 15 to 20 years,'' said
Christoph Ahlhaus, 29, a banker. ``Why should we?''
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that Germany has enough problems, and Kohl
enough years in power, for Schroeder to have a strong chance.
Another truth is that, whoever wins, Germany is likely to flex its
muscle more in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want a European superstate,'' Kohl declared in
Munich. ``We want a strong Germany in Europe.'' That statement
amounted to a shift: Germany long talked approvingly of a United
States of Europe, with a truly federal system.
</P>
<P>
   But the painful abandonment of the mark for the euro was
Germany's pledge of good faith to the European idea. Now, whether
under Schroeder or under Kohl once again, or under some other
chancellor, the country clearly feels it has the right and the
might to make its voice heard, and to do so without any complexes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
