<HEADLINE>
THE STARR EVIDENCE: THE BANALITY OF LEGAL _ BORING IN ON A
SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(editors: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The raw evidence made public last week in the presidential sex
scandal was a turnoff to many people in more ways than one: Not
only was it wince-inducing, thanks to its subject matter, but it
was also yawn-inducing, thanks to its sheer length and volume. This
curious fact undoubtedly occurred to those who fidgeted through all
four-plus hours of deposition verite starring Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the videotape wasn't the half of it. The accompanying,
3,100-page document-drop by the House Judiciary Committee (to be
followed by a far bigger one this week) included numerous
excursions into the tedious, the mundane and the irrelevant. Yep, a
lot of this is real forehead-bouncing-on-the-table material, folks,
and some of it is unintentionally funny.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing this out is not to judge whether the evidence, over
all, is compelling or not. Rather, the tedium is a reflection of
the legal and procedural rigamarole that is so much a feature of
modern American life.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's on display for all to behold, and writ large, in the
struggle between Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr and the White
House. Evidence follows.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TOM KUNTZ &QR;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Exhibit A: Profiles in penmanship. On May
28, Monica Lewinsky, her lawyer William Ginsburg and her father,
Dr. Bernard Lewinsky, were escorted by government agents up to the
17th floor of FBI headquarters in Los Angeles so she could give
handwriting samples to investigators. As noted in a memo from
Starr's office, it was a complex process. And it didn't go
smoothly: (END ITALICS HERE)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pens used for this examination were as follows: one Bic,
round stic, medium, black ink pen; one Paper Mate pen with black
ink; and one Paper Mate gel writer, with black ink. At various
times during the examination, LEWINSKY was asked to use one of the
three different pens. LEWINSKY's attorneys interrupted the
examination on numerous occasions so LEWINSKY could consult
privately with her attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   MONICA LEWINSKY was first asked to write the alphabet in its
entirety, with three different pens, on an 8{'' x 11'' sheet of
paper (unless specified otherwise, each sheet of paper used was
8{'' x 11'') attached to a pad. On the same sheet of paper,
LEWINSKY was asked to write the number 1 thru 10, three times,
using a different pen each time.
</P>
<P>
   LEWINSKY was then asked to perform the same task, this time
using a sheet of paper resting only on the desk where she was
sitting.
</P>
<P>
   LEWINSKY was then asked to print her name three times on a sheet
of paper attached to a pad, each time using a different pen.
LEWINSKY was then asked to sign her name on a sheet of paper
attached to a pad, each time using a different pen. LEWINSKY was
then asked to perform the same task, with the sheet of paper used
resting directly on the desk.
</P>
<P>
   LEWINSKY was then asked to sign her name to a photocopy of a
blank check. At that time, GINSBURG objected and advised his client
not to sign the form. GINSBURG advised that the OIC (Office of the
Independent Counsel) would need to get a court order before his
client would sign anything that resembled a check. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The handwriting examination continued until approximately 10:06
a.m., when LEWINSKY took a break to visit the restroom. . . .
</P>
<P>
   At approximately 11:00 a.m., the examination ended, at which
time GINSBURG was served grand jury subpoena number D-1319 for
LEWINSKY's appearance on June 4, 1998, in Washington D.C., to
provide handwriting exemplars. GINSBURG advised (that) he thought a
handwriting examination was just completed. GINSBURG was advised
that all requested exemplars were not provided; therefore, LEWINSKY
would have to come to Washington D.C., to do so.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Exhibit B: The ``dribble glass.'' In her
grand jury testimony on Aug. 20, Ms. Lewinsky was about to vent her
anger at President Clinton for giving away one of her gift ties to
his steward, Bayani Nelvis. But then her drinking cup started
leaking, eliciting this exchange involving Michael Emmick, an
associate independent counsel, and an unidentified grand juror:(END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   JUROR: Can you tell me what your thoughts were when you saw the
pictures of Nelvis wearing the first tie that you gave the
President?
</P>
<P>
   MS. LEWINSKY: Yes. Actually, you know what? I think my cup's
leaking. I'm sorry.
</P>
<P>
   JUROR: Do we have another cup up there?
</P>
<P>
   MS. LEWINSKY: Am I allowed to know people's names in here?
</P>
<P>
   MR. EMMICK: The answer to that is no.
</P>
<P>
   MS. LEWINSKY: Oh _
</P>
<P>
   MR. EMMICK: I know it seems _
</P>
<P>
   MS. LEWINSKY: It's so awkward.
</P>
<P>
   MR. EMMICK: It does seem awkward, but I think it's better if _
</P>
<P>
   MS. LEWINSKY: OK
</P>
<P>
   MR. EMMICK: _ the record not have any identifications.
</P>
<P>
   MS. LEWINSKY: OK
</P>
<P>
   MR. EMMICK: We didn't intentionally get you a dribble glass.
</P>
<P>
   MS. LEWINSKY: Oh, sure. At least it's water and not grape juice.
</P>
<P>
   I had two very different thoughts. My first thought was, ``You
jerk''. . . .
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Exhibit C: Answering machine blather. Many
of the phone messages left for Ms. Lewinsky at her Watergate
apartment, and transcribed by Starr's office, seem relevant to the
case. Others ramble on in pretty ordinary fashion:(END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   CHRIS (no last name given): Hi, Monica. It's Chris here. I guess
about 8:00 a.m. your time on Saturday morning. I was just ringing
up to say thanks so much for the brilliant Pentagon, um, sweatshirt
that I'm going to have a lot of fun wearing here in the winter
months.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, I won't get beaten up by any, um, anti-American
leftists _ leftists, so that we'll have to wait and see. But
anyhow, it was a really nice present. Thanks so much for that.
</P>
<P>
   And um, well, I hope you can get on the e-mail soon because I
miss, uh, our little e-mail chats, not to mention the jokes. I
haven't heard a good joke, except for some John Denver jokes, in
quite some time. So, anyhow _ and Sonny Bono jokes too, which is
rather crass. I got a Sonny Bono joke next day, which is terrible.
</P>
<P>
   Anyhow, uh, I'll, um, hope to be hearing from you soon. OK
Ta-ta. Bye-bye.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Exhibit D: Name that date. Linda Tripp's
recordings of her phone conversations with Ms. Lewinsky
(transcripts are expected this week) were originally not dated. So
Starr's office had to deduce when the tapes were made, and provided
painstaking written explanations:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Conversation (NU)3:
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Oct. 4, 1997 . . .
</P>
<P>
   The conversation that immediately precedes this conversation on
the tape occurred on Friday, Oct. 3, 1997. At the end of the
previous portion, Ms. Lewinsky notes that it is 10:20, that she is
going to sleep, and she indicates that she is not working the next
day. . . . This conversation begins with Ms. Lewinsky describing
her trip to the Potomac Mills Mall for the day. . . . The placement
of the conversation on the tape and the day-long trip to the mall
are consistent with a weekend day.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Ms. Lewinsky says Betty Currie was in the office
during the morning because of the Radio Address. . . . The
President delivered a Radio Address on Saturday, Oct. 4, 1997,
10:06 a.m. Also, Betty Currie rarely works on Sunday because it is
her ``church day.'' . . . Ms. Lewinsky further says she wants to
buy the President a gift because he now had a hearing aid. . . .
The President was fitted for hearing aids on Oct. 3, 1997. See
``Age Catching Up With Clinton; He's Getting Hearing Aids,'' Sandra
Sobieraj, The Associated Press, Oct. 3, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky also says there are three months before the
beginning of the year, and she refers to sunglasses she bought the
President for his Latin America trip. . . .
</P>
<P>
   These factors are consistent with a conversation on Oct. 4,
1997.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Exhibit last: The lunch bunch. The
presidency may be at stake, but people have to eat. At Ms.
Lewinsky's Aug. 6 grand jury deposition, Deputy Independent Counsel
Solomon Wisenberg checks to see if the food has arrived:(END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   MR. EMMICK: I have no more questions about this date, and I look
at the time and it looks like it's 12:30.
</P>
<P>
   THE FOREPERSON (unidentified): Sol, I think, went to check on
something.
</P>
<P>
   MR. EMMICK: Oh, all right.
</P>
<P>
   THE FOREPERSON: Did you check on something for lunch?
</P>
<P>
   MR. WISENBERG: I have checked. It is here. It's been here.
</P>
<P>
   MR. EMMICK: OK All right. Well, if this would be a good time to
break for lunch _
</P>
<P>
   THE FOREPERSON: Hourlong.
</P>
<P>
   MR. EMMICK: OK
</P>
<P>
   MS. LEWINSKY: OK
</P>
<P>
   THE FOREPERSON: OK
</P>
<P>
   MR. EMMICK: Thank you.
</P>
<P>
   (Whereupon, at 12:34 p.m., a luncheon recess was taken.)
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)When those assembled reconvened after lunch,
Ms. Lewinsky had a suggestion:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   MS. LEWINSKY: Time for a nap? . . .
</P>
<P>
   THE FOREPERSON: . . . Monica, I'd like to remind you that you
are still under oath.
</P>
</TEXT>
