<HEADLINE>
LAWS RULE IN INQUIRY, NOT POLLS, GOP SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans in Congress insist that they will not
be deterred in their investigation of President Clinton by polls
last week showing the public's disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't affect what we do,'' said Rep. Bill McCollum of
Florida, a senior Republican on the Judiciary Committee. ``We are
determined to do this fairly and objectively and not listen to the
polls at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde of, R-Ill., the committee's chairman, asserted,
``We're very blessed to live in a nation of laws, not governed by
opinion polls influenced by political spin.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest New York Times/CBS News poll shows that in the past
week, as the public's scrutiny of the congressional inquiry has
intensified, the percentage of adults who view Congress favorably
has fallen to 48 percent from 56 percent, and the percentage of
those who disapprove of the way Congress is handling its job has
increased to 41 percent from 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important, large majorities of those interviewed in
the poll disapprove of the way the Judiciary Committee is handling
the inquiry, believe the Republicans have been unfairly partisan
and think important work of the government is being sidetracked by
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 4 of 5 adults said it was unnecessary for Congress to
release President Clinton's videotaped testimony to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   These findings did not take lawmakers by surprise. ``Whenever
things get partisan up here, the public gets turned off,'' said
Rep. John Boehner of Ohio, the fourth-ranking member of the House
Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   After the Watergate investigation and President Richard M.
Nixon's resignation 1974, Congress rose in public esteem. Many
credited Congress with saving the American system of government.
</P>
<P>
   But more recently, the more Congress has been in the limelight,
the more its ratings have dropped.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the public's opinion of Congress fell in the
Iran-Contra hearings in 1987 and after the hearings on the Supreme
Court nomination of Clarence Thomas and the sexual harassment
accusations against him involving Anita Hill in 1991. Those
hearings, like the videotape of the Clinton testimony, were
television spectacles.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats in Congress and presumably Clinton and his staff
are hoping that if the trend in public opinion continues to run
against Congress, it will prove to be a life preserver for the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Dingell of Michigan, who has been in the House since
1955, said that his ``well-tuned set of guts'' told him that
Congress' lower standing in the polls ``is one of the things
Clinton is pinning his hopes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Vic Fazio of California, the third-ranking member of the
Democratic leadership in the House, said: ``Republicans seem to
think there's an unending appetite in the country for this scandal.
That's a misreading of the American people.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a large enough majority comes to feel that they are
overstepping their bounds and being too partisan,'' Fazio said,
``that might lead the Republicans to back off.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans said they were undaunted. They took their cue
from Speaker Newt Gingrich, who said Wednesday, ``I think people
would be, frankly, horrified if the Congress was simply a polling
institution that enacted a grotesque version of justice based on
the latest poll or talk show.''
</P>
<P>
   Prof. Richard Fenno, a political scientist at the University of
Rochester who specializes in Congress, said it was hard for him to
imagine that Republicans would continue down the impeachment trail
on a partisan basis in the face of public disapproval. But he
quickly added that the Republicans' track record in this regard was
so sparse that he could not be sure how they would respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were out of power for so long and are so inexperienced at
governing that they've had an occasional tin ear when it came to
looking at public opinion,'' Fenno said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-98 1300EDT &QL; 
