<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAKISTAN AND INDIA MAKE NUCLEAR TEST PLEDGE
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan and India promised to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban
treaty, which bars nuclear testing. Both countries have some
reservations, however, and both have prime ministers with wobbly
political bases. And India's military ambitions under a Hindu
nationalist government remain unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The United States wants to see signatures on this and other
nuclear control agreements before lifting the sanctions that were
imposed after the two countries set off nuclear explosions in May.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARBARA CROSSETTE
</P>
<P>
   U.N. WARNING TO SERBS
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations Security Council ordered Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to stop Serbian attacks on civilians in the
ethnically Albanian Kosovo region, and demanded that both sides
start talking. In sending its warning, the Council _ minus China _
papered over big differences about whether outside military
intervention will be necessary to stop the Serb-dominated Yugoslav
army from attacking civilians while battling Albanian separatists.
</P>
<P>
   The Council is using the same tactic against Saddam Hussein of
Iraq, putting on a common front to prevent troublemakers from
exploiting divisions among the most powerful nations. The hard part
is deciding what to do if the bluff fails.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARBARA CROSSETTE
</P>
<P>
   PENTAGON'S POLICY ON GAYS IS UPHELD
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has declined so far to take up the
constitutionality of the military's ``don't ask, don't tell''
policy. But the court may get another opportunity after a ruling by
a federal appeals court, which said the policy does not violate
homosexuals' rights.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, which said free speech and equal protection have
traditionally been more curtailed in the armed forces than in
civilian life, upheld the military's recent policy allowing
homosexuals to serve if they keep their sexual orientation a
private matter.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALAN FINDER
</P>
<P>
   POVERTY RATES FALL
</P>
<P>
   In a welcome bit of good news for the Clinton administration,
the Census Bureau reported that the proportion of Americans living
in poverty declined last year, a drop largely attributed to
progress made by black and Hispanic families.
</P>
<P>
   The overall rate was 13.3 percent in 1997, down from 13.7
percent the year before. Clinton said the statistics vindicated his
economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   READING TEA LEAVES
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan and Keizo Obuchi have almost nothing in common.
Except that the Federal Reserve chairman and the new Japanese prime
minister both enjoy reputations for making public comments that
leave investors puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   What investors heard from Greenspan last week was a slippery
statement that, ``We have to bring the existing instabilities to a
level of stability reasonably shortly'' before the global economic
turmoil really rocks America. The world immediately assumed that
the Fed will cut interest rates on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Obuchi. Before meeting President Clinton in New
York to discuss Japan's banking crisis, he said, ``Instead of `too
little too late' we want to deal with this in ways that people say
`too big, too fast.'''
</P>
<P>
   Even Clinton's economic team had a hard time faking much
optimism at those words. ``You have to remember, we've been in
office six years and we've already met six Japanese prime
ministers,'' one noted.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
<P>
   NEW EMBASSY FUNDS SOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration asked Congress for $1.8 billion for
emergency safeguards to protect the country's 260 embassies and
consulates. The spending, if approved, would nearly double the
total amount lawmakers have appropriated for security since 1985,
and reflects the administration's conclusion no overseas mission is
safe from terrorism since the embassy bombings in Kenya and
Tanzania last month.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ERIC SCHMITT
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA AND IMF SQUARE OFF
</P>
<P>
   Russia and the International Monetary Fund have never liked each
other, but now neither side is hiding it. The new Russian
government declared that unless it got more aid from the IMF it
might default on its international obligations. The IMF said that
it wouldn't tolerate ``blackmail,'' and that if Russia wants loans,
it might think about collecting some taxes and turning off the
printing presses that are spitting out rubles and creating
hyperinflation.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
<P>
   GIFT FOR SALVATION ARMY
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's, it's safe to say, has changed the world, imprinting
cookie-cutter standardization on the global psyche. Now Joan Kroc,
the widow of Ray Kroc, who made McDonald's into a golden-arched
juggernaut, is using a few of her millions to try to change one
corner of the world, donating $80 million to the Salvation Army for
a community center in inner-city San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   NASA SEEKS A RUSSIAN BAILOUT
</P>
<P>
   The biggest science project of all time, a sprawling outpost for
astronauts, is to start being hauled piecemeal into orbit in two
months. But the plan is shaky because a key Russian player has been
crippled by the nation's economic chaos.
</P>
<P>
   So NASA plans to buy up to $660 million in goods and services
over five years to help its partner complete a key station element.
Congress hates the plan. But the alternatives _ including dropping
the station, on which the Americans have already spent billions _
are unappealing.
</P>
<P>
   _ By WILLIAM J. BROAD
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NOT-SO-QUICK-CHANGE ARTIST
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Ginter was stuffing handfuls of quarters into a coin
redemption machine in a Waldbaum's supermarket in Queens, New York
City. In fact, the authorities said, he had put 1,086 quarters into
the machine and had 295 more quarters in his pockets when the
police emerged from the aisles to arrest him. The quarters, they
said, came from the city's parking meters.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Ginter was the city official in charge of collecting the
change. All told, Ginter was accused of stealing as many 14,400
bent or damaged quarters on a total of 12 occasions.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOHN KIFNER
</P>
<P>
   IRAN DROPS RUSHDIE THREAT
</P>
<P>
   Does Salman Rushdie really feel safe now that the government of
Iran has officially canceled its nearly decade-old death sentence
against the British author? He says he does. ``It's over,'' he
insisted. ``It's done.''
</P>
<P>
   But remember: millions of people have been told he's an enemy
whose authorial crimes against Islam were so heinous that he
deserved to die. Will each and every one of them instantly forgive
and forget?
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING &QR;
</P>
<P>
   SMUT? NOT IN THIS MAN'S ARMY!
</P>
<P>
   Military stores at bases around the world began pulling from
their shelves more than 150 magazines that the Pentagon decided are
sexually explicit.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy survived the cut. But lesser-known periodicals like
Kinky Fetishes, Barely Legal and D-Cup, were sent packing _ brown
paper wrappers and all _ banished to what the Defense Department
called its ``adult sophisticate'' list.
</P>
<P>
   The Military Honor and Decency Act, imposed by Congress two
years ago, bars the military from selling in its stores any film,
video or publication that ``depicts or describes nudity, including
sexual or excretory activities or organs, in a lascivious way.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Pentagon was blocked from carrying out the law after a
lawsuit was filed by Bob Guccione, the publisher of Penthouse
(which is on the banned list), who argued that the legislation
violated freedom of speech. Guccione's effort failed earlier this
year when the U.S. Supreme Court refused to review the case.
</P>
<P>
   That cleared the way for the Pentagon to start yanking offending
titles from store shelves. And while it's not yet on the banned
list, some lawmakers say the Whitewater independent counsel's
445-page report, with all its sexually explicit material, would
almost certainly qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Starr report would not pass this test,'' said Rep. Roscoe
Bartlett, R-Md., who wrote the bill. ``I can't believe military
mothers would want their 10-year-old's reading it.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is saying that GIs can't buy reading material like
Naughty Neighbors or Nude Readers' Wives anymore. They just can't
buy them at base commissaries or exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ERIC SCHMITT
</P>
<P>
   MAYBE IT'S JUST A COINCIDENCE ...
</P>
<P>
   For conspiracy theorists, the grassy knoll is already passe, as
is the identity of Deep Throat. But what about those new $20 bills
the Treasury Department started shipping last week _ 2 billion of
them _ with the oversized mug of Andrew Jackson?
</P>
<P>
   President Jackson, of course, was the only occupant of the White
House to be censured by Congress. Surely, there must be a
subliminal message here, one aimed at the millions of Monica-weary
Americans who will start pulling the new bills out of ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, introducing the
bills, DID say, ``Look at your cash and pay more attention to its
feel and appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   While you're looking, don't forget the vast West Wing
conspiracy. The reverse side of the bill shows the north side of
the White House, which faces Pennsylvania Avenue, instead of the
south side, which graced the old bill. The engravers carefully
cropped out the president's offices in the West Wing, to say
nothing of the Northwest Gate, where, according to Kenneth Starr's
report, Monica Lewinsky once threw a fit.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the Treasury says it began designing the new
bill in June 1986, during the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a job for Oliver Stone.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. SANGER &QL;
</P>
