<HEADER>
A5922 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     09-26 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SPORTS COLUMN: SPENCER IS CALLED BETTER THAN McGWIRE, SOSA  
(bl) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Yankees sent Shane Spencer back to their
Columbus farm team in August for the third time this season, the
26-year-old outfielder was naturally disappointed, but Joe Torre
cheered him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry, you'll be back,'' the Yankee manager told him.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, Spencer returned. And now, with a splurge of
five homers (including two grand slams) in seven days, this sturdy
crew-cut Californian has apparently slugged his way onto the Yankee
roster for the American League divisional series, which opens
Tuesday night at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he playing better,'' Torre was asked Friday night, ``than
Strawberry and Raines?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' the manager said, smiling, ``he's playing better
than McGwire and Sosa.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not as farfetched as it might sound. In Spencer's last 19
at-bats before Saturday's game against Tampa Bay, he had 11 hits (2
doubles and 4 singles in addition to the 5 homers) and 15 runs
batted in. In his 59 at-bats, he was hitting .390 with 8 homers and
22 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's amazing,'' Torre said. ``He looks like a high-ball
hitter, but he hits low balls for home runs. He's supposed to be a
fastball hitter, but he hits a changeup for a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees are surprised by Spencer's ability to hit home
runs on pitches he's not supposed to be hitting, imagine the
consternation among the scouts for the other AL playoff teams as
they prepare their charts for their pitching staffs on the Yankee
batters.
</P>
<P>
   For a pitcher, there's nothing worse than not knowing a batter's
supposed weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   What the Yankees don't know yet is whether Shane Spencer is here
to stay or whether he's a late-season sensation whose bat will
eventually develop holes when opposing pitchers learn more about
him. Actually, whether second baseman Chuck Knoblauch's bat will
develop holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Wonderboy broke his bat in Baltimore, he picked up
one of mine,'' Knoblauch said. ``That's what he hit all those
homers with.''
</P>
<P>
   With his first swing in each of four consecutive at-bats,
Spencer hit a grand slam against the Orioles left-hander Jesse
Orosco, a pinch-hit double off the top of the center-field wall
against the Orioles left-hander Jimmy Key, and two home runs
against the Indians right-hander Dave Burba.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four swings and what should have been four homers,'' Knoblauch
said. ``That double was really over the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer added a homer against the Indians' Jason Jacome on
Wednesday, then hit another grand slam against Tampa Bay's Wilson
Alvarez on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck's bats are the same as mine, 34{ inches and 32 ounces,''
Spencer said. ``I told Chuck I'm going to order my bats through him
from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer first joined the Yankees in April when Chili Davis
needed ankle surgery. He was back in June, then again in July, then
again on Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went 5 for 5 in Kansas City in early August; I used one
of Chili's bats,'' he said. ``I do well with other bats.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite being on the Columbus shuttle, Spencer hit 30 homers in
the International League for the second straight season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane has worked hard to make himself a major league player,''
Stump Merrill, the Columbus manager who once managed the Yankees,
said from his Maine home. ``He can drive the ball the other way
now. Early in his career he was a hook monster. He hooked
everything. The guys in the third-base dugout weren't safe.''
</P>
<P>
   In spring training with the Yankees in 1997, Spencer misplayed
some fly balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like that hangs with you,'' Merrill said. ``But he
worked hard on his fielding, chasing down balls in batting practice
every day. I thought we'd lose him in the expansion draft, but we
got lucky. Nobody took him. I think he's got the best bat speed in
the Yankee organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer's success at driving in runs for the Yankees doesn't
surprise Merrill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely an RBI man,'' Merrill said. ``Some guys fold
when there's runners on base, but his bat is jumping in the bat
rack. He can't wait to get up there.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Shane Spencer will be in a pinstriped uniform Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about next year?'' Joe Torre was asked Friday night.
``Will he be your left fielder next year?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll worry about next week first,'' the Yankee manager said.
``Next year will take care of itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-98 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
