<HEADER>
A5930 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     09-26 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PAYTON SHOWS HIS HUMAN SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Be nice to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Those were the first words from Jay Payton, a rookie who made a
base-running mistake on the last Friday night of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put me in to run; I messed it up,'' Payton patiently told
the phalanx of reporters who clumped over to his locker after the
New York Mets had squandered another chance, 6-5, to the Atlanta
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying the potential tying run in the eighth inning, Payton
tried to run on Andruw Jones, merely one of the highest-caliber
arms in baseball, and was out from here to Chattahoochee.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the Mets would be locked in a bizarre triple tie with the
Chicago Cubs and San Francisco Giants going into the last Saturday
of this compelling season. Ten teams in two leagues prepared for
playoffs without any secure knowledge of where or whom they would
be playing.
</P>
<P>
   On this same last weekend, Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire were
matching home runs as the entire nation seemed to root for these
two gallant sluggers to finish tied.
</P>
<P>
   But these thrilling final days were not only about the
superstars, Sosa and McGwire. The final weekend also belonged to
the role players, the fringe veterans and the rookies who, in a
month of expanded rosters, were suddenly thrust into games that
meant everything.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is the only sport with glory and ignominy etched on
scorecards, isolated for eternity. One botched play can stick with
a man forever. For the image of a runner forever a second late and
a yard slow, Cal Abrams of Brooklyn was gunned down at home by
Richie Ashburn of the Phillies on the last day of the 1950 season.
For September-October blunders, we have Bill Buckner's bobble, Fred
Merkel's base-running gaffe, Leon Durham's fumble, Mickey Owens'
passed ball.
</P>
<P>
   In the glaring sun of Milwaukee on Wednesday, an outfielder
named Brant Brown muffed a fly ball that cost the Cubs a game on
what should have been the very last play. Other major leaguers
shuddered when they saw the kid trudge off the field, wondering if
he had given the Cubs yet another season to despair.
</P>
<P>
   Brant Brown even flashed through Jay Payton's mind Friday, after
Payton had been gunned down at third base. Nothing disrespectful
toward Brown, but Payton knew he was not quite in that category.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' Payton would say later, quite kindly. ``If I
stay at second, you can't predict what would have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Mike Piazza was the next batter, and he had merely
drilled two line drives so powerful that they bounced past
outfielders on the grass for doubles instead of singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rule No. 1 is, you don't make the third out at third base,''
said the Mets' manager, Bobby Valentine, making it clear that Rule
No. 2 is, you don't make the third out when your cleanup hitter is
up next.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Payton knows this. He was a baseball all-American and an
academic all-American not just anywhere but at Georgia Tech, the
esteemed university right up the road from Turner Field. He helped
the Yellow Jackets into the final game of the College World Series
in 1994, and was a teammate of the noted Boston shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   While Garciaparra flourished, Payton needed two reconstructive
surgeries on his right elbow, missing the entire 1997 season,
finally making the majors for a few games this season. He's still
only 25 and the best hitting prospect in the Mets' organization;
and he can run.
</P>
<P>
   Payton was on the bench Friday when Tony Phillips walked, moving
a pinch-runner to second base. With his bench jammed with players,
Valentine went for youth and speed, sending in Payton for the
38-year-old Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Was this move necessary? Was it the compulsive act of a manager
who has never reached the playoffs, or a no-brainer move to get
younger legs on the bases? Would Phillips have run on Andruw Jones?
Should somebody have cautioned Payton against running on Jones?
</P>
<P>
   Before there was time to ponder such issues, John Olerud whacked
a single, and the runners took off. Mike Kinkade was going to be
safe at home, and Payton was not expected to glance at the
third-base coach because the play was in front of him, out in
center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Andruw Jones,'' Payton said later. ``I know he's got a
great arm. It was just an error in judgment. When I saw the ball
off the bat, I thought I could reach third. I got halfway to third
and I should have stopped and gone back to second. I made the third
out at third base _ and that's a no-no.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of ballplayers today who will blow off an
interview after going 3 for 4. Here was a poised college man up
from Class AAA ball, and he could handle the mob around his locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's not the end of the world,'' Jay Payton said.
``Not after all I've been through. I've had those surgeries on my
elbow. I learned from that. I'll learn from this. I feel I can
handle any situation. I'm hopeful I get in the same situation
again.''
</P>
<P>
   He already knows something important. You don't have to
surrender your good manners just because you were a few feet short
on the last weekend of a baseball race.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
