<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL NOTEBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAVENS' WOODSON APPEALS
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Ravens defensive back Rod Woodson refused to take a
drug test last month because he was irritated at having to take a
test only several days earlier. After cooling down, he eventually
took the second test, but it was too late. His original refusal was
an automatic violation of the NFL's drug policy, and Woodson was
automatically entered into the substance-abuse program.
</P>
<P>
   Woodson, one of the best defensive backs ever and a member of
the league's 75th anniversary team, is appealing the decision and
will meet with Commissioner Paul Tagliabue soon. If the decision is
reversed by Tagliabue, Woodson would be taken out of the drug
program. If it is not, Woodson will only remain in the program for
a short time since no one in the NFL believes Woodson has a drug
problem.
</P>
<P>
   PARCELLS' SHOTGUN OFFENSE
</P>
<P>
   What helped push the New York Jets past the Indianapolis Colts
last week was the relentless verbal battering by coach Bill
Parcells of his players as he threatened many of their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Parcells said his actions were exaggerated by the
news media. Not so say the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach dished out some threats during the course of the week,''
said linebacker Pepper Johnson. ``I know it definitely helped my
play when he personally threatened me. I don't know if the threat
is meant to be in the press but it's one of those things where guys
didn't want to be looking at 0-3, it's like looking down the barrel
of a shotgun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
