<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR GIANTS, `THE BEST OFFENSE' IS A MATTER OF
PERSPECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ So I am watching the New York Giants play the Dallas
Cowboys last Monday night, trailing by 10 points deep into the
third quarter, and I am thinking, no doubt about it, they are about
to score a touchdown any second now, put themselves right back in
the football game.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that I am only thinking this when Dallas has the
ball, not the Giants. When Danny Kanell is throwing short on
third-and-long, I am saying, hurry up, don't waste more time by
moving the chains. Get the defense back on the field in good
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   This, I agree, is somewhat extremist, and no way to instill
confidence in a young quarterback, much less get to a Super Bowl.
Yet I wonder if that's what goes through the minds of a few Giants'
defenders sometimes when they stand there on the sideline watching
their offense do well to avoid going backwards.
</P>
<P>
   After three games in a 1-2 season, with a date here Sunday with
a San Diego team whose rookie quarterback last week completed one
whole pass for 4 incremental yards, the Giants' defense would seem
to have a good chance to redeem itself for failing to reach the end
zone last week. A victory over the San Diego Chargers would not
prove much, only buy Giants head coach Jim Fassel time to somehow
pump heat into an offense that has not even been as tepid as it was
last year. It would help Kanell to have a running game that
measures more than three yards a carry. But sooner than later, this
notion that the Giants can actually go somewhere with their defense
as their offense, with Kanell merely ``managing the game,'' will
have to be junked.
</P>
<P>
   We have all heard the maxim that defense wins championships but,
let's face it, if the Knicks have taught us anything during the
course of the 1990s, it is that defense mostly manhandles
mediocrity. The offensive geniuses, the Michael Jordans and Brett
Favres, ultimately figure out the best defensive schemes, so here
is a better expression, albeit one a bit tortured, relating to a
Giants team that must play Denver, Green Bay, San Francisco and
Kansas City later this season:
</P>
<P>
   The best offense is not a good defense, but I guess it is better
than no offense at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big plays, that's our mentality,'' said John Fox, the Giants'
popular defensive coordinator, refusing to accept that his defense
can't replicate the roll it went on last season, when it habitually
handed the offense the ball in field position to die for. ``We're
going to get better. We're going to get turnovers. I can't tell you
how many, but we'll get our share.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a tough job, carrying the Giants' offense, but somebody has
to do it Sunday before this defending Eastern Division champion
falls to 1-3 with another road game at Tampa Bay next, and with
everyone well aware that the schedule will not be serving up a
steady diet of New Orleans and Alcorn State.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect for Fox and what his defense did to carry
the Giants to 10-5-1 last season, if the Giants don't start moving
the ball, the franchise's supposed turnaround will be revealed as
the product of last season's generous schedule. Conditions change,
year-to-year, in addition to the quality of a playoff team's
opponents. Injuries like the one that took right cornerback Jason
Sehorn obviously change the physical equation, and expectations
based on previous success may very well subtly alter defensive
psychology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've been freelancing to try to force
turnovers,'' Fox argued. ``I just think we're young, we have some
new kids and we haven't caught up yet. And what happened against
Dallas is that they had a game plan where they weren't going to
throw the ball, except on third down. They used a lot of short
yardage groups, multiple tight ends, to limit the number of ways we
could take it away. As coaches, we weren't ready for that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, well, it's true, teams are getting smarter against us,''
said Jessie Armstead, the big-play linebacker whose nagging ankle
injury hasn't helped either. ``We want to make big plays, we know
we have to make big plays. We just have to keep coming, keep
coming, and hope that sooner or later, they'll slip up and we'll
capitalize on a key mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, that sounds like a fair enough game plan for young Ryan
Leaf on Sunday but Elway and Young and Favre and a few others who
aren't going to disintegrate are out there this time around. The
Giants were a whole lot of fun last season when their defense was
so dominant that it became their offense.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to do that two years in a row, for the variety
of reasons already mentioned, and by the end of October, if the
Giants have not developed a real offense, their season will become
one long funeral procession that stalls on fourth down and punts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
