<HEADLINE>
HARRY CARAY HELPS BASEBALL TO A HEAVENLY YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- We've heard the stories of lifeless flowers
blooming anew in a family garden the spring after a loved one's
death. Now comes even more persuasive proof that there is an
afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   The rejuvenation of baseball in 1998 can't be explained any
other way than to say Harry Caray, God rest his irascible soul,
made it to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   For 16 years he was the Chicago Cubs' MVP, never mind that he
held a microphone and not a bat. He could belt out words as
impressively as Cubs outfielder Sammy Sosa -- or as Caray would
say, Thammy Thotha -- has belted out baseballs this year.
</P>
<P>
   Caray loved baseball, beer and (pardon the expression) broads.
</P>
<P>
   He observed games for a living but was a passionate participant
in life. So it figures that after succumbing to a heart attack,
he'd try to find some way to let the few detractors he left behind
know he had landed on his feet, up in the clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Holy cow, you'd have to be wearing glasses thicker than Caray's
black-rimmed numbers not to see the clues he has been scattering
about the country during the past six months.
</P>
<P>
   From the New York Yankees' season-long tear to the historic
home-run duel being waged by Sosa and St. Louis slugger Mark
McGwire to Cal Ripken Jr.'s astonishing decision to take a seat, it
has been a baseball season tailor-made for the fans that Caray
called the unsung heroes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   His love for the game is being perpetuated by die-hard
enthusiasts and dilettantes alike. After whiffing badly in 1994
when a strike led to the cancellation of the World Series, baseball
is soaring to heights heretofore reserved for one of McGwire's
blasts.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Illustrated, long a barometer of which way the sporting
winds are blowing, has devoted nine of its 21 covers since the
start of May to baseball -- three of four this month. In the same
five-month span last year, the weekly magazine slapped baseball on
its cover four times and not at all in September, when the regular
season is winding down and interest figures to be peaking.
</P>
<P>
   A phone survey conducted by CBS and The New York Times found
baseball is more popular than at any time since the news
organizations started polling people on the subject in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-three percent said they were at least somewhat interested
in baseball, up from 42 percent a year ago. Twenty-two percent of
the 960 adults surveyed described themselves as very interested in
following Major League Baseball, up from 14 percent five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the thinning of pitching talent due to expansion and
the squeeze plays so many franchises are trying in an effort to get
ever more luxurious and lucrative digs, more people than ever
(roughly 71 million) will have attended a game by today's
regular-season end.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not counting the crazies who have stood outside
Chicago's Wrigley Field, hoping to catch a piece of history
launched by Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Lest anybody doubt that Caray is orchestrating this season the
way he used to the seventh-inning stretch, the proof is in Sosa's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Before this year, Sosa never had hit more than 40 home runs in
any season. He went into the final weekend with 66, five more than
Roger Maris' previous single-season record. That tied him with
McGwire, who averaged 55 homers in 1996 and 1997, and who plays for
the Cubs' fiercest rival -- and Caray's first major-league
employer.
</P>
<P>
   Caray announced St. Louis Cardinals games from 1945 to 1969. We
imagine he's pleased as spiked punch to see Sosa and McGwire going
down to the wire, (ITAL)mano a mano(END ITAL) for bragging rights
to a chunk of 37-year-old history.
</P>
<P>
   We can picture him yelling himself hoarse in heaven: ``There it
goes . . . it might be outta here . . . it could be . . . It is! A
home run! Holy cow!''
</P>
<P>
   Boy, oh boy, as Caray would say. In this season to savor, there
has been something for every sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   The game's purists could revel in Yankees pitcher David Wells'
perfect game against the Minnesota Twins in May at the House That
Ruth Built.
</P>
<P>
   There also was Cubs rookie pitcher Kerry Wood fanning his age
against one of the more explosive lineups, striking out 20 Houston
Astros. (Can there be any doubt Caray was behind all of Kerry's
K's, as well as his 13-6 campaign?)
</P>
<P>
   The 13th perfect game in history. Thirteen wins for a rookie.
That Caray -- it's good to see his puckish sense of humor survived
his flight to the afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   For the game's historians, Caray delivered San Francisco's Barry
Bonds, who distinguished himself as the first player to record 400
home runs and 400 steals; Houston's Craig Biggio, who became only
the second player to steal 50 bases and hit 50 doubles in the same
year; Texas' Juan Gonzalez, who had driven in 101 runs by the
All-Star break; and Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr., who has joined Babe
Ruth and Lou Gehrig as the only players in history to drive in at
least 140 runs in three consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Ripken, baseball's iron man, who started his
consecutive-game playing streak the same year Caray started with
the Cubs and ended it the same year Caray bowed out, at an amazing
2,632 games.
</P>
<P>
   And leave it to Caray -- that kidder! -- to take a poke at the
buttoned-down baseball traditionalists. They saw their pastoral
illusions shattered in May when the Dodgers traded franchise player
Mike Piazza to the Florida Marlins, marking the start of a
season-long flea market with (blue and) white elephants galore.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' lineup and their front office have been nearly
gutted since Toronto's Roger Clemens lost his last game, on May 29.
Clemens should win his fifth Cy Young award this year, and it'll be
one long, fiendish winter -- Caray will personally see to that --
if Sosa doesn't win his first National League MVP award.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is smart; he knows there's a wizard working behind the
scenes to make this baseball season so wondrous. That's why he
salutes Caray after every home run he hits.
</P>
<P>
   Having surpassed Maris' record and swept two countries -- his
native Dominican Republic and the United States -- off their feet,
Sosa was asked what's next on his goal sheet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go to heaven,'' he said merrily.
</P>
<P>
   Why, of course. How else is he gonna high-five Harry?
</P>
<P>
   Karen Crouse's column appears in the Daily News four days a
week. She can be reached at (818) 713-3619.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
