<HEADER>
A5942 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GIANTS-ELLSWORTH-     09-26 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-ELLSWORTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW STARTING AT FREE SAFETY, A MAN WHO WANTS TO STAY IN THE
LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (bl) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   He calls his father the hardest working man in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty years of manual labor in a tractor factory,'' said the
New York Giants' Percy Ellsworth, who auditions for the starting
free safety job when he replaces the injured Tito Wooten on Sunday
in San Diego. ``He made sure I knew about that life. I did my three
summers at the plant as a teen-ager. No place for the soft.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth's parents raised him in a strict household with early
curfews and a respect for schoolwork. In high school, the
Ellsworths pulled their youngest child Percy off the baseball team
because his grades had slumped. Worried it might happen again,
Ellsworth never did play baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Sundays in the Ellsworth household were spent in church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially if you went out the night before,'' Ellsworth said,
smiling at the memory as he stood on the Giants' practice field.
``I remember saying that when I went to college I'd never go to
church again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended up going all the time. Still do. My parents did a
great job. I've never gotten into any trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, in the Giants' locker room, Ellsworth is one of the
most popular players.
</P>
<P>
   As Littleton Parker, his football coach at Southhampton High in
Virginia just a few miles from the North Carolina border, said,
``Percy's a gentleman and it's pretty hard to dislike him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth is also appreciated for his instinctive defensive
wisdom. You can almost discern the path worn in the carpet around
Ellsworth's locker. Call it the playbook pilgrimage. A new, or
younger defensive back will come with book in hand and Percy
answers their questions.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, for all this, Ellsworth has heard the derogatory buzz
that has surrounded his three-year National Football League career.
The off-the-record talk is of on-the-field lapses, that he is as
liable to make a big play as give one up. There are whispers that
he has had poor practice habits and lacks a consistent commitment
and drive.
</P>
<P>
   When the subject is raised, the smile that comes naturally to
Ellsworth's face dissolves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prove it,'' he said. ``Tell me where I've given up a touchdown
this year? Show me the tape of me chasing my receiver down the
field. I've made some mistakes, but nowhere as many as some other
people have. I don't know where that's coming from, but I resent
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other years, maybe football had come naturally to me and I
didn't do everything I could. But this past year, I went into the
weight room. I was never a weight lifter, but I went in there and
did everything in the off-season conditioning program. Compare my
play, my practice, my condition now to others, it stands up.''
</P>
<P>
   The riddle of Ellsworth's career is that he has size (6 feet 3
inches, 225 pounds), speed, good instincts and all of five NFL
starts _ each of them because someone got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   A high school All-American in basketball and a first-team
All-American in football at the University of Virginia, he has a
habit of being wherever the ball is _ a key attribute for a safety
_ but he gets on the field usually only in the nickel and dime
defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like my career is wasting away,'' he said. ``I never
thought my pro career would go like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Success in sports had always been a given for Ellsworth, who is
23.
</P>
<P>
   As a 14-year old high school sophomore, he made his first start
in a state semifinal playoff game. He picked off the first pass of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Percy has always had this knack for finding the ball and
taking it away,'' said fullback Charles Way, Ellsworth's teammate
on the Giants and at Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   As a Giant, he has seven interceptions in his five starts.
</P>
<P>
   His performance has not gone unnoticed around the league. Other
teams, including the Jets, have expressed interest in Ellsworth,
wondering if the Giants would unload him after Wooten had a
breakthrough year in 1997, and then, in the off-season signed a
four-year, $8 million contract. Those teams will get their chance
this winter when Ellsworth should be a restricted free agent.
Ellsworth said he wants to remain with the Giants, but the desire
to start may matter more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never want to play anywhere but the Giants,'' he said.
``It's funny because I was terrified to come here. I grew up in a
small Virginia town, I remember saying: `Please, Lord, don't let
the Giants or Jets draft me.'''
</P>
<P>
   They didn't, and neither did anyone else. He came to the Giants
as a rookie free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it here now,'' Ellsworth said. ``But I didn't get into
football to be a career back-up. I figure this winter I'll be 24
years old with three years in the league and at least seven
interceptions and 20-something passes broken up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping somebody will say: `Maybe this kid can play.'''
</P>
<P>
   A favorite of former coach Dan Reeves, Ellsworth got off to a
rocky start with Jim Fassel's staff when he missed Fassel's first
spring mini-camp and never called to explain his absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mistake that I wish I could take back,'' said Ellsworth, who
said at the time that he was attending to some personal business.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel does not seem to hold a grudge, and Ellsworth has been on
the field for more than 60 percent of all the plays in Fassel's
tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've very comfortable with Percy,'' said Fassel, who also
hinted that he was considering replacing the struggling Wooten with
Ellsworth before Wooten strained his hamstring in last week's loss
to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Giants defensive coordinator John Fox acknowledged that
Ellsworth had rededicated himself during the winter. Fox said
Ellsworth exceeded every conditioning and strength goal the team
had set for him.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said there is no easy answer to why Ellsworth hasn't already
been a regular starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not always his fault,'' Fox said. ``When your defense is
playing well, and ours was last year, you tend to go with the guy
who is in there. I understand Percy must be frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect him for never showing that to us. He keeps trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel and Fox won't say so, Ellsworth has a very good chance to
unseat Wooten beyond this week if he plays well Sunday. Although
it's something Ellsworth doesn't believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that Tito's beaten me out for three straight
years,'' he said Friday, helmet in hand outside the locker room.
``They signed him to a big contract this winter. I don't feel in
any way, shape or form that it's my job.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine Wooten fading too far from the picture _
even though his history of off-field troubles makes him a gamble
for the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   In Ellsworth's favor is the design of the Giants' defense, which
is intended to force turnovers. If Ellsworth produces in that
regard and the Giants win, the same don't-change-what-isn't-broken
philosophy that kept Ellsworth out of the starting lineup could
keep him in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish the Giants coaches had asked me about him,'' Littleton
Parker said last week. ``I'd have told them that Percy worked hard
as a youngster and was raised right. He's always become one of the
most valuable players on any team that's been lucky enough to have
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth _ plain-spoken and open with his opinions _ said he
just wants the whispers to stop and the frank evaluations to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can't do it and someone shows me that, then I'll shake
their hand and not bring it up again,'' he said. ``But until then,
I just want a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Sunday, Percy Ellsworth gets one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-98 1437EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
