u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-WHITESOX-NYT &LR;      09-26 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-WHITESOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG WHITE SOX SEEK TO PROVE THAT SECOND-HALF SURGE IS NO MIRAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't look for the Chicago White Sox in the playoffs this week.
They won't be there. But then, they aren't where anyone thought
they would be, based on their performance in the first half of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you told me at the All-Star break we were going to win
75-80 games, I'd have laughed at you,'' Ron Schueler, the White Sox
general manager, said.
</P>
<P>
   At the All-Star break the White Sox had a 35-51 record. Over a
full season that winning percentage (.407) would compute to a 66-96
record. But the White Sox have played so well in the second half of
the season (43-31) that they have a 78-82 record and Schueler can
legitimately laugh with enjoyment _ and relief. Only the Yankees
have had a better record (51-28) in that period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were awful young; we've gone through 11 rookies,'' Schueler
said, speaking of the first half. ``We just gave them a chance to
play. There was no pressure on them. The manager got to learn the
players, what they could and couldn't do. Give our scouting system
a lot of credit. We've brought up a lot of kids and they've
contributed. It was a gamble and it has worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the more prominent rookies have been 21-year-old Mike
Caruso, who became the team's shortstop after playing in Class A
last year, and Bob Howry, who became the team's closer after Matt
Karchner was traded to the Cubs. Their contributions have been
significant because they were two of the six minor league players
the White Sox acquired from San Francisco last season in the
controversial trade of Wilson Alvarez, Roberto Hernandez and Danny
Darwin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caruso has been terrific, considering he came from A ball,''
Schueler said of the team's second-leading hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 hitter is Albert Belle, who has been the American
League's most torrid hitter in the second half. After batting .278,
hitting 18 home runs and driving in 66 runs in 87 games before the
break, Belle has batted .378, hit 29 home runs and knocked in 82
runs in 74 games since.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday's games, he led the league in total bases
(388) and slugging percentage (.645), was tied for the lead in
doubles (48), was second in home runs (47) and runs batted in (148)
and was fourth in hits (195) and in batting average (.324).
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he moved up on the plate, made some adjustments,''
Schueler said. ``It took a little time. What a second half he's
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything Belle does offensively _ and he has done much
offensively in his career _ does not surprise baseball people. The
White Sox, however, have produced something that has been truly
surprising: Jim Abbott. Out of talent seemingly and out of
baseball, Abbott has made a remarkable comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled to pitch Saturday night, the player who was born
without a right hand won his first four starts since working his
way back to the major leagues, his first two victories coming
against the division champion Yankees and Cleveland Indians. Abbott
was last in the majors in 1996, when he staggered to a 2-18 record
with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   To what does Schueler attribute the stunning development?
``Learning how to pitch, believe it or not, at his age. Everything
used to be hard inside, hard inside. Now he's changing speeds,
using the outer part of the plate, learning how to throw soft.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox have also received workmanlike efforts from two
rookie pitchers, John Snyder (7-2) and Jim Parque (7-5), who had
made a combined eight starts before the break.
</P>
<P>
   James Baldwin, a relative veteran in his third year in the
majors, has been especially good in the second half, improving from
3-3 to 12-6.
</P>
<P>
   The question hanging over the new, improved White Sox is how
legitimate is their second-half surge.
</P>
<P>
   Large is the number of teams that, with no pressure, have played
well in the latter stages of a season, only to show the next season
it was all a mirage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's not what you see with Detroit,'' Schueler said,
``where a lot of kids had great years last year but didn't
improve.''
</P>
<P>
   The general manager said he would like to be able to add some
good veteran players for next season, but that remained to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a budget yet; I don't know what Jerry's going to
do,'' he said, referring to Jerry Reinsdorf, the Sox owner. ``I
think you definitely need to get a couple veterans to take the
pressure off the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   If Reinsdorf provides the cash, Schueler said he would like a
No. 1 starter and left-handed relief help. The most attractive _
and most expensive _ starters who are eligible for free agency are
Randy Johnson, Kevin Brown, David Cone and Al Leiter. The White Sox
won't have any excess funds from their attendance to spend on a
pitcher of their caliber. At 1.4 million, they have the league's
third-lowest attendance.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
