u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      09-26 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALKING ABOUT ALOU
</P>
<P>
   Now that Kevin Malone, a former general manager with the
Montreal Expos, has that job with Los Angeles, the Dodgers are
expected to ask the Expos for permission to speak with Felipe Alou
about their about-to-be vacant managing job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear they're going to ask permission to talk with me,'' Alou
said. ``I don't know what the club is going to do.'' But if the
Expos are asked and say yes, Alou knows what he's going to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the club says yes, I believe the club has some other
plans,'' said the classy Dominican, who has managed the team for
seven seasons. ``I have been with them one quarter of a century. If
they say we'll let you go ahead and talk, they're sending you a
message. I'm not looking for a job, but I have to say if that is
the case, if permission is granted, I'm leaving. That's very simple
because permission has not been granted before and I know there
have been some feelers before.''
</P>
<P>
   The Expos, strapped for money, have profited previously from
permitting their personnel to go elsewhere. Dan Duquette's 1994
move to Boston as general manager brought the Expos $500,000.
Felipe could fetch $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS BEDEVILED
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Anaheim Angels, now that you've blown another division
championship, what are you going to?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to Disneyland. We get free tickets from our
owners, and we can spend all day in Fantasyland, pretending we
won.''
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in the past four seasons, the Angels have
squandered a first-place position late in the season. In 1995, they
had an 11-game lead early in August (13 over Seattle, which
ultimately won) and still led the American League West by 6 games
approaching mid-September. Then they lost nine games in a row and
tumbled out of first. In 1997, they were in first by half a game
Aug. 15, then won 16 games and lost 25 the rest of the season and
finished second.
</P>
<P>
   This season they held the top spot for 33 consecutive days (not
to mention 38 of 57 days before that stretch) before the Texas
Rangers caught them Sept. 16 with the first of their five victories
in five games against them. They clinched the division title for
the Rangers Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S IN A NAME?
</P>
<P>
   When the Philadelphia Phillies called up Marlon Anderson to play
second base for them for much of this last month of the season, it
marked the first time a player named Anderson played second base
for them since George Anderson played there for 152 games in 1959.
It would be his only major league season. Some years later Sparky,
as he was known, became one of the game's greatest managers.
</P>
<P>
   BASES, BASES AND MORE BASES
</P>
<P>
   With Sammy Sosa reaching the 400 plateau in total bases, major
league baseball has had players attain that level in successive
seasons for the first time in 60 years. Larry Walker did it last
season. Since 1937, the only other players to have at least 400
total bases were Stan Musial in 1948, Hank Aaron in 1959 and Jim
Rice in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa also has become only the fourth player (Babe Ruth, Jimmie
Foxx, Hack Wilson) to reach 50 home runs, 150 runs batted in and
400 total bases in the same season.
</P>
<P>
   When Sosa, Juan Gonzalez and Dean Palmer played for the Sarasota
Rangers in the Gulf Coast League in 1986, their first season as
professionals, they combined for 4 home runs and 76 RBI. This
season they have collectively hit 145 home runs and driven in 432
runs.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN THE BENCH IS A PROMOTION
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Schack, a players association lawyer who has been with
the union for 16 years, longer than any staff official except
executive director Donald Fehr, is a candidate for a 10-year term
on the bench of the Civil Court of New York City. The executive
committee of the Kings County Democratic Party nominated Schack
after a sitting judge, Bernard Fuchs, died.
</P>
<P>
   Schack, 53, is running in Brooklyn, which means the nomination
is tantamount to victory. No Democrat for the court has lost there
in this century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
