 SPORTS COLUMN: FINDING A HUMAN DiMAGGIO UNDER THE MASK  
(bl) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Of all the celebrants at Joe DiMaggio Day on Sunday,
none will treat the living legend as carefully, as vigilantly, as
reverently as Joltin' Joe himself. DiMaggio has always been his own
best curator.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, he put himself in a glass case, to be seen from a
distance and not touched. He has never embarrassed us by word or
misdeed, even declining to parody himself in old-timers games and
avoiding the sitdown interviews that might show that he has little
of interest to say.
</P>
<P>
   In return, it was easy to forgive him for making cheesy TV
commercials, and we have steadfastly refused to wallow in the
rumored details of his troubled marriage to Marilyn Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   The Clipper is clean. His courtliness and reserve make him seem
a romantic reclusive, a Garbo or Salinger among the sound biters in
a game so starved for heroes that a mere honest workman like Cal
Ripken becomes an instant icon before he is shelved for a ``lack of
run production.'' Incredibly, DiMaggio's name comes up among the
transcendent athletes of our time, Muhammad Ali, Michael Jordan and
Billie Jean King.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is because there is something so elusive and elegant
about DiMaggio that he seems mythic without being that significant
an historical figure. He was one of a number of talented
Italian-American athletes of the 1930s, and even though the Yankees
had several of them, manager Casey Stengel always referred to
DiMaggio with a slur that sounded like an honorific _ he called him
``the Dago.''
</P>
<P>
   Life magazine, in an early picture spread, complimented him on
his speech _ DiMaggio did not talk with his hands. He was marked as
a role model for a nation of immigrants, a high school dropout, son
of a fisherman.
</P>
<P>
   The dignity with which he carried himself on the field was more
than matched in public as a civilian; the way he took charge of
Monroe's funeral and then ordered roses on her grave forever lifted
him above the players of Washington and Hollywood who had used and
discarded her.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio has always seemed like a grown-up. I first saw him in
the summer of 1951, when I was 13 and drawn to Yankee Stadium by
another teen-ager, Mickey Mantle. But through the course of the
game it was DiMaggio, at the end of his career, who captured my
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   He had few chances, but it did seem as if he ``drifted,'' as the
radio broadcasters would say, under fly balls. He moved, or at
least shifted his weight, with the pitch, then flowed into motion
with the crack of the bat. He would arrive at the ball just in
time, without fuss. The rest of the time in center field, he seemed
relaxed but alert of the game. What was he thinking about out
there, I wondered. Unlike me in the outfield, probably not snacks
and girls.
</P>
<P>
   The next time I saw him, I almost ran into him. This was on a
gray, chilly spring training day in 1967, in Fort Lauderdale. I was
reading a roster and his head was down to avoid eye contact as we
nearly collided in a concrete chute that led from the Yankee locker
room out to the field.
</P>
<P>
   He had been hired for public relations, yet avoided the press.
This was less than five years after Monroe's death, and she was
still a hot topic. Face to face with me, he froze; with his long,
melancholy face, the deer-in-the-headlights cliche seemed apropos.
</P>
<P>
   After an embarrassingly long time, I finally blurted, ``Not
baseball weather.''
</P>
<P>
   He blinked, took a breath and looked up. ``That's an
outfielder's sky.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, as if he were Michelangelo describing the ceiling of
the Sistine Chapel, he talked about the roof of his world, about
the danger of losing balls in the clouds as easily as in the sun,
about smog and shadows and smoke, about the line of the ball,
rising or looping, about the spin.
</P>
<P>
   Now I was frozen. I took no notes, I barely breathed, afraid to
break the spell. I think I understood (but maybe I inserted the
revelation later) that he hadn't just ``drifted'' after all, that
he was a scholar, that he had prepared for every kind of patch of
blue sky, every burst of sun.
</P>
<P>
   He paused only once, to notice I was shivering. ``Rook,'' he
roared at a young pitcher sprinting by, ``Get this man a jacket.''
</P>
<P>
   We might be talking still, but a Yankee PR official made a big
show of rescuing DiMaggio from a media ambush. DiMaggio seemed
reluctant to go. The PR man said DiMaggio was late for an
appointment. It sounded like a lie, but DiMaggio was too much the
gentleman to show the man up. He said goodbye and gravely shook my
hand.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, I sent a published account of our meeting to DiMaggio
in an attempt to get a rare long interview for television. When we
met, again at spring training, he said he had read the piece and
remembered our meeting, but didn't want to be interviewed just yet.
</P>
<P>
   But if I showed up at 10 a.m. on Old-Timers' Day in the Yankee
locker-room that summer, he would do it then. Over the next few
months, I was unable to reconfirm the date; he and his
representatives never called back.
</P>
<P>
   But I was sure he would remember and show up. This was Joe
DiMaggio! He meant what he said! The producer Brett Alexander and I
talked our show, ``CBS Sunday Morning With Charles Kuralt,'' into
letting us go to the Stadium with a crew on what was considered a
very long shot.
</P>
<P>
   He was there, waiting for us, tapping his foot impatiently.
``Where've you been? I've been here an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 10:05 a.m. We set up in the Yankee dugout, but the
public-address system was being tested and drowned our audio. This
had happened before. There was no recourse. No interview. We
explained this to DiMaggio, who lifted an eyebrow, then summoned a
Yankee official to bring him a telephone. In a moment there was
silence. Who else but the great DiMaggio could hush the Stadium?
</P>
<P>
   The rest was anticlimax. It was a long interview and I can read
my sweat in the transcript. He was cooperative, even chatty, but
his insights about baseball in his time, his fellow players, New
York in the 1930s and '40s when he owned the night, were shallow.
</P>
<P>
   He could be very precise about individual games, even at-bats
and catches, and about his various injuries and ailments, including
ulcers. He ``loved'' playing, he said, and poured into it all his
energy and emotion. But it wasn't easy, he said; he always had ``a
knot'' in his stomach because he was so shy and tense. He indicated
that those were the feelings that dominated his life _ only now was
the knot unraveling, he said _ but he could not or would not go
deeper than that.
</P>
<P>
   He had little to say about contemporary baseball, and his
wonderment at the Simon and Garfunkel line, ``Where have you gone,
Joe DiMaggio?'' seemed sad; at first, he had thought it might be an
insult, and later was flattered.
</P>
<P>
   Who could ever suggest that the truth might be simpler, that the
five melodic syllables of his name fit a lyric? Babe Ruth, Joe
Louis, Babe Didrikson just didn't scan.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter, of course, for anyone who ever found meaning
or beauty or inspiration in the grace that masked his painful
intensity and the myth that still hides the parts of him that are
merely human.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
