<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Sept. 27, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saturday, Hurricane Georges continued to forge northwest over
the Gulf of Mexico, heading for a stormy rendezvous with the
northern Gulf Coast. But as high-altitude steering winds over the
Gulf of Mexico weakened, Hurricane Georges began to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the storm will likely stay off the central Gulf Coast for
much of Sunday, churning slowly northwest while strengthening.
However, outer rain bands associated with Hurricane Georges will
reach the central Gulf States, with fitful and gusty showers and
thunderstorms affecting areas within 150 miles of the coast. Humid
air drawn inland from the Atlantic by the storm will also fuel
thunderstorms in southern Georgia and southern Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a broken line of scattered showers and isolated
thundershowers will escort a cold front into the Northeast. Before
showers arrive at the Northeast seaboard, humid, unseasonably warm
conditions will prevail. Behind the front, cool winds from the
northwest averaging 15 to 25 mph will sweep across the Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, scattered showers and a few thundershowers will
develop over parts of California and Nevada as an upper-level low
pressure system drifts eastward. North of the upper-level low,
winds will blow offshore over northwest Oregon and western
Washington, setting the stage for a mostly sunny, seasonably warm
day.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of western Kansas, where temperatures soared to 100
degrees or higher Friday and Saturday, will cool down Sunday as
clouds and showers associated with a cool front arrive.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: GROWING CONCERN
</P>
<P>
   A hurricane watch was issued late Friday along the Gulf Coast
from Morgan City, La., to St. Marks on the Florida panhandle as the
center of Hurricane Georges moved northwestward away from the
Florida Keys. A hurricane watch means that hurricane-force winds
are possible within 36 hours. By contrast, a hurricane warning
means that hurricane-force winds are expected within 24 hours. The
timing of Georges' next landfall will become more difficult to
assess as high-altitude steering winds over the Gulf of Mexico
continue to relax, setting the stage for the hurricane to slow
down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
