 FOOTBALL COLUMN: HEARST'S RUNNING HAS 49ers ROLLING  
(bl) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   San Francisco has the early look of a Super Bowl team.
</P>
<P>
   Think of all of the super 49er teams and consider this: None of
them produced consecutive 500-yard offensive games. No 49er team
had since 1961. But this bunch did against the Jets (a 36-30
victory in overtime) and against Washington (a 45-10 victory).
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta plays at San Francisco on Sunday after a bye week for
both 2-0 teams. It is an early test of National Conference West
supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has not won in San Francisco in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to win there because the 49er defense is usually
unheralded but sound. San Francisco's special teams produce big
plays. The 49ers' passing game is always of the highest order.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco safety Merton Hanks offers the prime reason no
team may catch the 49ers this season. ``Garrison Hearst is really
running that thang,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The way the 49ers play football, if they get the running game
going, it is like water to flowers. Like gasoline to a car. Like
yeast to bread. Everything rises.
</P>
<P>
   With all of their other supreme elements _ especially the
passing arm of the wily Steve Young, the fear provided by the star
receiver Jerry Rice and the brute force offered by linebacker Ken
Norton _ if the 49ers' running game clicks for them, they hum.
</P>
<P>
   It is clicking. They are humming.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, 27, is now in his sixth pro season.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in Lincolnton, Ga., and played football at the
University of Georgia. He was the third pick in the 1993 draft by
Arizona. He played in six Cardinals games before a knee injury
ruined his rookie year, and it looked as if it might ruin his pro
career. Arizona waived him in '96 and the Cincinnati Bengals
grabbed him.
</P>
<P>
   That one year in Cincinnati was torture for Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to look back,'' Hearst said, with obvious pain in
his eyes at just the mention of the Bengals. ``It was like I was
another person and player there. I did not have support, and I was
with an organization that wasn't at its best. And a lot of it was
my fault because I did not respond or play well there.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco signed him as a free agent last year and he
promptly rushed for 1,019 yards, the first 49er running back to top
1,000-yard rushing yards since Ricky Watters in 1992. In the 13th
game, Hearst broke his left clavicle and missed the next four,
including the playoffs. At that time, only Barry Sanders of Detroit
and Dorsey Levens of Green Bay had outrushed him.
</P>
<P>
   He is back now and he looks quicker and faster and more
comfortable. He is exploding through holes. He is bouncing it
outside with flair and running inside with determination. He is
catching the football, too, and breaking downfield.
</P>
<P>
   Even with last week off, Hearst ranks second in the NFL in
rushing with 325 yards on 42 attempts (187 rushing yards against
the Jets, 138 versus Washington). That is the most yards any 49er
back has gained in the first two games. It is the most for an NFL
back in Weeks 1 and 2 in the '90s. Hearst is averaging an
incredible 7.7 yards a carry.
</P>
<P>
   He is 5 feet 11 inches, 219 pounds. He does not look that big,
but he packs a punch. He is soft-spoken and hard-working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garrison Hearst is just a good running back,'' Steve Mariucci,
the 49ers' head coach, said. ``I mean, a really good back. He has
strong balance. He's hard to tackle. He feels more comfortable with
us this year. He is going to have a heck of a year if he stays
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers are showing that they know what they have in Hearst
and how to use him. He gets the ball often enough in both the
running and passing game. He gets it frequently in ways where he
can run with the football outside the defense, on the edges. Then
he explodes. He looks faster than he did before his injuries. That
is rare in football.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not that big,'' Hearst said, smiling. ``But my heart
is much bigger than most. I've got the big guys in front of me and
that's all I need.''
</P>
<P>
   He gives the 49ers what they need: a go-to-back. The water, the
gasoline, the yeast. If he keeps this up, the 49ers could gain
home-field advantage throughout the playoffs in the National
Football Conference. And reach way beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   They play a Falcons team that has not allowed a 100-yard rusher
in 10 consecutive games, a team that has won 7 of its past 8 games
and a team with a running back of its own who is running wild.
Jamal Anderson has rushed for 162 yards in his first two games;
last season he rushed for 75 in his first two.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco feels prepared. It is 12-4 versus Atlanta in the
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has only four games all season against playoff
teams from a year ago (at Green Bay and at New England, and home
against the Giants and Detroit). Right now, Green Bay looks like
the only team that can handle the 49ers. We are talking potential
for a 15-1 San Francisco regular season.
</P>
<P>
   That is a mouthful. Right now, just a 49ers dream.
</P>
<P>
   But with Hearst running wild mixed in with the rest of the
49ers' jewels, it is quite possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not win them all,'' Hearst said, winking.
</P>
<P>
   Run the table, then. Run that thang.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-98 1456EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
