<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6023 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-STUDY-GALA-ART-     09-26 1332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-STUDY-GALA-ART-930&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMOUS GUINEA PIGS CELEBRATE HEART STUDY'S 50TH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo of the Prince family is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRAMINGHAM, Mass. _ If all the Americans who owe some of the
length or quality of their lives to the Framingham Heart Study were
to express their gratitude by attending its 50th anniversary gala
on Sunday afternoon, the auditorium would need millions upon
millions of folding chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be fair to say that Framingham has arguably
contributed more than any other town in the United States to
advance the health of our nation,'' said Dr. Daniel Levy, the
study's director, who will be at the gala.
</P>
<P>
   So for a back-patting moment on Sunday, the study's staff will
focus not on drawing blood and measuring heartbeats and crunching
statistics, but on thanking the thousands of participants from this
midsized Massachusetts everytown who have become some of the most
famous and faithful guinea pigs in the world.
</P>
<P>
   For 50 years now, they have remained willing to be periodically
prodded, electroded, treadmilled, interrogated and _ the least
favorite test _ shouted at to blow, ever longer, into a tube that
measures lung capacity. And thanks in part to that willingness,
medical knowledge has so advanced that it has helped cut the
American death rate from cardiovascular disease by more than half
over the last 30 years, Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   Though cardiovascular disease remains the country's leading
cause of death, that death rate continues to drop, according to
1996 statistics published by the National Heart, Lung and Blood
Institute, which sponsors the Framingham study.
</P>
<P>
   When the U.S. Public Health Service, concerned about the soaring
coronary disease rate, began the study in 1948, no one in that
meat-eggs-and-butter era had documented the harmful effects of
cholesterol. Nor had they cemented the link between heart disease
and smoking, high blood pressure, obesity, diabetes, menopause,
stress _ all risk factors (a term coined by the study) so familiar
today.
</P>
<P>
   Neither had anyone established how significantly exercise helped
the heart _ in fact, exercise used to be considered dangerous for
people at risk for heart disease _ and how greatly preventive
measures like taking blood-pressure medication and quitting smoking
could reduce the likelihood of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Framingham study helped scientists determine all of those
things. Its findings led to clinical trials that proved the
benefits of reducing risk factors, which in turn led to the
aggressively preventive approach to fighting heart disease that is
now in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it was the doctors and researchers associated with
the study who produced more than 1,000 scientific papers and
disseminated the information that has changed so many American
habits and saved so many lives. But, as they plan to point out
humbly on Sunday, they could have done none of it without the
people _ more than 6,000 of them still living, and about 4,000 who
are dead _ whose multigenerational cooperation helped make the
study one of the most important in medical history.
</P>
<P>
   The study's relationship with its subjects is a happy symbiosis.
Participants give their time and access to information about them
that ranges from the contents of their blood and workings of their
organs to a detailed description of their diet. In return, they
receive the knowledge that they are doing good and, every couple of
years or so, a physical exam so intensive it takes a half-day to do
it.
</P>
<P>
   The study does not offer participants medical treatment, but
rather reports all results to their doctors. No money changes
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mainly, it's an honor to participate in something that's going
to benefit people long after we're gone,'' said Elaine Prince, 76,
who went with her father for her first heart study exam in October
1948.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's a two-way street,'' said her husband, Donald, 88.
``You get a lot of examination beyond the scope of what a physician
would do, and free of charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-year participants like the Princes, among the first bunch
of 5,209 people, are known as the original cohort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how many times I've heard, `I'm an original,
you know,''' said Sue Anderson, the study's clinic manager. ``They
feel like they're celebrities.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, the study, which had originally been planned to last
only 20 years, expanded to include more than 5,000 of the original
cohort's children. And in 1995, it expanded yet again to include
more than 500 minority participants.
</P>
<P>
   It has also continually added new areas of research, so that it
tracks not only heart disease but osteoporosis, dementia, cancer,
diabetes and more. Recently, it has also shifted more toward
genetic research, using its library of more than 5,000 DNA samples
to begin examining questions of genetic causes for high blood
pressure, cholesterol and the like. It also continues to examine
new possible risk factors that may contribute to heart disease,
like infectious agents and the amino acid homocysteine.
</P>
<P>
   That flexibility is one of the study's great strengths, said
Meir Stampfer, a professor of epidemiology at the Harvard School of
Public Health. As major studies go, he said, the Framingham study
is far from extraordinary in its size; the Harvard Nurses' Health
Study, for example, looks at more than 100,000 participants.
</P>
<P>
   But the Framingham study, because it is community-based, has
been able to bring participants in for unusually close study, he
said, and has also distinguished itself ``by never being content to
just keep redoing the same thing over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Stampfer noted, it has proved a fine investment of
tax dollars: just $43 million from 1950 through 1997.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For families like the Princes, the study's evolution means that
Donald, Elaine, and four of their six children could sit in the
parlor of their wedding-cake house recently and recall the
different tests they have undergone over the years. There have been
hearing tests, memory tests, X-rays, bone scans, urology tests. A
few years ago, they recalled, samples of their hair had been taken,
though they did not know why.
</P>
<P>
   (It was a project looking for obscure trace elements and trying
to link them to disease rates, Levy said, when asked later.)
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Prince, 47, recalled a sleep breathing test that
required being hooked up to multiple electrodes all night. (The
study was part of a national effort to learn more about the
prevalence and effects of disordered breathing during sleep.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awfully hard to sleep with those things on,'' he
recalled. ``I found out that all my dreams are at the end of the
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, in the waiting room of the heart study's no-frills
clinic housed in a former convent, Cynthia Liss, a 52-year-old
secretary, had not-so-fond memories of that sleep study as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the most comfortable thing to do, but I said, `For
science, I'll do it,''' she said. ``Whatever they've called us to
do, we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is one thing the participants seem to want most, said
Marian Bellwood, a participant coordinator at the study for the
last 24 years, it is that their children now be included in the
study as well. She is asked several times a day, she said, ``When
can my children join?''
</P>
<P>
   The study's current financing contract, which runs until 2001,
does not include money for a new generation, but Levy said he hoped
the money would come through in the next round.
</P>
<P>
   As she sat in the clinic waiting room in between tests, a paper
heart with her name on it stapled to her robe, Cynthia Liss said
she had similar hopes. ``I'm just looking forward to the time they
can take our children,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
