<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6027 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PRINTERS-PREEMPTED     09-26 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRINTERS-PREEMPTED-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANHATTAN PRINTERS OUSTED FOR CLEANER, BETTER-PAYING TENANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Harold Russell has to yell to be heard above the roar
of the Miehle Roland presses churning out 25,000 brochures for an
insurance company. The pungent smell of ink envelops the shop floor
like a thick cloud.
</P>
<P>
   Down the hallway, in Russell's office at 480 Canal St., near the
entrance to the Holland Tunnel, is the black skeleton of a
100-year-old Kelly letterpress and an oak time clock in which he
punched his first timecard, at the age of 9. Earlier this month as
he passed by the ancient clock, which runs 20 minutes slow,
Russell, now 56, said he believed that time was finally running out
for the printing industry in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Russell's landlord, Trinity Church, has put him and dozens of
other printers on notice that the church will not renew their
leases in its buildings in the 70-year-old printing district, near
the Holland Tunnel. Other landlords are following suit, replacing
printers who pay $10 a square foot with advertising agencies and
other office tenants that will pay $25 to $30.
</P>
<P>
   The current real estate boom, which has sent office tenants
scurrying into industrial districts in search of cheaper rents, is
threatening to wipe out what was once the second-largest
manufacturing industry in the city. The printers say they will be
forced to move to New Jersey, or even to close, if they cannot find
industrial space close to their corporate clients, who want, in the
words of Russell, to ``sniff and touch'' the sheets as they roll
off the presses.
</P>
<P>
   Even if commercial printing no longer accounts for one out of
every seven factory jobs in the city, as it did during the 1920s,
printers say the industry does provide skilled, relatively
well-paid jobs and critical services for financial, advertising and
entertainment companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the very short years to come, manufacturing will cease to
exist in Manhattan,'' said Russell, president of the Skillcraft
Group and a third-generation printer. ``They want boutique shops.
They say printers are dirty, so they don't want us. Between
technological changes in the industry and real estate, we're really
shoveling against the tide.''
</P>
<P>
   Trinity Church, at Broadway and Wall Street, is not the only
landlord with printing tenants, but it is the largest in the
printing district, which extends west from Avenue of the Americas
to Hudson Street and north from Vestry Street to West Houston
Street. Printers occupy about a sixth of the 15 buildings and 5.5
million square feet of space owned by the church. Trinity's
decision to convert all but one of its remaining factory buildings
to office space is forcing about 60 printers to hunt for new homes.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Heyman, director for leasing at Trinity Real Estate,
said the church could no longer afford low rents and special deals
for printers. These tenants, with their heavy presses and busy
loading docks, will have to go, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The highest and best use for our portfolio is office space,''
Heyman said. ``We decided to let the charitable work of the church
be run by those who run charities. So we've been unwilling to renew
or extend space to printers. You can't have a mixed-use building
with printers. They're dirty. They make a lot of noise. The noise
drives away a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Other owners of buildings that house printers are also seeking
quieter, more lucrative tenants.
</P>
<P>
   In the garment district south of Times Square, office tenants
are pushing their way in and pushing up rents, forcing out
manufacturers. Some large printers like Tanagraphic own their
buildings and are unaffected by the roiling real estate market. But
most of the printers are family-owned businesses that lease space,
and they say the expense of moving, which can run to several
hundred thousand dollars or more, is a serious burden.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Gimbel, president of Xerographic Reproduction Center, at
516 W. 34th St., said he wanted to expand his space to 50,000
square feet from 35,000, but his landlord, who is converting the
building to office space and selling it, refused even to renew his
lease. Gimbel's company is not an outmoded print shop on the verge
of extinction; it is a computerized digital operation whose
lifeblood is toner, rather than ink.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of picking up and moving is in excess of $1
million,'' Gimbel said. ``We'd rather put that into equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Downtown, Joseph Gitto, the president of Imtech, another digital
printer whose clients are mainly investment banks, faces the same
problem. He said his landlord at 130 Cedar St., a longtime
printers' building where he has rented 32,000 square feet for a
decade, wanted him out, even before his lease expires in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   New York has been hemorrhaging manufacturing jobs since the
1950s, and many of those jobs will probably never return. But urban
planners and economic development specialists say the city needs to
encourage manufacturers producing specialized, high-quality
products with ties to local markets, like computer software
businesses, apparel makers that can produce goods quickly, or
printers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every major real estate cycle, there's somebody getting
squeezed out of low-cost space in Manhattan,'' said Hugh O'Neil,
president of Appleseed, an economic consulting company. ``But the
city's land use and development policies need to insure that some
space remains available in Manhattan for blue-collar industries
that support finance and business services, the media and the arts,
or you could have the perverse effect of making Manhattan less
attractive for those high-value activities.''
</P>
<P>
   City Planning Department Chairman Joseph Rose agreed, saying he
had opposed efforts by landlords and speculators seeking zoning
changes to convert industrial buildings to apartment houses in
active manufacturing areas in Manhattan. But there is little he can
do to stop the transformation of the printing district, he said.
</P>
<P>
   About two dozen printers have banded together with the
Association of Graphic Communications, a trade association
representing 540 companies in and around New York City, to hire a
real estate broker to find a building or buildings in Manhattan
that could serve as a new center for printers, binders and
engravers.
</P>
<P>
   Association president William Dirzulaitis said the group had
talked with city and state officials about getting help with moving
expenses and electricity costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor has been good when it comes to helping the commodity
exchange, Conde Nast and the Yankees,'' Dirzulaitis said. ``Here's
a whole industry segment that could be lost if something isn't
brought to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Many printers are wary of alternative sites recommended by the
city, like the Brooklyn Army Terminal or Long Island City, because
they are hard to reach by truck or by public transportation.
Trinity has set aside space for printers at 200 Hudson St., but
Michael Geoghegan, a broker at Insignia/Edward S. Gordon who is
working for the printers, said there was little room left there.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of celebrating the 75th anniversary of the company their
grandfather started, Larry and Arthur Paladino, the owners of
Palographia, one of the largest engravers in the city, at 175
Varick St., are desperately looking for space in Brooklyn, Queens
and Jersey City, N.J. Their landlord has refused to renew their
lease.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of small printers like myself are going to get wiped
out,'' Larry Paladino said. ``I can't go home and tell my three
kids that Daddy doesn't work anymore. I guess I could get a cart
and stand in front of all these office buildings and sell hot
dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Printers began moving to Hudson and Varick Streets in the 1920s
to escape the congestion in lower Manhattan and to be closer to the
Holland Tunnel, then under construction. At the time, nearly a
quarter of all the commercial printing in the country was done in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity Church, which had owned a large piece of Manhattan under
a 1705 land grant from Queen Anne of England, ended up with many of
the factory buildings during the Depression. By the start of this
century, the church had already disposed of much of its property,
by either selling it or giving it to Columbia University. The
church leased some of the land it kept to developers who built
printing factories. And when the economy collapsed and the
developers defaulted on their mortgages, the church bought the
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, Trinity and the printing industry have been buffeted
by technological change and the vagaries of the economy. In the
1980s, Heyman said, companies leasing 3 million of the church's 5.5
million square feet of real estate failed. Like many landlords,
Heyman said, Trinity cut rents to help printers survive.
</P>
<P>
   The church also has sought to gentrify the neighborhood, and
named it Hudson Square. In the 1980s, Trinity leased land to
Tishman Speyer, which built 375 Hudson St., home to Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi DFS, an advertising agency. Later, Della Femina, McNamee
WCRS moved into another Trinity property, 350 Hudson St. Chic
restaurants like the Buddha Bar, Hudson Grill and Triplets replaced
printers' hangouts like Renato's on Vandam and the Printer's Pub at
480 Canal St.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Heyman said, Trinity is pouring money into transforming its
largest building, 75 Varick Street, into 1 Hudson Square, enlarging
the lobby, converting freight elevators to passenger use and
installing a new air conditioning system. At 480 Canal St., Trinity
has already leased part of the building to a caterer.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mastellone, president of D&AMP;L Offset Lithography, is
particularly incensed by the conversion at 75 Varick St. Ten years
ago, he spent about $1.5 million moving his company there from
Trinity's building at 100 Avenue of the Americas. ``We were told at
the time that they had no plans to turn this building over to
office space,'' Mastellone said. ``We tried to get something in
writing, but they said they could not do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Alice Langon and her sons moved their
engraving operation, I. Scheff, to West Babylon, N.Y., after 70
years at 480 Canal St.
</P>
<P>
   George Linder, president of Linder &AMP; Co., another small printer
at 480 Canal, has decided to go to Jersey City. ``We're one of the
first to leave, but our location will be easy to find in another
two to three years,'' said Linder, a fourth-generation printer,
``because the printing industry is leaving Manhattan.''
</P>
<P>
   But most printers worry that they will lose many customers by
leaving Manhattan. Given the boom-and-bust nature of real estate,
they say Trinity is being short-sighted in ousting its longtime
tenants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just getting clobbered,'' said William Abrams, vice
president of AGW Lithographers at 225 Varick St., a Trinity-owned
building near Houston Street. ``When this building was half empty,
we still were paying our rent in a timely fashion. All of a sudden
we're not good tenants. The market will face another downturn and
we'll probably look like good tenants again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
