<HEADER>
A6033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSTON-COURTHOUSE-ART     09-26 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-COURTHOUSE-ART-780&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW FEDERAL COURTHOUSE IN BOSTON KEEPS THE PEOPLE IN MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The new federal courthouse that opened for business on
a spectacular waterfront site here last week is in many ways the
first of its kind in modern judicial architecture: a building
designed to welcome rather than intimidate, to invite the public to
stop by for a meal, an art exhibit, a film festival, a chamber
music concert or a stroll through the new two-acre ``harbor park''
that surrounds the building. There is even a floating boat dock,
although the only boat tied up there during Friday's opening
ceremony was a Boston police cruiser named the Due Process.
</P>
<P>
   The brick building, with its curving, seven-story glass wall, 21
Ellsworth Kelly paintings and more public space than any federal
courthouse in the country, promises to be a resounding success, the
expected anchor of a resurgent South Boston neighborhood. In fact,
the only cloud hanging over Friday's official celebration was the
question of whether this ambitious and creative $220 million
project might be not only the first of its kind, but also the last.
</P>
<P>
   For the second fiscal year in a row, the Office of Management
and Budget has declined even to request a capital appropriation for
courthouse construction. Plans long in the works, like an 18-story
courthouse for downtown Brooklyn, face delays and budget-driven
demands for cutbacks. Members of Congress, rarely known to stint on
their own office space, have for years tried to make the project
here a symbol of judicial excess, although its construction cost of
$200 a square foot is comparatively modest and the building came in
on budget and on time.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 people will work in the courthouse on Fan Pier. It
will serve as headquarters for the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
1st Circuit and for the U.S. District Court for the District of
Massachusetts, as well as for Boston-based federal prosecutors and
marshals. It replaces cramped and outdated quarters the federal
courts here shared with other federal agencies in a 65-year old
post office building downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Though the need for a new courthouse was clear, here and
elsewhere, the future of the General Services Administration's $8
billion, 13-year program to construct or renovate more than 150
courthouses around the country _ the biggest public construction
program since the New Deal _ is nonetheless in question. Despite
recent indications that members of Congress, pressed by community
leaders in their districts, may add some construction money to the
1999 budget, it is likely that the expansive era in which the
Boston courthouse was conceived nearly a decade ago has come to an
end.
</P>
<P>
   So in a way, the many events here this weekend _ including the
official dedication on Friday, a daylong public open house Saturday
and a Boston Bar Association dinner for 600 guests in the
courthouse on Monday night _ celebrate not only a notable new
building but a particular moment in history, an elusive combination
of time, place and personality that brought it into being.
</P>
<P>
   As the speeches on Friday emphasized, this courthouse reflects
not only the vision of its architect, Henry Cobb of Pei Cobb Freed
&AMP; Partners, but to an unusual degree that of the judges who will
work here. The driving force behind the project was Stephen Breyer,
now a Supreme Court justice but for nearly 14 years before that a
judge on the 1st Circuit. As chief judge of the circuit from 1990
to 1994, Breyer took an intense hands-on role, as did District
Judge Douglas Woodlock, a student of architectural history who
writes and lectures on the subject and received an award two years
ago from the American Institute of Architects.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview at the Supreme Court, Breyer recalled the
moment it became clear that Cobb, a partner of I.M. Pei's, was the
right architect for the job. ``Other architects, knowing this was a
public building, started talking about how many plumbing fixtures
there should be,'' Breyer said. ``Harry showed us a picture of a
one-room 17th-century brick courthouse in Virginia, with a front
porch where people gathered. We said, `Where's the courthouse?' and
he said, `That's the room behind the porch.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The idea, Breyer said, was to take the court back to the
community. ``Courthouses today are like jails, or at best like
office buildings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a courtroom, a person actually meets face to face with the
high government official who will decide what that person is
entitled to,'' Breyer continued. ``That ideal was what the building
had to facilitate. In microcosm, it's about the relationship
between judge and litigant; in macrocosm, the relationship of the
citizen to the court.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was a tall order, at once abstract and self-conscious. It
translated into 27 courtrooms that do away with the grand elevated
bench. Judges sit behind a bench, but only three steps above floor
level, the better to take part in the courtroom ``discussion,''
Breyer explained. ``The courtroom belongs to the litigants and
counsel,'' he said. ``A judge is not a king. A judge is part of the
furniture.'' Courtroom spectators will sit on benches designed to
be reminiscent of a New England town meeting.
</P>
<P>
   To this heady symbolic stew, the architect added his own
imagery. The dramatically curved 33,000-square-foot glass wall
facing the harbor, Cobb said, is intended to convey the message
that ``our system of justice is transparent; it is accessible, not
hidden away.'' The building ``is connected to the life of this
town,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The public spaces in the building have the best views, with the
glass-walled corridors creating a kind of interior streetscape from
which people enter individual courtrooms . The entire effect could
not be more different from the federal courthouse that opened two
years ago in lower Manhattan, a 27-story granite tower that is as
uninviting as it is imposing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Courthouses are inherently intimidating,'' said Judge Sandra
Lynch, who succeeded Breyer on the 1st Circuit. ``They represent
high-risk propositions for people. It's very important for the
building to be welcoming, to offset that.'' The Boston Bar
Association, which Ms. Lynch led before she became a judge, has
taken an unusual role in the project, setting up a public education
foundation that has raised more than $400,000 from area lawyers to
support community programming in the building.
</P>
<P>
   Through film festivals, symposiums and programs for children in
connection with the nearby Boston Children's Museum, the aim is to
get people into the building, Thomas Dwyer Jr., the bar
association's president-elect, said in an interview. He noted that
in recent years, rulings by the federal court here had transformed
Boston's harbor, jails and schools. ``The court has been a focal
point of community life here, and we want to help people understand
what the law is all about,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
