<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-RESEARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RALLYING TO INCREASE AID FOR CANCER RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Thousands of people who have cancer, who have
overcome it, who have lost friends and relatives to the disease or
are working in laboratories to conquer it marched in the nation's
capital Saturday to seek more money for research.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers called it the first time that all the major cancer
organizations have rallied together, summoning people to the
National Mall for a daylong series of speeches, memorial events,
educational sessions and other efforts to mobilize support for the
war on cancer, which kills about a half-million Americans each
year. One in four deaths in the United States is from cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Bill and Terri Tomoff of Crofton, Md., arrived at the rally
pulling a little red wagon. In it sat their 6-year-old daughter,
Olivia, and 4-year-old son, Ryan, whose leukemia was diagnosed two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll live the rest of our lives fighting cancer,'' Mrs.
Tomoff said. Her husband said doctors at Georgetown University
Medical Center here, where Ryan is being treated, tell them that
three-quarters of children with leukemia survive, but often with
complications from therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This rally should raise awareness of the need for funding,''
Mrs. Tomoff said. ``They are on the brink of so many new things.''
</P>
<P>
   Haruo Tsuchiya, a researcher in cancer immuno-therapy in the
oncology department at the Johns Hopkins University School of
Medicine, took his wife and children to the rally, he said,
``because it's my job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People do not realize the importance of cancer research,''
Tsuchiya said. ``They know, but they don't feel seriously about it.
This is a kind of advertisement.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the rally's sponsors have called for doubling and
redoubling federal financing for cancer research, to a level of $10
billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer spending is now about $2.4 billion a year, and the House
and Senate budgets call for increases of 16 percent and 20 percent,
respectively, next year.
</P>
<P>
   The National Cancer Institute estimates that cancer costs the
nation $107 billion, including $37 billion in direct medical costs,
$59 billion to care for terminally ill patients and $11 billion in
lost productivity.
</P>
<P>
   At noon, the ralliers heard from Vice President Al Gore, the
Rev. Jesse Jackson and two survivors of prostate cancer, Gen.
Norman Schwarzkopf and financier Michael Milken, whose family
foundation helped pay for the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be the generation that wins the war on cancer,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address Saturday, President Clinton, noting
that his mother died of cancer, urged Congress to increase
financing for research over the next five years by 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also introduced an assortment of new anti-cancer
initiatives, including a proposal by the cancer institute to let
patients participate in reviewing research grant proposals and
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also directed the institute to make it easier for
patients to participate in trials of new cancer treatments, and
called on Congress to cover the costs through Medicare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
