<SLUG> BC-CYCLING-ARMSTRONG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG IS PEDALING BACK UP THE LADDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By SAMUEL ABT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Lance Armstrong has a new philosophy _ finish what you
start _ and, he reports happily, it's working like a charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armstrong's the man of the year,'' said a longtime rival,
Laurent Jalabert, the Frenchman who ranks first among the world's
professional bicycle racers. After Armstrong finished sixth among
169 riders in a time trial two weeks ago, Jalabert added, ``He's
come back from so far down that you can't help but admire him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased so far,'' Armstrong said on the phone from Spain,
where, somewhat to his surprise, he ranked No. 4 over all in the
extremely demanding three-week Vuelta a Espana or Tour of Spain,
surging from ninth place with a third-place finish Saturday in the
same time as the stage winner, Alex Zuelle. The race ends Sunday in
Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing pretty good and I feel very good,'' he said. ``I've
been pleased and surprised at the way it's gone _ the climbs and
the time trials both.
</P>
<P>
   ``After two weeks of a big tour, I've never been top 10 before.
I've never been in the front group in big climbs, so for me it's
definitely been a success.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who turned 27 on Sept. 18, has come a long way in
this comeback season after a year away from the sport while he was
recuperating from testicular cancer, which spread to his lungs and
brain. After months of chemotherapy in late 1996, his cancer is in
remission and he said he feels fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be here if I didn't,'' he said. His next checkup is
scheduled in a few weeks, probably in Europe after his major goal
of the season, the world championship road race in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been quite amazing,'' said Johnny Weltz, Armstrong's
coach with the U.S. Postal Service team. ``He's better now than he
was before he got sick. In this race you've got most of the best
climbers in the world. So if you're up there with them after two
weeks of racing, it's because you're climbing very well yourself.
It's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong brushed off speculation that he had planned to use the
Vuelta as a training race for the world championship, and would
drop out after two of the three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always planning on doing the full three weeks,'' he
insisted. ``After I came back to Europe in July, that was the only
goal I set for myself: to finish every race I entered.'' He has,
too, from a fourth place in the Tour of Holland to results back in
the pack in the August one-day classics.
</P>
<P>
   His new determination can be traced to the Paris-Nice race in
March, where he dropped out on the first road stage after leading a
long chase in cold and rainy weather. While Armstrong has not
publicly explained his reasons for withdrawing and heading home to
Austin, Texas, he did some soul-searching before he returned to
Europe in June and won the Tour of Luxembourg and a minor race in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the advice of his doctors, he did not compete in the Tour
de France in July but continued training in the United States,
where he won the Cascade Classic and rode a strong support race to
help a teammate, George Hincapie, finish first in the United States
professional championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Paris-Nice, I really felt that I left a quitter, and I
didn't like that feeling,'' Armstrong said from Spain. ``So I said
to myself, `I can't put any pressure on myself to perform, but I
have to finish.'
</P>
<P>
   ``My approach to the bike now and the whole sport is that I try
to relax instead of worrying. It's better that way. In the spring I
was so serious, so concerned about the comeback _ whether or not it
was going to work and whether or not it would be considered a
success _ I think it got to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now I just train hard and focus on the other things that
you have to do and race hard. That formula seems to be working.
It's a long season. I said to myself, `If I come back, I have
plenty of time to get results,' and that's where we are now.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has signed to race again next year for U.S. Postal
Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable with this group,'' he said. ``It doesn't have
a lot of internal pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise he is looking ahead only to his honeymoon, probably in
the Caribbean in late fall. It was delayed by his race schedule
after his marriage to Kristin Richard in May.
</P>
<P>
   His remaining races before the season ends in late October
include the Paris-Tours classic, the Tour of Lombardy and
especially the world championship in Valkenburg, the Netherlands,
on Oct. 11. The course, including 17 climbs of the tiring Cauberg
hill, is considered to be tailored for strong riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard it's a good course for me,'' he said, ``but I
really don't know what's good for me or not. I've seen it. The
Cauberg is a pretty awesome climb _ doing it 17 times will be
tough. But I plan to be there and plan to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've finished two world championships. One of them I won and
the other I was seventh. I'm always in the thick of it when I
finish.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
