<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-FLA-KEYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA KEYS REVIVED AFTER DESTRUCTIVE NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also HURRICANE-CARIB.) 
(bl) 
 By JIM CARRIER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY WEST, Fla. _ Thousands of residents woke to a sultry sea
breeze and a giant mess Saturday after Hurricane Georges blasted
the southern half of the Florida Keys on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of homes were destroyed, and half a dozen yachts were
sunk during 18 hours of winds up to 100 miles an hour, but no one
was reported killed or seriously injured. Countless trees were
uprooted, power lines were toppled and roofs ripped apart, but by
Saturday afternoon power was returning in zones throughout the
string of low islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're alive,'' said Kelly DeFore, who weathered the winds and
six-foot surge of ocean water inside a used Greyhound bus parked on
an oceanside dock on Cudjoe Key. The bus began to float at dusk
Friday when winds were their strongest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like we were in a sail boat,'' she said. Ms. DeFore
and her partner, Michael Horn, lost everything they owned.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. 1, the sole highway that connects Key West to Florida's
mainland, along a long string of low-lying islands and bridges, was
being reopened in stages. It was covered with five feet of water in
places during the storm, and property ranging from sofas to hot
tubs to motorboats floated onto and blocked the road.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 30,000 people who evacuated early in the week were
expected to return over the next few days. Full power restoration
could take a week. A curfew remained in effect in downtown Key West
after looting was reported, but many residents were out walking,
driving and cleaning up. The National Guard and state troopers were
brought in.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe County officials attributed the low casualty rate to the
fact that the hurricane did not cross the Keys with full force, and
that tides were moderate, reducing the surge of seawater that comes
after the eye has passed.
</P>
<P>
   Officials estimate that half the island residents heeded
evacuation orders, leaving 35,000 throughout the Keys and 12,000 in
Key West.
</P>
<P>
   The areas of the Keys that were hit the hardest appeared in the
50-mile stretch between Marathon and Key West. The hurricane's eye
brushed the southern coasts of the islands, and the fierce
counter-clockwise winds coming from the east and south did most of
the damage. Waterfront homes and trailers that faced the Florida
Straits were beaten by both waves and winds.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeFore and Horn said everything they owned was now piled in
the mangroves. Parts of their 90-foot reinforced dock were on U.S.
1. Their boats floated away in the storm.
</P>
<P>
   In Key West, the picturesque Houseboat Row, a collection of
floating homes and rental units, was largely destroyed. The row has
been the focus of a contentious battle between state and local
officials over the lack of sewage treatment. Many in Key West
wanted the row to remain, but the question may have been resolved
by the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably won't replace the power and cable,'' said Kevin
Boswell, a 16-year resident who surveyed a floating pile of foam,
furniture and walls in the shallow water along the island seawall.
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner, near the Key West Airport, Joe Hanlin was
sitting in his 22-foot sailboat that came to rest high and dry on
the grounds of a Best Western motel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call the boat the Wayward Wind,'' he laughed. ``Next time,
I'm going to high-tail it out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the ocean side of Cudjoe Key, 22 miles from Key West, a group
of nine trailer-court renters wandered around their piles of trash
in a collective daze.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just moved here last month from Philadelphia,'' said Mike
Devlin. Their trailer, full of new furniture, television sets and
appliances, was in ruins. ``I start work Monday at a new job _ if
it's still there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Dean, a neighbor, said he watched from his trailer while
the water rose to cover his $18,000 Harley Davidson motorcycle,
then he went out and sat on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If God was going to take my Harley, I was going to go with
it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
