<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FENCING-TAUSIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORKER HONES EPEE SKILLS WITH BEST COMPETITION HE CAN FIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 6 feet 4 inches and 180 pounds, with a neat Vandyke beard, a
ponytail, two earrings on his left ear and one on his right, Justin
Tausig looks like one of the Three Musketeers.
</P>
<P>
   The comparison is fitting because this 28-year-old native New
Yorker is an epee fencer who has lived the last five years in Paris
to better learn his craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be the best you can, you have to compete against the best
competition you can find,'' Tausig said during a recent vacation in
New York. ``In basketball, that would be the NBA. In fencing, you
have to go to Europe, to Germany, Italy, France or Hungary. France
has the depth in epee and a training system that gives them
depth.''
</P>
<P>
   Tausig will be a member of the U.S. team at the 1998 world
championships Oct. 5-11 in Chaux de Fonds, Switzerland. He joins
two other New Yorkers, Jon Normile, a three-time national champion
and 1992 Olympian, and Ben Atkins, a two-time national champion, on
the men's epee team, as well as Weston Kelsey of Brush Prairie,
Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Tausig (the first syllable rhymes with ``now'') went to a
college rich in fencing tradition, New York University, and
graduated in 1993 with a degree in archeology. He now ranks third
among Americans in epee and considers himself among the top 70 in
the world. On the French circuit in January, he finished fifth, a
creditable showing for the only amateur there.
</P>
<P>
   By modern standards, he is certainly an amateur. He says he
receives a grant of about $2,000 a year from the U.S. Fencing
Association, the national governing body, and a similar grant from
the U.S. Olympic Committee. He gets energy bars and T-shirts from
PowerBar and the remaining support from his parents. He pays for
much of his travel in frequent-flier miles.
</P>
<P>
   As for his personality, Tausig acknowledges he can be hard for
some to take. ``I think I provoke a strong reaction in people,'' he
said. ``You love me or you hate me. I'm very passionate about the
things I do. I can be somewhat off-putting or intimidating. I
certainly don't mean to be, but any reaction to me in the U.S. is
amplified in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   That does not derail him at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a quick-fix sport,'' he said. ``There's such a
demand for experience. The technical level of the sport is very
high. You may have a great attack or a great defense, but your
opponent is always trying to prevent you from using your strength.
I think I'm good, absolutely, but I want to be great. That's why
I'm training in France. It's the level of competition, the level of
training.''
</P>
<P>
   Fencing took over Tausig's life just before he turned 13. He
read a newspaper article about Giorgio Santelli, a 1920 Olympic
gold medalist and son of a fencing champion. He was so impressed
that he looked up Santelli and called him. Santelli said to drop
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``That day,'' Tausig said, ``he taught me the basics. He said,
`You're going to be my new student.' I don't take orders very well,
but I couldn't say no to him. I'm not a rebel or a nonconformist.
But I've always kind of gone my own way. I never did something
because everyone else was doing it or no one else was doing it. It
was just that I had to do it on my terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he was different. The next two years changed my life. He
never had a son who fenced competitively, and in his day fencing
was passed on from father to son. He took me into his family and
treated me as a son. He taught me not only about fencing, but about
life. If I hadn't met him, I can't imagine what I'd be today.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 15, he died. To this day. I'm proud I was his last
student, that he had not only faith in me, but respect for me. When
you're that age, you don't have a lot of belief in yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Tausig said his immediate goal was to compete in the 2000
Olympics. ``Then I figure to move back to the U.S.,'' he said.
``I'm not sure what I would do. I could be in a swashbuckling
movie. Maybe I could coach a little. And I'd like to write. I'm
writing a murder mystery set in Paris. It will be a great movie. I
love writing because it gives me a way to express myself and be
creative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fencing does that, too, but within the restrictions of a
sport. If I just fenced, maybe I could create more, but you can't
do just one thing. At least I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Tausig hopes to convince Americans that fencing is a major
league sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans aren't good in fencing because it's not part of our
culture,'' he said. ``It's a relatively obscure sport in the U.S.
You tell Americans you're in fencing and they think you're selling
watches in Times Square.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
