<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-TESTAVERDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EFFICIENT TESTAVERDE FINDS `RIGHT SPOT' FOR JETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla.)  (bl) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vinny Testaverde is surrounded by the trappings of his youth,
when he could steamroller Sewanhaka High to victory by force of
will. But now, at age 34, playing for the team whose legendary
quarterback's picture used to adorn his bedroom wall, Testaverde is
happy being a smart veteran _ and just being happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I loved about last week,'' he said, ``is that from the
first snap of practice till the game started, I enjoyed it. I
allowed myself to enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, he still longs for the downfield bomb, even after four
touchdown passes in his New York Jets debut last Sunday, a 44-6
victory against the Colts. But he is not even sure whether he will
be the quarterback again next Sunday when the Jets return from a
bye week to face the Miami Dolphins. Glenn Foley is the designated
starter, and if he is healthy enough following a rib injury, he
will take on Miami in what could be a pivotal game.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde has also demonstrated something else in his week of
leading the team: pride. He talks reluctantly about himself. He has
never even been one to celebrate unduly when things were going
right _ he always worried that his fortunes could change. For him,
they often did. It has been a career of many lows, including his
first six years at Tampa Bay, and then a Pro Bowl selection two
years ago with Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, people were saying, `Some of those touchdown passes
didn't go very far,''' said Testaverde as he reflected on his
performance last week. He joked that Leon Johnson's 82-yard catch
and run started with a pass ``that only went 3 yards.''
</P>
<P>
   But Testaverde said, ``I got it to him in the right spot, and
put him in position to run.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to get it to the players in stride,''
Testaverde continued. ``Sometimes it sounds easy and it looks
easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, Wayne Chrebet's little 8-yard score off a
pass, most of it a run, half of that a dive over the goal-line
marker.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, I led him, so he could catch it in stride and make
something happen once he got it. It wasn't behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also a 1-yard lob to Kyle Brady, who was alone in the
end zone.
</P>
<P>
   What Testaverde really was proud of, though _ and coach Bill
Parcells thought was his best play _ was standing in the pocket and
checking off his receivers on Keyshawn Johnson's 11-yard touchdown.
One receiver was covered, then another, then another. As Testaverde
waited, the pressure from the pass rush increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to move to my right when the pressure started,'' said
Testaverde. ``Then I hit Keyshawn. He wasn't my primary receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't tell Keyshawn that,'' quipped Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   There was something else about that day's performance, in which
Testaverde completed 12 of 21 passes for 203 yards, that Parcells
loved.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first fumble recovery; that was a big play,'' Parcells
said.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde pounced on a fumble by Curtis Martin, and prevented a
momentum shift on the Jets' opening series. Instead, one play later
Testaverde tossed his touchdown pass to Leon Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde played a smart, efficient game. These are not
adjectives that always tripped lightly off the tongue in describing
the 6-foot 5-inch, 238-pounder. Big plays and bad plays always
seemed to be in equal measure. Also, his size tends to make
observers think of him as a big-play sort of guy. He doesn't exude
subtlety.
</P>
<P>
   He does, however, have a stomach that used to churn incessantly
_ despite his heroic stature at Sewanhaka, in Elmont, N.Y., a long
pass from the Jets' training complex; or his Heisman Trophy season
at Miami, or his selection as the league's overall No. 1 draft pick
of 1987 by Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things Coach Marchibroda told me; as hard as I
worked at the game, I needed to enjoy it more,'' Testaverde said of
his epiphany two years ago when he played for the Ravens under Ted
Marchibroda.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would see how I would get down on myself for a bad play,''
Testaverde said. ``Now I'm trying to be as happy after a good play
as unhappy after a bad play.''
</P>
<P>
   In his two seasons under Marchibroda, and his big game with the
Jets, Testaverde's touchdowns-to-interceptions figures have
improved dramatically _ he has tossed 55 touchdowns to only 35
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want it to be my regret _ that I'll retire one day and
look back and say I should have enjoyed the game,'' said
Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe even his father, Al, is learning how to enjoy watching his
son. Ten years ago, Al Testaverde went to a game in Tampa to watch
Vinny. Al got a heart attack. He is usually so stressed when Vinny
plays that he decided after that not he would not even watch his
son on television.
</P>
<P>
   But he watched last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a little bit,'' said Vinny. ``If I wasn't playing for the
Jets, he probably wouldn't have watched.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps it's a start after all these years, for father and
son.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
