<SLUG> BC-TRI-IRONMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRONMAN TRIATHLON GROWS; IT'S NOW 20 AND STILL BRAGGING 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By VINCENT M. MALLOZZI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On that February morning in 1978, only 15 sets of footprints
dotted the shores of Waikiki. To every man fit and brave enough to
take the challenge went three sheets of paper listing a few rules
and a course description.
</P>
<P>
   Scrawled on the last sheet of paper were these words: ``Swim 2.4
miles! Bike 112 miles! Run 26.2 miles! Brag for the rest of your
life!''
</P>
<P>
   Then came a single gunshot, and the challenge was under way.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven hours 46 minutes 58 seconds later, Gordon Haller, a taxi
cab driver on most days, a local hero on that day, became the
world's first Ironman Triathlon champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't seem like such a big deal at the time,'' said the
former Navy commander John Collins, who created the Ironman and
placed ninth among the 12 finishers of the inaugural run. ``I mean,
I remember that first year before the race, we gave swimming
lessons to some of the guys from the back of a lifeguard boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, the Ironman Triathlon has emerged as one of
the most intriguing and recognizable sporting events in the United
States. Having grown in tandem with fitness-conscious America the
past two decades, the grueling spectacle now has a field 100 times
its original size.
</P>
<P>
   Next Saturday, nearly 1,500 triathletes from around the world,
ages 18-80, will sink their footprints on the shores of Kailu-Kona,
where the event is now held. The race will be televised in more
than 50 nations including Russia, South Africa, Japan, Korea and
Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of Saturday's competitors, aiming for a top prize
of $35,000, or all the personal satisfaction money can't buy,
earned their spots in qualifying races worldwide, leaving in their
dust almost 50,000 Ironman applicants who were turned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not, `If I can do it', but, `How can I do it,''' said
55-year-old Leon Okurowski, a financial executive from Concord,
Mass., who flew to Hawaii three weeks before the race to get
acclimated to the course and train in the intense heat and windy
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to this race is knowing how to expend your energy,''
said Okurowski, who is using his appearance in the race to raise
money for the Joslin Diabetes Center in Boston. ``What you need to
know most of all is how to temper your energy to the conditions of
the course.''
</P>
<P>
   Okurowski, who trains 12-18 hours per week, is one of 150
competitors who have joined the field via a lottery to insure that
average Joes are represented. In addition, some 20 celebrity
invitations are sent out to help promote the event.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, the celebrity list has included the Denver
Broncos' owner, Pat Bowlen; the former NFL players Butch Johnson
and Darryl Haley, the astronaut Bill Gregory; New Mexico Gov. Gary
Johnson; actress Alexandra Paul, and Benjamin Kendrick, the judge
who presided over the Marv Albert trial.
</P>
<P>
   For Saturday's anniversary race, the celebrities include Mike
Adamle, a former football standout at Northwestern University who
later played in the NFL and is now a sportscaster, and David
Bailey, the Michael Jordan of motocross racing in the 1980s who
became paralyzed in a racing accident and will compete in a
wheelchair along part of the course.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Collins, the man who created the Ironman race
after a dispute with some of his Navy buddies back in 1978. At the
time, Collins and company debated as to whether runners, swimmers
or cyclists were more fit. At an awards banquet that year, Collins
issued a challenge, proposing to tie together the three toughest
endurance races in Hawaii: the 2.4 mile Waikiki Roughwater Swim,
the 112-mile bike race around the island and a run of the Honolulu
Marathon course's 26.2 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said the gun will go off about 7 a.m., the clock will keep
running, and whoever finishes first we'll call the Ironman,'' said
Collins, who named the race after an elderly long-distance runner
he and his running mates had nicknamed Ironman.
</P>
<P>
   In the next two years, a Sports Illustrated article describing
the Ironman and coverage of the event by ABC's ``Wide World of
Sports'' raised global interest in Collins' challenge, and
suddenly, a sport was born. Perhaps the most enduring moment of the
race came in February 1982, when Julie Moss collapsed as she headed
toward the finish line of a nationally televised race. Passed by
Kathleen McCartney for the women's title, Moss stole the hearts of
fans and competitors by crawling across the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, now 62, will run Saturday's race with his wife, Judy,
and their son, Michael.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone asks how I earned my spot in the race, tell them I
qualified back in 1978.'' said Collins. ``Hey, I finished ninth in
the world that year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
