u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SENATE-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      09-26 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING `LIBERAL' AS EPITHET MAY FAIL D'AMATO THIS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also moving in ``p'' news file.) 
(bl) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the very first sentence of a commercial that he
unveiled on the very first day of his general-election campaign,
Republican Sen. Alfonse D'Amato signaled his plan of attack on his
Democratic challenger, Rep. Charles Schumer. To anyone who had
followed D'Amato's previous campaigns, or the candidacies of a
dozen Republicans across the nation who read from the same
strategic playbook, it was anything but a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck Schumer's a New York City liberal, and he proves it
every day,'' the announcer proclaims, as the word ``liberal,'' in
bold block letters, rolls across the screen. Since then, virtually
every campaign statement, television advertisement and speech by
D'Amato that mentions Schumer has been larded with the word.
</P>
<P>
   In casting the race in such ideological terms, and using a word
that is so loaded with often negative political imagery,
particularly in upstate New York, D'Amato and his chief political
adviser, Arthur Finkelstein, have reprised a strategy that helped
the Republicans become the majority party in Congress in 1994 and
led to the re-election of D'Amato in 1992 and the election of Gov.
George Pataki in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But many political analysts believe that it is a strategy that
has lost its bite. In 1996, a half-dozen of Finkelstein's clients
who used variations on the liberal theme lost their elections. This
year, D'Amato is the only major Republican running nationally to
have, so far, built a campaign on attacking an opponent as liberal,
according to Charles Cook, the editor of the Cook Political Report,
which monitors congressional campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general feeling is that this has sort of run its course,''
Cook said. ``It's doesn't work so much anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., who withstood a challenge in 1996
directed by Finkelstein that characterized him as liberal, said the
line of attack has ``just become tiresome to people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems hackneyed and it seems like the same old poison
politics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, it seems fitting that the strategy that
Finkelstein and D'Amato employed so successfully in the 1990's
should be getting one more, perhaps final, test in New York. It was
D'Amato's defeat of Robert Abrams in 1992 and Pataki's defeat of
Gov. Mario Cuomo in 1994 _ both in campaigns that demonized
liberalism _ that led many politicians to conclude that liberalism
was no longer the powerful ideological and political force it once
was in one of the nation's most liberal states.
</P>
<P>
   Yet New York, or at least this New York race, would seem
particularly ill suited for this kind of attack. And in Schumer,
D'Amato is facing an opponent who has closely studied D'Amato's
political style. In Congress, he cast a series of strategic votes _
restricting illegal immigrants, favoring a federal death penalty,
deregulating banks and the securities industry _ that, apart from
presumably reflecting Schumer's genuine beliefs, were calculated to
deflect Republicans' efforts to categorize him as a liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, many analysts say, D'Amato will find it more difficult to
present Schumer in stark ideological terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will lose in New York,'' said Robert Shrum, the
Washington Democratic consultant who worked for one of Schumer's
rivals for the Democratic nomination, Geraldine Ferraro. ``If
Schumer is out there arguing real issues, and D'Amato is saying,
`Liberal, liberal, liberal,' we're going to start saying Senator
Schumer. People are not buying these labels.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato and his advisers strenuously disputed that argument,
asserting that the tactic continued to enjoy political potency _
especially outside Manhattan _ and that Schumer was another in a
long line of liberal candidates nominated by the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard anything so silly,'' said D'Amato, who
championed this approach in contests across the nation when he was
chairman of the Senate Republicans' campaign committee in 1995 and
1996. ``Somebody who is running on the Liberal Party line. Somebody
who has proclaimed themselves as liberal over the years. Someone
whose votes opposing welfare reform, opposing workfare, opposing
mandatory sentences for violent criminals. Why don't you write that
down?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you ask him why he calls me a conservative, a
right-winger?'' D'Amato continued. ``To suggest that somehow this
is some terrible offense to characterize him as a liberal is
preposterous.''
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of demographics, the number of New York voters who
identify themselves to pollsters as liberal _ about 22 percent _
has remained essentially unchanged in surveys and exit polls taken
since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   But in truth, political strategists say, the constant use of the
word liberal by D'Amato has to do with more than ideology. It is
also intended to reinforce D'Amato's strategy of turning upstate
voters, who as a rule are more conservative than voters in New York
City, against Schumer. In that regard, the word ``liberal'' is
meant to conjure up a series of urban images that D'Amato's
advisers say are alien to the rural and suburban stretches of
upstate: crime, government spending, welfare, ethnic diversity and
public disorder.
</P>
<P>
   And it seems likely to play to what Schumer's own advisers have
worried is a liability for the congressman among many voters north
of New York: the fact that he is a Jewish politician from Brooklyn,
making him very different from the people whose votes he is trying
to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people wonder whether being Jewish from New York City
makes it more difficult to pull upstate votes,'' Cook said. ``And
to the extent that you're talking about a New Yorker being liberal,
liberal, liberal, that's an inference you can draw. I think it's
something nobody is talking about, but everybody is thinking
about.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato's aides said they were playing to the state geographic
rivalries, and had no intention of stoking ethnic or religious
divisions in the state. Indeed, D'Amato has long been known as a
champion of Israel, and most recently has led the fight to recover
assets of Holocaust survivors that were held in Swiss banks. Polls
have shown him to be extremely popular among Jewish voters.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 20 years, Republicans have used the ``liberal'' label
to undermine Democrats, forcing them to chose between the historic
base of their party and the evolving segment of blue-collar and
middle-class voters who have come to decide elections.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bill Clinton who first began to construct a defense
against those charges in 1992, in a strategy that Schumer has
appropriated: identifying himself with issues that play against
type. D'Amato has tried to counter that by picking votes from the
early years of Schumer's career, before liberalism fell into
disfavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck Schumer's record is just crying for conversation,'' said
Kieran Mahoney, one of D'Amato's senior political advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are signs that times are changing. John Zogby, the
Syracuse-based pollster, contends that the specter of liberalism in
New York has been replaced by the specter of House Speaker Newt
Gingrich. ``The Contract With America and the Republican Revolution
gave most New Yorkers something to be more fearful of than
liberalism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Zogby is correct, D'Amato is in for a difficult six weeks.
And that is the view of a well-known Democrat who is now working as
a lawyer in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing they have going for them is the cheap labels,''
Mario Cuomo said. ``But they're all four years old. This isn't
1994.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-98 1606EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
