<HEADER>
A6065 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISEASE-RESEARCH-COX     09-26 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISEASE-RESEARCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CANCER DEMONSTRATION FOR PUBLIC AWARENESS _ AND DOLLARS
 &HT;    For immediate release. Resending for those who need it.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As cancer survivors participated this weekend in
``the March,'' a nationwide demonstration against the disease,
organizers of the affair had their eyes on more than $14 billion
the government spends each year on medical research.
</P>
<P>
   Many cancer survivors feel that given the number of lives it
takes, the disease does not get a fair share of federal research
funds distributed by the National Institutes of Health (NIH), said
Ellen Stovall, president of the March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we feel we are getting a disproportionately small
share,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The main purpose of the March, she said, was to raise public
awareness of the need for increased government funding for
research.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to an actual event on the Mall in downtown
Washington on Saturday, the nationwide show of force included
satellite events in more than 150 other U.S. cities.
</P>
<P>
   The event was supported by celebrities such as retired Army Gen.
Norman Schwarzkopf, honorary chairman of the event, and television
newsman Sam Donaldson, both survivors of prostate cancer, as well
as numerous corporate sponsors, including some pharmaceutical
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Patterned after the annual Earth Day expressions of concern
about the environment, the March was an attempt to bring together
support from different groups that have traditionally lobbied
independently, sometimes competitively, for research dollars for
specific types of cancer, said Stovall, who founded and heads the
National Coalition for Cancer Survivorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know from the advance reports that 500,000 people will
participate nationwide,'' Stovall said. She said supporters were
organizing bike-a-thons, walk-a-thons, marches, road races and
rallies around the country.
</P>
<P>
   She said the idea for the event came during an appearance on
CNN's ``Larry King Live'' talk show when King asked her and
Donaldson why people ``aren't marching in the streets'' over the
need for more cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the March comes after congressional leaders and the
Clinton administration have already committed themselves to
doubling the National Institutes of Health budget for medical
research over the next five years. The NIH increase contained in an
appropriation bill still pending in Congress for next year amount
to about 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although estimates of the government investment in cancer
research since 1971, when then-president Richard Nixon committed
the country to a ``war on cancer,'' have ranged as high as $25
trillion, a hoped-for ``breakthrough'' cure has evaded scientists.
</P>
<P>
   The search has followed different tracks and moved at different
speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Some forms of cancer, most notably breast cancer, receive
substantially greater research support than others. This has been
seen as part of a ``squeaky wheel'' tendency that supposedly causes
federal agencies to be more responsive to political pressure than
to need when they set priorities for financial support or
regulatory actions.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, factors other than pressure - such as public concern or
indications a disease like HIV is spreading out of control - can
affect differences in levels of research support.
</P>
<P>
   Government data show that cancer fares less well than some other
diseases in the competition for federal funds, and far better than
some others.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal 1997, the last year for which comparable statistics
are available, the NIH invested about $1.5 billion on AIDS
research. The National Center for Health Statistics reported that
32,655 people died of the disease in 1996, the comparable calendar
year.
</P>
<P>
   That works out to federal research support of $45,965 for each
AIDS death.
</P>
<P>
   NIH cancer research funding in fiscal 1997 was $2.76 billion and
cancer deaths in 1996 totaled 544,278 _ a research expenditure of
only $5,072 per cancer death.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the country largest killer, heart disease,
took 733,834 lives in 1996, while NIH was spending $1.08 billion on
cardiovascular research _ or $1,472 per death.
</P>
<P>
   Stovall said the March ``isn't just about funding,'' and that
some participants were concerned about issues involving quality of
care and access to treatment among minorities and underserved
communities.
</P>
<P>
   She said a ``science task force'' had developed a report on the
type of research most needed to deal with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The task force, which includes representatives of private
industry, also would recommend ``some changes, perhaps, in federal
regulatory systems that impede research.''
</P>
<P>
   The report was not available last week and would not be released
until a week after the March, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
