<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DEMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS PUSH NEW THEME OF `LOST WAY' REPUBLICANS
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-RELATIONSHIP, CLINTON-REPUBS) 
 (nk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Picking up where President Clinton left off on
Friday, three past or future presidential aspirants Saturday
attacked the Republican-led Congress for focusing on the White
House scandal at the expense of passing a budget bill and other
important legislation.
</P>
<P>
   In speeches on the final day of the Democratic National
Committee's fall meetings, Vice President Al Gore, House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt and the Rev. Jesse Jackson all joined in what
has emerged as a major Democratic Party theme with the midterm
elections less than six weeks away: In the same way that
Republicans have made impeachment of the president a force to
energize their base, Democrats are using Republican demands for
punishment as their own clarion call.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a raw partisanship on Capitol Hill,'' Gore said in a
reference to the House Judiciary Committee, which is making public
reams of documents from the independent counsel's investigation of
the president as its members weigh a vote on impeachment
proceedings. ``Whoever thought we would look back at the Contract
on America as the good old days?''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt referred to his colleagues as ``the worst Congress that
ever sat in the building down the street.'' And Jackson, in a
45-minute speech packed with Biblical references, conjured an image
of low-wage workers building ``a train, a midnight train to
Georgia, and let's put Newt Gingrich on that train.''
</P>
<P>
   The three speakers were preaching to the choir, and the audience
of several hundred Democratic faithful cheered each of them
heartily.
</P>
<P>
   But their combined themes provided more evidence that Democrats
are building a campaign strategy of demonizing a Congress hungry
for Clinton's scalp in hopes of spurring a higher Democratic
turnout in the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Republicans hold an 11-seat advantage in the House
and a five-seat advantage in the Senate. Democrats are bracing for
results that would continue to leave them in the minority in the
House and Senate, perhaps by an even greater margin.
</P>
<P>
   Before the call for impeachment had gained so much momentum,
Democrats seemed content to keep the elections localized, stressing
how administration policies on education, the economy and the
environment would help the average family .
</P>
<P>
   They still make those arguments, as all three speakers did
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But with the scandal providing such a vivid and divisive
backdrop to the campaign season, they are selling the notion that
Republican zeal is blocking progress. Indeed, many of those
attending Saturday's session wore newly minted buttons that read,
``Progress Over Partisanship,'' a phrase Clinton has used.
</P>
<P>
   Of all three speakers, it was the usually more placid Gore who
seemed to turn up the heat the most. Unlike his standard remarks
that accentuate administration policies, his speech was a full-bore
repudiation of Republican ideas. He called the GOP's economic
legislation ``the recycled, reheated, rehashed Republican
retronomics that drove this nation into a fiscal ditch.''
</P>
<P>
   And chiding the Republicans for their focus on the Whitewater
independent counsel's inquiry into the president, he said, ``When
we say health care for families, they say investigations; when we
say protect the environment, they say investigations; when we say
education, they say investigations.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt, a presidential candidate in 1988 who is expected to
challenge Gore for the party's presidential nomination in 2000,
warned the audience that two more years of a Republican majority
would result in ``nothing but investigations and fishing
expeditions.'' He also criticized the Congress for accomplishing
what he described as virtually nothing but renaming Washington's
National Airport after Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Delivering more of a Sunday morning sermon than a pure political
speech, Jackson, who has run several times for the presidential
nomination, said he ``has not decided to run the race for 2000, but
I'm going to set the pace for 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, he wove a familiar Jackson theme into his remarks:
the need to improve the lives of all Americans and to redistribute
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't leave the poor behind,'' he said. ``Our moral obligation
is to include all, and leave no American behind. That's the way to
win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
