<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-CARIB-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING A TOLL AFTER THE STORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER and RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic _ Four days after Hurricane
Georges clobbered the Dominican Republic with shattering force _
and as help arrives from around the world _ this Caribbean country
is still counting its dead.
</P>
<P>
   With 200 confirmed deaths, government officials say they fear
scores more lives may have been lost as whole blocks of homes were
splintered and the storm's drenching rains flooded towns and
villages in an arc stretching as far as 100 miles from this capital
city of 3 million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the flood waters recede, the bodies keep emerging,'' said
Adriano Tejada, the chief spokesman for President Leonel Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   The government estimates that more than 500,000 homes were
damaged and that more than 500 people were injured. Thousands of
acres of sugar cane, coffee and tobacco, the country's main crops,
have been ruined. Clusters of people are camped along some of the
main roads, sharing food and trying to piece together what they can
of their broken homes. The United States and France have sent
disaster relief aid.
</P>
<P>
   The capital is pocked with damage. Roofs are gone, windows
broken, awnings torn and tattered, and huge metal billboards with
nothing left but the iron frames line the roads. But almost
magically, many houses and stores appear to have been virtually
untouched. Everywhere, though, trees and shrubs have been snapped
off, shredded and sometimes uprooted.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Ventura, the mayor of Santo Domingo who is also a popular
merengue singer with a big following among Dominican emigres in the
United States, said it was difficult to put a price on the damage
in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not quantified the damage,'' he said. ``It's
enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   In a flight over one of the most severely battered cities, San
Pedro de Macoris about 30 miles east of here, clumps of wood and
tin houses looked as if they had been smashed by an angry giant.
Scores of other houses had been turned into what from the air
looked like rows of tiny doll houses with their roofs lifted off.
</P>
<P>
   A huge sugar mill lost all but a few strips of tin from its roof
and at the Tetelo Vargas Stadium, where the Estrellas Orientales
(Oriental Stars) play the nation's favorite pastime, baseball,
racks of spotlights dangled into the bleachers and much of the tin
sunshade was gone.
</P>
<P>
   While rescue teams were trying to reach people in outlying
areas, the streets of the capital were jammed Saturday with cars
and trucks snaking past downed power lines, trees and heaps of
roofing and rubble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first day that people have really been able to
move,'' said Leonardo Luzon, 44, whose house lost its roof and an
outside wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were trees and pieces of houses blocking all the
streets. Now people are out looking for building supplies and
food.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Much of the country has been without electricity since the
hurricane hit on Tuesday, and with no power to operate pumps,
drinking water has been in short supply. At least a dozen men,
women and teen-agers were lined up with plastic jugs and pails at a
water hose at one house on the edge of the capital at midday.
Others made their way through the wreckage balancing buckets of
water on their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the water was fresh and clean, good for drinking, one
woman struggling with a heavy pail that she had filled at one of
the many water trucks that have been parked in neighborhoods simply
wagged her finger and her head in a strident no. But she was taking
the water anyway. She said she would boil it and hope for the best.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster stirred human misery and cruelty. Julio Romero, a
handyman whose tiny home on the outskirts of Santo Domingo was
destroyed, had in recent days collected a pile of lumber and cinder
blocks to begin rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   But the other night, as he slept with neighbors who put him up,
thieves made off with the material he had collected. ``They are
evil, but they are clever,'' he said. ``They prey on those of us
who are suffering, and that's how they survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolores Santos, 52, a neighbor of Romero, echoed those thoughts
as she surveyed the heap of wood beams, glass, tables and chairs
that was once her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thieves have taken everything,'' she said screaming, as if on
the verge of tears. ``They took TVs, wood, whatever worthwhile that
was left. How can people do this to each other?''
</P>
<P>
   Mothers and their children wandered the outskirts of Santo
Domingo like nomads.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica Suna led her 5-year-old son by the hand as they walked
over to survey the damage to their humble four-room home. Almost in
tears she looked at the child, who was barefoot and wearing only
blue shorts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
