<SLUG> BC-NJ-FAMILY-HOTEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS HOTEL MAKES ROOM FOR TODDLERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JANE GROSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARSIPPANY, N.J. _ At this week's staff meeting, Cathy Hart will
ask the employees at the Marriott Residence Inn here how to make
Halloween a festive occasion for the hotel's guests.
</P>
<P>
   How about reverse trick or treating, with hotel employees
delivering candy to each room? Or maybe a pumpkin-carving contest
in the courtyard?
</P>
<P>
   These are novel challenges for Ms. Hart, general manager of this
new hotel, who is more accustomed to worrying about data ports and
treadmills for the jam of businessmen in the exercise room at 6
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Those details were in place when the apartment-style hotel
opened in May, geared to the business traveler on extended
assignment, a growing niche in the industry. But to everyone's
surprise, the clients here have been mostly families with children,
who stay a month on average.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like the LaMond family from Kalamazoo, Mich., are in the
midst of relocation and waiting to close on a house. A few, like
the Van Warts, are renovating homes in the vicinity. Others, like
the Knotts, are on extended assignments and don't want to be apart
that long.
</P>
<P>
   The solitary business people _ and there are some _ seem to
function in a parallel universe. They come downstairs for their
breakfast by 6:30, when they can watch CNN in peace on the lobby
television. An hour later, the room is vibrating with boisterous
children fighting for the last box of Froot Loops and enjoying
Nickelodeon.
</P>
<P>
   For the families, the place seems to work on the principle that
misery loves company. The displaced gather in the lobby here, where
cartoons blast on the wide-screen TV and the kitchen staff appears
with hot cocoa just as the school bus pulls up each afternoon. They
trade relocation horror stories, the kind that friends not in the
midst of moving quickly find boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask how can you be so good humored,'' said Jen Van
Wart, who remains cheerful despite twin 3-year-old boys with bad
colds and a 16-month-old who has just learned to shriek. ``Well,
what choice do you have?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Van Wart compared the experience to a college dormitory,
with the distraction of children. She squirrels away quarters for
the washing machine and always seems to come upstairs with one sock
too many or one too few. She meets her new friends in the lobby for
gossip before dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The Van Warts' baby, Paige, learned to walk here, by imitating
Logan Knott, who is a month older and also took his first steps in
a hotel lobby. Now Paige and Logan toddle about in tandem, managing
not to trip on the twins' Batman cars.
</P>
<P>
   Logan's mother, Angela, set up housekeeping here in August and
won't return home to Arizona until February, when her husband
finishes installing a corporate software system. Part of the
justification for building the hotel here is the unusual
concentration of corporations nearby, including Lucent
Technologies, American Home Products and Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   The needs of the families have led to improvisation. High chairs
were clearly a necessity. So were games, toys and children's books.
In a room adjoining Ms. Hart's office there are Pictionary, plastic
foam noodles for the indoor pool and ``Rabbit's Search for a Little
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hart wrote to the local school district affirming that the
children lived here so they could enroll. And she drew up a release
form so the hotel, without liability, could accept delivery of cars
that had been transported from one address to another.
</P>
<P>
   A decision was made to allow pets, but some housekeepers won't
go into a room if a big dog is there, like the 100-pound Akita that
belongs to Gabrielle LaMond. That room is cleaned while Ms. LaMond
drives her daughter to school.
</P>
<P>
   Once there was a mix-up when a moving van made a stop here to
pick up a family's belongings, on the way to a new house. Later,
Ms. Hart went into the vacated room and discovered that a couch was
missing.
</P>
<P>
   But more than confusion, there is camaraderie. When Ms. Knott
worried about how to entertain Logan in winter, the Van Warts were
quick with advice. Go to Gymboree for mother-and-baby exercise
classes, they told her. Try the children's readings at Barnes &AMP;
Noble. And don't forget to buy mittens and a winter coat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
