u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COLLEGES-STUDY-675     09-26 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLEGES-STUDY-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. SEEKS TO ASSESS COLLEGES AND UNIVERSITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its ratings of primary and secondary schools well
established, the New York state Department of Education is
embarking on an effort to assess the state's colleges and
universities, both public and private.
</P>
<P>
   As early as 2001, the state could issue its first report
evaluating the performance of colleges. The format is yet to be
worked out, and department officials are reluctant to speculate
about specifics. But they say the wide range of institutions _ from
research universities to community colleges and trade schools _
means that the report must be more complex than the school report
cards, perhaps something more like the reports issued by U.S. News
&AMP; World Report and the Princeton Review, but somehow going beyond
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly U.S. News &AMP; World Report has taken an opportunity,
but my personal view is that the higher education community could
do a better job,'' Richard Mills, the state education commissioner,
said. ``The fact that their reports are so eagerly consumed by the
public tells me there are a lot people who want to know.''
</P>
<P>
   The department is seeking an additional $400,000 in its budget
to help pay for the evaluation efforts, which it plans to shape in
the coming year with the help of educators in New York and
nationally and with consultants.
</P>
<P>
   In the next week or two, it will name a new higher-education
advisory council that will include about 20 college presidents, the
chancellors of the state's two public university systems and other
leaders from public and private institutions. The department hopes
to use the council as a sounding board on higher education policy
as well as on the new evaluation process.
</P>
<P>
   And in February, the department plans to hold what it is calling
a ``summit'' on higher education in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Primary and secondary education are moving in the right
direction now,'' Carl Hayden, chancellor of the board of regents,
said. ``It is time to turn the focus to higher education and to
really bring the discussion of higher education issues to the
fore.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the board had already taken aggressive steps in higher
education, including its removal of Adelphi University's trustees
and the imposition of new teacher education standards, and now
planned to move even more broadly.
</P>
<P>
   Measuring the quality of New York's diverse higher education
institutions _ 260 degree-granting colleges and universities and
260 other postsecondary institutions _ is something Mills and the
regents have wanted to do for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Mills proposed a higher-education report card
that would have applied 41 performance indicators to colleges,
measurements like graduate employment rates, changes in tuition and
the proportion of students needing remedial education. But he was
criticized for proposing a ``one-size-fits-all'' approach, and it
was put on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that it wasn't yet ripe,'' Mills said last week.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he is trying to remedy that problem by recognizing
the differences and inviting college leaders to help him and the
Regents devise ways that take them into account while judging the
performance of institutions with widely differing missions _ from a
Hostos Community College, for example, to a graduate research
university like Rockefeller University.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Patton, deputy commissioner for higher education and the
official charged with leading the assessment effort, said he
expected that some criteria, like graduation rates and graduates'
scores on licensing exams, would be applied to all or most
institutions. But he said he expected colleges to define their
special goals and to figure out ways to measure whether they are
meeting them. ``It does require faculty to talk more about their
goals and objectives,'' Patton said. ``We aren't trying to tell
them how to do it. We want them to develop the methodologies.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he hoped that a framework would be in place by next year
and that assessments would begin by 2000. Any proposals will be
subject to public discussion and approval by the Regents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While many states are trying to make their universities more
accountable, the New York effort is more ambitious than most.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, unlike most state boards, the board of regents
has jurisdiction over all higher education in the state, including
its two Ivy League universities (Columbia and Cornell), religious
institutions like St. John's and Fordham, and commercial colleges
like DeVry Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   For another, many performance-measurement systems have gotten
bogged down in counting what is easy to count, like numbers of
students and scores on tests.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Newman, president of the Education Commission of the
States, a nonprofit organization in Denver that advises state
officials on education policy, called the effort a ``complex
undertaking'' _ significantly more complicated than assessing high
schools, which as a group have much more similar objectives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the states that have struggled with this haven't done
much once they have gotten past simpler measures to the more
profound question of whether students are learning what they need
to know to be effective citizens in the 21st century,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Standards have become a mantra in education. Mills, who has an
oversize set of alphabet blocks spelling ``S-T-A-N-D-A-R-D-S'' atop
the tall bookcase behind his desk, has made an art of figuring out
what they ought to be and then applying them.
</P>
<P>
   He has laid out standards for his own performance as education
commissioner. He has adopted the system of school report cards for
rating primary and secondary schools in the state. And he is
imposing strict new requirements for teacher education programs and
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   His plan to evaluate colleges, which has yet to be publicly
announced, has drawn a mixed response. Some educators, like Newman
of the Education Commission of the States, applauded it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time in American higher education, we assumed
quality, and that was a modestly reasonable assumption,'' he said.
But those days are over, he added, because of the enormous change
taking place in who is providing higher education, the new
technologies being used, the broader range of students and the very
different demands on graduates in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, we can't make the simple assumptions we've
all made that just because students have been through our
educational process they are well educated,'' he said. ``Seat time
is not a good enough measure of quality any more.''
</P>
<P>
   But others question whether another layer of measurement will be
worth the time and cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe very strongly in accountability and in people's
right to know,'' said Lois DeFleur, president of SUNY-Binghamton
and chairwoman of The American Council on Education. ``But we
already devote unbelievable resources to the accrediting process
and performance assessment and evaluation of our programs. They
have to understand the cost in time and energy.''
</P>
<P>
   L. Jay Oliva, president of New York University, offered a
similar perspective: ``There is no institution in the whole world
that spends more time looking at itself than universities,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Patton said he recognized the concerns, but added that he hoped
colleges and universities would ultimately see the system as a
benefit for them, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be an avenue for them to do better,'' he said. ``And
it will send a message to the community at large about how higher
education is improving.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
