<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL BRIEFS: FORBES SLAMS SURVEY IN ARIZ.; DISSIDENT GREENS IN
N.M.; RACE TIGHTENS IN S.C. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Tenn.)  (mk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back during the 1996 presidential campaign, Steve Forbes, the
publishing magnate, spent the better part of $4 million, much of it
from his personal fortune, to win a surprise victory in Arizona's
Republican primary. Since then, his eye now fixed on the Election
2000 primary, he has returned often to the Grand Canyon state to
meet and greet and to preach his special brand of conservative
economics.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days ago he spoke at a fund-raiser for a fellow
Republican, Rep. J.D. Hayworth, who is running for a second term in
Arizona's 6th Congressional District. And in another week or so, he
is scheduled to be the keynote speaker at the annual fund-raising
dinner of the Arizona Christian Coalition, a major force in the
state's politics.
</P>
<P>
   Is he making any political progress? Maybe not, if a newly
released presidential preference poll is to be believed.
</P>
<P>
   Taken late last month by Arizona Chamber Info, a subsidiary of
the Arizona Chamber of Commerce, it asked 231 registered
Republicans to pick a favorite from a list of party members who
have indicated that they might run in 2000. Topping the list were
Jack Kemp, the 1996 vice presidential candidate, with about 18
percent, and House Speaker Newt Gingrich, 14. Among bottom dwellers
were Gov. George Bush of Texas, with two percent, and Forbes and
Lamar Alexander, the former governor of Tennessee, each with zero.
</P>
<P>
   How soon they forget ...
</P>
<P>
   Not so, Forbes counters. He slammed the survey as ``preposterous
fiction'' and ``random selection that just doesn't cut it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a sampling of just 231 voters is on the thin side, as
political polls go. Nevertheless, chamber officials defend the
accuracy of their survey, calculating its margin of error to be
plus or minus about 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Since 52 percent of the respondents were undecided this early in
the run-up to Election 2000, the chamber officials added, there is
plenty of time and room for Forbes to improve and make another good
showing.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, maybe Forbes should forget about Arizona and
concentrate more on another state he has also been working hard _
Iowa, quadrennial home of the first presidential caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   In a new Mason-Dixon poll of likely GOP caucus-goers, Forbes and
Bush ended up in a dead heat, with the rest of the wannabe field
lagging badly, most notably Alexander, who has spent more time
trodding the Election 2000 trail than just about anybody. In Iowa a
mere 2 percent of poll respondents picked him as their favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Greens Abandon One of Their Own
</P>
<P>
   There is no state where the Green Party is stronger or more
active than New Mexico. In recent years, Green candidates, with
their appeal to environmentalists, hard-left liberals and
counter-culturists, have helped put several New Mexican Republicans
in office by stealing away the votes of dissident Democrats
concerned about the ideological purity of Democratic
standard-bearers.
</P>
<P>
   And this year they are again a political force to reckon with in
several important races.
</P>
<P>
   Arguments by Democratic leaders that third-party swing voting is
ultimately counterproductive have been ignored by Green leaders.
They contend that the only way to force Democrats to pay attention
to Green issues is to cost them elections.
</P>
<P>
   But now a raison d'etre fissure has opened in the ranks of the
Greens.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, nine members of the party issued a statement
calling on members to abandon the Green candidate, Carol Miller, in
this year's House race in New Mexico's 3rd Congressional District.
Instead, the statement said, Greens should support state Attorney
General Tom Udall, the Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't, the statement warned, the hard-right Republican
incumbent, Rep. Bill Redmond, will surely win a second term _ just
as he won his first term in a special election last year when
Greens split the Democratic vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Miller candidacy ``is detrimental to the goal of building
the Green Party'' and, in the end, will be seen by the public as
``destructive,'' the statement concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miller, a health care consultant, argued in response that
her presence in the race ``guarantees'' that Udall will take more
progressive positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole point of having third parties in political races,''
she added, ``is so that people have to take positions on the
issues. This isn't just a smile and a handshake.''
</P>
<P>
   Can a letter from nine unhappy members of a party whose
membership numbers in the thousands have any effect?
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the dissidents is Abraham Gutmann of Albuquerque,
a founder of the state party.
</P>
<P>
   More Troubling Signs for a Governor
</P>
<P>
   More re-election problems for Gov. David Beasley of South
Carolina ...
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few weeks, several Republican colleagues, some of
them party leaders, have begun to whisper that his campaign for a
second term is flagging and that his Democratic challenger, Jim
Hodges, the former minority leader of the South Carolina House,
just might be coming on strong enough to nip him at the tape in
November.
</P>
<P>
   The governor denies there is any slippage. At the same time, he
has begun to hammer that Hodges is one of the most outspoken
advocates of ``organized'' gambling, especially video poker and the
lottery, in a state where the Christian right is perhaps the most
powerful political force.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, mindful that many voters have never forgiven him
for suggesting several years ago that the Confederate flag should
no longer be flown over the state Capitol, he has begun reaching
out to members of South Carolina's many Southern heritage groups,
still an important constituency in the state where the Civil War
started.
</P>
<P>
   Never again, he promises, will he try to lower the Stars and
Bars.
</P>
<P>
   But no sooner did the governor begin to make amends on the flag
issue than a major heritage group, the Palmetto League, started
running an ad that said he still could not be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   The governor countered with an ad that tried to shift the
political focus to Hodges' veracity. ``There's a difference between
what he says and what he does,'' the announcer intoned as Hodges'
picture appeared on the screen. Then, as Hodges' face slowly
``morphed'' into the face of Clinton, the announcer asked: ``Remind
you of anybody?''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the week, a new poll conducted by the Palmetto
Project found that three of every five adult South Carolinians were
dissatisfied with the ``direction'' of the state and that, whatever
the governor might think, only one in four believed gambling was
the most important issue in the governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   The others, three of every four, said the most important issue
was education _ the issue that Hodges is hitting hardest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-98 1756EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
