<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PARKS-STATUS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE GROUP SAYS CITY OVERRATES PARK CONDITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Conditions in New York City's parks are considerably
poorer than city officials say, partly because most of the more
than 27,000 acres of parkland are never inspected, a private parks
group says in a report to be issued Monday. It found benches
collapsing, paths in shambles, landscape overrun by weeds and
almost no working drinking fountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the kinds of conditions that any New Yorker will
find on any given day walking into a park,'' said Marcia Reiss,
policy director for the group, the Parks Council.
</P>
<P>
   The council, a research and advocacy group, said the recently
released Mayor's Management Report painted a flawed and inadequate
picture of the park system. The reason, it said, is that the report
is based _ as all past mayoral reports have been _ only on
inspections of playgrounds and parks of less than six acres. This
traditional, more limited means of analysis has shown park
conditions to improve steadily, to 80 percent rated acceptable
today from 39 percent three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Parks Council studied 10 large parks not now
inspected by the city. In them, it found that only 56 percent of
park features were in acceptable condition. Many pathways, trees,
lakes, lawns and especially drinking fountains of the 10 parks were
found to be in unacceptable condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poor conditions we found in the 10 parks are a strong
argument for increased city funding for park maintenance,'' Ann
Buttenweiser, president of the Parks Council, said. ``But the first
step is broader park inspections.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's parks commissioner, Henry Stern, sharply disagreed
that park conditions had deteriorated, citing the work of 6,000
welfare recipients assigned to the parks and 25,000 volunteers. Of
the Parks Council's report, , he said, ``They look at wine and call
it vinegar.''
</P>
<P>
   But he agreed that broader inspections were ``an excellent
suggestion'' and said he was ordering a pilot program to do the
larger reviews urged by the Parks Council. The new program is to
start this fall with what the agency calls its flagship parks,
including Flushing Meadows-Corona Park in Queens, Riverside Park in
Manhattan, Prospect Park in Brooklyn, Van Cortlandt and Pelham Bay
Parks in the Bronx and the collection of parks on Staten Island
called the Greenbelt.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The commissioner said the broader inspections would be more
difficult than the checklist approach used for playgrounds. ``The
smaller sites are more ratable,'' he said. ``How do you know if a
woodland is good?''
</P>
<P>
   In defense of the current system, Stern said that playgrounds
were the most intensively used part of most parks and that the
safety of play equipment was a critical concern. The Parks Council,
which first raised private money to begin playground inspections in
the 1970s, agreed that the city ``has done a superb job of bringing
heavily used playgrounds up to standard.''
</P>
<P>
   But the vast majority of park space is shamefully deteriorating,
the council charged. In the nine parks that have drinking
fountains, the council found only one fountain that worked. That
was in Springfield Park in southeastern Queens, which has only one
fountain. Pathways were in acceptable condition in only three of
the 10 parks, and more than half the parks had a large number of
trees with dead or low-hanging branches along pathways, the group
said. Invasive vines and other plants that choke and kill native
trees were found in 69 percent of the 10 parks' natural areas, it
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the study found no abandoned cars, which a
decade ago had littered many of the city's parks.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia University's School of Public and International Affairs
joined the Parks Council in devising, conducting and analyzing its
report. Staff members from the two organizations and volunteers
visited two parks in each of the five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   The Parks Council study is part of the group's campaign to
increase public spending on parks, which was cut dramatically
during the previous administration and has recovered only fitfully
under Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani. The idea of the council performing
its own inspection gained support when the council's analysis
showed that the 85 percent of park areas not inspected receive very
little staff or management attention.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the council found that the large areas of
uninspected parkland receive more capital spending than the places
that are inspected. The report suggested that it could therefore
not be concluded that capital spending was directed toward
improving inspection scores. The report said the arrangement raised
the possibility that conditions would be allowed to deteriorate
until a major capital expenditure was required.
</P>
<P>
   ``While this study shows substantial capital investment in the
10 parks we examined, it also reveals that limited numbers of park
workers are assigned to maintain this investment,'' said Elizabeth
A. Cooke, executive director of the Parks Council. ``Without
increased personnel, we can expect deferred maintenance and the
need for continued capital expense in much of the park system.''
</P>
<P>
   Park volunteers and their organizations said they hoped the
study, and the city's commitment to follow up with its own
inspections, would be useful in their fight for more money for
parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't fault the Parks Department,'' said Susan Morgenthau,
president of Friends of Van Cortlandt Park. ``What can you do with
the lack of funding?''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
