<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VALLONE-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUTH IS ELUSIVE IN VALLONE'S STATEMENTS ABOUT PATAKI 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the night Peter Vallone won the Democratic primary
to run against Gov. George E. Pataki, he told supporters in a
speech broadcast statewide that Pataki ``wrote the Republican
Party's anti-choice platform in 1990.''
</P>
<P>
   At campaign stops, Vallone, the New York City Council speaker,
often says that Pataki has doubled state debt and doubled college
tuition. And he told reporters recently, ``Al D'Amato wrote out a
check for $3-and-a-half million in one week to George Pataki.''
</P>
<P>
   What all these statements have in common is that they are
untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone is not the first politician to cast ill-founded
aspersions on an opponent, and in fact, Pataki has been known to
toss off a few. A television advertisement for the governor, for
instance, says that Vallone voted 78 times for ``higher taxes,''
but most of those votes were to continue existing taxes. And Pataki
has been roundly criticized for stretching the truth about his
record with inaccurate claims, like his easily refuted assertion
that New York is a national leader in job growth.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor has not said anything notably inaccurate about
Vallone because, in his best Rose Garden style, he has barely
mentioned his opponent. Vallone, on the other hand, has shown what
might charitably be called a gift for hyperbole when talking about
Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another indication that Peter Vallone just doesn't
know the basic facts,'' said Zenia Mucha, Pataki's campaign
manager. ``We have warned him about engaging in these kinds of
distortions of the governor's record.''
</P>
<P>
   Going on the offensive is standard practice for a candidate in
Vallone's position: a challenger, trailing badly in the polls, with
much less money than the incumbent. But attacks based on
inaccuracies could easily backfire, exposing him to charges of
dishonesty. And in some instances, by overstating his case, he has
undercut what could have been effective _ and accurate _ attacks on
the governor.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Pataki's record on debt has drawn harsh criticism
from independent fiscal analysts, and attack ads from B. Thomas
Golisano, the Independence Party candidate, and Lt. Gov. Betsy
McCaughey Ross, the Liberal Party nominee. State debt has grown
about 30 percent during Pataki's four years in office, and it is
projected to rise more than 20 percent in the next four, but it has
not doubled, as Vallone has charged.
</P>
<P>
   The governor raised public college tuition about 30 percent in
1995 and cut financial aid for low-income students, but did not
double tuition, as Vallone has said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ragone, a spokesman for Vallone, refused to back away from
those claims. ``George Pataki has increased state debt and college
tuitions enough that if working New Yorkers aren't already paying
double, they're seeing double,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Vallone's claim about tuition took into account
tuition increases and aid reductions that Pataki proposed in 1996
and 1997, but which were defeated by the Legislature. If those
plans had taken effect, the nominal tuition would have increased by
50 percent, and the tuition actually paid by students would have
nearly doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Of Vallone's comments about the governor, his statement on the
Republican Party's abortion stance was the most patently untrue.
</P>
<P>
   At the Republican convention in 1990, Pataki, then an
assemblyman chairman of the platform committee, wrote a party
platform that supported abortion rights for the first time. He
prevailed after a bitter fight, and over the objections of the
party's powerful anti-abortion figures, including his future
mentor, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   Ragone traced Vallone's statement to an erroneous newspaper
article, and said the candidate had not repeated the mistake since
primary night.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone's claim that D'Amato gave Pataki $3.5 million is an
attempt to remind people of the connection between the governor and
the less popular senator, who sponsored his 1994 race.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, late last year, the state Republican Party, not
D'Amato, transferred $3.1 million to Pataki's campaign. While the
party's formidable fund-raising machinery was largely built by
D'Amato and his former aide, Bill Powers, now the party chairman,
it could be argued that the governor has become the chief
fund-raiser for the party.
</P>
<P>
   On that count, Ragone insisted that Vallone was not mistaken,
even if D'Amato had not actually written a check to Pataki, and he
cited a March 1 New York Times article detailing the transfer from
the party to the governor. ``Three million dollars is
underestimating what the D'Amato machine has contributed to George
Pataki,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Vallone's claim skirted a more well-founded attack: that
Pataki is exploiting a loophole in the state law that limits
individual contributions to a gubernatorial campaign to $28,000.
Many people who had contributed the maximum, or close to it, also
made large contributions to the party, money that was then
transferred to Pataki's campaign. That allowed the governor legally
to collect, in some cases, double the limit from wealthy donors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-98 1759EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
