u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-OFFICER-SLAYINGS-N     09-26 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-OFFICER-SLAYINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE DYING, DAUGHTER TELLS 911 OF POLICEMAN'S RAMPAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY and DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a typical Friday, Officer Patrick J. Fitzgerald
would leave the 34th Precinct in Manhattan, drive 90 minutes home
to Orange County, and take his 7-year-old daughter, Ashley, to flag
football practice. He was the coach, and she was the only girl on
the team.
</P>
<P>
   But last Friday, Ashley Fitzgerald frantically dialed 911,
telling the dispatcher: ``My mommy is shot. She is going to die.''
</P>
<P>
   When state police officers arrived at the Fitzgeralds' two-story
log cabin six minutes later, they discovered a gruesome scene:
Fitzgerald had shot his wife, Leanne, as Ashley called for help.
Then he shot his 4-year-old son, Shane, as Ashley watched. Then he
shot Ashley.
</P>
<P>
   Then, finally, he called a desk sergeant at his precinct,
confessed to the murders, hung up the phone and shot himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a walk through hell,'' said Maj. Alan G. Martin, a
state police commander, describing the scene at the house.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, as Leanne Fitzgerald's family began to make funeral
arrangements, state police investigators said that her husband's
murderous rampage may have been set off by longstanding domestic
difficulties. ``We know they weren't getting along,'' he said.
``They were definitely having marital problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends and neighbors, while saying the couple were caring
parents, also told of a marriage with a history of problems. Last
summer, Mrs. Fitzgerald and the children moved out of the family
house in rural Greenville, N.Y., outside Middletown, N.Y., and into
an apartment. Friends said the couple reconciled about two months
later.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Schwartz, a family friend, recalled Mrs. Fitzgerald often
saying, ``I love my husband, but I don't like my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Saturday in Middletown, Martin said Ashley
Fitzgerald called the state police dispatcher at 6 p.m. on Friday.
Three times, the dispatcher said, ``911, what's your emergency?''
before Ashley responded.
</P>
<P>
   Martin described Ashley as calm at times, near tears at others.
``They're fighting again,'' she told the dispatcher. ``My daddy is
trying to kill my mommy.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, a gunshot can be heard, Martin said, and Ashley says: ``My
mommy is shot. She is going to die.'' Troopers later found Mrs.
Fitzgerald, shot in the head, in an upstairs bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald apparently walked down the stairs and spotted his
son, Shane. ``Now, he's right near my younger brother,'' Ashley
told the dispatcher. ``He's only 4 years old.'' Martin said the
popping sound of a gunshot can again be heard on the tape.
</P>
<P>
   Within moments, Martin said, the telephone was hung up. At that
point, investigators believe Fitzgerald shot his daughter and then
called the 34th Precinct, reaching the desk sergeant on duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've shot my family,'' he told the desk sergeant. ``Now I'm
going to kill myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Fitzgerald used his own .38-caliber handgun,
not his service revolver. He picked up the bodies of his two
children and placed them side-by-side on a bed in a downstairs
bedroom. His own body was found beside them, as if they were all
asleep, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The shock caused by news of the slayings was compounded by the
contradictory image fellow officers and co-workers had of
Fitzgerald. A 13-year veteran who had recently been promoted, he
was described as a caring, involved father who, in addition to
Ashley's flag football team, also coached a youth soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said Fitzgerald worked for the
Warrants Squad at the 34th Precinct and had been promoted about
three months ago to ``police officer special assignment.'' This
promotion left Fitzgerald's rank and duties unchanged, but gave him
a $1,500 annual pay increase.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, speaking at a news conference in Queens,
also expressed regret. ``It's a terrible tragedy of tremendous
dimensions, to see an entire family destroyed,'' the mayor said.
``Looking at his records as a police officer, there were not any
suggestions that something like this would happen. If anything, he
appears to have been a really excellent police officer.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In rural Greenville, an unincorporated hamlet of 3,200 people,
many of them city firefighters and police officers, stunned friends
and neighbors said that the Fitzgeralds had had marital troubles,
but Martin said there were had no police reports of domestic
violence in the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just crazy,'' said Joe O'Brien, a neighbor who is a city
firefighter. ``They were over here the day before, and the kids
were happy. There was no sign of stress.''
</P>
<P>
   Michele Cassidy, a regular baby sitter for Shane, said the
Fitzgeralds ``always had problems,'' adding, ``She had left a few
times but it was no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 5 p.m. on Friday, Ms. Cassidy said, she spoke to
Mrs. Fitzgerald by telephone. She said Mrs. Fitzgerald was
concerned because her husband was late even though it was practice
night for the flag football squad.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Emanuele, another neighbor, said Mrs. Fitzgerald left her
husband in July 1997, moving into an apartment with the children.
However, the couple reconciled two months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she moved back in, supposedly she bought all new
furniture,'' said Ms. Emanuele. ``They were starting over. They
were doing it for the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Emanuele also added, ``Anybody who knew them knew they
were having some kind of problems.'' She described Fitzgerald as
particularly excited about his daughter's flag football team. ``I
never found him to be unpleasant,'' she said. ``I just found him to
be a very quiet man.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cassidy said that Mrs. Fitzgerald started a new job three
weeks ago with a mortgage company. Mrs. Fitzgerald was active in a
Protestant church, Ms. Cassidy said, but her husband was Roman
Catholic and the children attended a school run by the local
diocese.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said the couple moved to Orange County about nine years
ago; neighbors said they had come from Queens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
