<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLUMPING METS FALL BEHIND IN THE WILD-CARD RACE
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Will be updated after Cubs-Astros and Padres-Rockies
games.) 
(nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the last five days, the Mets controlled their
postseason hopes. But after Tom Glavine and an assortment of Braves
relievers shut them down here Saturday in a 4-0 loss, the Mets'
season _ and the National League wild-card race _ came down to the
Mets hoping the Cubs and Giants would lose.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets (88-73) have lost their last four games. Saturday's
loss dropped them a half-game behind both the Cubs and the Giants
in the wild-card race, before those teams played later. Now the
Mets face a must-win situation against the most successful National
League pitcher of this decade, Greg Maddux, with their flickering
wild-card hopes on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are the Mets in danger of being swept by the Braves
this weekend; they are also perilously close to being swept out of
their season, as well. Al Leiter (17-6) did all he could to match
Glavine zero for zero for the first five innings. But Leiter, who
had escaped one bases-loaded jam in the fourth, could not repeat
the feat in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   And because the Mets could not score on Glavine on a
bases-loaded opportunity of their own, they were left waiting,
watching and hoping that the Cubs and the Giants would both lose,
too, to minimize the damage of yet another loss.
</P>
<P>
   It was a pitchers' duel from the start, as might have been
expected in a game featuring Cy Young Award candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter was perfect through three and a third innings, although
he did have trouble with the bottom of the order in the third.
Danny Bautista drilled a ball a couple feet outside the left-field
pole before flying out, and then both Tony Graffanino and Glavine
hit hard balls to left, Graffanino flying out to the track and
Glavine lining to Tony Phillips, who made a snow-cone catch.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine had more trouble with the Mets early on. Brian McRae, a
switch-hitter who always bats left-handed against the left-hander
Glavine, and Luis Lopez delivered back-to-back, two-out singles in
the second, but were stranded when Rey Ordonez lined to first. And
in the third, Edgardo Alfonzo singled with two outs and John Olerud
walked on four pitches, but Mike Piazza struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Both pitchers saved their best for bases-loaded situations,
however.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves loaded the bases with one out in the fourth on a
double by Gerald Williams, a four-pitch walk to Chipper Jones and
an infield single by Andres Galarraga. Galarraga's hit appeared to
hit him in the batter's box, which would have made it a foul.
Instead, Galarraga barely beat Piazza's throw to first, as the
Mets, who had left home uncovered, scrambled to get back to the
plate as Williams held at third.
</P>
<P>
   But Leiter retired Javy Lopez on an 0-1 foul-out to Olerud, then
struck out Andruw Jones on a 1-2 fastball that was high and
outside, two pitches after Jones barely missed at least a two-run
double with a foul drive down the left-field line.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was the Mets' turn to leave the bases loaded, something
they have been doing with great frequency the last few days. With
one out in the fifth, Leiter unexpectedly slammed a double over
Bautista's head in left (Leiter had only two extra-base hits in his
career, both coming this season). Phillips, who had batted
left-handed against Glavine his first two times up, switched and
worked a full-count walk.
</P>
<P>
   After Alfonzo struck out on a 2-2 pitch for the second out,
Olerud singled sharply to left as the third-base coach, Cookie
Rojas wisely held Leiter up at third. Up came Piazza, who was
14-for-32 with three home runs against Glavine before the day
began. The All-Star catcher hit Glavine's first pitch hard _ but
right at Williams in right. And the Mets had left three more
runners on base.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Mets, it turned out Glavine was on a pitch
count, after all. Manager Bobby Cox had insisted before the series
that both Glavine and Sunday's starter, Greg Maddux would be
pitching as if these were normal starts. But the Braves clinched
the best record in the National League on Friday night, and after
throwing 83 pitches in five innings Saturday, Glavine was given the
rest of the afternoon off to rest for his first playoff start.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Mets, Glavine's replacement, Denny Neagle,
is no slouch. Neagle, a 15-game winner this season, came on and set
the Mets down in order in the sixth. And unlike Cox, Mets Manager
Bobby Valentine had no such luxuries with his pitching staff, what
with the Mets fighting for a playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   That meant the Mets were going as long as they could with
Leiter, for better or for worse. And things turned ugly for the
tall left-hander in the sixth, when the Braves finally broke
through for three runs.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the inning was over, Leiter, who finished with 113
pitches, was done for the day _ and perhaps the season, which has
been the best of his career. Walt Weiss opened the sixth with a
double to left, before Williams worked a walk after falling behind
by 0-2 in the count. Leiter then fell behind Jones by 3-1 before
Jones could not check his swing as the count ran full. With the
runners going on the full-count pitch, Jones blooped a single to
center to score the game's first run, and Williams took third.
</P>
<P>
   After Galarraga walked, Leiter bore back to strike out Lopez.
But after a meeting at the mound with pitching coach Bob Apodaca,
Leiter surrendered an 0-1 double to Andruw Jones inside the
left-field line. And that was all for the Mets' Cy Young Award
candidate, who was replaced by Turk Wendell.
</P>
<P>
   It took Wendell only four pitches to end the threat, as he got
two ground balls. But Leiter had allowed three runs, three walks
and five hits in his five and a third innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
