<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS IN CONNECTICUT SEE TROUBLE IN NOVEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Unnerved by their gubernatorial candidate's
dismal poll ratings and President Clinton's political troubles, the
11 Connecticut Democrats running for statewide and federal office
held an emergency meeting with Sen. Christopher Dodd Saturday to
discuss how the party can avoid a disaster in the November
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Several national polls have shown that among the people who are
most likely to vote, Republican candidates have a solid edge over
Democrats. Connecticut Democrats face added peril because of the
falling fortunes of their candidate for governor, U.S. Rep. Barbara
Kennelly, who was 37 points behind Gov. John Rowland in a recent
poll. The state's Democratic leaders say they fear that the
combination of those two factors could result in a historic blowout
for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   So before candidates headed out for a warm day of fairgoing and
parade walking, Dodd summoned them for an unusual strategy session
at the state's Democratic Party headquarters. Dodd, a former
chairman of the Democratic National Committee, is running for a
fourth term but appears to have a comfortable lead over his
Republican challenger, Gary Franks, a former congressman from
Waterbury.
</P>
<P>
   Participants said Saturday's meeting, from which a reporter was
barred, was a combination of a revival and an encounter group. Most
of the candidates and their many staff members seemed to leave in a
chastened but determined mood. Some pointed to Clinton's continuing
improvement in polls, but one party strategist, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity, said Democrats were looking for realistic
ways to prevent rejection of Mrs. Kennelly from becoming ``a
tsunami that swamps the whole ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodd said he believed the governor's race would almost certainly
wind up closer than it looked now. ``I'm not trying to blow smoke
here,'' he said. ``I realize we've got a tough battle, and she
does. But we think we can create a possibility that this race gets
in the range of winnable. It's hard. Anyone who says otherwise is
deluding themselves. But at least we're trying to manufacture and
create an environment where that can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   As a reminder of what was at stake, the meeting took place
beneath a huge memorial sketch of Mrs. Kennelly's father, John
Bailey, who was the national Democratic chairman for seven years
and the state party chairman for 29 years. Mrs. Kennelly, who was
in Washington for a vote Saturday, joined the meeting by
speakerphone and gave an impassioned and optimistic report on her
campaign, saying she would continue to give it everything she had
for the remaining 39 days.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The state Democratic chairman, Edward Marcus, left in the middle
of the Democratic National Committee meeting in Washington to
return to Hartford for Saturday's session. Marcus urged Mrs.
Kennelly and the other candidates to be more aggressive about
pointing out their differences with their opponents instead of
simply discussing their own ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly has been only indirect in her attacks on Rowland
in her advertisements and speeches. ``She has to talk about what a
chameleon John Rowland is _ the king of the flip-flops,'' Marcus
said after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus served as the session's spirit chairman, proclaiming that
``a top-to-bottom win'' by the Democratic ticket was still
possible. During the meeting, officials decided to focus on towns
and precincts that are the most reliably Democratic, and blitz
those areas with phone calls, mail and visits. The campaigns also
resolved to distribute the best-known candidates throughout the
state instead of attending events together, to keep local
Democratic workers energized.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd, speaking on the crisis engulfing the president, said he
wanted to convince voters that however the impeachment matter is
resolved, the issues of health care, education and crime would
remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that this presidential thing is having a
dampening effect on some people,'' Dodd said. ``We want to
challenge Democrats across the country: Whatever else they may be
angry about or down about in the short term, they need to think
about the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodd already was following Marcus' advice in his own race.
Despite Dodd's wide lead, he began airing harsh television
advertisements over the weekend denouncing his opponent, Franks.
``I always assume I'm at least one vote behind,'' Dodd said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd's aides say he has always run aggressive campaigns, and
that the senator was simply responding to an attack ad by Franks
that began running on Tuesday. ``Democrats have learned that even
when you have a decent lead, you don't let a negative be unanswered
for,'' said Rob Engel, Dodd's campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   The ad by Franks showed a black-and-white, slow-motion clip of
Dodd, then an ever-growing pile of money. ``Chris Dodd says he
supports a balanced budget,'' the ad says. It goes on to discuss
several votes by Dodd and then concluded, ``Yet while voting new
taxes on us, Dodd sponsored a 40 percent pay raise for himself.
Chris Dodd _ taxes for us, pay raises for him. It's time for a
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodd's campaign said the pay raise was part of a bill to limit
outside income for members of Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
