<SLUG> BC-BOAT-AROUND-ALONE-810&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACE GOES ON FOR PAIR WHO NEARLY LOST THEIR LIVES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ The sideburns on Josh Hall's brush-cut are
graying now. And the smile lines in the corner of Isabelle
Autissier's blue eyes are etched a little deeper. But the same
tenacity that allowed them to overcome losing their sailboats at
sea _ and nearly their lives _ in a round-the-world race four years
ago has brought them back to the starting line again.
</P>
<P>
   Both in new 60-foot sailboats, Hall and Autissier are among 14
skippers starting out from here Saturday in the Around Alone, a
26,000-mile single-handed competition formerly known as the BOC
Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Two competitors, Neil Hunter of Australia and Viktor Yazykov of
Russia, decided at the last minute to delay their start a day or so
because they said they were not ready. Hunter broke the mast on his
40-foot boat, Paladin II, while sailing it here from Australia. He
was only able to replace it two days ago. Yazykov and his
40-footer, Wind of Change Russia, arrived here late and has been
playing catch-up ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The fleet of 40-to-60-foot yachts are apt to be dodging
hurricanes on the way to their first stop in Cape Town. With eight
months of racing ahead, including three stops along the way,
anything can happen. But excitement and anticipation were more
common on the docks early Saturday than fear and loathing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have fully come to realize that this is what I love doing,''
the 36-year-old Hall said. ``You hope that the disaster that struck
in the last race was one of those one-off things. Certainly, for
the first five or six days afterwards, I was having trouble
sleeping. But you put things in perspective over time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1994-95 race, radio and satellite contact with race
headquarters here guided Alan Nebauer, a fellow competitor, to
Hall's stricken yacht in the mid-Atlantic minutes before the yacht
sank. Hall surmises that his 60-foot yacht hit a submerged object.
</P>
<P>
   For Autissier, now 41 and the only woman in the race, major gear
breakdowns struck twice in 1994-95 on the way from Cape Town to
Sydney. Picked up from her crippled boat by an Australian
helicopter rescue team, Autissier took a year to regain her
strength. She has since made peace with a lawless sea by building
PRB, another 60-footer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through some things _ some good, some very bad,'' she
said Wednesday. ``When I went through the bad things, I learned
that I could keep going and not give up. I did what I could, and I
was not in despair even though I knew it was a very serious
situation. It gave me confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Weighty as the episode was, Autissier, like many of the other
solo sailors here, seems to have an uncanny ability to ignore fear.
Autissier will pack a bottle of Champagne for dumping overboard at
the Equator for King Neptune, the god of the sea that she sees as
the imaginary protector of all sailors.
</P>
<P>
   Giovanni Soldini, the 32-year-old Italian whose similarly
designed 60-foot sailboat, Fila, is one of Autissier's closest
rivals, has chosen to drink his spirits: ``I must have one glass of
wine each evening with my meal.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is sobered by the death last spring of Andreas Romanelli,
a sailing colleague who was lost overboard during a trans-Atlantic
passage on Fila. For weeks, Soldini was unsure that he could
continue with his plans for the Around Alone.
</P>
<P>
   As one of seven boats in Class I, all 60-footers, Soldini is
among an inner circle of five with a reasonable chance at winning.
All five yachts are designed by Groupe Finot, a French naval
architecture firm known for its innovation in Open Class,
round-the-world race boats.
</P>
<P>
   Autissier, with PRB, and Soldini, with Fila, have the most
experience and miles on their yachts. But Hall has built a newer
Finot design, which he has named Gartmore Investment Management,
the same as his last boat. Two newcomers to the race, Mike Golding
of England, skipper of Group 4, and Marc Thiercelin of France,
skipper of Somewhere, also chose Finot as their architect.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the Finot yachts are built with ungainly looking
rotating masts supported by outriggers on either side instead of
conventional shrouds. The rig allows for better sail shape, and
purportedly, quicker speed. Canting keels, which swing from one
side of the boat to the other to control leeway upwind, are also
Finot creations. All five boats are wide, about 18 feet, and low to
the water.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about safety are prompting designers to come up with
new ways to keep the boats afloat should they capsize and stay
upside down like an overturned saucer. Bulkhead air bladders, stern
balloons with compressed air cartridges, and automatic water
ballast systems have been developed in case the worst happens.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the technology, however, most experts agree that the
race comes down to talent and experience. ``This race is really
about how many smarts you've got,'' said Golding.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At 37, Thiercelin is considered a wild card given his top
showings in French single-handed competition. His campaign,
sponsored over three years by La Redoute, a French mail-order
company, is flush with $3.5 million in ocean-race funding.
</P>
<P>
   But Autissier remains the top choice. Her record includes a
seventh-place finish in the 1990-91 BOC race.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the logical favorite because she smoked all the guys on
the first leg in 1994, but then lost because of tragedy in the
second leg,'' said Jean-Pierre Mouligne, French skipper of the
50-foot Cray Valley, a top boat in Class II. ``She's also the heart
favorite because she's a woman. This is her third attempt, and it
should be her race.''
</P>
<P>
   Autissier said that the unsettled weather is apt to reduce the
area of Atlantic Ocean trade winds, which sailors count on for a
consistent breeze within the first two weeks at sea. Taking the
long way round, while probably safer, is also very likely to delay
the passage to Cape Town. Hurricanes along the way may also
lengthen a section of doldrums, a band of mid-ocean calm that
sailors tend to dread because it slows them down.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one seems particularly worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really doing this for pleasure,'' Autissier said. ``I
still know that a small percentage is really hard, and that there
is something in between. But there are also wonderful times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
