<SLUG> BC-NY-ROBBERY-RING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR ACCUSED OF INVADING HOMES AND TORTURING VICTIMS FOR CASH 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After several incidents this month in which armed men
wearing masks burst into homes in Queens and tortured the people
living there until they gave up their cash and valuables, the
police charged four men Friday with the well-planned robberies.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the robbers paid for tips on the street about
business owners who had recently made large sums of money. They
stalked their victims before invading their homes and, in some
cases, burning them with irons or scalding them, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Though the men are charged in only four robberies, Lt. William
Nevins, commanding officer of the Queens robbery squad, said that
they were suspected in several others in Brooklyn and Long Island
over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   The first hint of the gang came on Sept. 11 in South Ozone Park,
Nevins said, when four men entered a two-unit apartment building
belonging to a bodega owner.
</P>
<P>
   He said the men broke down the front door of the upstairs
apartment around 5 p.m. After they used extension cords to tie up a
36-year-old woman, her 15-year-old daughter and seven men who were
living there, the armed robbers took $300 and some jewelry. Then
they forced the woman and her daughter down the stairs to the first
floor.
</P>
<P>
   The robbers were looking for the landlord, a 41-year-old bodega
owner, the police said. They had been told by a paid informer that
the man had won $85,000 in a South American lottery, the police
said. After the robbers found the man inside the first-floor
apartment, he pleaded with them, saying they had mistaken him for
someone else, the police said, but that only angered them.
</P>
<P>
   When the bodega owner failed to produce the money, one of the
robbers hit him in the head with a pistol, the police said. Over
what became a two-hour ordeal, they also burned him on the back
with a hot iron and forced him to stand in a tub of scalding water,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevins said the men fled with jewelry and about $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Six days later, apparently acting on another tip, the robbers
waited for a 12-year-old boy to leave his apartment in Elmhurst for
school, the police said, then forced him inside, where they tied up
his 47-year-old mother with hanger wire.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the robbers believed that the woman, who owned a
restaurant in Corona, had recently taken home a large amount of
cash. The police said that when she failed to hand it over, the men
forced both the woman and her son into a tub of scalding water and
threatened to slice her face with a knife.
</P>
<P>
   They left with $1,100, some stereo equipment and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   The robbers attacked again on Sept. 22, the police said,
breaking into a woman's apartment in Jackson Heights, then burning
her on the back with an iron when she failed to give them money.
The robbers left after taking an undetermined amount of money.
</P>
<P>
   The police said they were not releasing the names of the
victims, because of the violent nature of the crime and to protect
their families. In all of the cases, the victims' burns were
extensive enough to require hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   The police identified the suspects as Edwin Nunez, 19, Mailky
Mota, 21, and Miguel Thomas, 24, all of Brooklyn, and Omar Taveras,
22, of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Nevins said the evidence included three guns, one of which was
found inside a hidden compartment in the wheel well of a Ford
Taurus. The compartment, which opened only if the car's defroster
and turn signal were in use, also held a crowbar and a ski mask, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were pretty organized,'' he said. ``They picked their
victims carefully, used code names during the robberies and went to
the trouble of having a trap in the car. They didn't want to slip
up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-98 1816EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980926.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6113 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-HOME-REAL-2TAKES-N     09-26 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: SAFETY, AS WELL AS STYLE, COUNTS IN LOBBY
REDECORATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When a co-op or condominium decides to redecorate a
lobby, questions of design usually take precedence. Safety issues,
such as the flammability of carpeting, draperies and other
furnishings, are sometimes neglected. But co-op and condo lawyers
say that a careful consideration of those issues is not only
advisable but is required by law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are at least two good reasons for complying with
flammability regulations,'' said James Samson, a Manhattan co-op
lawyer. ``One is because landlords and co-op and condominium boards
are responsible for complying with regulations concerning tenants'
safety. And the other is that if you have a fire in a common area
filled with flammable materials, just watch how fast it goes up. It
can turn a lobby into an inferno in a matter of seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City Fire Department regulations have long required
those responsible for public buildings like theaters, restaurants
and museums to insure that combustible materials in their buildings
_ things like draperies, curtains and decorative plants and trees,
but not carpeting _ have been treated with fire-retardant
chemicals. In June 1996, those regulations were amended to include
common areas of multiple dwellings.
</P>
<P>
   James Hansen, a spokesman for the Fire Department, said that
regulations require all combustible materials in public areas of
buildings to be certified as flameproof by a person who has been
issued a New York City Fire Department certificate of fitness.
``And we do enforce the law when we find a violation,'' he said,
adding that an initial violation can result in a $1,000 fine and
subsequent offenses carry a fine of up to $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Molla, the owner of Cleantex Process Co., a Manhattan
cleaning and flameproofing company, said that many residential
landlords and co-op and condominium boards appear to be unaware of
the change in the law. Molla, who holds a certificate of fitness
from the Fire Department, said that his company had been
flameproofing draperies and curtains in theaters and restaurants,
as well as in some co-ops and condominiums, since 1928. He said he
had not seen an increase in the number of calls he gets from
residential buildings since the law was changed two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Molla said that according to the law, all combustible materials
in covered buildings must be certified as flameproof once a year.
To meet the standards, he said, the material must either be
inherently flameproof or chemically treated to make it that way.
</P>
<P>
   An untreated fabric will burn when exposed to flame or extreme
heat and continue burning after the flame or heat is removed, he
said; a flameproof fabric will stop burning when the ignition
source is removed.
</P>
<P>
   Fabrics that are inherently flameproof, he said, are generally
manufactured that way. In most cases, he said, the flameproofing is
permanent.
</P>
<P>
   All combustible fabrics are tested by exposing a small portion
to a flame and seeing if the fabric continues to burn when the
flame is removed. Fabrics that fail the test must be treated and
retreated on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our treatment usually lasts three to five years,'' Molla said,
adding that in addition to requiring recertification every year,
Fire Department regulations require retreatment once every three
years or whenever the fabric has been laundered or dry-cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, Molla said, when his company is hired by a co-op or
condominium to flameproof curtains or draperies in a lobby, he will
suggest removing the items and then cleaning and treating them at
his factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you spray the treatment on dirty fabric you end up with
streaks and smudges,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, Molla said, treatment is relatively inexpensive.
``It depends on the size of the lobby and the number of drapes and
curtains,'' he said. ``But an average building usually runs about
$500 to $600.''
</P>
<P>
   Molla added that boards should always ask to see a flameproofing
company's certificate of fitness. ``There are companies out there
without certificates that will come in, test the fabric, and then
just sell you the flameproofing treatment, saying you can save
money by spraying it on yourself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, is inadvisable for two reasons. First, he said,
some fabrics, such as velvet, can be permanently damaged if they
are not treated properly.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Molla said, the Fire Department will accept
certifications only from a contractor holding a certificate of
fitness. Self-treatment, even if done properly, is legally invalid.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to insuring that draperies and curtains are
flameproof, boards should also make sure that carpeting in lobbies
and hallways complies with existing regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that many of the common-area and hallway carpet
installations in Manhattan's residential buildings are in violation
of city codes,'' said Marilyn Sygrove, president of Sygrove
Associates, a Manhattan interior design company.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sygrove explained that under the New York City Building
Code, only 100 percent wool carpeting can be installed in lobby
areas, exit passageways and convenience stairs of buildings
constructed after Dec. 6, 1968 _ the date of the adoption of the
current code. In interior hallways, she said, carpeting that is at
least 80 percent wool can be used, as well as nylon carpeting,
provided that the nylon is installed properly.
</P>
<P>
   The reason wool is preferable, she said, is because it is
inherently flame-retardant. Nylon is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, apartment buildings have used nylon because it
supposedly lasts longer,'' she said. ``But if nylon carpet is laid
atop a pad that is attached to the floor only around its perimeter,
pockets of air can be trapped underneath. And when oxygen gets
under nylon, it becomes highly flammable.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, she said, the only legal way to install nylon
carpeting is to glue the entire carpet directly to the floor, or to
glue a carpet pad to the floor and then glue the carpet to the pad.
</P>
<P>
   Wool, on the other hand, can be installed over a pad without any
gluing by nailing tack-imbedded wood strips _ called ``tackless'' _
around the perimeter of the area to be carpeted.
</P>
<P>
   Herb Frank, the owner of Quality Carpet in Brooklyn, said that
in addition to being inherently fire-retardant, wool is preferable
to nylon for other reasons. ``Basically, wool looks newer longer,''
Frank said. ``It has better detail, clearer patterns and beautiful
color and clarity.''
</P>
<P>
   And while wool generally costs about $10 a square yard more than
nylon, the difference is reduced to about $4 a square yard when the
cost of installing nylon according to the strict requirements is
taken into consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about an overall price difference of about 10
percent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Samson, the lawyer, said that co-op and condominium boards in
buildings built before the 1968 change in the law _ and not
technically subject to the current requirements _ should follow
them anyway if they are considering installing new carpeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because you don't have to do something doesn't mean you
shouldn't,'' he said, adding that failure to address a potential
problem _ even without the legal requirement to do so _ can result
in expanded liability.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the city is saying is that the wrong carpeting in a
common area can be dangerous,'' he said. ``And if it's dangerous in
a fairly new building, it's going to be dangerous in an old one
too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
