<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: THE PONIES OF CHINCOTEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (mk) 
 By THOMAS BRANDT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHINCOTEAGUE, Va. _ Some 50 feet away, the palomino stared me
down and, seeing nothing in my hands to mooch, she walked off
through the salt marsh toward the sand dunes in Chincoteague
National Wildlife Refuge, with water spraying at each hoof step.
The white cattle egret on her back rode quietly along since these
semiwild horses are a buffet table for bug-eating birds.
</P>
<P>
   However, this symbiotic relationship between egrets and horses
is the exception. While the ponies have an almost mystical draw on
tourists, who are now economically critical to the survival of this
tiny seaside town, in the refuge their trample of ground-nesting
birds, the eating of plant life critical to barrier islands, soil
compaction and other negative impacts of these nonnative horses are
of growing concern to scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Here on one of the East Coast's wildest barrier islands some 150
feral horses run free. In late July, thousands of people come for
the annual Pony Penning festival, where many bid to buy the
captured colts. Since 1924, the saltwater cowboys of the
Chincoteague Volunteer Fire Department have saddled up their own
horses, rounded up the island's scattered herds and swum them
across Assateague channel to the town of Chincoteague. There, the
yearlings are sold to raise firefighting funds so the town will
never again be nearly lost to fire as it was in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being the inspiration for ``Misty of Chincoteague,''
Marguerite Henry's 1947 children's book classic about two orphans
drawn to a pony named Misty, the refuge is also a critically
important major Eastern flyway. Some 1.4 million people are drawn
here each year by the grazing ponies, the beach, birds, surf
fishing, crabs and clamming. But they often go away with much more,
a new appreciation of America's once-common wildfowl and the
commitment of the National Park Service to protect this refuge.
More than 300 varieties of migratory birds grace these lands in
various seasons of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, tension has grown. As the nation's
wild habitat shrinks, biologists and environmentalists are
increasingly concerned that the nonnative horses at Chincoteague,
and several other East Coast barrier islands, will further damage
the land and kill off endangered birds and other species. The
horses' main food is marsh and dune grass which are critical to the
islands' ecological stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that lives and breeds in the salt marsh will be
damaged by foraging horses,'' said William Dunson, professor
emeritus of biology at Penn State. ``You don't want nonnative
species to be present; you never know what their impact will be. If
you wanted to bring horses out to this refuge for the first time,
they would never allow it.'' Research and argument are still under
way as to what should be the environmentally acceptable horse
population on this island refuge of some 10,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Lore has it that the horses came from two different sources some
300 years ago: The first horses perhaps swam ashore from Spanish
galleons, wrecked off the coast; better documentation shows that
Eastern Shore planters put the horses on the barrier island to save
the cost of both building fences on their own land and paying
English taxes on the herd.
</P>
<P>
   The horses are often called wild ponies, though neither term is
accurate. They are not native nor completely wild, and are thus
feral horses, meaning they evolved from domesticated animals. And
the endearing pony term is used because the horses are small
because of the strains of the saltwater habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Those in the middle of the debate over how many horses are too
many for the island include John Schroer, refuge manager. ``When I
first came here in '89, the firefighters were getting about $350
for each foal they sold,'' he said. ``This year they sold nearly 90
and averaged more than $1,700 each. If there was an effort to cut
the herd size, there would be a tremendous outcry.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the government-mandated herd size of 150, Schroer said,
``We can be fairly assured there's not a lot of environmental
damage.'' Still, Chincoteague's topography is unique and, as Dunson
said, quite vulnerable. The refuge has wide beaches backed by low
dunes which yield to extensive salt marshes. There are also large
areas of pine and oak and freshwater ponds, and more than 2,600
acres of shallow, freshwater moist soil to maximize the refuge's
appeal to waterfowl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the blue-collar town of Chincoteague, which you must pass
through to reach the refuge across Assateague channel bridge, the
controversy is not about the environment but down-home economics.
This village once thrived on commercial fishing, but as that trade
declined, the ponies began drawing more and more tourists. ``Misty
of Chincoteague,'' and the 1961 film of the book, breathed new life
into the town and a protection from poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chincoteague remains more a village than a resort. Here
you forget about rubber-stamp subdivisions and resort sprawl.
Chincoteague is a blend of ponies, crabs, decoy carvers, wildfowl
and families, with an ocean running through it. While a case can be
made for shrinking the horse herd below 150, elimination would be
tantamount to burning down the town.
</P>
<P>
   So an unprecedented deal has been cut between the Chincoteague
Volunteer Fire Department and the Fish and Wildlife Service. A
special use permit allows the fire department to maintain the
150-horse herd on the federal refuge land under certain conditions.
These include a twice-a-year roundup by the fire department to
allow for veterinarian examinations and vaccinations, which are
also paid for by the department. Also, fencing through the woods
now keeps the horses off the beaches and dunes, protecting the
plant life that stabilizes these areas. Fencing also keeps the
horses from the roads, limiting the number of ponies hit by cars to
one or two a year (and the number of tourists bitten by ponies).
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at visitation as a challenge,'' added Schroer, the
refuge director. ``How can we let that many people in _ 1.4 million
a year _ and keep it a refuge? Still, it is a great opportunity to
educate people, and many leave here as great new advocates for
wildlife.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
