<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-RAMAPO-FOOTBALL-NY     09-26 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-RAMAPO-FOOTBALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FATHER-SON UNION HELPS RAMAPO TO SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By GRANT GLICKSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three years ago, Greg Toal was forced to make the
hardest decision of his young life. He had to choose between family
and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't want to leave my friends and my school,'' said
Toal, who was a 14-year-old sophomore at the time. ``I decided to
stay at Ramapo.''
</P>
<P>
   So rather than following his older brother Mike _ a star
offensive and defensive back _ and transferring to Hackensack where
their father, Greg Sr., was the head coach, Greg Jr. opted to
remain at Ramapo High School in Franklin Lakes, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   It could have created hard feelings in a less reasonable family,
but not in this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to be his decision,'' said Greg Sr., who began
building Hackensack's program in 1990. ``I knew that he would have
changed his mind if I would have pressured him. But I told him,
`Don't do it for me. Do it for yourself.'''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Mike Toal moved onto William Smith College, and
Greg Sr., who guided the Hackensack Comets to five consecutive
North Jersey Section 1 Group 4 titles, resigned as the head coach
of Hackensack and signed on with Ramapo as an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned about him becoming an assistant coach after
being the head man all those years,'' said Greg Jr., now a
17-year-old senior. ``But then I realized that he didn't mind
leaving Hackensack. He just wanted to coach me. That's all he
really cared about.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ramapo, the decisions made by father and son could not have
been diagrammed any better. Greg Jr., a signee of Boston College,
has rushed for 3,943 yards and 68 touchdowns. As a defensive back,
Toal has three interception returns for touchdowns. Coach Toal's
knowledge and experience has proved to be invaluable in practice,
prep sessions and on game days.
</P>
<P>
   Ramapo, (2-0) after Friday night's 56-0 victory against Pascack
Valley (1-1), has not lost a game since father and son were united
on the Raiders football field in 1997. After Toal rushed for 256
yards and 4 touchdowns Friday night, the Toals are 13-0 together.
Of course, the presence of Chris Simms, the nation's top-rated
signal-caller and son of former Giants' quarterback Phil Simms, has
certainly helped Ramapo's winning percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've witnessed over the last two years a great father-and-son
relationship,'' said Ramapo Coach Mike Miello. ``There is
absolutely no animosity. When they are on the field, it's
coach-player. When they go home, it's father-son. Exactly the way
it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Toals on board last season, the Ramapo Raiders managed
to wrest away Hoboken's three-year hold on the North Jersey Section
1 Group 3 title. The Raiders defeated Hoboken, 21-14 in overtime,
to claim their first championship since 1993. The victory snapped
the Red Wings' 38-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most exciting finishes in New Jersey State playoff
history, Greg Jr. went from hero to goat back to hero again in the
final minutes of play. After rushing 27 times for 249 yards and a
touchdown to help Ramapo take a 14-7 lead late in the fourth
quarter, Toal fumbled away the game-tying touchdown with 2 minutes
20 seconds remaining. It was Toal's third fumble of the day. Ramapo
later tied the game, and Toal managed to redeem himself in
overtime, knocking down the last pass of the game in the end zone
to preserve the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I fumbled that ball I was so down,'' Toal recalled. ``I
went back to my father as I always do and he told me: `Don't worry
about it. Stay up. No big deal.' It was a great feeling being able
to help the team after blowing it.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Toal was able to assist the team at all _ let
alone perform at such a high level _ was a testament to his
courage, strength and work ethic. Toal had strained the medial
collateral ligament in his left knee the week before the
championship game. He did not practice until late in the week and
his availability was in question up until game time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that Greg knows what it takes to be
successful,'' said Coach Toal, who has started all three of his
sons as seventh-graders on a strict exercise regimen that entails
wind sprints and resistance training. The youngest Toal, Brian, 13,
is a fullback on his junior high school team. ``Greg realized early
on that if he worked hard and put the time in, a lot of great
things would happen. It was his choice to make.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
