<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKLA-FARM-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: PAYING THE ESTATE TAX WITHOUT SELLING THE FAMILY
FARM 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SUSAN DOUZE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Estate taxes _ both federal and state _ have
historically been a threat to intergenerational ownership of family
farms and ranches. The sons and daughters of land owners have often
been unable to find the cash to pay estate taxes due on farmland
that has greatly appreciated in market value over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, there was some sense of gratification among farmers
and ranchers in Oklahoma this year when the state joined
neighboring states in enacting a law that eases state estate taxes,
especially for smaller farms and ranches.
</P>
<P>
   But with federal laws still regarded as a threat to longterm
family farming, landowners who hope to sustain family ownership in
the next generation and beyond are putting their hopes in astute
estate planning, not the relaxation of estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched 15 to 20 customers close down,'' said Rodd
Moesel, who owns American Plant Products and Services here, which
sells commercial greenhouse equipment. ``They didn't have the cash
to put up and once they reduced the size of the property to pay
taxes it no longer was a viable economic entity.''
</P>
<P>
   Moesel also heads a statewide coalition of about 20 farm, ranch
and business groups _ including the Oklahoma Farm Bureau, Oklahoma
Farmers Union, State Chamber of Commerce and the Oklahoma Business
Council _ that is dedicated to tax reform.
</P>
<P>
   All its neighboring states _ Texas, Kansas, Arkansas, Missouri
and New Mexico _ have acted to ease the problem by modifying their
state estate tax. They have chosen to peg their state's tax at a
level no greater than the amount that the federal government allows
as a tax credit for the payment of a state estate tax as part of
the calculation of the federal tax that is due.
</P>
<P>
   Currently 33 states have adopted this system, becoming what the
tax lawyers call ``pickup'' states. Ten of these states have taken
the step within the last six years. Kansas became the latest
convert in May.
</P>
<P>
   That left Oklahoma as a ``pocket of overtaxation,'' Moesel said.
But this year the Legislature acted. As part of a $104 million tax
relief package, it raised the minimum level of farm value on which
a state estate tax is due, and made other adjustments to bring its
tax system more in line with neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
   The changes will mostly benefit smaller estates, typically less
than $625,000 in value, where no federal estate tax is due. Prior
to the enactment in 1987 of the Tax Reform Act, an estate below
that amount in value would still have paid an Oklahoma tax of as
much as $17,725. The state tax will be phased out in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   But for larger estates in which farm property forms a major
element in the valuation, the basic problem remains, farmer
representatives maintain. The federal estate tax rate is 55 percent
for the amount of an estate's value over $3 million (based on all
assets, including property, minus liabilities such as
administrative expenses and fees).
</P>
<P>
   For estates valued between $625,000 and $3 million, the tax rate
is on a sliding scale starting at 37 percent. In coming years, the
threshold at which estate taxes start will rise gradually from
$625,000 until it reaches $1 million by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for farmers and ranchers is that the appraised value
of their land may call for heirs to produce far more cash to pay
taxes than the working farm can generate. It becomes necessary to
sell land to pay taxes. If too much acreage is sold, there's too
little left to make a living. Sometimes, remedies that harm the
land, like clear-cutting timber, are a last resort to pay the tax
bill.
</P>
<P>
   For estate tax purposes, farms and ranches are appraised by
comparing them with similar properties in the region. Worth can
vary wildly with the economy. Challenges by Internal Revenue
Service appraisers to the valuations made on estate-tax filings are
common. On a multimillion dollar farm or ranch, a squabble over $1
million in an appraisal can translate into $400,000 to $500,000 in
additional estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's worth fighting for,'' said Henry Will, a lawyer with
the Tulsa firm of Conner &AMP; Winters. ``But it's a swearing match.
You can go to court. You need an attorney, an appraiser and a good
accountant. If you're cash strapped, as a lot of farm and ranch
families are, you may not be able to afford to.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Will gave the hypothetical example of a northeastern Oklahoma
dairy farmer who over 20 years bought 4,000 acres of land at an
average price of $350 an acre for a total of $1.4 million. He made
$600,000 in improvements, including roads, fences, barns and silos
to store grain.
</P>
<P>
   Because the entire estate was left to his wife through joint
tenancy and a simple will, there was no federal or estate tax at
his death. But when his wife died shortly thereafter, the estate
was appraised at $3.5 million. Federal estate tax, at the 40
percent rate, was $1,134,550. State estate tax, before reform, was
an additional $229,200.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are his kids going to pay those taxes and keep the farm?''
Will asked.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Payne, a lawyer whose family owns ranches in Osage
County, said that that he knows of 100,000 acres of family-owned
land in the county that has been sold off to corporations over the
last 10 years to pay estate taxes. In ranch country, it's
considered rude to banter about the number of acres owned and how
many head of cattle graze them. But for a rancher, it takes at
least $1 million in land and equipment _ some would say as much as
$2.5 million _ to ``make a respectable living,'' said Frederick
Drummond, 66, a third-generation cattle rancher in Osage County,
who plans to keep his land in his family.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of heavy estate taxes has led farmers and ranchers to put
heavy emphasis on estate planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are technical laws, but they can be very beneficial,''
said Will, the Tulsa lawyer. Basically, he said, by using gifting
techniques and available credits, a $5 million ranch or farm
property can pass to children tax free.
</P>
<P>
   One tax-avoidance technique that is increasingly used is called
a disclaimer: after a woman's husband dies, leaving an estate of
more than $3 million to his widow, she disclaims their $500,000
house. It therefore goes to the next heir as a trust.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the trust, the widow would be allowed to live
in the house, or the house could be sold, allowing the widow to
collect income from investments from the proceeds of the sale. When
she dies, the couple's children pay $295,000 less than they would
have paid without the disclaimer.
</P>
<P>
   Also useful is Section 2032A of the tax code, said John Mee Jr.,
an Oklahoma City lawyer. Under this provision, farmland that the
heirs continue to work as farmland can be assessed as farmland
rather than at the higher assessment that would result from a
valuation based on the land's ``highest and best use.'' When
farmland is surrounded by new housing developments, the
highest-and-best-use appraisal can be disastrous for the
continuation of farming. Other techniques include making use of the
maximum gift allowable each year under the federal tax rules _
$10,000 to each individual.
</P>
<P>
   When he's not on horseback working the herd just like his
grandfather or mending the same family fences, Drummond toils to
beat what he calls the ``death tax.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I make those allowable $10,000 gifts every year and I buy life
insurance,'' Drummond said, explaining that his son can use it to
pay the ``death tax.'' ``I come from sons and daughters of the
soil. I work the soil because I want to. I want my son to have the
chance to do the same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
