<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-COLUMBIA-BUCKNELL     09-26 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLUMBIA-BUCKNELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG PLAYS HELP BUCKNELL DEFEAT COLUMBIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEWISBURG, Pa. _ All the momentum that Columbia carried from its
upset victory over Harvard last week dissolved in one minute
Saturday at Bucknell. An interception that led to a Bucknell
touchdown late in the first half and a 93-yard kickoff return for a
touchdown to begin the second half helped turn Columbia's 14-3
cushion into a 27-20 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big plays in the kicking game against good teams are hard to
overcome, and we couldn't overcome it today,'' Columbia Coach Ray
Tellier said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Lions managed to tie the game late in the third quarter at
17-17 on Sam Warren's 23-yard field goal. But the Bison (3-1) drove
58 yards early in the fourth quarter to set up a 40-yard field goal
by Ross Coleman to make it 20-17.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the final blow. Columbia's Avery Moseley, one of the
cornerbacks filling in for Chris Tillotson and Andre Ogundare, who
were suspended for disciplinary reasons, had played brilliantly,
intercepting two passes. But with 5 minutes 52 seconds left and the
Lions trailing 20-17, Moseley bit on receiver Ron Rockett's fake to
the sideline. Rockett cut back straight ahead without any defender
on him, and quarterback Don McDowell lobbed the ball to him for a
game-clinching 32-yard touchdown pass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``On third-and-5, you have to take a chance,'' Moseley said. ``I
was looking for them to get to the sticks.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 35-yard field goal by Warren, who came in early in the first
quarter after Neal Kravitz pulled a muscle in his hip, made it
27-20, but the Lions' final drive died at the Bucknell 35-yard line
when quarterback Paris Childress lofted a rainbow into the end zone
that was tipped away from receiver David Holmes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Childress completed 19-of-37 passes for 247 yards, 123 of those
yards going to Armand Dawkins. Dawkins' 49-yard touchdown reception
in the first quarter gave Columbia a 7-3 lead. The Lions widened
that to 14-3 when Jason Bivens' 1-yard run capped a 14-play,
53-yard drive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We had established good rhythm on that drive,'' Childress
said. ``But it's something we should have done all day.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the Lions' next drive, Childress threw a short pass that was
bobbled by Lendell Thompson and flew into the hands of Bucknell's
Shawn Redd, and McDowell soon followed with a 17-yard touchdown
pass to Rockett. Jabu Powell then started the second half by
fielding Warren's kickoff at the 7, turning upfield to the 25,
cutting to the outside and sprinting untouched into the end zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
