Prince and Nancy Prince Anschuetz, with their parents in front,
Elaine and Donald Prince, holding photos of Elaine's parents, Aline
(mother) and Alton (father), who, with Elaine and Donald, were
among the first to be in the study. (Evan Richman/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UROSEVAC, Yugoslavia -- Sept. 26, 1998 -- YUGO-KOSOVO-2,
9-26 -- Sanije Dugolli, mother of two sets of twins, was widowed by
Serbian authorities, who kept her husband, Cen, 32, in custody
without being charged. On his death certificate, Dugolli is said to
have died from blows to the head and body. Despite repeated visits
to the prison where he was being held near his hometown, and then
in Pristina, his relatives say, the family was never allowed to see
him. (Wade Goddard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UROSEVAC, Yugoslavia -- Sept. 26, 1998 -- YUGO-KOSOVO-1,
9-26 -- Hava Bislimi, 63, with a photo of her eldest son, Rexhap,
33, who died while in the custody of Serbian officers, after they
repeatedly beat him. Bislimi's death is one example, human rights
officials say, of the arbitrary arrests and torture that the
Serbian authorities are using to warn ethnic Albanian civilians to
stop supporting a separatist guerrilla force fighting for the
independence of Serbia's Kosovo province. (Wade Goddard/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 26, 1998 -- TAXCUT-SHOWDOWN, 9-26 --
Rep. Bill Archer, the chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, discussing support for the tax cut, with an aide to a
fellow Texas Republican, Rep. Tom DeLay, the majority whip.
Brushing aside a veto threat from President Clinton, the House
passed the $80 billion Republican tax cut Saturday that would be
paid for by projected federal budget surpluses. Democrats strongly
oppose spending any surpluses before they materialize. (Justin
Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LIXIAN, China -- Sept. 26, 1998 -- CHINA-LOGGING-BAN,
9-26 -- Jiang Lianhui, 22, started working as a logger last year.
Now, like many others in the Lixian region in China, he faces an
uncertain future. After a half-century of rampant clear-cutting,
China has decided to save the remaining forests along the upper
reaches of the Yangtze and other major rivers, representing a
dramatic shift in priorities in favor of environmental protection.
Huge tree-planting campaigns have also been promised. (Erik
Eckholm/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) TEWKSBURY, N.J. -- Sept. 26, 1998 -- NJ-BALLFIELD-SUIT-2,
9-26 -- Kathleen DeSerio, 41, a garden designer and hairdresser has
worked for seven years to restore her 1,500-square-foot Cape
Cod-style house. Ms. DeSerio, along with the Tewksbury Township, is
suing to have a three-acre ball field, built on a neighbors
property, razed. ``My house is finally to the point where it is
livable, and it is really quite beautiful, and now I have Fenway
Park behind me. The only person who hasn't shown up is Kevin
Costner.'' (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) TEWKSBURY, N.J. -- Sept. 26, 1998 -- NJ-BALLFIELD-SUIT-1,
9-26 -- In New Jersey's horse country, Bill Ingraham, 44, built his
11-year-old son, Brian, a full-size ball field equal to
major-league specifications, in his backyard. Brian loves the
field. Brian's friends, who show up every day, love it, too.
Neighbors and the town of Tewksbury are suing to have it razed. It
seems that a three-acre ball field is not what residents of
Tewksbury moved out here to see, or hear. (Norman Y. Lono/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
