<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Referee files protest against Bean promoter
 &HT;    By Chris Freeman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Ohio _ Vaughn Bean's promoter has said he plans to
file a protest against referee Brian Garry over his officiating of
Bean's championship bout against Evander Holyfield last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But Garry has beaten him to the punch and already filed his own
official protest against the promoter, Butch Lewis, for his conduct
during the fight, the president of the International Boxing
Federation said.
</P>
<P>
   IBF President Robert W. Lee said he has received Garry's letter
of protest. He said he has been told by Lewis that he would also
file a protest against Garry.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has until Oct. 2 to file his protest and said he planned
on filing it early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Lee will convene a 10-member executive committee to hear the
protest from Garry, Lewis or their representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they've been heard, then we can render a decision,'' Lee
said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Lee was present at the fight Saturday, he elected not to
comment on the protests until the executive committee had met.
</P>
<P>
   Garry's protest, filed with the IBF and the Georgia State Boxing
Commission, alleges Lewis verbally berated him during and after the
fight and physically confronted him in the ring after the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God we didn't have a riot or something like that,''
Garry said. ``He was trying to intimidate me. He held on to the
ring ropes, was up on the apron swearing at me from Round 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis did not dispute yelling and berating Garry but felt he was
justified.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the second round on, it seems as though one of two things
was happening in the ring,'' an excited Lewis explained. ``Either
he was favoring Holyfield because he was intimidated being in front
of those 40,000 people, or he was incompetent. ... I don't care
which one he chooses, but when the protest hearings happen, the
tape will not tell a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis claims Garry did not penalize Holyfield for elbowing,
head-butting and holding throughout the fight, culminating in a
controversial 10th-round knockdown where Bean was hit near the
ropes by Holyfield. Garry said Bean was coming off the ropes and
was fair game; Lewis strenuously argued that Bean was still tied up
in the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spun and pivoted back into fair territory,'' Garry said.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield ``flung my guy into the ropes, held him with one arm
and punched him twice when he was in the ropes!'' Lewis countered.
``Then my guy got up and he gave him an eight-count! I'm like,
what?!''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Lewis stepped up his abuse of Garry, continuing
to yell obscenities at him and getting in Garry's face during an
interview after the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Bean got knocked down (in the 10th round), Lewis went
ballistic with obscenities at me,'' Garry said. ``He was pounding
on the ring and apron, I had to ask a highway patrolman to control
him. ... The (Georgia boxing) commission wanted me to take a point
from Bean to punish Lewis, but I wouldn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm cussing, my blood pressure is going up and Garry just
says, 'I'm in charge' and walks away,'' Lewis said. ``I'm all upset
about what this Garry was not doing in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm emotional, everyone knows that. I stand up for my guy. If
you don't like it, so what. ... He said he was going to have me
removed. You're going to have me removed?! You're going to be
(expletive) removed!''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
