u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMERCIAL-REAL-2TAKE     09-26 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMERCIAL-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: THE TREND TO INTERNATIONAL EXPANSION IS GROWING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Sept. 15 announcement by the real estate services
company Cushman &AMP; Wakefield that it is merging with the
London-based firm of Healey &AMP; Baker will create a company that, by
real estate standards, is huge, with annual revenues of over $700
million and more than 7,700 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important, it will largely complete the
transformation of what was once a New York-area company into a
global player, with 129 offices in 39 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The deal comes at a time when many leading commercial real
estate executives are predicting that within a short time there
will be just a handful of companies operating internationally to
provide services for multinational corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing the elimination of the midsize real estate
company in the United States,'' said William S. Rothe, a senior
executive managing director of CB Richard Ellis, which has been
active in the acquisition contest.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, CB Commercial acquired Richard Ellis
International and changed its name to CB Richard Ellis. Because of
a previous split in the Richard Ellis company, the purchase did not
include the Richard Ellis operations in Britain or the use of the
name in that country.
</P>
<P>
   To round out its operations in Europe, CB subsequently acquired
Hillier Parker, which has 500 employees and is based in London. The
company claims to be the largest commercial real estate company
operating globally, employing 9,400 people, with 215 offices in 29
countries and revenues of $848 million.
</P>
<P>
   Another company, Insignia/ESG, which is based largely on the
Edward S. Gordon company of New York, has been on an acquisition
tear as well. In the last two years, it has taken over 10 real
estate companies in this country, including operations in Chicago,
greater Philadelphia, the Washington area, Denver, Oregon,
Washington State, Orange County in California and the
Rostenberg-Doern firm of Westchester County in New York and
Fairfield County in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding internationally, Insignia/ESG acquired the Richard
Ellis Group in Britain and hired two executives from the European
Richard Ellis company to open an office in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   As its focus has grown on commercial real estate, Insignia is
divesting itself of the residential ownership and management
operations on which the business was originally built. The company
said it expects to complete the divestiture to Apartment Investment
and Management Company, or AIMCO, by early next month. That will
leave it with commercial operations, a residential brokerage in
Ohio and 59,000 residential units in the New York City area, which
are managed by the Insignia Residential Group.
</P>
<P>
   Once that sale has taken place, the company will go shopping
again in this country, said Stephen B. Siegel, Insignia/ESG's
president and chief executive, looking initially at the Boston and
San Francisco Bay areas. ``We are cleaning ourselves up with the
AIMCO deal and once that is done we're back to growth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidation is taking place on the residential side of the
business as well. The group that took control of Brown Harris
Stevens in 1995, which includes Kent M. Swig, William Lie
Zeckendorf, Arthur W. Zeckendorf and David A. Burris, has formed a
company called SBZZ NorthStar Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   This vehicle has acquired the Feathered Nest brokerage in
Manhattan, William Hutton Associates in Palm Beach, Fla., and the
Real Estate Center of Winter Park in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the commercial side, LaSalle Partners of Chicago, which
acquired the Galbraith Company last year, recently agreed to buy
Compass Management and Leasing from Lend Lease, making LaSalle the
largest real estate management services company in the country,
with 400 million square feet. The company has also said that it has
had discussions for some kind of combination with Jones Lang
Wootton, which has it roots in Britain. Both Compass and Jones Lang
have operations in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Although real estate has traditionally been a local business,
executives say the industry's current consolidation reflects
changes in corporate America. The trend to hire contractors to
fulfill functions deemed to be not essential to a company's basic
business and the reduction in the number of white collar employees
has made many companies unwilling to deal with separate service
providers in hundreds of local markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outsourcing, downsizing and globalization all originated in
America,'' said Arthur J. Mirante, the president and chief
executive of Cushman &AMP; Wakefield. ``Companies are finding it more
efficient to do business with one or two real estate companies than
try to deal with 50.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago this was a New York company that did not care
about Los Angeles or Miami,'' said John B. Coppedge III, Cushman &AMP;
Wakefield's executive managing director for international
operations. ``Then we started to care because our clients cared. If
a New York client wanted an office in Los Angeles we realized we
had better be able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirante said Cushman &AMP; Wakefield began a partnership with Healey
&AMP; Baker eight years ago and had recently been averaging 100 joint
transactions a year. He said both firms placed executives in each
other's offices so they could learn each other's culture and ways
of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   He said the merger was driven by client demands for uniformity
and technological capability that would be difficulty to achieve in
an informal alliance. ``You just can't call a partner and say you
have to have Lotus Notes in all your offices by next week, even
though it is a $10 million investment,'' Mirante said.
</P>
<P>
   Rothe of CB Richard Ellis said he agrees that a formal
relationship is preferable to even the closest alliance in
presenting a uniform face to clients. ``Suppose you have an
assignment to find four expansion sites for a client, three of
which will be profitable and one not,'' he said. ``If you ask an
affiliate to do the unprofitable work, they will start to make
excuses. And if you have to start negotiating with a partner, the
client hears about it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So the two parties devised the transaction whereby Cushman &AMP;
Wakefield invested $112 million to buy the Healey &AMP; Baker
partnership and Healey &AMP; Baker took 35 percent of that amount, or
slightly over $39 million, to buy Cushman &AMP; Wakefield stock for
distribution to Healey &AMP; Baker partners.
</P>
<P>
   Mirante said the arrangement builds in an incentive for existing
partners to remain and work to further build the company by tying
their compensation to financial performance. He said Cushman &AMP;
Wakefield would invest in what is now its subsidiary in Europe, the
Middle East and Africa to further develop its operations.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the work of integration will have to take place at
Cushman &AMP; Wakefield's New York office and 44 other offices around
the country, because of their domestic origin. ``I doubt that 10
percent of our people know how to dial the international access
code and country and city codes,'' said Coppedge. ``We've got 1,000
brokers we have to get accustomed to doing business overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   Real estate executives acknowledge that there are risks
associated with rapid expansion. Mirante concedes that his company
went too far in its domestic development, and was forced to cut
back from a high of 60 offices to the present 45.
</P>
<P>
   Integrating diverse cultures is a major issue, said Neil Young,
the chairman of Grubb &AMP; Ellis, which expanded rapidly after
becoming a publicly traded company in 1981, and then nearly failed
when the slump at the end of the decade forced $100 million in
writeoffs and office closings.
</P>
<P>
   Young said many of the problems were associated with trying to
pull a rapid series of acquisitions into a single organization.
``I've been here for 14 years, and I've seen the problems that can
happen with integration,'' he said. Of the 23 companies that Grubb
&AMP; Ellis bought to go national, all but two turned out to be
disappointments, he has said. In many cases, the acquisitions
turned out to be exit strategies for the former owners, who did not
contribute to the business after the transaction, Young said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has had an office in London for the last year and a
half to serve clients interested in the European market. He said he
is talking to companies about possible acquisitions, but is also
considering opening his company's own offices in major foreign
markets. ``We could go de novo,'' he said. ``That way you open up
with one name and no integration problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Others think global consolidation is moving too rapidly for such
an approach. ``The clients have made it clear what they want,''
Mirante said. ``Only the companies that provide the highest quality
of services on a global basis will get the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Coppedge said that ``there will be three or four of us globally,
and if you are not global quickly you may be left out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very expensive and complicated to open offices in
different countries on your own,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
