<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-FIFTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICIOSA WINS 5TH AVE. MILE 4TH STRAIGHT TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the 1970s, the Oakland A's won three straight
World Series, but not four. In the 1980s, Ivan Lendl won three
straight U.S. Open tennis titles, but not four. Early in the 1990s,
the Chicago Bulls won three straight National Basketball
Association titles, but not four.
</P>
<P>
   Isaac Viciosa, a 28-year-old, dark-haired Spaniard, has gone one
better. He won the Donald Trump Fifth Avenue Mile for men Saturday
for the fourth year in a row, a tribute to fine conditioning, a
keen sense of racing tactics and a killing sprint. Regina Jacobs of
Oakland, Calif., at 35 the oldest of the 12 in the women's race,
won that mile easily.
</P>
<P>
   The 19 races for children as young as 7 and veterans as old as
95 began at 80th Street and ended at 60th Street. In the men's
race, which had 17 starters, Viciosa felt the early pace was too
fast and backed off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to pay the consequences at the end,'' he said
through his coach and translator, Miguel Mostaza. ``But at the same
time you have to watch out for the other favorites. As the race
went on, I saw they were there. I was not really worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through the race, Viciosa was in front. He stayed there,
sprinting the last 60 meters and holding off Anthony Whiteman of
Britain by two feet. Viciosa's time of 3 minutes 55.59 seconds was
the slowest of his four victories, but because his kick is so good
he seems to run only as fast as he must.
</P>
<P>
   Whiteman, the runner-up last year, too, was surprised he did so
well this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very tired,'' he said. ``I'm on my fourth continent in
10 days. In that time, I've run in the World Cup in South Africa
and the Commonwealth Games in Malaysia, gone back to England to
pick up my girlfriend and flown here.''
</P>
<P>
   In the women's race, Jacobs took an immediate lead and ran by
herself. She beat Kelly Holmes of Britain by 13 meters in 4:20.8
and then sprinted back toward 62nd Street to thank the spectators
for cheering so loudly. She, like Viciosa, earned a winner's purse
of $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a career year for Jacobs, who ran her fastest ever
for 800 meters, the mile, 3,000 meters and 5,000 meters. Two weeks
ago, in the World Cup, she finished second at 5,000 meters and
third at 3,000. Viciosa has had a big year, too, winning the
European 5,000-meter title and setting a European record at 3,000
meters.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said she was getting excited because she was running so
well in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan to run more and more in the U.S. next year,'' she said.
``Maybe I'll motivate some young kids to succeed me. If they just
read about performances and don't see them, they won't get
inspired.''
</P>
<P>
   Viciosa wants to run here, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race is mucho prestigio,'' he said. ``I'm very happy to
run in New York every year and make history. Winning four years in
a row is very hard. I hope next year I can come back and win a
fifth time.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump, who puts up the prize and appearance money, had a quick
response to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be back,'' Trump said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
