<HEADER>
A6136 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEARDOWNS-REAL-3TAKES     09-26 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEARDOWNS-REAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: TEARDOWNS, `MCMANSIONS,' AND ANGRY NEIGHBORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LISA PREVOST   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In some wealthy New York suburbs, the tearing down of older
homes to make way for massive new luxury houses has moved beyond
the curiosity phase. As the pattern has picked up speed, several
towns have begun to look at ways of scaling back the size of what
some irritated neighbors call ``McMansions.'' And many longtime
residents who associate the older, smaller homes that are being
knocked down with their towns' very character are speaking out
against houses they say are out of sync with their communities.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury home builders such as Richard R. Girouard, owner of
Girouard Associates in New Canaan, Conn., however, consider the
selective razing of houses from generations gone by a suburban
upgrade. ``Esthetically, I believe, I'm improving the town,'' said
Girouard, who specializes in building $1.8-million-to-$4-million
mansions.
</P>
<P>
   But others view the towering displays of wealth encroaching on
their neighborhoods with little short of horror. In response, a
number of communities, including New Canaan, Greenwich and
Westport, Conn., and Ridgewood, N.J., as well as Hamptons
communities on Long Island, N.Y., are weighing proposals that would
extend restrictions on the size of houses or slow the demolition
process.
</P>
<P>
   Planners say the teardown trend can detract from a well-planned
community in a variety of ways. If the new houses are out of scale
with the rest of the neighborhood, they can upset the streetscape
by eating up lawn space and shade trees. And, they add, the
architecture of some of these trophy houses is of questionable
quality _ too much emphasis on ``big,'' and not enough attention to
design. Moreover, they say, the stock of lower-priced housing
declines as luxury homes replace smaller dwellings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of incremental redevelopment of a neighborhood could
have a social impact,'' said Jeffrey Soule, policy director for the
American Planning Association, based in Washington. ``People with
different goals and values moving into the same neighborhood can
create conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   New Canaan is a case in point. A history-minded community with a
well-preserved architectural and natural beauty, New Canaan has
attracted moneyed professionals ever since the arrival of rail
travel in the late 19th century. Recent cases in which smaller
homes have been knocked aside to make way for what some call
``starter castles'' have provoked a debate that, at its ugliest,
has come down to questions of class and taste.
</P>
<P>
   Residents have taken to insulting each other anonymously through
The New Canaan Advertiser's reader opinion line. In August the
column printed the opinion of one defender of the sizable new
houses who accused critics of being ``jealous'' because they live
in ``tacky ranches and crummy houses that need work.'' Other
callers responded with equal intensity. One man said the statement
showed an ``obvious and total lack of breeding.'' Another caller
said the people who live in the enormous new houses were ``more
into showing how much money they have'' than in housing quality.
</P>
<P>
   The divide has echoes of an earlier era in New Canaan's history.
As recalled by Richard R. Bergmann, chairman of New Canaan's
Historic District Commission, in the 1940s and '50s a handful of
pioneering architects ran up against considerable criticism when
they began building what were considered odd-shaped houses in the
modern style throughout the town.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn together through various ties to Harvard, Philip Johnson,
Marcel Breuer, Eliot Noyes, John M. Johansen and Landis Gores
followed one another to New Canaan to practice the flat-roofed,
boxy, minimalist style of architecture inspired by the Bauhaus. The
most famous example of this style, Johnson's Glass House on Ponus
Ridge Road, was considered particularly scandalous at the time,
Bergmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Now the houses are considered works of art by like-minded
architects such as Bergmann, who once worked for Noyes. But at
least three of the 30 or so houses built during this period have
since been razed, he said, lost to the more contemporary preference
for soaring ceilings, Palladian windows, multicar garages and even
a turret or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that the rooms are too small by today's
standards,'' Bergmann said. ``But it's too bad they couldn't keep
the house as a guest house and build a mansion beside it.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Homebuilders, based in Washington,
estimates that 100,000 to 200,000 houses a year are now either
completely gutted and rehabilitated or razed, primarily to make
room for high-end housing, said Gopal Ahluwalia, the organization's
director of research. Parts of the New York area where teardowns
are common have seen a gradual increase in the trend since the
early '90s, but the pace has accelerated during the latter half of
the decade.
</P>
<P>
   In Greenwich, for example, demolition of single-family homes has
nearly tripled since the 1996 fiscal year, from 16 in that year to
45 in the 1998 fiscal year, which ended Sept. 1, according to the
town Building Department. Westport counted 29 residential
demolitions in the 1998 fiscal year, which ended July 1, up sharply
from the 16 demolitions in the 1996 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Land is so scarce and demand so high for new luxury homes that
among builders ``sometimes there are feeding frenzies when a house
comes on the market,'' said Robert M. Haroun, co-owner of SIR
Development in Westport. Both Greenwich and Westport are seeking to
more tightly control the scale of the houses going up by adopting
new lot-coverage ratios.
</P>
<P>
   In New Canaan, 16 houses were demolished in 1997, twice as many
as in 1996, according to Gordon M. Donley, the town tax assessor.
He estimated that this year's total has already surpassed last
year's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The typical complaint is that these houses loom very large
over older homes,'' said Jon McEwan, New Canaan's assistant town
planner. ``They cast at least a psychological shadow. I think what
people are really opposed to is something that looks very different
from their home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These houses are often built big and wide to the street,'' he
continued, ``and so consequently, most of the trees in the front
yard are cut down. People remember the old town, so they get upset
by the new.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Richard Bond, New Canaan's First Selectman, is not convinced
that the town needs to take any action to rein in the scale of
these houses, especially, he noted, when bigger houses mean more
tax dollars for the town. Of approximately 6,000 homes in New
Canaan, he said, only about 100 would fall into the ``starter
castle'' category.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them are very attractive, some of them I don't care
for, but you come back to personal taste,'' said Bond. ``I think it
would be very difficult to legislate what size house you can
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, a subcommittee of the Planning and Zoning
Commission is considering whether to lower the maximum building
height allowance, currently 40 feet in the town's one-, two- and
four-acre zones, according to McEwan. Another possible change, he
said, would be the exclusion of overhangs (eaves and other
horizontal projections) from the lot coverage measurement to
encourage better architectural details.
</P>
<P>
   New Canaan already has what McEwan says are among the most
stringent building coverage regulations in Fairfield County. In the
two-acre zone, buildings may cover up to 5 percent, or 4,356 square
feet, of the lot; in the four-acre zone, the footprint must not
spread beyond 4 percent of the lot, or 6,969 square feet, he said.
Add in a second floor plus an attic in which 60 percent of the
space may be converted to living area, and ``you're talking a big
house,'' he said. ``But,'' he noted, ``everybody wants more.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Canaan Historical Society is lobbying for a 90-day
demolition delay on houses that are more than 50 years old. The
neighboring towns of Greenwich and Darien require such a delay.
This is intended to give adjoining property owners and historic
preservation officials time to object or discuss possible
alternatives when a particular building is set to be demolished.
</P>
<P>
   A demolition delay is already in place in New Canaan's Church
Hill historic district, a small area of 18th- and 19th-century
houses and churches adjacent to the village center. Though Bergmann
said he believes a town-wide ordinance would help ``discourage the
get-rich-quick people,'' he has only to look out the window of his
160-year-old home in the district to be reminded that a demolition
delay does not actually halt teardowns.
</P>
<P>
   The 18th-century farmhouse that once stood next door was razed
about 10 years ago, he said, after the owner ``managed to get the
Building Department to condemn the house as being unsafe.'' The
empty lot was only recently sold, and construction has since begun
on what Bergmann described as a federal-style house in keeping with
the district.
</P>
<P>
   Demolition delays and other proposed regulatory measures may, of
course, be beside the point in many cases. The oft-overlooked
truth, said James A. Fieber, a partner in the Fieber Group, which
builds luxury homes throughout Fairfield County, is that not all
houses are worth saving, particularly in areas with such high land
values. While the Fieber Group generally buys existing properties
solely for the building lot, the company will save a house with
high architectural value, such as the 1920s farmhouse sitting on
what is now a seven-lot subdivision on Pastures Lane in New Canaan.
</P>
<P>
   The six new $2.8-million-to-$3.2 million homes in the 22-acre
subdivision will have stone elements, window styles and other
details that mimic those of the original farmhouse, which is being
painstakingly renovated _ at a cost of close to $3 million _ for a
buyer who was uninterested in new construction, Fieber said. But
for that kind of property, he added, ``you have to have the right
buyer.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the new caveat might be ``seller beware'' _ fine
architectural details do not necessarily guarantee a house's
permanence. Hilary Nocka Jones. a resident of Ridgewood, N.J.,
learned that lesson the hard way this year when she sold her
deceased parents' house in the historic Heights Road area. Situated
just south of Saddle River in Bergen County, the village of
Ridgewood is known for its bounty of large stately homes, many of
them grand Victorians. The Heights Road area is particularly
desirable because of its proximity to the train station.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones' parents' house, which she described as a 1901
Colonial Revival with a gambrel roof, was their ``absolute pride
and joy,'' she said. With five bedrooms, the house was sizable, she
said, and was loaded with such period details as 18-inch-high
moldings and an oak stairway with a mahogany railing.
</P>
<P>
   She agreed to sell the house for $650,000 to Mark and Wendy
Epstein of New York City in April, but only found out an hour
before the closing that the Epsteins intended to tear it down.
Because the buyers had met all the terms of the contract, Mrs.
Jones was unable to stop the sale. The house was torn down in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been awful. I can't even drive up the street to look,''
said Mrs. Jones, who grew up in the house. ``I happen to believe
houses have souls at this point _ I never thought about it before
this crisis. I just wanted someone to buy it who would love the
house the way my parents did.''
</P>
<P>
   Epstein declined to comment on the matter other than to
acknowledge that he was surprised by the reaction to his plans.
Mrs. Jones circulated a petition protesting the teardown and
obtained signatures from 60 residents.
</P>
<P>
   And a neighbor, Martha Steinbach, began soliciting support for a
demolition delay and reduced floor-area ratios in Ridgewood. After
she distributed flyers on the subject, about 30 residents showed up
at a Planning Board meeting last July to voice their support, Mrs.
Steinbach said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ridgewood has one of the largest concentrations of Victorian
homes in Bergen County. And we're very proud of it,'' said Mrs.
Steinbach, who, with her husband, Robert, owns a 100-year-old
Victorian surrounded by perennial gardens on Heights Road.
``Homeowners spend thousands and thousands of dollars to maintain
these homes. So when people come in and start tearing them down,
those of us who live in these homes get a little concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start tearing down the old homes,'' she added, ``we're
going to be like anybody else. How much of the town are we willing
to let go?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
