<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6140 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEARDOWNS-REAL-3RDTAK     09-26 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEARDOWNS-REAL-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: let go?''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Epsteins were the second buyers in two years to demolish a
house on Heights Road. Across the street from their lot, all but a
small portion of another house was taken down to make way for a
sprawling contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   But Ridgewood is by no means under siege by bulldozers. The
Epsteins' teardown represented the first complete residential
demolition since 1995, when there were four, according to the
village's Building and Inspections Department. But Mrs. Steinbach
argues that the village should act now before more houses are lost.
Under the village's existing floor-to-area ratio, or FAR, a house's
gross floor area may cover up to 30 percent of lot size, according
to Arthur Wrubel, chairman of the village's Historic Preservation
Commission and a former member of the Planning Board.
</P>
<P>
   The village's mayor, Patrick Mancuso, said the Planning Board
was reviewing the matter and would eventually present its findings
to the Village Council. But he said he was leery of acting too
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people feel unquestionably that people have a right
to do whatever they want with their property,'' the mayor said.
``Some feel it's up to the seller to prevent (demolition), possibly
through a deed restriction. Others feel any restrictions should be
done on a neighborhood by neighborhood basis. We have to listen to
a lot of different people.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Greenwich and Westport are poised to adopt zoning
regulations that set new limitations on house sizes. In Greenwich,
residents of the more rural parts of town are upset with both the
size of the houses going up in their neighborhoods and the
increasing density, according to Peter K. Joyce, chairman of the
Planning and Zoning Commission, who is a real estate agent for
Coldwell Banker.
</P>
<P>
   In those two- and four-acre zones, the town has no limits on the
size of houses as long as they meet the setback requirements, Joyce
said. So the commission is currently drafting floor-area ratios for
those districts. The town's other residential zones already have
either floor-area ratios or building coverage limits.
</P>
<P>
   Westport residents will have an opportunity to review proposed
changes in that town's building coverage regulations at a public
hearing on Oct. 29. According to Katherine G. Barnard, the planning
and zoning director, current regulations allow total lot coverage
of up to 25 percent in the one- and two-acre zones. That allowance
includes such things as driveways, tennis courts, outbuildings, and
swimming pools. The Planning and Zoning Commission wants to specify
a separate building coverage allowance similar to New Canaan's so
that the ground-floor footprint could not exceed 7 percent in the
one-acre zone and 5 percent in the two-acre zone, Ms. Barnard said.
The total coverage allowance would not change.
</P>
<P>
   The draft regulations also call for a decreased building height
allowance of 30 feet instead of the 40 feet currently allowed in
both zones, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Hamptons communities on Long Island, some towns and
villages are considering or putting into place historic-district or
landmarks measures to save older houses from demolition.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of East Hampton, administrator Larry Cantwell
said the village recently created a historic district, the third in
10 years, to protect older houses. ``Homeowners support these
districts because they see what's going on, and they want to
protect the character of their neighborhoods,'' Cantwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinances for creating historic districts are on the books in
the village of Sag Harbor and under discussion in the town of East
Hampton. In the town of Southampton, officials are debating
amendments to a historic landmarks law to protect historically
significant houses.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 8, the Southampton Town Board voted to limit new houses
to 20,000 square feet of floor space to counter what the town said
were ``recent housing market and construction trends in which new
residential construction in Southampton can occur in a scale
disproportionate to existing residential construction.''
</P>
<P>
   The law was proposed after residents in Sagaponack questioned
whether a 29-bedroom, 39-bath oceanfront mansion on which work is
now under way could be considered a single-family home. The five
building estate complex planned by Ira Rennert, an industrialist
and investor, would occupy 110,000 square feet on 63 acres of
former farmland. It would include a 77,000 square-foot house that
would be the largest home in America.
</P>
<P>
   While no houses or other structures were demolished to make way
for Rennert's complex, the pace of demolitions of older homes is
trending upward throughout the Hamptons. George Mathys, owner of
George's Roll Off and Demolition Service in Quogue, said he had
demolished 16 large homes so far this year and 18 last year.
``Probably 50 percent of them were totally livable,'' Mathys said.
``It makes me sad because I would love to live in a lot of them
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwin M. Schwenk, a founder of a preservation group, East End
Forever, said the knocking down of old houses was changing the
town's character. ``They are tearing down some of the old,
substantial structures that we knew Southampton by and coming up
with all this new-type architecture,'' said Schwenk, a Southampton
native. ``I think we are losing something.''
</P>
<P>
   Haroun, the Connecticut builder, commutes to New York City
during the week where he works full-time as a patent attorney. He
and his wife, Julie, got into the luxury home-building market as a
sideline about five years ago, he said, and since that time have
built about 15 speculative houses in Westport.
</P>
<P>
   He described the houses they have torn down as primarily 1960s
raised ranches and split levels that were never improved.
Sometimes, he said, neighbors are grateful for the changes. For
example, his company recently tore down a 600-square-foot ``shack''
that was located adjacent to a three-lot subdivision they were
developing. The shack had no running water and had been occupied by
a recluse, Haroun said. ``Three or four neighbors came to me, and
it was like I was now their godson,'' he said. ``It was an
eyesore.''
</P>
<P>
   Haroun acknowledges a backlash in Westport against the latest
round of development, adding that the financial burden placed on
the town because of school overcrowding makes it understandable.
``But at the same time,'' he noted, ``you don't want to end up a
dead community where nothing happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, observed Fieber, ``It's a luxury problem to have to sit
down and talk about teardowns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
