<HEADER>
A6141 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-N     09-26 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE NOTCHES NO. 20 AS YANKS DOWN DEVIL RAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was supposed to be a tuneup for the post-season
for David Cone. Five innings, maybe fewer, and gone. Even Cone
conceded that the chances were slim that he would hang around long
enough Saturday to win his 20th game, and climax an amazing regular
season in stylish fashion.
</P>
<P>
   But, as has often been the case with the Yankees, the game
proved unpredictable and unbelievable. Trash the script again
because Cone wound up tossing seven sharp innings to power the
Yankees to a 3-0 victory over the Devil Rays on a festive day at
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   When Mike Stanton bagged the 27th out, the Yanks had extended
their American League record for victories to 113 in the
penultimate contest of the regular season while Cone notched his
20th after faltering in two previous attempts. It was the first
time Cone had reached that magical plateau since going 20-3 with
the Mets in 1988 and his 10-year stretch between 20-victory seasons
set a major league record for the longest gap ever.
</P>
<P>
   Cone (20-7), who will start Game 3 of the division series on
Friday, looked sharp as he unleashed a nasty slider, a tricky
curveball and a sneaky fastball in limiting the Devil Rays to four
hits while whiffing eight and walking one. If Joe Torre had any
doubts about whether Cone is prepared for October, they were erased
Saturday because he let the 35-year-old right-hander work
economically and effortlessly for 101 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre might have another problem, although it is a pleasant
one. Shane Spencer blasted a titanic 420-foot homer off Terrell
Wade into the Devil Ray bullpen in the third, his ninth of the
season, his seventh of the month of September, setting a Yankee
rookie record, and his sixth over his last 20 at bats. With Spencer
sizzling, with Tim Raines and Darryl Strawberry hobbling and with
Chad Curtis fizzling, Torre may have to consider starting Spencer
in left field. The Texas Rangers, who could be New York's opponent
in the division series, are scheduled to start four right-handers,
which would obviously hurt Spencer's chances of starting.
</P>
<P>
   While Cone and Spencer reveled in a splendid day in the Bronx,
Bernie Williams went 1 for 4 and maintained his thin lead over
Boston's Mo Vaughn in the batting race. Williams, who singled in
his last at bat, is now batting .33601 while Vaughn, who went 1 for
3 Saturday, is at .33553, meaning they are separated by less than
half a point entering the final day of play.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest moment for Cone actually came on an out. Rich
Butler smacked a one-hopper to the mound to open the third, which
Cone did not have an opportunity to react to. He caught the ball in
his stomach, mostly out of self-defense, cradled it close to him
and then skipped on one foot and flipped side-armed to first.
</P>
<P>
   After collecting the out, Cone immediately put his hands on his
knees and exhaled. His face turned red and he looked like a
quarterback who had just been sacked by Reggie White. Trainer Gene
Monahan raced to Cone's side and the pitcher told Torre that he
felt as if he had the wind knocked out of him. Torre looked
concerned and might have thought about removing Cone right there.
But Cone threw some warmups, stayed in the game and was virtually
unhittable.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Cairo blooped a double to right after Cone was jolted in
the stomach, but he never budged. The Devil Rays also placed
runners on first and third with out one in the fifth, but John
Flaherty bounced into a fielder's choice in which Butler was nailed
at home and Quinton McCracken punched a grounder to second. After
the out, the normally stoic Cone pumped his fist. He realized that
he was on the verge of an important milestone and Torre let Cone
stay in two more innings to protect the potential victory.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Torre lounged in the dugout and spoke about the
Yankees for close to an hour. On and on, the manager chatted about
this remarkable team. Torre was thoroughly enjoying the banter and
even balked when a club official tried to terminate the lengthy
interview session.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing?,'' asked Torre. ``I'm comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre stayed in the dugout a little longer and stayed
comfortable all afternoon as the Yankees won again. Cone was
tremendous, Spencer was terrific, Tino Martinez also homered and
Williams is still leading the batting race.
</P>
<P>
   Trash the script. The Yankees keep writing better stories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
