<HEADER>
A6143 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOMINICAN-RECOVERY-09     09-26 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMINICAN-RECOVERY-0926-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RELIEF SLOW IN COMING, AS BATTERED DOMINICAN REPUBLIC STRUGGLES
TO RECOVER
 &HT;    ATTN EDs: Optional add begins at 600 words.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   POLO, Dominican Republic _ On a fresh stream bed of rocks --
many the size of basketballs -- the friends and neighbors of Julio
Feliz sifted through the soaking documents of a family lost to
Hurricane Georges.
</P>
<P>
   Four members of the family were killed during the night last
Tuesday when the hurricane swept through this town of 14,000
people, spawning massive rock slides and slashing deep ravines that
damaged roughly 80 percent of the ramshackle tin-roofed wooden
houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have much pain in my heart because what passed through here
was so immense,'' said Lydia Maria Jimenez Reyes, 51, a neighbor
who helped delicately peel the Feliz family's documents apart and
put them on rocks to dry. ``We were fabulous friends and all of a
sudden they are gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the smashed wooden house -- partially swallowed by the
torrent of rocks that swept down from the mountains, its roof
tilting at a precarious angle, one edge touching the ground --
Carlo Feliz poked through the remains of his brother's house. Feliz
held a photograph of a nephew, one of two members of the family
still missing. He cried as he told reporters of his fruitless
four-day search for anyone still alive from his brother's family.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of the number dead in this town varied from to 23 to 30
-- an enormous blow to a community used to burying one or two
people a month.
</P>
<P>
   The death toll in the Dominican Republic -- one of the hardest
hit countries on Georges' path -- was put at more than 200 late
Saturday with hundreds more reported missing.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said damages to farms, roads and buildings
from Hurricane Georges will surpass $1.2 billion. The hurricane hit
several large islands in its march across the Caribbean, but damage
and death were especially heavy in the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The Americas International Airport outside Santo Domingo was
reopened Saturday morning, and water service was restored to much
of the capital, said Temistocles Montas, aide to President Leonel
Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Still, exact numbers and conditions were still uncertain
Saturday as government officials continued trying to reach
widespread rural communities.
</P>
<P>
   The first rescue teams reached Polo, about 120 miles southwest
of the capital of
</P>
<P>
   Santo Domingo, about 1 a.m. EDT Saturday and the first relief
efforts did not arrive until mid-morning.
</P>
<P>
   What they found was a poor but thriving town devastated by
Georges, with many people looking to the government and
international relief as their only salvation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to live with it,'' said Mayor Ana Cuevas Pena. ``Of
course they feel destroyed in their hearts, but they have to live
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of one of the dirt roads that sprawl across this
mountainous town, Clavin(CQ) Feliz Cuevas, 48, sat in a house
stripped bare by the hurricane. Her sister and brother-in-law,
their son and his wife, and one grandchild were killed by the
storm. Another grandchild, a 4-year-old girl, was missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not eaten,'' Cuevas said. ``We have no water, no food
... no beds, no clothes. We have nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   In a week, Cuevas predicted, things would be even worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nowhere to buy food. Nowhere to buy anything. In a
week we will run out of strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Teh Associated Press reported that U.S. relief officials said
aid was arriving in Santo Domingo but could not be distributed to
many parts of the country by land. Relief flights would begin
within 48 hours, they said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to personnel and supplies from the United States,
aid began arriving from France, Spain, Italy, Canada, Chile and
other nations. The government also sought help from the World Bank
and other international agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Only 5 percent of the country's tourism centers were damaged by
the storm, Montas said. But some of the natural beauty that draws
tourists will need time to recover.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add begins.)
</P>
<P>
   Ernestina Ferreras, 48, one of about a dozen people who crowded
into Cuevas' house to talk to reporters, summed up the attitude of
many whose livelihoods were uprooted with the local coffee crop:
``There is no future in this place.''
</P>
<P>
   The burials here have been hasty. Because of the rain that
continued for days after the storm, the bodies were interred
without the usual funeral processions. Most, but not all of the
dead, were buried in quickly constructed caskets. Some were just
wrapped in sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Anibal Espinal, a thin wiry man with grizzled stubble is a
carpenter. He made three of the caskets used to bury the dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very tragic situation for us, and it is very
important to bury our people, the poor people of this country, with
dignity,'' he said. ``We cannot allow a monster to take this away
from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Georges, Polo was a marketplace for fresh fruits and
vegetables. Klaus Leiders, the German manager of a nearby salt
mine, said Polo was his favorite spot in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was paradise,'' he said. ``Now the feeling is desperate.
A lot of people would like to leave this place, but they have
nowhere to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of the disaster that hit Polo were everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   A road was cut by a deep ravine whose gravelled bottom lay some
40 feet below. Part of a house perched over the ravine, its
splintered side hanging in the air.
</P>
<P>
   A stream ran through an area where once there were a half-dozen
houses. The owner of one of the houses appeared in shock. Asked
what the future holds for him, he could not understand the
question.
</P>
<P>
   A church on top of a hill was crowded with people waiting to
speak to a military officer. Pews were pushed together to form
beds. On one pew were children's' shoes and toys. A chicken
scurried noisily beneath the pews.
</P>
<P>
   Men, women and children clutching jugs and buckets -- some
lashed to horses -- stood patiently in line next to a hillside
where water spouted from a narrow pipe.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the devastation there were signs of life. A group
of men hammered at a tin roof covering a demolished house. They
planned to use the metal to cover another house.
</P>
<P>
   In the street outside the town's tiny hospital, young boys
played stickball using a lively rubber ball.
</P>
<P>
   Freddy Alba, the hospital director, noted that many people are
waiting for help from the government, relief agencies and the
world. Many don't want to remain in Polo, but he said the town will
survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a town of workers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
