<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY EMBARRASSES U.S. IN DAVIS CUP PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Strange things have been happening in Davis Cup ever
since this international competition began in 1900. Patriotic
pipsqueaks have scrambled past powerhouse shoe-ins, insurmountable
deficits have inspired miraculous comebacks, and nationalistic fans
have thrown everything but kitchen sinks at players they viewed as
visiting villains.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why this weekend's semifinal between a virtual
tag team assembled by the United States, whose big stars boycotted
the round, and a revenge-minded group of overachievers from Italy,
which hasn't won a Cup since 1976 and was routed, 5-0, by the U.S.
in Palermo five years ago, veered toward the bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   No projectiles were thrown, but logic was continually defied.
Whenever Andrea Gaudenzi, Italy's chatty top gun, spoke to the
ball, he did so in English, and it obeyed him. Could Italy be so
brazen as to throttle the United States right here in the
heartland? Yes, it could. Three strikes and the United States was
out.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling off an upset that humiliated the host nation, which owns
31 Davis Cups and had designs on securing a 32nd at Sweden's
expense in the December finale, Italy completed a giddy 3-0 sweep
of the U.S. in this best-three-of-five-match semifinal. That they
didn't face an American dream team didn't bother the Italians at
all. Taking full advantage of the absence of Pete Sampras and Andre
Agassi, and also reaping benefits from captain Tom Gullikson's
decision to confine Jim Courier to bench duty, Gaudenzi and Diego
Nargiso blithely finished off the United States with a 6-4, 7-5,
5-7, 2-6, 6-3 defeat of Todd Martin and Justin Gimelstob.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that without Sampras and Agassi, it's another
team, but it's still the U.S. team,'' said Italy's captain, Paolo
Bertolucci, whose country was 2-7 against the U.S. prior to its
defiant performance in this round. By humbling the Americans,
Italy, which had never before hosted a final in seven previous
appearances but will now entertain Sweden on red clay, reached its
first final since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday at the Milwaukee Arena, where a not-so-coincidental
Italian street festival with a Nashville beat pulsated just outside
the painfully sluggish hardcourt, the atmosphere inside had wavered
between pep rally and seance. With the United States pushed to the
brink of elimination once Friday's singles losses by the veteran
Martin and the rookie Jan Michael Gambill put the hosts in a 2-0
hole, it was left to Martin and another 21-year-old rookie,
Gimelstob, to stave off Italy's attempt to bury them with a 3-0
sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Desperation didn't pay off, and the U.S. Davis Cup team's record
of recovery from 2-0 deficits dropped to one for 29. (Their only
comeback occurred in 1934 against Australia.)
</P>
<P>
   Saturday the Americans were forced to save two match points
against Gimelstob's serve in the 10th game of the third set, and
buoyed by their success there, they broke for 6-5 and captured the
set with an ace from Martin. The Italians backed off in the fourth
set, but in the fifth, anxious to snuff their host's comeback
hopes, they picked up their pace again.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of responding in kind, the U.S. duo ultimately buckled.
Hamstrung by Martin's slow start in the first two sets and by
Gimelstob's catastrophic service games in the fourth and eighth
games of the final set, they were upstaged by Gaudenzi's array of
heroics, including a diving backhand volley that upheld a 4-3 edge
in the fifth set, and Nargiso's calm passes down the sidelines. The
match took three hours 29 minutes to resolve, and when Martin's
final return had caromed harmlessly out of bounds on the third
match point, Nargiso, who hadn't played in a month due to
hypoglycemia-induced fatigue, fell smack on his back and was
immediately joined by his partner, who belly-flopped on top of him.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I served a really poor fifth set; you can't play two egregious
service games in a row like that,'' said Gimelstob, whose Grand
Slam poise _ he captured two mixed-doubles titles with Venus
Williams this year _ deserted him in his Davis Cup debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I panicked a little bit,'' said Gimelstob, who doublefaulted
twice in succession to put his team down 3-1 in the final set, a
lapse they only temporarily repaired by breaking back in the fifth
game for 3-2. When Gimelstob failed again in the eighth game, the
Italians went up 5-3 and got their first chance to serve for the
match and seal their spot in the final.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the 1973 final, when Australia's Rod Laver and John
Newcombe made themselves overly at home in Cleveland, had the U.S.
been swept on its own turf. Not since 1987, when Boris Becker led a
West German team to victory in Hartford, had the U.S. surrendered a
home stand. Italy's coup ended an 18-match home winning streak for
the U.S. and was, said Gaudenzi, possibly the start of something
big at home for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tennis is not the main sport, but when it gets to Davis Cup,
when there is a flag involved, Italy is very emotional, so I hope
this can help the tennis movement in Italy,'' said Gaudenzi. ``Even
if we didn't beat the best U.S. team, this is a big result for
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
