<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6150 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BENEFITS-COX     09-26 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENEFITS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Employee benefits to undergo major change
 &HT;    By Angela Townsend
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Employee benefits, which many working Americans
consider only slightly less important than wages or salary, are
undergoing unprecedented change.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, companies nationwide are offering benefits once
unheard of. These perks include elder care, adoption assistance,
government-mandated family leave and continuing health care
coverage even after you become unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   But the big news is what traditional benefits workers are losing
these days.
</P>
<P>
   In June the U.S. Supreme Court refused to consider an appeal of
a January ruling by the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Cincinnati that said General Motors Corp. had the right to change
or end the free lifetime health care benefits to retirees. The
court said GM's plan plainly stated the company could amend or
terminate it. In 1989, 84,000 salaried employees who retired from
GM between 1974 and 1988 filed suit, saying GM had reneged on a
promise.
</P>
<P>
   Sears Roebuck &AMP; Co. retirees are still fighting the company's
decision last year to reduce all retiree life insurance policies to
$5,000 over 10 years, while entirely cutting benefits for current
employees. The average retiree had a $17,000 whole life policy
through the company, although some policies were for as much as
$100,000. About 84,000 retirees were affected by the change. The
retirees, who have formed a national association, say Sears used
the life insurance ''lifetime'' benefit as a recruiting tool.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton-based NCR Corp. last week sent out letters to its
employees and retirees outlining future changes in its health care
benefits plans, which have the reputation of being extraordinarily
rich. In 1999, NCR will go from assuming the total cost of benefits
to requiring workers to contribute a percentage of their paychecks.
Also, employees hired on oR after Jan. 1 will not get retiree
medical coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than a year ago, we began taking a close look at our
health care plans, and we found that they were `out of line' with
comparable companies both inside and outside the markets where we
compete,'' NCR Chairman and Chief Executive Lars Nyberg said in the
letter. Companies such as Andersen Consulting, IBM and the
Hewlett-Packard all require employee contributions for coverage,
Nyberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Nyberg went on to say he remained ``convinced that these
difficult moves are essential for NCR to remain competitive and to
ensure the survival of our company.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCR decision comes as no surprise. In fact, it's a wonder
the company didn't make the move sooner.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 survey by the Washington D.C.-based management consultant
firm William M. Mercer Inc. showed the number of companies offering
retiree health care benefits is declining, down to 31 percent from
39 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Employee Benefits Research Institute, also in
Washington D.C., employer spending on group health insurance also
is down. From 1980 to 1990, spending grew from $61 billion to
$188.6 billion, an average annual rate of 11.9 percent. But from
1990 to 1996, the increase in spending dropped to about 5.7 percent
a year, from $188.6 billion to $262.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Ken McDonnell, a research analyst with EBRI, said NCR's move
simply follows a larger trend. ``Companies have started bracing for
the health care costs they are anticipating coming up against,'' he
said. By not asking employees to foot the bill, NCR has been in a
``definite minority.''
</P>
<P>
   Employee benefits experts agree that employees everywhere have
access to far superior health care plans, but they're also paying a
lot more for that coverage. Workers typically spend anywhere from
25 to 35 percent of their paycheck on health care insurance,
depending on the type and size of company and its geographical
location. Coincidentally, the paycheck compensation of NCR
employees opting for single health care coverage next year will
still be far below average at 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, company-sponsored retirement plans such as 401(k)
plans are quickly eclipsing traditional pensions. A recent national
study found the number of companies with more than 100 employees
that offered 401(k) plans nearly doubled from 1994 to 1998. So it's
quite possible these days for big chunks of someone's paycheck to
go toward insurance and retirement costs _ expenses that once were
the sole responsibility of the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend is going toward the cafeteria approach, where the
employee picks up a core level of benefits. Companies are saying,
'anything above that and we'll pay for it,' especially the ones in
large urban areas that can work with networks and (preferred
provider organizations) to manage costs, `` said Kathryn Kennedy,
an assistant professor at John Marshall School of Law in Chicago
and the director of the school's program in employee benefits.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that employers earmarked the majority of benefits
money toward retirement. That has changed, with health care and
dental care plans taking precedent, Kennedy said. ``Benefit
packages are much better, but there's a huge cost associated with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies are well aware of those costs; to offset them, they've
taken steps to create other benefits to ensure the ability to
recruit new employees and to keep current ones from jumping ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are trying to off-set (the added costs) with
freebie-type benefits such as auto club memberships, discount
tickets to different events, opportunities at shopping clubs,''
said Mary Carl, president of the 415-member Miami Valley Human
Resources Association and herself the human resources director of
the Senior Resource Connection. ``By and large, most are trying to
get very creative with benefit packages, looking at it as total
compensation. They're making it much more attractive to potential
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Other perks that larger companies are starting to adopt include
flex time, summer hours and additional sick days for emergency
child care.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Chernoff, a managing partner and founder of Chernoff
Diamond, a New York-based benefits advisory firm that provides
strategic advice to mid-sized employers on qualified retirement
plans and health and welfare programs, says it's all about
employers competing for qualified workers. ``There's a need to
reward them in every meaningful respect _ compensation, retirement,
disability/health insurance programs, things such as vacation and
sick time.''
</P>
<P>
   That also mean taking greater care to address the needs of women
and physically challenged employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general terms, benefits have become more
employee-friendly,'' said Alex Jones, human resources manager of
Shopsmith Inc., a locally based power tool company with just over
100 employees. ``There's stiff competition (for workers). One of
the tie-breakers in a lot of instances is the benefits package.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts predict that health care costs for employees will
continue to creep up. But that's probably the only certainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until there's relief from the federal government _ which could
be a good thing or bad _ the companies are going to shift more and
more of the cost burden to employees,'' Carl said. On the flip
side, however, workers will take more ownership of what their
benefits packages look like.
</P>
<P>
   And that will likely be dictated by the Baby Boomer generation,
whose members want great health care now and great retirement
benefits when they begin leaving the work force shortly, Kennedy
said. She added that a continued push toward universal health care
would not surprise her.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, it will be expensive, Kennedy said. ``The cost
is becoming so dramatically higher. It's got to come out of
somebody's pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
