<HEADER>
A6151 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORISON-TRIAL-COX     09-26 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORISON-TRIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fraud trial of former professor begins Monday
 &HT;    By Carrie Teegardin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Dr. Richard Borison, once a high-profile professor at
the Medical College of Georgia, is set to go on trial Monday in
Augusta to face charges that he masterminded a research scam and
stole more than $10 million from the college.
</P>
<P>
   The central issue in the long-awaited trial will be whether the
case even belongs in a criminal court.
</P>
<P>
   Borison's attorney will argue that the researcher didn't steal a
dime, that he earned all of the $10 million in payments from
pharmaceutical companies through private contracts that had nothing
to do with the Medical College. But the state will argue that
Borison was required to funnel all research grants through the
college and that when he didn't, he was stealing.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Borison and his former research partner
stunned the Augusta academic community and cast a shadow over the
administration of the Medical College. The college responded by
creating a new department to keep closer tabs on its researchers,
their grant money and the human subjects participating in trials.
State and federal agencies also opened investigations to determine
whether patients were harmed.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston native, Borison was chairman of the college's
Department of Psychiatry and one of its most respected faculty
members when administrators learned in 1996 that he was running
clinical drug trials, without their knowledge, that might be
jeopardizing the safety of patients.
</P>
<P>
   Borison and his research partner, Bruce Diamond, were charged
last year in a 172-count indictment with theft, making false
statements, bribery, racketeering, tax evasion and other crimes
after an investigation by the Georgia attorney general's office. In
a separate civil action, the state is suing Borison to recover more
than $5 million in assets from his corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The subject is money
</P>
<P>
   The investigation concluded that Borison and Diamond, a former
MCG pharmacology professor, stole from the college by setting up a
research operation near the campus in a private office staffed in
part with college employees.
</P>
<P>
   The two men got dozens of contracts for experimental drug
studies with many of the nation's top pharmaceutical companies,
then pocketed millions of dollars from the research grants rather
than funneling the money through the college's research institute,
investigators said. College policies required researchers to inform
the college of research proposals, share research funds with the
college's research institute and get approval from an ethics board
for projects involving human subjects. Investigators found more
than $10 million in grants dating back to 1988 that they contend
should have gone to the college. ``This is one of the largest
cases, in terms of amounts of money involved, that we have ever
handled,'' said Attorney General Thurbert Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Borison used the money, investigators said, to live an upscale
life in which he traveled and lectured internationally, collected
expensive antiques from auction houses and planned to build a $4.5
million, 11,000-square foot ``castle'' to house his collection.
Borison kept a model of the building in his office.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond pleaded guilty in December to a variety of charges,
including 26 counts of theft. He was sentenced to five years in
prison and 10 years' probation and fined $125,000. He agreed to
make restitution of $1.1 million to the college and to testify
against his former partner at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta attorney Michael C. Garrett, Borison's lawyer, will
argue that Borison was, in essence, moonlighting. The contracts
were made between pharmaceutical manufacturers and private
companies created and run by Borison and Diamond, and the checks
were made out to them, not the Medical College.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funds which the state of Georgia has accused Dr. Borison
of stealing are the proceeds of outside research that he did,''
Garrett said in an interview last week. ``This was never the
property of the Medical College of Georgia Research Institute to
begin with. I don't know of any legal basis for them to say it's
theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial will focus almost exclusively on money. But the
attorney general's investigation and inquiries by other agencies
concluded that Borison's research operation also put human subjects
at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Risks involved
</P>
<P>
   Borison won contracts because he was good at finding people
willing to try experimental medications, which the drug companies
need to prove to the U.S. Food and Drug Administration that their
products are safe and effective.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the trials were for people with Alzheimer's disease,
schizophrenia and certain psychiatric conditions. Some patients
responded to advertisements, while others were recruited at the
Augusta Veterans Affairs Medical Center, where Borison had
privileges.
</P>
<P>
   The patients and their families often came to Borison's office
desperate for help with hopeless conditions. Most were certain that
the Medical College of Georgia was overseeing the studies.
</P>
<P>
   But later investigations have found that enrolling large numbers
of patients in drug studies often was a higher priority than the
patients' health:
</P>
<P>
   An FDA investigation observed 20 violations of research rules,
including a failure to report serious side effects, enrolling
patients who did not fit study requirements and allowing
unqualified employees to perform medical tasks. Researchers also
failed to properly obtain informed consent from some patients, the
cornerstone of ethical research. The FDA has not issued a final
report.
</P>
<P>
   A Veterans Affairs investigation found that vulnerable patients
were coerced to enroll in trials by promises of money, that
research workers with no medical training were given signed
prescription pads and allowed to order controlled substances, and
that some patients were enrolled in studies without being properly
informed of the risks.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Advocacy Office, a government-appointed watchdog
organization for people with psychiatric conditions, still is
investigating the way patients were handled. But the organization
has been hampered by state officials' refusal to allow the release
of patients' records that the group says it is legally entitled to.
The GAO is taking legal action to try to secure the records.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people were damaged and it's our duty to look into abuse
and neglect,'' said Joyce Ringer, executive director of the
Advocacy Office. ``They were vulnerable and they did not get good
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Many family members of patients in the Borison trials were
shocked to find out they were being run outside of the Medical
College and that unqualfied staff people had been in charge of the
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel like the Medical College is kind of a front and
that they're not really keeping tabs on what's going on,'' said
Janis Huckeba, whose husband Lewis was enrolled in a study of an
Alzheimer's drug.
</P>
<P>
   Huckeba, who had always held the Medical College in esteem, said
Borison and his staff abandoned her when her husband became
extremely agitated and paranoid, even when he took a loaded gun and
refused to relinquish it. When she called the research office for
help, she said, Diamond offered nothing, telling her to go to her
private physician.
</P>
<P>
   Huckeba had been assured when her husband enrolled that the
doctors and college would handle any medical problems. Huckeba
later became infuriated when she found out that research assistants
who took charge of her husband's care and saw him during his
regulation visits had no medical training.
</P>
<P>
   What is Huckeba hoping for from the jury who hears Borison's
case?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see him pay for what he's done,'' Huckeba said.
``He has used people to pad his own pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
