<HEADER>
A6152 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARTER-AGING-COX     09-26 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARTER-AGING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Age-old virtues
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Kurylo
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_ His hair is pure silver. His face is lined with
wrinkles. At the end of a long day, his weariness occasionally
betrays him and becomes obvious.
</P>
<P>
   But as his 74th birthday approaches, Jimmy Carter shows no signs
of slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, the former president spent a week building
Habitat for Humanity houses in Houston, visited 13 countries to
promote peace and human rights and made more than 100 speeches
across the globe. He taught Sunday school in Plains two to three
times a month; lectured at Emory University, where he is a
distinguished professor; and finished writing his 14th book, which
is to be published next month.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, Rosalynn, his wife of 52 years, was by his
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we stay as busy as we ever did,'' the former president
said in an interview at his Carter Center office in Atlanta, where
he spends about a week each month. ``We're both in good health.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who turns 74 on Thursday, tackles the topic of aging in
his new book, ``The Virtues of Aging'' (Ballantine, $9.95,
paperback only). If you have good health, growing old gracefully is
simply a matter of having a positive attitude, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person is old when one thinks he or she is old'' and begins
to depend on others, Carter said. It's important to approach each
day with ``an inquisitive attitude,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Each day offers the chance to ``learn more about God's world,
learn more about other people, learn more about myself, do
challenging, interesting, exciting and unpredictable things,'' said
Carter, who still rises before dawn and works several hours before
breakfast. ``We have a unique capability when we reach retirement
age, an element of freedom we haven't had before, because in the
past we were pursuing a career, or trying to earn enough money for
our families or for retirement and security in our old age. But
then we reach a point where we don't have all those duties. What do
we do with our life?''
</P>
<P>
   Carter was 56 when he was ``involuntarily retired'' from the
White House. The defeat was painful, and his return to Plains was
depressing. ``We felt that nothing could replace the four more
years that I had anticipated spending as the nation's president,''
he says in his new book. ``Rosalynn was especially bitter and
angry, unable to accept with equanimity the result of the 1980
election.''
</P>
<P>
   He figured he had about 25 years left, considering that he
expected to make it to 80. He wrote his memoirs; she wrote her
autobiography. Then they worked together to establish the Carter
Center, a think tank linked to Emory University in Atlanta, which
is their home base for programs to improve health, agriculture,
democracy and human rights around the world. For years they
traveled the world, monitoring elections, convening peace talks
between combatants and seeking to improve the health of
impoverished people in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   When they entered their 70s (Mrs. Carter turned 71 in August),
they had to face the fact that both fit almost any definition of
``old age.'' But neither feels old.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were out running together yesterday. We ran three miles,''
Carter said, adding that he used to run seven miles a day as
president. ``The day before yesterday we played two vigorous sets
of tennis. We ride our bicycles often.''
</P>
<P>
   They also watch what they eat and enjoy fly-fishing, mountain
climbing, hiking, skiing and bird-watching. He also likes to hunt
and work in his wood shop at home. The Carters relish the time
spent with their nine grandchildren and try to gather everyone
together for a family vacation every year between Christmas and New
Year's.
</P>
<P>
   Both still write books. Her latest is ``Helping Someone With
Mental Illness: A Compassionate Guide for Family, Friends and
Caregivers'' (Times Books, $24). It's part of her nearly 30-year
crusade to fight the stigma associated with mental illness. He's
halfway through a novel set in the Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   Family friend Betty Pope of Americus says she and her husband,
John, have encouraged the Carters to slow down, but ``I just don't
think they like to stay still.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy will ride his bike some nine miles from his house to the
farm to go fishing, even in the heat,'' she said. ``My husband
fussed at him for doing that. But they both just stay on the go.
... They have a great deal of stamina.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Ariail, pastor of Maranatha Baptist Church in Plains,
where the Carters worship and teach Sunday school, said they show
no signs of slowing down. ``I just turned 60 and I can't keep up
with them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jody Powell, Carter's former press secretary, said Carter will
stay as active as he can for as long as he can. ``He truly enjoys
what he is doing,'' Powell said. ``He seems to me to be about as
happy and involved and excited about life as I can ever remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Carter said she is so busy that she doesn't think about
aging. ``I think having something to do and having things that you
need to do and want to do'' is important, she said. ``I don't see
any difference in our schedule or what we do now.''
</P>
<P>
   Both use laptop computers to keep in touch with friends and
family through e-mail. They also use the Internet to research and
write their books and read newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get the daily papers in Plains,'' Carter said, ``but
I read the newspapers (on the Internet) first thing when I get
up.''
</P>
<P>
   They acknowledge that they are phasing down their day-to-day
involvement in the Carter Center and are preparing for retirement.
``We haven't set a specific time,'' Carter said, ``but I don't
think there's any doubt that everyone at the Carter Center knows
that our involvement is inexorably becoming less and less on a
personal basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said several people will split the lead roles at his
think tank when he retires.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leadership of the Carter Center will not be taken over by
one person,'' he said. ``We're making very careful plans to have
people take over all the responsibilities that we have now.''
</P>
<P>
   It probably won't happen anytime soon, Betty Pope predicts.
``They'll just keep on going until they can't,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
