</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Congress, crucial bills pushed aside
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the eve of the public release of Ken Starr's
report to Congress, a chagrined President Clinton summoned Senate
Democrats to the White House to apologize for the Monica Lewinsky
scandal and the way it crippled the Democratic Party's agenda, from
managed care reform to tobacco legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told each of us in a very personal way that he had let us
down,'' recalled Sen. Robert Torricelli (D-N.J.). ``It was more
than an apology. It was an expression that he knew that he had
disappointed us and caused us problems that we didn't deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   With Starr's report to Congress now more than 2 weeks old and
the House consumed with the prospect of impeachment hearings, it is
increasingly clear that the fallout from the presidential crisis
isn't limited to the Democrats alone.
</P>
<P>
   Preoccupation with impeachment at both ends of Pennsylvania
Avenue is delaying crucial spending bills. The deepening
partisanship from both parties all but assures there will be few
compromises on any major legislation _ from tax cuts to health care
_ before Congress is scheduled to adjourn Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to keep a focus, but it's pretty hard to do with
everything that is going on over here,'' conceded Senate majority
leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) on Friday. Lott said he hadn't spoken
to the president since Aug. 20 and said ``normal communication''
with the White House was much less than in previous sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Some also are sounding alarms over the toll that impeachment
will take on the long-term issues facing the country, such as the
troubled global financial markets, the still unresolved problem of
chemical weapons in Iraq and the potential for all-out war in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are issues that cry out for attention here on Capitol
Hill,'' said Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.). ``Unfortunately, it seems
that all this year has been one big Jerry Springer show.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamenting the heightened partisanship over impeachment, Sen.
Patrick Leahy (D-Vt.) warned in a Senate speech Thursday that ``the
Congress, the presidency and the Constitution itself may suffer
damage that will linger long after we are gone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not only going to end up badly damaging the Congress,
but we are going to have relationships of trust and respect built
up over a decade, especially among senior members, that will be
destroyed,'' Leahy said after his remarks. ``And then the Congress
will not be able to work in the times we have to rise up above
party politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Pre-election battle plans
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans largely dismiss such concerns, saying
it is the Democrats, not the GOP, who have been partisan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats are trying to shift the attention,'' said Sen. Larry
Craig (R-Idaho), a member of the Senate leadership. ``They are in
desperate straits right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in their political best interests to make this
partisan,'' said Rep. John Linder (R-Ga.). ``As they see the damage
the White House is causing their party in the elections, they have
got to find a way to respond to that. The best way is to blame the
other party for all that's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Republicans and Democrats had drawn up their pre-election
battle plans well before Starr's report reached Congress.
Republicans planned to return from the August recess, finish work
on the spending bills, pass some sort of tax cut and go home.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats had planned to trumpet all the legislation Republicans
were blocking, such as campaign finance reform, greater protection
for consumers in health maintenance organizations and the
president's plan to finance 100,000 new teachers and reduce class
sizes.
</P>
<P>
   But the distraction of impeachment has derailed both strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has made it difficult for our candidates out in their
districts to talk about the issues we think are important,'' said
Rep. Martin Frost (D-Texas), who heads the Democrats' effort to
regain control of the House. ``The press only wants to talk about
what's going on with President Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, riven with internal disagreements, are struggling
to complete work on the major spending bills. The fiscal year
expires Wednesday and only one of the 13 spending bills has been
signed into law. It is possible Congress may adjourn Oct. 9 with
some of the biggest bills left undone, requiring Congress to pass
stop-gap financing measures to carry the government into 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects for an agreement on tax cuts, a top priority for many
Republicans, is also very much in doubt. Democrats, particularly in
the Senate, are in no mood to deal when their own agenda is being
blocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not the kind of momentum you'd expect a month out
from going home,'' said Rep. Charlie Norwood (R-Ga.), who urged
Clinton to resign so impeachment would not impede Congress' other
business. ``My gosh, there ought to be a flurry of activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Managed-care reform, a proposal Norwood has been pushing for
three years, also appears dead, languishing in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I don't have a chance over there because they
can't talk about it or won't bring it up,'' Norwood said. ``I don't
know if (the impeachment controversy) is directly affecting this or
not, but I suspect so. Even if it takes us off target just a little
bit, that's not good.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives also have cause to gripe. Within the span of a
week, the Senate failed to override Clinton's veto of a bill
banning certain late-term abortions and another that would have put
restrictions on minors crossing state lines to receive an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Johnson, legislative director for the National Right to
Life Committee, said the ``background noise'' created by
impeachment ``allowed some senators to vote with the pro-abortion
lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we are a little frustrated,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   This year's wind-up differs dramatically from the end of the
1996 session, when Congress reached major agreements on welfare
reform, increasing the minimum wage, new clean water standards and
requiring insurers to allow workers to carry their health insurance
from one job to another.
</P>
<P>
   Like all compromises, each side was motivated by self interest.
Clinton needed to show voters he could work with the Republican
majority. Republicans needed to prove they weren't the party of the
far right.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
