</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich walking fine line in handling Clinton inquiry
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Jack Kingston thinks he has a pretty good idea
of what would happen if the House were to shut down its impeachment
review and speedily resolve the case against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The nation as a whole might be grateful, if public opinion polls
are to be believed. But, Kingston (R-Ga.) said, the Republican
Party's ``base would go berserk and leave us in droves.''
</P>
<P>
   The election is 37 days away, and there is no underestimating
the role Nov. 3 plays in the saga unfolding in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Democrats are hoping to minimize their losses.
Republicans want to use the Clinton sex scandal to cement their
majorities in the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the emerging dilemma confronting Speaker Newt
Gingrich: Can he keep the GOP's most motivated constituency, social
conservatives, happy by holding out the prospect of impeachment and
simultaneously assure moderate voters that the House is adhering to
a fair process?
</P>
<P>
   The proposition is a difficult one even for the most skillful
politician, which by most accounts the speaker is.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls indicate that the public does not think Republicans
have treated Clinton fairly. A New York Times/CBS News poll shows a
majority of Americans disapprove of the way the Judiciary Committee
has handled its review of independent counsel Kenneth Starr's
report, and even two-thirds of Republicans say the videotape of
Clinton's testimony should not have been made public.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the same poll also shows that those people most likely to
vote in November prefer Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   And among conservative Republicans, there is strong support for
beginning the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   So Republicans would seem to benefit from continuing on a path
that probably will lead to the start of an impeachment inquiry in
early October.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank (D-Mass.) reflected Democrats' complaints
about the treatment of the Starr report when he said, ``Republicans
can't even intimate before the election that they won't hold
impeachment hearings.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Kingston said he gets far angrier input from people who
``want to lynch'' Clinton and want Kingston to take an active part
than from constituents who are concerned about a fair process.
</P>
<P>
   But Gingrich's own political history complicates his role.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is suspicion from both liberals and conservatives, and
the moderates don't like him much either,'' said Stuart Rothenberg,
a Washington political analyst. ``He has decided to inject himself
into the process, which makes it an even bigger deal for him.''
</P>
<P>
   At risk may be Gingrich's political future, and a possible
presidential candidacy in 2000, Rothenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunities for the speaker, however, also loom large if
``he can somehow get kudos from conservative Republicans who want
the president to go down in flames and from moderates who are
looking for someone statesmanlike,'' Rothenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich declined to comment on Friday, but Republican
strategists say this notion of a balancing act is misleading.
Gingrich has been at the forefront of a call for the House to do
its constitutional duty, nothing less and nothing more, these
strategists say.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a censure and possible fine for Clinton, which
Democrats floated last week, illustrates their point.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich put an end to such talk when he said the investigation
would be concluded before there would be any talk of punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats cited Gingrich's statement as one more indication that
he was pandering to his party's right wing.
</P>
<P>
   But Rich Galen, a longtime Gingrich ally, said the censure
proposal never struck Republicans as a serious idea. ``A resolution
of condemnation or censure has the same force as a resolution
declaring National Pumpkin Week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He cast the proposal as another Democratic attempt to divert
attention from the Democrats' real problem, a dispirited core that
appears more likely to sit at home rather than vote this year. If
an artful political compromise to bring Congress' consideration of
Clinton's fate to an end is not possible now, Gingrich might be
more amenable to one after the election, when short-term political
considerations can be expected to wane, Rothenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, a negotiated solution might be preferable to a
``constitutional blood bath,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich has some experience with unusual political settlements.
He accepted a reprimand and $300,000 fine from the House last year
in exchange for being allowed to remain speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
