<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-PANHANDLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gulf dwellers flee Georges' fury
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GULF SHORES, Ala. _ Hurricane Georges intensified Saturday in
the Gulf of Mexico, and more than a million people in four Gulf
Coast states were evacuated as the increasingly dangerous storm
barreled toward New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   A hurricane warning was in effect along the Gulf Coast from
Morgan City, La., to Panama City, Fla., and residents across much
of that stretch anxiously boarded up their homes and then tried to
leave the coast via gridlocked roadways.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane had sustained winds of 105 mph Saturday. Its
center was expected to reach the mouth of the Mississippi River,
about 75 miles southeast of New Orleans, late today. By that time,
there was a chance the hurricane could have strengthened to a
Category 3 storm, with sustained winds around the center of more
than 111 mph, forecasters said.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical storm-force winds of at least 39 mph were expected to
reach the Gulf Coast by this afternoon. Forecasters also said
Georges could slow as it neared land, drenching the coast with
sustained heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of like looking down the barrel of a shotgun and
hoping it turns,'' said Louisiana State Police Lt. Col. Ronnie
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Bumper-to-bumper traffic lined up on I-10 leaving New Orleans on
Saturday. About 1 million people had been ordered or urged to leave
the city and low-lying coastal areas, but total evacuation would
take an estimated three days, according to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands more were told to leave coastal sections of
Mississippi, Alabama and the Florida Panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency officials in Mississippi closed beaches and the 11
casinos on the state's coast. Boats were moved inland from Gulf
marinas.
</P>
<P>
   The Gulf will be Georges' first landfall since leaving a trail
of wreckage along the scenic Florida Keys.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, residents of Key West surveyed the collapsed walls,
missing roofs and other damage wrought by Friday's winds of more
than 100 mph. Broken trees and debris covered many other islands in
the chain, but no deaths were reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coconuts were like cannonballs blowing in the wind,'' said
Davin Kusik, who lives at the Venture Out mobile home park on
Cudjoe Key.
</P>
<P>
   With Georges blamed for more than 300 deaths in the Caribbean,
many residents along the oft-stricken Gulf Coast were not of a mind
to test the fates Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This one has the potential to be bad,'' said Gerald Berg, 58,
working at Pier One Marina in Gulf Breeze, Fla., where plywood
plastered the windows of pastel-colored houses and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ''God does protect drunks and fools, and here we are,'' said
Barbara Barnes, bartender at Flora-Bama Lounge and Package, a
popular haunt in Perdido Key, Fla., which threw a hurricane party
for people who decided to ride out Georges.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency officials said most people heeded evacuation orders,
which stretched for more than 300 miles from Louisiana to the
Florida Panhandle. Powerful Georges' wobbly course in the Gulf of
Mexico prompted the widespread warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Meteorologist Kent Frantz at the National Weather Service in
Peachtree City said Georgia is expected to feel only minimal
effects from Georges. ``Southwest Georgia has a 40 percent chance
of showers and an occasional thunderstorm from Sunday through
Monday,'' he said. The chance of rain in the rest of Georgia is 30
percent or less, with no significant wind velocities.
</P>
<P>
   When Georges slowed Saturday, it reminded people of how previous
storms as far back as Hurricane Frederic in 1979 stalled and
meandered before gaining strength and roaring ashore, causing
widespread damage.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is doing just like Frederic did,'' Addie Page White, 79,
said Saturday as she and her husband, Travis, prepared to evacuate
from Gulf Shores, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   After Frederic, the couple returned to find their beach-front
house gone, except for two pilings. They rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, as they did before hurricanes Erin and Opal in 1995
and Danny last year, the couple evacuated with family pictures and
other keepsakes.
</P>
<P>
   Strong winds in advance of Georges whipped red warning flags in
Orange Beach, Ala., where high-rise hotels and condominiums line
the white-sand beach like dominoes. Most were vacant, as were the
houses and businesses in coastal Baldwin County, at the
southeastern tip of Mobile Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody is taking the storm seriously,'' said Baldwin County
emergency management director Steven Denham, who estimated that
40,000 people evacuated Gulf Shores, Orange Beach and Fort Morgan.
''They remember Danny and the 40 inches of rain it dumped on us.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Hampton Inn in Pensacola Beach, Fla, the staff evacuated
Saturday, but not before nailing up plywood and scrawling on one of
the panels, ''In your eye Georgie's boy!''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Georges stays to the west, the Panhandle could still
suffer because the eastern side of hurricanes hold the most wind
and water.
</P>
<P>
   Evacuation orders had gone out for upwards of 183,000 Panhandle
residents of barrier islands, low-lying areas and mobile homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We debated whether to stay, but decided it would not be vert
smart,'' said Harrell Cushing, 67, who disrupted his Perdido Key,
Fla., vacation to return home to Montgomery, Ala. ''You have to get
out of here before they close the bridges, or you have to sit out
the storms.''
</P>
<P>
   People who live in coastal and other low-lying areas and in
mobile homes scrambled for hotel rooms a few miles inland. Others
showed up at emergency shelters operated by the American Red Cross
and other relief agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said I'd never spend another storm at home,'' said Miriam
Edwards, 74, sipping coffee in the muggy heat outside of the
emergency shelter at Robertsdale High School in Baldwin County,
Ala.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Harry, 75, rode out Hurricane Danny in
their Orange Beach home in July 1997, and the wind and rain scared
her badly enough to consider moving.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is nerve racking, very nerve racking,'' she said. After
seven feet of water during Hurricane Opal blew through his
Pensacola Beach, Fla., house, Mario Jimenez, 59, began taking
precautions. As he nailed up plywood Saturday, he looked nervously
across the street at a trash dumpster overflowing with scrap lumber
from a house remodeling.
</P>
<P>
   ''That debris will fly like bullets,'' Jimenez said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Hughes, 35, and her fiance, 40-year-old Jimmy Nicholson,
quickly made new arrangements for their wedding Saturday when
Pensacola Beach officials decided to evacuate the town.
</P>
<P>
   The couple canceled the band, but they held the ceremony at
their Gulf Breeze home.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very disappointed, but our families and friends have
made the best of it,'' Hughes said. ''That's all we could do at
this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
