<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6156 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEGALESE-COX     09-26 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGALESE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton, prosecutors speak it _ it's courtroom coin of realm
 &HT;    By Jay Croft
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Did you hear the one about the homemaker, the
accountant and the lawyer?
</P>
<P>
   Each was asked, ``What's the sum of two and two?''
</P>
<P>
   The homemaker said, ``Four!''
</P>
<P>
   The accountant said, ``It's either three or four _ let me run my
spreadsheet again and I'll get back to you.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer turned out the light, huddled close and whispered,
``What do you want it to be?''
</P>
<P>
   As the intricate details of the war of words between President
Clinton and independent counsel Kenneth Starr have come into public
view, many Americans are scoffing at legal distinctions they see as
just more doublespeak from Spin City lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   But in many ways, some attorneys and experts say, the case
reveals how lawyers, defendants and witnesses proceed
linguistically in court every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people say it's legal mumbo jumbo, this is important
legal mumbo jumbo,'' said Atlanta attorney Craig Gillen, who was a
prosecutor in the Iran-Contra investigation. ``Words mean
everything. Words are exceedingly important.''
</P>
<P>
   Semantic precision is vital, even in the most ordinary legal
situations _ from rental agreements to police search warrants to
the tax code's definition of ``income.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a situation of unprecedented embarrassment, no one has
shown a keener awareness of that than Clinton lately. In his speech
to the nation Aug. 17, Clinton insisted that his deposition in
Paula Jones's sexual harassment suit had been ``legally accurate''
but conceded he misled people about his involvement with former
intern Monica Lewinsky. And in his grand jury testimony televised
last week, Clinton told an inquisitor that an answer ``depends on
what your definition of 'is' is.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans also have seen Starr's team repeatedly ask the same
question in slightly different form, leading some to sympathize
with Clinton for apparently being nit-picked into a corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``People unfamiliar (with legal proceedings) would see it as
trifling on both sides, but it is a very serious matter,''
explained Joseph DiGenova of Washington, D.C., a former U.S.
attorney and independent counsel. ``The lawyering on both sides is
quite classic, in the sense that this is the way things are, this
is the way things work.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 25 years ago, as Watergate was closing in, President Nixon
offered a classically straightforward, if tragically ironic,
defense: ``I am not a crook.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans since have grown more savvy and cynical, through
exposure to legal proceedings via cable TV and other media, from
Judge Wopner to C-SPAN to the biggest court TV event of them all,
the O.J. Simpson murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   And in this media age, it's the Simpson case that Clinton's
troubles most resemble, with their unyielding coverage and instant
analyses, in many ways more than Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes in the glare of the spotlight, it's not pretty,''
said Kent Alexander of Atlanta, a former U.S. attorney now in
private practice. ``Lawyers often move on technicalities and cases
are made on technicalities. A lot of what's going on (in the
Clinton case) is not unusual'' in the sense of attorneys' and
participants' choosing their words with extreme care.
</P>
<P>
   But many people still are shocked and disillusioned at the
president's hairsplitting, with citizens and congressmen in both
parties saying that the president should speak more directly to the
truth than, perhaps, to the exact wording of his inquisitors.
</P>
<P>
   Even at Yale, Clinton's law school alma mater, scholars said
last week they are not responsible for his legal interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to tell the truth,'' said Law School Dean
Anthony Townsed Kronman, a 1975 graduate who was an acquaintance
of Clinton's at the school. ``It has to be part of your
professional character, and it is not something that can be taught
by putting it down in a rule book and handing it to students.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor Kate Stith said, ``I worry, do we teach you that all
that counts is your brains, your creativity? I worry that we teach
you the Constitution means whatever you can make it mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you lie under oath if there are no lies, if words have
no meaning, if ... it all depends on what the meaning of the word
`is' is?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Simpson's trial was muddied by the power of celebrity,
by race and by a judge criticized for lack of control, so has
Clinton's case been clouded by the power of his office, by politics
and by a prosecutor criticized for showing little discretion.
</P>
<P>
   For example, no one has to appear before a grand jury when he or
she is the target of an investigation, yet Clinton chose to do so.
Similarly, he could have pleaded the Fifth Amendment to avoid
incriminating himself.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's political concerns outweighed the advice of his
attorneys, observers say, and led to his grand jury appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone giving testimony must answer truthfully. And lawyers
always advise their clients to answer only the questions they are
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, people get in trouble by volunteering
information,'' Alexander said. ``Even in a deposition, you can
plead the Fifth.''
</P>
<P>
   The burden, experts say, is on the questioner, and not on the
witness to help him. Clinton told the grand jury he tried to speak
truthfully in the Jones case without helping his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's normal'' to have everyone carefully analyze questions
and answers, said Bruce Yannett, a New York attorney who worked in
the office of the independent counsel during Iran-Contra.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I ask who you talked to yesterday, and you say your mother,
that would be a truthful and accurate answer,'' Yannett said. ``But
if I don't ask you who else, I'm stuck with your answer, and the
fact that I didn't ferret out that you spoke to 10 other people is
really my fault,'' Yannett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saying `Tell me everyone you spoke with yesterday' is
different than `Who did you speak with yesterday?'''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers failed to follow up
</P>
<P>
   During Clinton's deposition in the Jones case, Yannett said,
Jones' attorneys did a poor job of following up. ``You didn't see
questions like, `Did you say anything else? Was anyone else
present? Did you speak to anyone else?'''
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't Clinton's job to ``clarify the question,'' even on
the now infamous definition ``sexual relations'' he was given,
Gillen said. ``I don't care if you're the president of the United
States or the grand poobah of the Elks Club.''
</P>
<P>
   What, then, is perjury? It's not just lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to lie, and you have to lie about something that
really matters'' to the case, Alexander said. ``You have to have
the intent of misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   So although Clinton lied in the since-dismissed Jones case, that
might not be legally relevant in Starr's investigation into whether
Clinton had an affair with Lewinsky and then tried to cover it up.
Still, it gave Starr a reason for getting so specific in Clinton's
grand jury testimony, when the president repeatedly perjured
himself again, Starr charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lying is a very big deal,'' DiGenova said. ``Once that's the
game _ is he telling the truth? _ then it becomes absolutely
essential that there be extremely detailed questions.''
</P>
<P>
   That means questions from lawyers, with answers shaped, at least
in part, by them.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Georgia State University law professor Roy Sobelson put
it, ``The way people talk in their everyday language is not the
same way that lawyers are trained to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
