A6157 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUDOLPH27-COX     09-26 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUDOLPH27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feds hope bear hunters can sniff out Rudolph
 &HT;    By Kathy Scruggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Birmingham bombing suspect Eric Robert Rudolph is a
loner _ a man who, investigators say, enjoys the chase and is so
determined to elude capture that they fear he may construct a
suicide bomb rather than go to prison.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, bear hunters are gregarious, adventuresome,
persistent and cunning _ all driven by the thrill of the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials hope that by pitting those characteristics
against each other _ the doggedness of the bear hunters against the
stealth of the suspect _ they finally may catch the fugitive
Rudolph, or at least unearth more clues.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 12, the Nantahala Forest, including the 30-square-mile
area where investigators are concentrating their search, will be
crawling with hunters and their wily hounds searching for wild boar
and black bear.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dangerous game made even more so by the specter of one of
the FBI's Ten Most Wanted fugitives being among the prey.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, at 7 p.m. in the Andrews, N.C., recreation center,
members of the Southeast Bomb Task Force will have a meeting with
the hunters to enlist their help. There are no plans to restrict
access to any of the forest, FBI agent Terry Turchie said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to impart to them that they could really help us,''
Turchie said.
</P>
<P>
   Hunters will be shown the brands of vitamins and food _
including Bi-Lo oatmeal, green beans, raisins and Planters peanuts
_ that they know Rudolph carried into the woods with him. Some of
the containers have been found buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they find something in an area that doesn't seem to fit _
call us,'' Turchie said. The task force information number is
1-828- 321-1336.
</P>
<P>
   From clues gathered, investigators then will determine what to
send to the lab in an effort to chart a trail of the fugitive's
movements. Officials also want to warn hunters of the potential
danger of mixing hunters, bounty hunters and investigators and
their guns, Turchie said, adding that anyone who bears a
resemblance to Rudolph may be questioned, and such people should
not be offended. A pickup truck registered to Rudolph was seen near
the site of the Jan. 29 explosion at a Birmingham abortion clinic
that killed a moonlighting police officer and maimed a nurse.
</P>
<P>
   He disappeared shortly after and wasn't seen again until months
later, when an acquaintance said he came out of the woods and made
off with a large quantity of food and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Bounty hunters
</P>
<P>
   The hunt for Rudolph has not been popular among bounty hunters,
said Lewis Nachamkin, a fugitive recovery agent in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   For those who go, the hook is the fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you get this guy and give money away to charity, you
will be world famous for about 10 minutes,'' he said. ``Then you
can put it on your resume that you're the guy who pulled in Eric
Rudolph.''
</P>
<P>
   Bounty hunters, however, have run into many obstacles from law
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, you're not welcomed up there,'' Nachamkin said.
``And the terrain is terrible to negotiate, and this guy is
supposed to be an explosives expert,'' he added.``I'm sure he's got
booby traps set up.''
</P>
<P>
   While many bounty hunters have left the area after a July
sighting of Rudolph, this fall is the first time the itinerant
carpenter has been forced to match wits with bear hunters. The
spring and summer brought campers, hikers, rafters and turkey
hunters, who all tend to stay on trails, said David Allen, wildlife
management technician with the N.C. Wildlife Resource Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bear hunters use the deep woods like rafters and hikers use
the pathways,'' he said. ``They go where there are no pathways.
They go into areas that other people only look at from afar.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen's job is to monitor the black bear population of about
2,000 that wander the steep slopes and crags in the area where
investigators are searching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked with a lot of bear hunters, and they haven't seen
this bird,'' Allen said. ``This guy is supposed to have spent
months in the woods, yet nobody ever remembered seeing him.
Apparently, he's acted like a fugitive all these years, or he
didn't spend the time in the woods they think he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen said Rudolph will be up against real woodsmen when the
hunting season begins. ``They know how to move in the woods,''
Allen said. ``They look for tracks, evidence of animals. They can
look for evidence of humans as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Nachamkin, the Atlanta fugitive recovery agent, said he's
satisfied to sit back and observe the manhunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't afford six months up there looking for this guy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
