<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-ELECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST HOLDS KEY TO KOHL'S FATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRESDEN, Germany _ Standing in the rubble that once was
Frauenkirche, the Church of Our Lady, Helmut Kohl had his political
epiphany nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He looked out at a sea of East Germans, and he promised them
``flourishing landscapes.'' They would, he vowed, share the
prosperity of the West. They would, he promised, escape the losses
rained upon them by the Allied bombs of late World War II, which
leveled Frauenkirche and the rest of Dresden, and which preceded
the division of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's plea for unity brought cheers to the throats of East
Germans, and tears to his eyes. By his own admission, the
enthusiastic embrace he received outside the Frauenkirche gave a
spiritual purpose to what had been a largely pragmatic political
career.
</P>
<P>
   As Germans vote Sunday, it is the East in general, and Dresden
in particular, that could decide whether Kohl retains his post as
chancellor for an unprecedented fifth four-year term.
</P>
<P>
   According to polls, Kohl's conservative Christian Democrats are
a few percentage points behind the liberal Social Democrats, led by
his challenger, Gerhard Schroeder. Statistically, the race is a
dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 11 states of the former West Germany, voting patterns
have deviated little in the past half-dozen general elections. But
in what used to be East Germany, unemployment is about double the
10.7 percent national figure, and everything, including voting
habits, is more volatile here.
</P>
<P>
   In the last general election four years ago, Kohl's party took
46 percent of the vote in Saxony, one of the five states of the
former East Germany _ almost double what Schroeder's party
received. In Dresden, Saxony's capital, Kohl's party took 45
percent to the Social Democrats' 18 percent. The gap was wider in
1990, when Kohl took 54 percent in Saxony to the Social Democrats'
19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If Schroeder can narrow that gap _ and many people here think he
can _ he will return the Social Democrats to power for the first
time in 16 years. Even if Kohl prevails, he could be forced to form
a coalition government with the Social Democrats. Polls have found
that most Germans favor such an arrangement. Kohl has vowed to
resign rather than participate in it.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the East could send Kohl, its self-appointed savior,
packing.
</P>
<P>
   The election is critical not only to Germany's 80 million
people, but to Europe, where Kohl is the undisputed leader of the
European Union as it embarks on its most ambitious venture _ the
conversion to a single currency.
</P>
<P>
   The election is also important to an international community
that, stung by economic crises in Russia, Japan, and South America,
seeks stability in the world markets where the German mark rivals
the US dollar as the leading currency.
</P>
<P>
   But as Tip O'Neill observed, all politics is local. Sunday's
vote seems destined to be decided by who Germans believe is best
equipped to lead them from the economic uncertainty into the next
millennium: Kohl, the longest-serving leader in Europe, or
Schroeder, the governor of Lower Saxony, which despite what its
name implies is actually north and west of Saxony.
</P>
<P>
   Once the most self-assured of Europeans, Germans seem unsettled
these days. Some saw the June crash of a high-speed commuter train
in Eschede that killed 102 people as compelling evidence that
Germany could not rest on its reputation for precision. Such
anxiety may explain why polls this week showed that 25 to 30
percent of voters were still undecided.
</P>
<P>
   While Kohl harps on the past, especially his stewardship of
reunification and the decision to join the single European
currency, Schroeder points to the future and charges that Kohl is
incapable of taking Germany there.
</P>
<P>
   Following the examples of President Bill Clinton and Prime
Minister Tony Blair, an American and a Briton who broke
conservative strangleholds on power by moving their dogmatically
liberal parties to the center, Schroeder has been purposely vague
on plans for a Germany that might be fundamentally different from
the Christian Democratic vision.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders seem wary of his promises to crack down on
generous worker benefits, such as six weeks of vacation each year,
and on a welfare state that has almost bankrupted the social
security system. Schroeder's lead, which in March stood at 12
points in most polls, has slipped this month as Kohl, a tireless
campaigner, has pulled out all the stops.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this campaign has been long on slogans and short on
specifics about how to tackle unemployment and the loss of
competitiveness that has weakened Germany's position as Europe's
most envied economy. Helmut Schmidt, the last of Schroeder's
predecessors to serve as chancellor, has described the campaign as
the most superficial in German history. TV and wardrobe consultants
have never wielded so much influence.
</P>
<P>
   Now 68, Kohl declares without a hint of irony that this is ``the
last battle of the '68-er generation,'' a reference to the
revolutionary movement of 1968 led by radical students, some of
whom are Schroeder's advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, 54, is as handsome, telegenic, and suave as Kohl is
double-chinned and stammering. But Kohl has always been
underestimated by his opponents. And unlike Kohl, the most enduring
of democratic world leaders, Schroeder is unproven on anything but
a provincial stage. Not surprisingly, he dismisses Kohl's politics
as dated.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Dresden, however, as in much of Germany, the past is
inescapable. Reunification has dramatically improved the roads and
has replaced the dreary gray buildings of the communist era with
pastel facades, notably a ubiquitous salmon pink that adorns many
an apartment front.
</P>
<P>
   But some people here complain that the changes are, like the
paint, mostly cosmetic, and that west Germans have not embraced
them with open arms and open pocketbooks, as Kohl promised.
Instead, they consider as stingy the amount of money and assistance
sent here from the German government. They worry that growing
alienation is driving disenfranchised young people into the arms of
extremist groups.
</P>
<P>
   With a population of about 500,000, Dresden is roughly the size
of Boston. It is the capital of Saxony, which, with a population of
nearly 5 million, contains almost a third of the people who used to
be East Germans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, a year after the fall of the Berlin Wall, the
distinction between West and East Germans was to have been erased
in the merger of East and West. But, by most accounts, there still
are two Germanys: the more affluent and free-market oriented west,
and the former communist east, where, Kohl's promises outside the
Frauenkirche notwithstanding, progress has been slower than many
here had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Razed by Allied bombs in 1945, Dresden is a resilient,
culturally refined city with a glorious history. After the war, it
experienced the deprivations imposed by a communist regime. It then
emerged as the top tourist destination in the former East Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But because of its geographical isolation in the southeast
corner of the country, Dresden was the only East German city that
did not pick up West German television stations. As a result, the
cultural separation here seems more pronounced.
</P>
<P>
   Just a mile from the stunning Semper Opera House of Dresden is
Neustadt, a section of Dresden that has experienced the polar
extremes of reunification.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Claus-Peter Dippel sat on a stone wall in Martin
Luther Square, drawing hard on a cigarette. He declined to say whom
he would vote for, but he betrayed his sympathies when asked if
life has been better since reunification.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can guarantee you I will not vote for Kohl. I lost my job
and my apartment because of reunification,'' said the 69-year-old
former chemist. ``At night, you don't dare go out, because of the
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither will Dippel vote for Schroeder, whom he regards
merely as a different shade of capitalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schroeder is slick. But he offers no fundamental change,''
Dippel said. ``Not everything was good before reunification. But
the right to work, to an apartment, to education, was guaranteed.
These are fundamental rights no longer valued here. There is only
one yardstick now, and it is money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
