444-8286. 
 
OSHA-BENEFITS (undated) _ For Sue Scully, the question doesn't go
away. It haunts her as she drives the 75 miles from Golden Valley
to her job as a grocery store checker in Boulder City, Nev. It
stays with her as she sits in her dilapidated mobile home, and
watches the bills stack up. How can her husband's life be worth
$183.75 a week? That's what Scully gets from workers' compensation
_ a poor replacement for her husband, Regis, who was killed in an
industrial accident in Kingman in 1995. Arizona ranks dead last
among the 50 states in workers' compensation benefits paid to
widows and widowers of workers killed on the job. BILL MULLER.
