<HEADER>
A6163 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-TAXES-BOS &LR;      09-26 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TAXES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE ENDORSES $80 BILLION TAX CUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With its eye on the November elections, the
Republican-led House voted Saturday to reduce taxes by $80 billion
over five years, drawing protests from President Clinton and other
Democrats who want to reserve the money for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would cut taxes on death, marriage, businesses,
and school construction, was approved in a 229-195 vote, largely
along party lines. &UR;  &LR;  It faces dim prospects in the Senate, and
Clinton Saturday renewed his vow to veto it, should it reach his
desk.
</P>
<P>
   Still, debating the tax measure enabled both parties to preview
the arguments they will take to the voters before the Nov. 3
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said they want the tax cuts _ House minority leader
Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri called them ``very desirable'' _
but at the same time attacked Republicans for funding them from the
nation's expected budget surplus. Democrats say that money should
be reserved until lawmakers find a way to shore up the Social
Security system, which faces insolvency in about 2029.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican tax plan drains billions of dollars from the
surplus before we have done the hard work of strengthening Social
Security,'' Clinton said while on a fund-raising trip to
California. ``First things first.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans argued that taxes are so high that the government
can repair Social Security while returning some money to taxpayers.
On Friday, House Republicans approved a plan to set aside $1.4
trillion for Social Security, or 90 percent of the estimated $1.6
trillion in surpluses expected over the next decade. The remaining
surplus could be spent on a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social Security is a manufactured argument on their part this
year for political reasons,'' said Representative Bill Archer of
Texas, chairman of the House tax-writing committee. ``My liberal
Democratic friends never want to be for tax relief. There is always
a reason it shouldn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, are wary of the charge that they might
damage Social Security. Last week, the AFL-CIO began running
$500,000 of radio and television ads in 20 House districts that
attack Republicans for the tax cut and suggest that Social Security
benefits might be reduced. In 1996, similar ads that claimed the
Republican Party was out to destroy Medicare helped Democrats in
the election.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans Saturday won votes from 19 Democrats for the tax
cut, far short of the number needed to override a veto. Eleven
Republicans voted against the tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats cited the vote as proof that the party has
regained momentum before the fall elections, despite the prospect
of impeachment proceedings against Clinton over his affair with
Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic votes for the tax cut were far fewer than the 40
to 60 defections that were considered possible two weeks ago, said
Representative Richard E. Neal of Springfield, Mass. Democrats
stayed in the fold, he said, because they liked the party's use of
the Social Security argument against tax cuts, and because the
president seems to be bouncing back from his personal and political
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, you can sense the fortunes of the president
rebounding, and if we can get the message back to Social Security
and Medicare, we will do well,'' Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   The tax bill allowed Republicans to extend a hand to some of
their core constituencies. Aiding businesses, the bill would revive
a tax credit for research that expired in June. It would allow
small businesses to write off more expenses. It would speed up an
already-planned cut in estate taxes incurred at death, and would
allow self-employed people to deduct the full cost of their health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also would save state and local governments money
when they issue bonds to build public schools.
</P>
<P>
   However, the plan is far smaller than the original tax cut
proposed by some Republicans, which might have been as large as
$700 billion. It also includes no cut in capital-gains taxes and
does not eliminate the death tax altogether, two top priorities of
business lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   The tax bill also aims to reduce the so-called ``marriage
penalty,'' a quirk in the tax code that forces about 42 percent of
married couples to pay higher income taxes than they would if they
merely lived together as single people.
</P>
<P>
   This feature of the tax code has troubled lawmakers for years,
but it is hard to fix without making other elements of the tax laws
less fair. Eliminating the penalty is a top priority for
Republicans, and party leaders touted their efforts two weeks ago
at the Christian Coalition annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But just as some people pay a tax penalty for marriage, about
half of all couples receive a bonus, meaning they pay lower taxes
as a married couple than they would as two single people. The House
plan would give those families a tax cut as well. When the Senate
debated a marriage penalty plan earier this year, several senators
opposed spending money to help families that already receive a
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Under the House bill, the average annual tax cut for all married
couples would be $243.
</P>
<P>
   While the House Republican plan is unlikely to become law,
Congress may pass a more modest tax bill this year. There is broad
support for extending several tax breaks that expired, such as the
research credit for businesses. And on Wednesday, Senate Democratic
leader Thomas Daschle of South Dakota said he would offer a $25
billion tax cut aimed at reducing the marriage penalty, easing the
cost of health insurance for the unemployed, and helping farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said he would propose spending cuts so that his tax cut
did not drain the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Economists and budget analysts differed on whether the House tax
cut was a wise idea, but they agreed that it would have only a
small effect on the $8 trillion-a-year US economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's small potatoes,'' said Murray Weidenbaum, who was
chief economic adviser to President Reagan and now heads the Center
for the Study of American Business at Washington University in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the same time, the timing is right for a tax cut,'' he
said. With much of Asia in recession and the world in economic
turmoil, the House plan would allow US consumers to spend more
money, spurring economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Reischauer, a former Congressional Budget Office director
who is now with the Brookings Institution, took a far less
charitable view of the House plan. ``It's bad tax policy. It's bad
budget policy, and bad macroeconomic policy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reischauer said the marriage penalty provision was a windfall
for people who already receive a marriage bonus. And a measure that
exludes $200 in interest or dividend income from taxes, or $400 for
couples, is so small that it would not prompt anyone to save or
invest more, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Recent CBO figures show that, at least in the next few years,
any budget surpluses would be created by the Social Security
program. The CBO says Social Security will raise $657 billion more
in payroll taxes over the next five years than it pays out in
retirement and other benefits. In the same time, the rest of the
government will run a $137 billion deficit. The result will be $520
billion in surpluses through 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
