<HEADLINE>
TCU SETTLES 40-YEAR-OLD TIE WITH AIR FORCE _ FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Although the two sides seemed as evenly
matched as they had been 40 years ago, this time, TCU had an edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a bit nervous, because frankly, we can't lose,''
Horned Frogs quarterback Hunter Enis confided, as the climactic
moment approached.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a code of honor. We don't.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, capping off a reunion of the 1958 squads that played to
a 0-0 tie in the Cotton Bowl, Enis skillfully won a coin toss with
Air Force captain Brock Strom, settling the issue after four
decades and a slight change of venue.
</P>
<P>
   A howl of protest immediately filled Los Vaqueros restaurant on
North Main Street, as the Falcons _ correctly _ suspected foul
play. The original coin _ with a Falcon on one side and a Frog on
the other _ had disappeared into Enis' pocket. The replacement had
a Frog on each side.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief negotiation, the two sides agreed to hold another
reunion in a few years and make it best-of-three.
</P>
<P>
   It was a festive moment, celebrating TCU's last Cotton Bowl team
and the first bowl adventure ever for the 4-year-old service
academy.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with its first-ever graduating class, Air Force amazed
the nation by sailing through a 9-0-1 season highlighted by a 13-13
tie with Iowa, the eventual Rose Bowl champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an incredible season,'' recalled Strom, who played
guard and linebacker at 217 pounds in the one-platoon era and
became the academy's first All-American. ``Nothing like that had
ever happened before, and it never will again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iowa game, early in the year, gave us a tremendous lift,
and it was just a totally amazing thing for me. I grew up in
Michigan, and I never envisioned us even playing a Big Ten team,
much less doing so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for the Cotton Bowl, we weren't disappointed at the tie. We
were just thrilled to be playing the Southwest Conference champion
in such a big event. Back then, there were only four New Year's Day
bowls, and it was a tremendous thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Strom spent 27 years in the Air Force and helped develop an
anti-satellite system that his son, Brock, used as a pilot in the
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Enis, a former star at Polytechnic High School, quarterbacked a
TCU team that finished 8-2 and featured tackles Bob Lilly and Don
Floyd and fullback Jack Spikes, all of whom gained All-America
recognition during their TCU careers.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Cotton Bowl, both teams were thwarted by a field
frozen hard from a recent snow. Recalling that he slipped and fell
on the turf with a receiver open in the end zone, Enis was proud to
redeem himself with the winning coin toss.
</P>
<P>
   ``As usual, I relied on the advice of my friend, Sherrill
Headrick,'' Enis said, ``who has always been able to calm my nerves
in pressure situations. When we were at TCU, he would always come
by before the game and say something encouraging, like, `Well,
we'll probably win this one, if you don't mess it up too much.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Headrick, the former North Side High School star who spent
several All-Pro season with the Kansas City Chiefs, returned the
compliment, saying, ``Enis saved my (NFL) career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once when we were rookies, he kept badgering the coach to put
me into the game because the other team was running this draw up
and down the field, and Enis told him I could stop it. I'm sitting
there listening to this, and finally the coach says, `Shut up,
Hunter. We're gonna cut Headrick after this game.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But they finally put me in and I won the job and they cut the
other guy. So I'm always willing to help him out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
