<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-DEPTH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HICKS' MONEY BEEFS UP STARS' DEPTH AND PUNCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Mike Heika 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If only Tom Hicks' money could buy good health. Then maybe the
Stars might get a guarantee on that Stanley Cup they so dearly
covet.
</P>
<P>
   But with humans being the fragile creatures they are and San
Jose Sharks defenseman Bryan Marchment still roaming the NHL, the
Stars have to prepare to enter the 1998-99 campaign with their
biggest problem from last season _ injuries _ still an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing you can do to prevent them, injuries are going
to happen,'' said Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk, who is
rehabilitating a left knee that underwent major surgery in June.
``Maybe the only thing you can do is be prepared for them when they
eventually happen.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's where Hicks' money comes in. While the Stars can't
completely avoid injuries this season, they certainly have tried to
be more prepared to deal with them. First, they bought additional
lineup depth on the free-agent market. Second, they toughened the
lineup in anticipation of a season in which they will move into the
raucous Pacific Division, where they will meet injury-producing
players like Marchment as many as six times this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you watch a player over a five-year period, then I believe
you can get a picture of their injury situation,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``Mike Modano is almost certainly going to miss
10-15 games every season because of injuries. Joe Nieuwendyk likely
will miss some time because of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the organization has done then is looked at how we can be
better prepared to address that.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason the Stars acquired tough guy Brent Severyn
during the summer. By adding his $425,000 to the payroll, the Stars
are buying an insurance policy of sorts against players like
Marchment. Last season alone, Marchment's questionable hits caused
knee injuries to Modano and Nieuwendyk, former Stars player Greg
Adams (now with the Phoenix Coyotes) and Carolina Hurricanes winger
Kevin Dineen. Marchment served two suspensions for a total of 11
games because of the hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be in perfect shape and never know when something like
that's going to happen,'' said Nieuwendyk, who missed all but one
period of the playoffs and has not participated in preseason games
due to off-season surgery on both knees. ``That's the hardest
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Stars had 318 ``man games'' lost to injury last
season, trainer Dave Surprenant said the ``health'' of the team was
surprisingly good.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have overuse injuries that you can control to some degree,
and we didn't have a lot of those,'' he said. ``The injuries we saw
were ligament injuries that were explosion injuries or violent
injuries. And those basically come down to bad luck.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had plenty of that, losing impact players such as
Modano (30 games), Nieuwendyk (25 games), Jere Lehtinen (15 games),
Adams (38 games), Shawn Chambers (28 games) and Bob Bassen (24
games) to violent injuries. To combat that ``bad luck,'' they
purchased a good luck charm in Severyn. His job will be to make any
opposing player pay for creating dangerous play around one of the
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not protection, I certainly don't need protection,'' said
Brett Hull. ``It's more, put that seed of doubt in their head, make
them think twice about coming after you in the corner; that if they
run you, they'll have to pay for it. If we didn't have that
element, people would be running us all game.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Severyn might be the Stars' health insurance, Hull
provides further peace of mind]. If it was proven last season that
the team's offensive output suffers when either Modano or
Nieuwendyk is out of the lineup, and if it's also a fact that both
have a history of missing some games, then why not add depth in the
position of ``offensive superstar''?
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get in a situation where we lose a player like Joe
again, we should be better equipped,'' veteran Guy Carbonneau said.
``But that's the key to any good team in the NHL, you need depth in
every area. Last year when we had key people hurt, we could still
beat 17, 18, 19 of the teams in the league. But when it came down
to beating Detroit without our best lineup, then it became a lot
tougher. That's hopefully where we're better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are so stacked with depth this season that they should
have two power-play units that could be considered No. 1 on most
teams. They should also have the deepest group of defensemen in the
NHL, as well as two goalies (Ed Belfour and Roman Turek) who could
take the No. 1 spot on many rosters. It's clear they are taking few
chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are who you are, and we are a team with some players who
have a history of injury,'' Hitchcock said. ``But by getting those
players in top shape, teaching them different ways of not making
themselves vulnerable and giving them plenty of rest during the
season, we think we can improve our odds.''
</P>
<P>
   They certainly can't be any worse than last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
