<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA DEFENSIVE LINE IS A WORK IN PROGRESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The characters have changed, but the challenge
remains the same for UCLA assistant coach Terry Tumey: turning a
makeshift defensive line into a cohesive, effective unit.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Tumey worked wonders with Jeff Ruckman, a converted
fullback, Weldon Forde, a converted linebacker, and Damon Smith, a
transfer who did not receive a Division I-A scholarship offer out
of high school. From first game to last, no unit improved more than
Tumey's line.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Tumey has more talent at his disposal. But it's young
talent. And it's injured talent.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Pete Holland couldn't have played against Miami (sprained
ankle). Sophomore Kenyon Coleman is out at least another week
(sprained knee) and may not be ready for the Oct. 10 showdown at
Arizona. True freshman nose guard Ken Kocher missed several weeks
of training camp (sprained ankle), then aggravated the injury
Friday. Another true freshman, Anthony Fletcher, was ready to
redshirt until Coleman went down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The injuries have taken a toll, but they haven't decimated
us,'' Tumey said. ``Fletcher is a nice surprise. Physically, he's
gifted enough to play as a freshman. He's been an added bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   To compensate for the injuries, for the inexperience and for the
sweltering weather, Tumey used a nine-man rotation against Texas
and Houston and will continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
   That means freshman Steve Sua, sophomores Micah Webb and Kory
Lombard, junior Travor Turner and seniors Jayson Brown and Vae Tata
_ the supporting cast _ must become regular contributors, at least
until their injured linemates return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's helped us is we've played so many guys,''
Tumey said.
</P>
<P>
   Fullback glut: All those years without an effective fullback,
and now the Bruins have two, Durell Price and Craig Walendy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a tough one,'' offensive coordinator Al Borges said.
``We've got to get Walendy more involved, but Durell is playing
really well. We've got to find a way to use both their talents.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto, tight ends: The Bruins are even deeper at tight end, with
four capable players and a fifth, Gabe Crecion, sitting out the
season as a redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   Seniors Mike Grieb and Ryan Neufeld have monopolized the playing
time, leaving little opportunity for transfer Randy Hakes and
redshirt freshman Bryan Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, we have two good frontline players and we've got
to give them time,'' Borges said.
</P>
<P>
   Weather update: Hurricane Georges did not slam Miami as school
officials had feared when they canceled the game. But 200,000
people were without power Friday, and schools and businesses were
closed, as was Miami International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did the right thing,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo said. ``I'm
totally convinced.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-98 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
