<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-VOSBURGH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFFIRMED SUCCESS EASILY WINS VOSBURGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ In five starts this year, Affirmed Success had
done everything his trainer, Richard Schosberg, had asked of him _
except beat Kelly Kip.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday at Belmont Park, the 4-year-old son of Affirmed did
just that, soundly defeating six acclaimed sprinters, including
Kelly Kip, to win the $250,000 Vosburgh by 1 1/2 lengths over
Stormin Fever.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Schosberg wants Affirmed Success to do what no Vosburgh
winner has ever done _ win the Breeders' Cup Sprint. Seven Vosburgh
winners have been favored in the 14 editions of the Sprint, but not
one has won.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jinx or no jinx, if I can keep him this way for six weeks,
they're going to have a tough tiger on their hands,'' Schosberg
said of Affirmed Success. ``You could not ask for a better bunch of
horses in America than in today's race.''
</P>
<P>
   And Affirmed Success, who had won his last two starts by a
combined 15 lengths, handled them convincingly. Pressuring Kelly
Kip for the first half-mile, Affirmed Success took over on the turn
and pulled clear by daylight heading into the stretch to win in
1:45 4/5 for the seven furlongs.
</P>
<P>
   With Kelly Kip, who had won three straight, fading to fifth in
the stretch, the 10-1 shot Stormin Fever closed well from the back
of the pack to gain second. He also finished second in his last
race, to Skip Away in the Iselin.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people thought he would regress after his last race,
but I thought he would run his race,'' said Mark Hennig, trainer of
Stormin Fever.
</P>
<P>
   Another five lengths back was Tale of the Cat, followed by
Banker's Gold, Kelly Kip, Distorted Humor and Rare Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two times he ran with Kelly Kip he was green,'' said
Jorge Chavez, who was aboard Affirmed Success when he finished
second to Kelly Kip in the Finger Lakes Breeders' Cup and the
DeFrancis Dash at Laurel. ``Today it was a different story. From
the beginning I had complete confidence in my horse.''
</P>
<P>
   In extending his record to four victories in six starts and
earning $150,000 for his owner, Albert Fried Jr., Affirmed Success
returned $5.50 for a $2 bet to win as the 8-5 favorite. He won the
Forego in the slop at Saratoga in his last start, and the Vosburgh
was his third straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing is there are six weeks between now and the
Breeders' Cup,'' Schosberg said. ``I plan to breeze him at
Churchill Downs twice. He's run over every track and I feel good
about the six furlongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this race, you have to put him at the top when talking
about sprinters.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINES
</P>
<P>
   Subordination led all the way to win the $200,000 Belmont
Breeders' Cup by 2 1/4 lengths over the favored Yagli, covering the
nine furlongs in 1:45 4/5, one-fifth off his own track record on
the inner turf. Subordination, ridden by David Flores, returned
$8.60 for a $2 bet to win as he won his fourth race in seven starts
this year. His trainer, Gary Sciacca, said the 4-year-old colt
could start in the Breeders' Cup Mile on Nov. 7 ... The trainer
Sonny Hine said the Woodward winner, Skip Away, will most likely
breeze Tuesday as he prepares for the $1 million Jockey Club Gold
Cup on Oct. 10 ... The Groom Is Red, owned in part by Boston
Celtics Coach Rick Pitino and trained by Nick Zito, may make his
next start in the $400,000 Champagne the same day. Also being
pointed toward the race are the Hopeful winner, Lucky Roberto; the
Futurity winner, Lemon Drop Kid, and Prime Directive, who won the
Saratoga Special.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
