<SLUG> BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUD MAY BE WISER THAN WE THOUGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bud Selig is on the line from Milwaukee, and the commissioner of
major league baseball is exuberant about his sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``A generation from now, people are going to look back at this
season and say it was the greatest in the history of baseball,'' he
says. ``At least I know I'll be one of those people saying that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just unbelievable what's been happening this season. It's
just unbelievable the drama and suspense that have been provided by
Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire. Their home-run battle has captivated
an entire nation, if not the entire North American continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always remember when I was a kid what my dad told me. He
said to be successful in life you have to work hard and you have to
have a lot of luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa have been my luck. And it's not
only what they've accomplished with their bats. It's the way in
which they've handled it. They've done it with such incredible
grace and dignity. I can't tell you how wonderful this has been for
me personally and for the game I oversee.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a mere four years ago that Bud Selig was overseeing the
game during one of its darkest moment when a bitter strike shut it
down in August and eventually caused Selig to cancel the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you can say I'm now batting 1 for 2 during my
tenure,'' says Selig. ``We've gone from having one of our worst
periods to perhaps our best. We still don't have any margin for
error. It's taken us a long time to get the fans back to the ball
parks, and we have to just keep the momentum going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Proof of just how popular baseball has become again is the
fact we've set all-time attendance records in both the majors with
more than 70 million and the minors with more than 34 million. The
average attendance in the majors this season has been 29,000. In
the so-called good, old days of the 1950s, it was only 13,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he succeeded the ousted Fay Vincent on an interim basis in
1992, Bud Selig has been relentlessly battered by the reactionary
factions of the sporting press who angrily disapproved of his
creating new divisions, two wild cards and interleague play.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out Bud Selig has been vindicated on all counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interleague play has turned out to be a huge success,'' says
Selig. ``The fans in the cities love it. And having a wild card
keeps teams who would otherwise be playing out the string in the
playoff race. Just look what's happening this month in Chicago, New
York and San Francisco. The people in those towns are all excited
about their teams going into this last weekend because their teams
have a chance at the wild card. The wild card has done what I
thought it would do create excitement and interest among the
fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even during a dream season, there has been
controversy for Bud Selig, who came under media criticism recently
for his not being in Chicago when Sammy Sosa also surpassed Roger
Maris' single season home run.
</P>
<P>
   Nine days earlier, Selig, Maris' family and others were a high
profile presence in St. Louis when McGwire became the first person
in major league history to hit 62 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I've debated my decision not to be in Chicago when
Sammy also went ahead of Roger Maris,'' says Selig. ``Of course, I
wish now I had been there. I'd never want Sammy Sosa to be slighted
in any way. He's just a wonderful, wonderful person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we had that ceremony for him last Sunday in Chicago, we
were sitting alone on the Cub bench when he turned to me and said,
`I'm just so grateful. You've all been so great to me.' And then he
hugged me. Like I said, Sammy's a wonderful, wonderful person.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig has owned the Milwaukee Brewers since their inception in
1969, but he has put his ownership in trust and his daughter is now
in charge of the team.
</P>
<P>
   But Selig still occasionally attends Brewer home games, and was
present on Wednesday when Sammy Sosa dispatched his two home runs
against his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 30 years of watching the Brewers play, I've never once
rooted for a visiting player,'' he says. ``But I have to admit I
was rooting for Sammy Sosa the other day. I felt like crying when
he hit those two home runs out. It was just such an emotional
scene. You just had to be there to enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are watershed moments and defining figures in athletics in
the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   They say Babe Ruth's charismatic personality and booming home
runs were responsible for reviving baseball after it tumbled into
the dark abyss after the Black Sox Scandal.
</P>
<P>
   They say Jackie Robinson's presence in the Brooklyn Dodger
starting lineup dramatically changed the sociological landscape of
baseball, if not an entire country.
</P>
<P>
   They say that the 1958 NFL championship game overtime between
the New York Giants and Baltimore Colts proved to be the lightning
rod for the incredible growth of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   They say Magic Johnson and Larry Bird were responsible in the
1980s for resurrecting the NBA that had deteriorated into a
moribund state.
</P>
<P>
   And now Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire have come along a couple of
years before the millennium to vault baseball to heights of
popularity unmatched in its sacred history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole McGwire-Sosa drama has been turned into a wonderful
celebration of baseball throughout the country,'' says Selig.
``I've never seen anything like it in my lifetime. Everyone's now
talking baseball. Just look how the press has reacted to it. The
New York Times and so many other papers have been putting the story
on page one of the news sections. As a commissioner I couldn't have
asked for more. As a baseball fan, it's been delightful and
enjoyable. I wish it could go on forever. ...''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
