<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6184 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAYTONA-COX     09-26 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYTONA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Officials hope big fall events offset summer woes
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ After Labor Day and the end of the summer
busy season, Laura Pittman is accustomed to business slowing down
at the gift shop where she works.
</P>
<P>
   But this year the slowdown is troubling, because it comes after
a summer in which Florida's wildfire crisis devastated the normally
busy June-July period. Even after the fires were put out, many
visitors stayed away, thinking the area was in charred ruins,
business owners say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night I worked from 4 p.m. to 10 p.m. and didn't have a
single customer come in the door after 6 p.m.,'' Pittman said on a
recent weekday. ``It's really hurt business a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourism officials hope to recoup some of the losses with several
big events this fall, but business owners fear it will be too
little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``October will be better than normal, but it can't replace
July,'' said Patrick Welsh, owner of the 10-room Beach House Motel,
which suffered a 50 percent loss during July. ``If you lose the
summer, it's really hard to recover.''
</P>
<P>
   While Daytona's biggest events come during the winter and spring
_ the Daytona 500 stock car race and Bike Week in February,
followed by Spring Break in March _ businesses rely on a steady
stream of summer visitors to round out their annual revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The summer of 1998 began normally, with large crowds for the
Memorial Day weekend. By early June, though, wildfires had begun
popping up across the state as an unprecedented drought and searing
heat baked Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Western Volusia County is covered with large stands of pine
trees, most grown for timber and paper companies. Fires sparked by
lightning erupted there, sending firefighters scrambling to contain
the flames.
</P>
<P>
   In late June, the situation took a dire turn, as fires marched
steadily eastward toward heavily populated suburbs. Gov. Lawton
Chiles called in federal help, and thousands of firefighters from
across the country rushed to Florida to fight the blazes.
</P>
<P>
   But things got even worse as the July Fourth weekend approached.
With fires surrounding several metro areas, Chiles and federal
officials took the unprecedented step of closing a 125-mile stretch
of I-95 between Jacksonville and Cocoa. They also ordered the
evacuation of an entire county, Flagler, just north of Daytona
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The impact on business was devastating.
</P>
<P>
   ``July Fourth is normally our busiest week and we only had 12
guests in 50 units,'' said Barbara Beaudoin, a desk clerk at the
Dolphin Beach Club, a condominium complex. ``People couldn't even
get here because the highways were closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Cancellations mean loss
</P>
<P>
   Worse, officials had to cancel the Pepsi 400 stock car race,
which is normally the biggest tourist draw of the summer. The race
routinely attracts 150,000 visitors, most of whom book hotel rooms
for at least three nights and spend freely on meals and souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our normal rates are $60 to $80, but during race week we get
$100 a night with a four-night minimum,'' said Janine Dabkowski, a
clerk at the 45-room Seascape Motel. ``Everybody here took a big
loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourism officials say sales tax receipts dropped 34 percent in
June and July over 1997 tallies.
</P>
<P>
   The fires were under control by late July, and while about 500
homes statewide were destroyed, the flames never reached the
tourist strip along the beach.
</P>
<P>
   But business owners say faraway visitors didn't seem to grasp
that fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had people calling from as far away as Germany and Canada
asking if we were on fire,'' said Welsh of the Beach House Motel.
``They were watching television and thought all of Florida was on
fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Graziano, owner of Gator's Pizza, said it was his worst
summer in 15 years. He blames the media for hyping the story while
the fires roared, then never reporting the aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never reported that on the beach side we didn't have any
damage,'' Graziano said. ``Some people think we're still damaged.
I've had a lot of customers saying they were surprised that the
beach side was so clean. People don't know it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps hardest hit of all were several fireworks stores. State
officials banned all fireworks for July Fourth because of the
danger, and the stores simply closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost our biggest month of sales,'' said Pat Moran, manager
of Phantom Fireworks. ``We do more than 50 percent of our business
for the year during the week before the Fourth. It's really put a
scar on our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials encouraged residents to shoot off their fireworks over
the Labor Day weekend, but Moran said his sales were nothing
compared to a normal July Fourth. Tourism officials are hoping to
replace some of the lost revenue with the rescheduled Pepsi 400
stock car race, which will take place Oct. 17. They also have
extended a fall motorcycle event called Biketoberfest from three
days to 10 days, hoping to draw more tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Business owners hope the events will help, but many have doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have their kids in school in October,'' Graziano said.
``They can't take a whole week off then. It won't be like July.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
