<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-ASTROS-SOSA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT A HOMER, SOSA SCORES WINNING CUB RUN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ With the regular season reduced to two games, Sammy
Sosa and the Chicago Cubs won the first one with one arm tied
behind their backs: Kerry Wood's.
</P>
<P>
   The sore-elbowed rookie phenomenon sat on the bench, filing his
nails, during Saturday afternoon's game against the mighty Astros,
20 of whom he struck out in a single game back in May. As the game
moved into the late innings, with the Cubs behind 1-0, Chicago had
to struggle to keep its playoff hopes alive.
</P>
<P>
   Wood filed harder as Sosa struck out in the sixth inning,
leaving the Cubs a run behind the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Wood started to chew on his nails in the seventh, when the Cubs
tied the game on a double by Gary Gaetti, a wild pitch and a
sacrifice fly by Orlando Merced. Neither player was a Cub until the
past month.
</P>
<P>
   Wood stopped chewing in the eighth, when the Cubs took the lead
after Sosa hit a mere single. Sosa finished the day as he began it,
with 66 home runs, and fell two behind Mark McGwire, who hit Nos.
67 and 68, but that single to left field started a rally that kept
the Cubs even with the surging Giants and ahead of the tumbling
Mets with only Sunday's games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   His base hit was followed by a single to right by the veteran
Mark Grace and another double by Gaetti. Sosa may be the most
valuable player of the league, but Gaetti is the most valuable
player of the Cubs for September. After being dropped by the
Cardinals, he signed with the Cubs on his 40th birthday and has hit
.322 since.
</P>
<P>
   Then Wood nearly chewed up to his sore elbow in the ninth, when
the Astros pulled to 3-2 on a home run by Jeff Bagwell, then put
the tying run on third base with a Moises Alou double and a
groundout.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later the 51,950 fans thought the game was tied when
reliever Rod Beck fielded a nubber up the first-base line by David
Clark, swiped a tag at the runner and threw the ball into Clark's
back. It appeared to be the beginning of another Cubs loss for the
ages. But Umpire Eric Gregg said Beck tagged the runner, and the
game was over. The Cubs slapped backs in celebration as the Houston
crowd groaned.
</P>
<P>
   The day began with a three-way tie in the National League
wild-card race. It ended with the Giants and Cubs a game ahead of
the Mets. The Mets lost in Atlanta, 4-0, and the Giants won in
Denver, 8-4. If two or more teams end up in a tie, it would result
in playoff games beginning on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Wood will sit out the Sunday afternoon game as well. He has
thrown without pain in practice, but the Cubs say they will not
risk a 20-year-old's career, even for a chance at their first World
Series since 1945.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want him to hurt himself,'' Cubs Manager Jim
Riggleman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs were saved Saturday not only by Gaetti but by pitcher
Mark Clark. With a $5 million salary, Clark is paid more than any
other Cub but Sosa, who is making $8 million this year. Clark has
been the least consistent member of the Cubs' starting rotation,
with a 4-6 record since the All-Star Game break.
</P>
<P>
   Clark was nearly removed after only five batters, when Houston
took a 1-0 lead and loaded the bases. But he got out of the jam and
allowed only five hits in eight innings. He was matched by Shane
Reynolds, who failed to win his 20th game, leaving with the game
tied 1-1 in the eighth. Clark is now 9-14. Jay Powell (7-7) was the
loser.
</P>
<P>
   Beck escaped with his 50th save.
</P>
<P>
   A questionable left arm starts for the Cubs on Sunday: Terry
Mulholland. Mulholland, the nonstarting starter, is scheduled to
face Mike Hampton. The Cubs paid the veteran Mulholland $600,000
for the year, plus healthy contract incentives for successful
starts, then kept him out of the rotation. Mulholland gave the Cubs
two terrific starts recently in Wood's place, made all the more
remarkable because Mulholland's father is very ill. The 35-year-old
won games on the road this month in San Diego and Milwaukee, giving
up a combined three earned runs.
</P>
<P>
   Scoreboard watching was the national pastime in the Cubs dugout.
As leadoff hitter Lance Johnson was digging into the batter's box
to start the game, the scoreboard showed the Mets losing, 4-0,
while San Francisco put up four runs to take a 4-1 lead against the
Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   The starting pitcher for the Cubs in a playoff would be Steve
Trachsel, who is 14-8 but has been pummeled in three starts since
he gave up Mark McGwire's record-breaking 62nd home run in St.
Louis on Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   If the teams finish in a two-way tie, the Cubs or the Giants
would play Monday afternoon at Shea Stadium, or the Cubs would play
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   If it is a three-way tie the Giants would play Monday at Shea,
and the winner would entertain the rested Cubs on Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
