<HEADLINE>
HISTORY RIDES WITH CLASSIC CAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSSIER CITY, La. _ Fifteen years ago, trainer David Cross
accompanied Sunny's Halo to Louisiana Downs for the most impressive
performance in Super Derby history.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Classic Cat could become his most profitable winner.
</P>
<P>
   If the opportunistic 3-year-old colt can give Cross a second
Super Derby score, he will receive the first-place share of the
$500,000 purse, plus a $1 million DeBartolo Challenge Bonus for
also winning the July 19 Ohio Derby and Aug. 30 Remington Park
Derby. That $1.3 million check would be the largest non-Breeders'
Cup payday in the country this year, and would lift Classic Cat's
1998 earnings over $2 million, tops among 3-year-olds and higher
than any horse except Silver Charm and Skip Away.
</P>
<P>
   Classic Cat is the 8-5 program favorite in the
mile-and-a-quarter Super Derby, and will be ridden by Shane
Sellers, who dominated the NTRA All-Star Jockey Championship in
June at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   Fate seems to be on their side. The Super Derby ranks have been
decimated the past month by the defection of Coronado's Quest,
Victory Gallop's brief but untimely illness, and a knee injury this
week to Raffie's Majesty.
</P>
<P>
   But although the leftover eight-horse field contains just two
other stakes winners (A Fleets Dancer and Code Six), Classic Cat
does not lack for competition.
</P>
<P>
   Arch, co-owned by Claiborne Farm and trained by all-time
Louisiana Downs stakes champion Frank Brothers, is lightly raced
but brimming with potential. Dogwood Stable's Early Warning came to
hand in August at Saratoga for hot trainer Todd Pletcher. And
locally based Code Six should not be dismissed, based on home-track
advantage and his comparable speed figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The others will make him work for it,'' Cross said. ``But I'm
going in there thinking I've got the best horse. If they get beat,
they get beat, and I'll be the first to congratulate the winner.
That's the only way you can look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other time Cross ran a horse in the Super Derby, he
brought the race its first Kentucky Derby winner. Sunny's Halo
romped to a 10-length victory in 1983 in the fourth running of
Louisiana Downs' most important race.
</P>
<P>
   Owned by Gary Garber of Tarzana, Calif., Classic Cat earned his
stripes with a victory in the Lexington Stakes in April and a
subsequent third in the Preakness Stakes. In the Preakness, he
finished only three-quarters of a length behind Victory Gallop.
</P>
<P>
   Another trainer going for a Super Derby double is Phil Gleaves,
who saddles John Franks' Sophisticated Man today and won in 1986
with Wise Times. Dogwood Stable also won the Super Derby in 1992
with long shot Wallenda.
</P>
<P>
   Two horses have Texas ownership: Sir Tiff races for Jim McGuire
of Dallas and John Pierce of Navasota, and Houston Slue is owned by
Royce Roberts of Longview. Houston Slue's trainer, Tony Richey,
operates a ranch in Tyler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
