<HEADLINE>
SOMETIMES FLY-FISHING CAN BE THE BEST WAY TO LAND LARGEMOUTH BASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By BOB HOOD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many view fly-fishing as an escape from the norm, a more polite
way to catch bass than on a bait-casting rod of brute strength and
with a lure full of hefty treble hooks.
</P>
<P>
   Philip French of Cresson simply looks at fly-fishing as another
fun way to outsmart Mr. Largemouth, a fish revered by Southern
freshwater fly anglers.
</P>
<P>
   ``On some days, you will catch a lot more bass on a fly rod than
you will on other tackle,'' French said, ``but there are other days
that when you do draw a strike, you certainly appreciate it.''
</P>
<P>
   On a cloudy, cool morning one day last week, French shoved his
23-year-old Skeeter boat into a Parker County lake and slipped
together a two-piece, seven-weight fly rod. At the end of his
monofilament tippet, he had tied a deer hair bug, a chunky,
brilliant yellow and black lure with a pair of big plastic eyes.
</P>
<P>
   French has caught as many or perhaps more largemouth bass on
conventional bait-casting tackle than most anglers, but he
occasionally likes to bring out his fly rod, whether it be for
striped bass at the tailrace of a large reservoir, trout in a
Montana stream, tarpon and bonefish in the Florida Keys, or
largemouth bass in a freshwater lake.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, fly-fishing is an art, but it certainly is not a sport
limited only to the artful. Novice anglers, between wrapping the
line around their hats or in the trees behind them, can experience
the same thrills of a fish exploding on a tiny fly or popper at the
surface as can the veteran fly fisherman.
</P>
<P>
   The main difference between fly-fishing and using a conventional
baitcaster is that the rod used by the fly fisherman casts the line
while a baitcasting rod is used to cast the lure.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the fly angler's equipment allows him to cast a much
smaller lure, one weighing no more than a tiny feather, as far as
most baitcasters can cast a one-ounce lure.
</P>
<P>
   Matching the hatch, a term used by trout anglers when trying to
choose a fly that best resembles a particular species of insects
rising to the surface to hatch, doesn't carry a tune with
largemouth bass fly anglers. But that doesn't mean it isn't
important to know what the bass are feeding on.
</P>
<P>
   French chose the deer hair bug because he figured the fish would
be feeding in shallow water. He handed me an almost identical lure,
along with several others to switch to if the bugs failed to draw
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   As we cast the lures toward the outside edge of a heavy bed of
moss that lined the entire lake, an occasional bass could be seen
breaking the surface in a furious attempt to catch a minnow. It was
the kind of surface action that causes the fly fisherman to keep as
close an eye on the waters around him as he does on the spot where
his fly has just landed.
</P>
<P>
   French let his deer hair bug rest silently on the calm waters at
the edge of the moss for a few seconds before making the lure dart
by stripping the line between his fingers. The sight of the tiny
morsel resting at the surface must have been more than a 2-pound
bass could stand, for the fish engulfed the lure seconds later and
tried to head beneath the moss.
</P>
<P>
   French landed the fish, one of more than 20 that would be taken
in just a few hours of fishing. But, to catch many of the others,
it would take a bit of strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The early morning top-water strikes didn't come as often as
French had hoped, so he switched to a Woolybooger, a sinking lure
that, when wet, looks something like a dragonfly.
</P>
<P>
   Dragonflies, as most anglers know, are a favorite food source
among bass living in small lakes and ponds.
</P>
<P>
   Although French was using a floating line, the monofilament
leader allowed the lure to sink several feet in a relatively short
period of time. In turn, that allowed French to work the lure deep
around a row of stumps near the moss where less active bass might
be hiding.
</P>
<P>
   The tactic soon paid off when another 2-pounder grabbed the fly
as it passed by the shaded area at the base of the stumps.
</P>
<P>
   Later, a third fly _ a Rubberlegs _ was put into action. A
sinking lure like the Woolybooger, the slender Rubberlegs fooled
several bass into striking as it passed along the outside edge of
the moss.
</P>
<P>
   Although the fly rod is a limber tool, setting the hook on the
sinking lures is relatively easy due to the sharpness of the small
hooks and the aggressiveness with which the bass strike.
</P>
<P>
   Anglers who have never fly-fished but who want to get started
can do it two ways, French said. They can take the expensive route
or the inexpensive route.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can buy fly reels and rods that cost several hundred
dollars each, but you also can buy a pretty nice outfit for around
$75 to $95,'' French said.
</P>
<P>
   Fly rods and line are classified by their ``weights,'' which
indicate their strength and size.
</P>
<P>
   ``For largemouth bass, any seven- to nine-weight rod will work
OK,'' French said. ``Just make sure that if you buy a seven-weight
rod, you use seven-weight line. You must match the line with the
rod for it to work right for you.''
</P>
<P>
   How much a person spends on a rod also is a personal choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, you don't need an expensive reel for largemouth bass,
because all the reel is used for is to store the line. But, if you
are fishing for big fish like tarpon, you will want a really good
reel with a good drag system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
