<HEADLINE>
IT'S COBI VS. STERN JOHN IN FINALES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Galaxy concludes its Major
League Soccer campaign this evening against the Chicago Fire, but
the real battle is between Cobi Jones and Stern John.
</P>
<P>
   Half of it will play out at the Rose Bowl, where Jones needs
four points two goals, four assists or a goal and two assists to
pull even with John in the MLS scoring race, more if John tallies
in Columbus' clash at D.C. United this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Jones enters today with 49 points (18 goals, 13 assists) in 23
games for the Galaxy (23-8, 65 points) he missed eight games while
off on World Cup duty having dominated opposing defenses sinnce the
season kicked off more than six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   John, a 21-year-old Trinidadian, has emerged in his first MLS
season as the league's best striker, totaling 53 points (23 goals,
4 assists); he's been America's hottest player the past two months,
with 14 goals and three assists in his past 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, who wins doesn't really matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the last couple years,'' says Jones, the top MVP
candidate. ``Roy Lassiter and Preki won (the scoring title) the
first two years, but the thing that everyone remembers most is that
D.C. United won the championship both years. ... That's the most
important thing, winning the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   That's been in the Galaxy's sights all season. They won't gain
any ground toward it with a victory today over the Fire (20-11,
53), their expected foe in the Western Conference finals, but would
love to see a good result against a team they've struggled against,
especially after being shut out by San Jose in their last two
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we want to make a statement to ourselves,'' said
Galaxy captain Robin Fraser. ``We need to know that we can outplay
(Chicago) and beat them. ... It would be nice to establish some
sort of dominance.''
</P>
<P>
   That, to the Galaxy, takes precedence over the Jones-John duel,
but they'll be watching what happens in Washington. John has been
the league's hottest player the past two months, scoring nearly at
will; he has 14 goals and three assists in his past 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has only two goals and two assists since his hat trick
(plus two assists) Aug. 22 at New England, and his teammates say
they'll do what they can to help him in his quest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's on my mind,'' says Fraser. ``I'd love to see Cobi win, or
Welton (third with 45 points) or Cien (Mauricio Cienfuegos, seventh
with 42).''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm out there trying to get goals, and he's out there trying
to get goals,'' Jones says. ``Both of us are trying to better our
teams. We'll see what happens. If he wins it, more power to him. If
I win it, more power to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I'll be happier if it's me.''
</P>
<P>
   GALAXY NOTES: The Galaxy has set MLS records this season for
goals (84) and points (65), and they share the record for wins (23)
with D.C. United. ... Rookie midfielder Clint Mathis is serving a
suspension after receiving a red card in last week's loss to San
Jose. ... Goalkeeper Jorge Campos will make his first appearance
against L.A. since the Galaxy traded him and Chris Armas to the
Fire last spring. ... Second-place Chicago, which has won three in
a row, will face Colorado in the first round of the Western
Conference playoffs. The opener is Thursday at Soldier Field. ...
Rookie-of-the-year candidate Josh Wolff, a former college teammate
of Mathis' at South Carolina, has six goals and three assists in
eight games since the Fire fell to the Galaxy in Chicago on Aug. 8.
Galaxy castoff Ante Razov has five goals and two assists in that
span. ... Razov, a former UCLA star from Long Beach, leads the Fire
with 29 points (10 goals, 9 assists).
</P>
</TEXT>
