<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-SIDEBAR-TEX </SLUG>
 
McGWIRE TO LEAVE STRESS IN ST. LOUIS FOR OFF-SEASON 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ A season of glory, history and mental stress comes
to an end today for Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the St. Louis Cardinals play their final game against
the Montreal Expos, McGwire is packing his bags and heading home to
California. The Great Home-Run Chase will be over.
</P>
<P>
   He's planning to play golf, spend some time with his son Matt
and vegetate on the couch. He doesn't plan to use his brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you get a break from using your brain, I'm going to
take it,'' McGwire said. ``It will be a big relief to get back to a
normal life and to have a vacation. This is by far the most
grueling season I've ever had. Knock on wood, my body has held up,
but it's been grueling mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire enters today's last game against Montreal with 68 home
runs after hitting two yesterday. Sosa has 66 home runs, and today
will determine who walks away with baseball's most prestigious
single-season record.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire seems glad just to be walking away, although he does
admit being envious of Sosa's situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be in his shoes going into the last (weekend)
trying to make the playoffs,'' McGwire said. ``What a great
position.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals aren't in that position. Their chances of making
the playoffs crumbled long ago, leaving McGwire an entire winter to
reflect on his individual accomplishments and decompress from the
overwhelming attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has more mental strength than any player I've ever been
associated with,'' Cardinals infielder Pat Kelly said. ``It's
absolutely incredible what he's gone through and still stayed
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire insisted his satisfaction won't center around winning or
losing the home-run title but what he and Sosa have done for
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I've realized,'' McGwire said. ``And it's hit me
over the past few weeks from the letters and gifts I've received
from people, is the impact Sammy and I have had on the game and on
people's lives. That hits home more than any numbers. For people to
tell me that, it's amazing. No matter how the season ends, I'm
(darn) proud of what I've done.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers reinforce the impact baseball officials say the
Great Home-Run Chase has had on the sport, doing much to heal the
damage inflicted during the 1994-95 players strike.
</P>
<P>
   A record 70.5 million people are expected to attend
major-leagues games this season, and a CBS/''New York Times'' poll
taken last week showed 63 percent of the respondents said they were
at least somewhat interested in baseball, up 19 percent from last
year. The poll showed 22 percent were very interested, up 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire and Sosa could ride the popularity to a financial
bonanza after the season. Advertising and marketing experts said
the two sluggers could command between $3.5 million-$6 million in
endorsement opportunities. Both made less than $250,000 from
endorsements last year, while Cal Ripken, because of his
consecutive games played streak, made an estimated $9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood director Penny Marshall, who worked on ``A League of
Their Own'', said last week she might be interested in making a
movie about the Great Home-Run Chase.
</P>
<P>
   But McGwire, who could only be played by Arnold Schwarzenegger,
said, ``The whole country already saw the movie. How much more can
you do?''
</P>
<P>
   That might be the question people ask McGwire next year. He is
looking forward to getting his life back to normal, but it may
never be the same as long as he wears the uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Media coverage began as far as back as last September, when he
finished the 1997 season with 58 home runs. Coverage picked up in
spring training, increased when he hit four home runs in the
Cardinals' first four games and never abated as the season
progressed.
</P>
<P>
   He won't be ignored in spring training next year. Roger Maris
discovered that in 1962, the year after he hit 61 home runs, when
people immediately started asking him if he would hit 62. Those who
were there at the time said Maris had a much tougher time with the
press in 1962 than he did during the record-breaking year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just deal with it then,'' McGwire said.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, he's one game away from a state of vegetation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
