<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOLAN RYAN ROOTING FOR HIS FORMER `HOME' TEAMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The only man who has stared down Roger Maris, Mark
McGwire and Sammy Sosa from the rather intimate distance of
60-feet, 6-inches is watching the home-run chase with the same
intense interest as the rest of the nation, but he's also keeping a
close eye on his two favorite teams.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Ryan, favorite son of not one but two Texas metropolitan
areas, hopes to be at The Ballpark in Arlington to watch the
Rangers in the first round of the playoffs this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier for me to watch games there than at the
Astrodome,'' said Ryan from his home in Alvin just outside Houston.
``I hope both the Rangers and Astros do well in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``An all-Texas World Series, now that would be something,
wouldn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   It's not all that far-fetched either, Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Rangers keep playing like they have been of late, I
think they have a legitimate shot of going deep into the
playoffs,'' he said. ``The Astros are more of a balanced club and
if Billy Wagner does the job as a stopper, they can go a good ways,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have no reason to concede anything to the Yankees,
Red Sox or Indians in the postseason, according to Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is a strong, strong club but if a team catches them
right and is playing well, they can be beat,'' Ryan said. ``If the
Rangers' pitching performs like it did this last week, they've got
a shot at beating them. The Rangers can put up the same kind of
offensive numbers the Yankees can, maybe better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan faced Maris at the end of his career, in 1968 and 1969, and
McGwire and Sosa at the beginning of theirs. Here's his scouting
report on the three most prolific single-season home run hitters in
baseball history:
</P>
<P>
   On Maris: ``He was more of a line drive type hitter. He didn't
hit these mammoth blasts like these guys have been hitting. He
liked the ball down and in, what I'd call a typical left-handed
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure didn't view him as an out. I certainly respected his
ability and thought that in that (Cardinals') lineup (in the late
'60s), he was definitely still a threat. I didn't look at him as
much as a home run hitter in those days because his home run
numbers had dropped but he was still a legitimate hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   On McGwire: ``I considered him and Bo Jackson a lot alike in
that they both liked the ball below their waist. You almost
couldn't throw it too low for them. They'd hit the ball down even
out of the strike zone. I always tried to pitch him up and in hard
and if I threw him a curveball I'd keep it low and away and out of
the strike zone, so he'd have to reach for it. He was such an
aggressive hitter you were hoping you could get him to chase a bad
breaking ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a lot of guys pitching him right on his hands
today and I don't know if they're afraid to because they know if
they make a mistake it'll cost them dearly or what. A lot of guys
are pitching him out and over the plate and he's hitting a lot of
balls to center field.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sosa: ``Sosa was just a youngster then and a free-swinger. In
those days he wasn't really a disciplined hitter. He'd get himself
in trouble swinging at bad pitches. I'd change speeds on him and
try not to make a mistake, because if you left the ball in the
strike zone, he'd take a pretty good hack at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
