<SLUG> BC-FBC-CLEMSON27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wake Forest silences Tigers
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEMSON, S.C. _ With a 29-19 loss to Wake Forest Saturday,
Clemson flashed back to 1985. That was the last time the Tigers
committed seven turnovers (against Kentucky) and the last season
Clemson opened with a 1-3 record.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the '85 Tigers also earned an Independence Bowl bid,
but this team may not be so fortunate. The next three games are
against North Carolina, Maryland and Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost three in a row; it's eating at my gut and the
team's guts and everybody else's,'' said Clemson's fifth-year coach
Tommy West, who has three years left on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   The last Clemson coach to lose to Wake Forest, Ken Hatfield in
1993, was fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm not as worried about history as I am our team,''
said West, who is 0-2 in the ACC.
</P>
<P>
   This was an important ACC road victory for Wake Forest (2-1, 1-0
ACC for the first time under coach Jim Caldwell). The Deacons have
won only twice in Death Valley since 1961 and are trying to live up
to their No. 22 preseason ranking by Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Clemson's seven turnovers _ three fumbles and three
interceptions in the second half _ silenced the crowd of 60,000 in
Death Valley, and negated the fact that Clemson had more total
offense than Wake Forest (405 yards to 373) and that the 350 yards
passing were the second-highest total in Tigers history (behind 364
in 1963). Injuries in the backfield forced Clemson to the air.
</P>
<P>
   Each team had its share of big plays. Wake's Brian Kuklick had
touchdown throws of 48 and 56 yards, which were his only two
completions of the second half in nine attempts. Clemson's Brandon
Streeter had a 58-yard TD in the fourth quarter and a 63-yard pass
that set up a 4-yard score in the first.
</P>
<P>
   But Streeter, who had 319 yards passing, the second-highest
total in school history, was intercepted four times and fumbled a
snap at the Wake 12 with 3:53 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turnovers are killing us,'' said Streeter, who was lifted for
backup Woodrow Dantzler. ``It doesn't matter how many yards you
throw for if you can't put it in the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Wake Forest, which had 16 days off since its last game, had the
fumble-fingers in the first half, losing three, including one on
the Clemson 3. The odd 12-7 halftime score was a result of the
first safety against Clemson in 14 years, a product of holding in
the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we had to win it down the stretch with our defense,''
said Caldwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were going to win the game in the fourth quarter,
and we have third-and-1 and fumble the snap,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   Wake Forest had possession most of the first half, Clemson the
second.
</P>
<P>
   Kuklick, playing without a leg brace for the first time this
season, was ``turned loose,'' Caldwell said. The quarterback broke
his leg against Clemson last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main goal is to finish in the top third of the ACC, so
we've got to beat Clemson,'' Kuklick said. ``This is a big
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   And a big loss for West, who's refused to speculate on his
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't ever quit anything, and I'm not going to quit on our
football team,'' West said. ``I didn't hire me and I'm not the one
who's going to get rid of me, so you're asking the wrong person.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
