<HEADER>
A6200 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GATECH-UGA-COX     09-26 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-UGA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recruits gain admission despite low SAT scores
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- As director of admissions at Georgia Tech, Deborah
Smith knows that George O'Leary's football recruits get special
consideration when their applications reach her office. But even
she admits surprise at the difference between their entrance-exam
scores and those of the overall student body.
</P>
<P>
   Tech football players, in the four years of freshman classes
beginning with the fall of 1993, averaged 897 on the Scholastic
Assessment Test, according to an NCAA study of major colleges
during that period. The SAT is the most widely recognized
college-entrance exam.
</P>
<P>
   With an average SAT score of 1,305 during the same period for
all Tech students, the gap is 408 points _ third-largest among
Division I-A schools, behind Wake Forest and California-Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   While Tech is in impressive overall academic company with those
schools, the football team's SAT ranking in the Atlantic Coast
Conference is unflattering. The Yellow Jackets are ahead of only
perennial national power Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize we were that low,'' Smith said. ``That is
interesting. ... I guess we should be winning more games.''
</P>
<P>
   Such favorable admissions treatment for players is not limited
to the Flats. Every Division I-A football school dips under its
academic norm in admitting players.
</P>
<P>
   Can they succeed?
</P>
<P>
   University of Georgia football players averaged 939 on the SAT,
compared with the average UGA freshman's score of 1,180. The
reality is that coaches retain their jobs by winning games. And
they win by recruiting players who, if not for their skills, would
have the admissions doors closed on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a place for college athletics, but I think we've lost
perspective,'' Smith said. ``There aren't many coaches that get
promotions because they graduate a specific number of players.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Smith said, Tech's position on welcoming
athletes who score well below average is consistent with the
school's philosophy of ``bringing a special talent to campus,''
whether they be football players or international students. She
said several applicants who scored the maximum 1,600 on the SAT
were denied admission recently because their classroom performance
was unimpressive or they weren't considered well-rounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, can this person succeed at Georgia Tech?''
Smith said. ``Coaches are told not to bring kids to us that they
don't think can graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials point out that the limited number of majors
offered at Tech means athletes are compelled to take rigorous
courses because they cannot choose popular career paths such as
physical education, communications and education, available at most
state universities.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure for admission at Tech is similar to that of other
colleges. Transcripts are screened early in the recruiting process
by Smith's office so coaches have an idea on a player's chances of
acceptance. If the coaching staff wants to lobby for a player who
is denied admission, it can present a case before the executive
admissions committee.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said a maximum of 10 cases were heard last year and all
were resolved. No appeal has gone to the ultimate authority _ Tech
president Wayne Clough _ since the system was created in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   At Georgia, appeals can be brought before the faculty admissions
committee, but president Michael Adams gets more involved than his
counterpart at Tech. School officials said Adams often signs for a
Presidential Admit, including 16 of 19 freshmen on the team this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is for the president to make sure all the i's are
dotted and all the t's crossed,'' said Glada Horvat, associate
athletic director for student services.
</P>
<P>
   Academic support system
</P>
<P>
   Like most Division I-A schools, Tech and Georgia accept athletes
who barely meet the NCAA minimum requirements.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary personally screens recruits' transcripts. He is less
concerned with SAT scores than with whether players have taken
legitimate courses and how they've performed in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found kids that had the lowest minimum test scores for
acceptance but actually made the dean's list a couple of quarters
because they worked at it,'' he said. ``You have others who were in
the 1,200s on the SAT and they end up with academic problems.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary mandates 12 hours a week of study hall for all freshmen
and upperclassmen not in good standing. Tutors are available for
every subject. This summer, reading specialists were brought in.
</P>
<P>
   They meet in the room above his office. ``If I hear a lot of
stomping,'' he said, ``I'm up there in a second.''
</P>
<P>
   In Athens, Georgia has an almost identical support system in
place. When coach Jim Donnan evaluates a recruit, he looks to limit
his risks. It's a bad investment, he said, to take on a player who
will flunk out in two years. But a lot of players would be lost
without a watchful eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see around the country is most people have an
academic counselor, just like you have an offensive coordinator or
a trainer,'' Donnan said. ``You've got people you delegate to, but
in each phase you've got to stay on top of these areas. We have a
guy that counsels them about student life. He's involved in trying
to get them involved in things off campus, getting them to go speak
to groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot more things now that didn't used to be part of
an athlete's whole deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's academic conditions for athletes have improved
dramatically since the embarrassing Jan Kemp saga in the mid-1980s,
when the former remedial-studies instructor was fired after she
charged that players received preferential treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal moved UGA administrators to stop accepting incoming
freshmen who failed to make the NCAA's minimum academic standards,
although an exception was made recently for a football player.
</P>
<P>
   For SAT scores, the Bulldogs' program ranked fifth in the
Southeastern Conference. That doesn't mean gambles aren't taken on
borderline academic players. Five recruits from Georgia's
nationally ranked class failed to qualify this fall, matching last
year's number.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-98 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
