<DOCNO> NYT19980926.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6201 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SAT-COX     09-26 1743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A double standard
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Any college football coach worth his shoe contract
has carried on about wanting players who can think on their feet.
Does it mean that superior students in helmets and cleats help pad
his victory total?
</P>
<P>
   The evidence says no.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry DiNardo has worked both sides of the field in the 1990s,
first at academically rich Vanderbilt and now at football-crazy
LSU.
</P>
<P>
   According to an NCAA study of college-entrance board scores for
a four-year period beginning with the 1993-94 school year, LSU
players had the lowest average of all Southeastern Conference
schools on the Scholastic Assessment Tests and ranked No. 4 for the
American College Test. For high school grade point average, the
Tigers were ninth. Vanderbilt led in all three categories.
</P>
<P>
   During the same period, LSU went 30-16-1, the fifth-best record
in the SEC. Vandy was worst at 12-32.
</P>
<P>
   DiNardo concludes that a player's test scores and grades mean
little after the opening kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember running a fairly simple offense when I was
coaching the offensive line at Colorado,'' DiNardo said. ``We had
bright engineering students, but they struggled some with what we
were doing because they were more comfortable actually learning out
of a book.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had one guy who was a Rhodes scholar, and he wasn't as
quick a learner as other guys who weren't as good in school.''
</P>
<P>
   The autumn game never will be confused with the College Bowl, an
old TV show matching campus brains. And no recruiting coordinator
ever hit the road in search of a future Jeopardy champion.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-yard dash times and bench-press totals carry more weight
than college-entry test scores and grade-point averages, just as
long as players measure up to minimum NCAA eligibility
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   That conclusion was borne out of a review of admissions
standards at all 112 Division 1-A schools by the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. Among the findings:
</P>
<P>
   The average scores on the SAT and the ACT, which are the
standard entry exams taken by high schoolers, were lower for
football players than for the overall student body at every school
but Fresno State, San Jose State, Southwestern Louisiana and
Texas-El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Schools with lofty academic reputations drop below those levels
in courting football players. The leader was Wake Forest, where the
average freshman was admitted with a 1,390 SAT score, compared with
923 for football players. The liberal admission policy for
athletes, which took effect during the term of current coach Jim
Caldwell, might explain in part why the Demon Deacons, a longtime
ACC doormat, had improved enough to surface in Sports Illustrated's
preseason top 25 poll.
</P>
<P>
   Of teams in this week's AP Top 25, only third-ranked UCLA
(1,002) had a team average of more than 1,000 on the SAT. Ten
scored under 900 _ with LSU (807) and Tennessee (847) the lowest.
</P>
<P>
   Among Southernschools, Duke and Vanderbilt made the 10
universitieswith the highest combined exam scores, while the South
dominated the bottom 10, with Southern Mississippi and Arkansas
leading the way.
</P>
<P>
   What does it all mean on the football field? Although recruits
with strong academic backgrounds aren't to be ignored, you win with
athletic talent.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan P. Niednagel, a consultant to NFL teams and author of
``Your Key to Sports Success,'' has studied the records of players
coming out of colleges to the pros. ``If you were to put together
an All-Pro team, it would be dominated by types that usually don't
do so well academically,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches and athletics officials whose players score low on
standardized tests, or are substantially lower than the student
body's, routinely claim that the tests are biased against those
from disadvantaged backgrounds, a position supported by many
academicians. They say the scores might not reflect a person's
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to think tests are not as reflective of a person's
ability as their high school records,'' said Doug Bland, Wake
Forest's director of academic services, who cites the football
program's respectable 73 percent graduation rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these are minority kids, and you take into account
their backgrounds and where they came from. Many of them have never
been encouraged about their academic life but instead have heard
(about) how fast they run or how well they tackle. You get them in
an academic environment, give them proper help, and you see
wonderful things happen with them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, the worst ACT/SAT scores are in the Southeast,''
Southern Mississippi coach Jeff Bower said. ``So I would assume the
(teams) in the Southeast are probably at the lower end of your
scale.''
</P>
<P>
   They prefer to focus on such traits as character and desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working an advanced math problem on a test, having very little
experience on the subject, is a lot different than closing an
off-tackle hole on a run play,'' Tennessee coach Phil Fulmer said.
``The (test) is relevant to how you measure intelligence, but
there's a lot of bright young men out there that just haven't had
the opportunity or been disciplined enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia coach Jim Donnan, a former North Carolina State
quarterback, talks of a teammate who excelled on the field but
barely cut it in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day we had a guy who was a 4.0 (GPA) student jump
offsides, and this other guy says, 'What are you doing, stupid?'''
Donnan said. ``This guy was a very poor student and he was calling
this 4.0 guy stupid. This poor student never made many mistakes on
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you might think a Phi Beta Kappa guy is never going to
make any mental errors, but the pressure of football and different
things that happen cause you to make mistakes even though you might
be mentally stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   At the most reputable academic schools, however, coaches say
they would rather put their fate in the hands of a smart player. Of
course, those are the student-athletes they have to recruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smart players make fewer mistakes,'' Stanford's Tyrone
Willingham said.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Widenhofer at Vanderbilt says his players are so sharp
that the defense calls audibles _ adjusting formations or strategy
at the line of scrimmage before the ball is snapped more than most
college offenses. ``You can do it here because you have quick
thinkers, very bright kids who can absorb a lot,'' Widenhofer said.
</P>
<P>
   It has not translated into many wins, however. So Widenhofer
widened the school's recruiting base and tweaked the approach,
which might result in more academic risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible that some of my predecessors made a mistake, of
recruiting student-athletes they knew they could get in school and
they were hoping they were athletes,'' Widenhofer said. ``I'm
recruiting athletes who can play in the SEC and hoping we can get
them in school, and then have the academic support system to make
them successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt is not alone among esteemed universities that stray
from the campus philosophy when it comes to admitting football
players.
</P>
<P>
   At California-Berkeley, the average freshman in the NCAA study
was admitted with a 1,305 SAT score, compared with 877 for football
players. Striking differences also were found at Florida (1,245 and
883), Michigan (1,260 and 929) and Notre Dame (1,314 and 925).
</P>
<P>
   DiNardo acknowledges that universities must wrestle with the gap
between student and student-athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``How low do you want to go?'' DiNardo said. ``When that person
sits in a classroom, how far away (academically) from people on his
right and left is he? That is really the moral decision, because
you could put someone in an impossible or very difficult situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets real complicated for a coach, because we're the ones
that have a personal relationship with the kid. A lot of people
just come to the stadium. They don't really care when the game is
over if the kid ever graduates. The (players) are basically in the
entertainment business. So there are a lot of tough decisions when
you get in those high-academic private schools.''
</P>
<P>
   At many universities, the coaching staff consults with the
admissions office early in the recruiting process to ascertain a
prospect's chances of academic survival. Often, there's an avenue
to appeal a valued player who is denied admission _ all the way up
to the university president.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage of academics and athletics can work, and Stanford
is proof.
</P>
<P>
   The school has produced a steady flow of NFL players, notably
Super Bowl-winning quarterbacks John Elway and Jim Plunkett. Its
players have been tutored by eventual pro coaches Bill Walsh,
Dennis Green and John Ralston. The Cardinal have made 18 bowl
appearances, four in the last 10 years, and own a 50-44-2 record in
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford wins games while compiling the highest Division 1-A SAT
average among football teams, at 1,108.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most major state universities, which get the bulk of
their players in-state, schools such as Stanford must travel
farther, which requires larger recruiting budgets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to (recruit) better and harder,'' Willingham said.
``Other conference schools can go (just) to Los Angeles and find
the guys they need. I have to go to Los Angeles and beyond to find
what I need. They're out there _ great athletes who are great
students.''
</P>
<P>
   At Duke, one of Stanford's mirror schools in the Southeast,
coach Fred Goldsmith says that at least 35 percent of college
players would not be admitted there. Duke is the only Atlantic
Coast Conference school that does not accept players who meet just
the NCAA minimum entrance standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all talk about their academics. They're all great
schools, but our test scores reflect the credibility of our
university,'' said Goldsmith, who indicated he was not using the
variation as an excuse for lack of football success.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State, the ACC's football juggernaut with titles in all
six of its years, had the lowest SAT (827) and ACT (71) scores
within the period of the NCAA study.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is about as low as you can get,'' Goldsmith said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what league officials thought about the numbers, Goldsmith
noted that FSU's football exploits carried more weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what the conference wanted,'' he said. ``We got a big
television contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
