<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How a player juggle football and academics
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adrian Hollingshed
</P>
<P>
   Georgia
</P>
<P>
   -- Position: Starting middle linebacker
</P>
<P>
   -- Year: Sophomore
</P>
<P>
   -- Major: Arts &AMP; sciences
</P>
<P>
   -- Class load: Four classes for 12 hours (15 hours outside of
football season)
</P>
<P>
   -- Class days: Monday through Friday
</P>
<P>
   -- Courses: English composition, introduction to political
science, college algebra, coaching football
</P>
<P>
   A typical Wednesday
</P>
<P>
   7 a.m.: Awakens, eats breakfast
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m.: First class
</P>
<P>
   10 a.m.: Goes to library or student center to study
</P>
<P>
   11:15 a.m.: Second class
</P>
<P>
   12:10: Lunch, study break
</P>
<P>
   1:20 p.m.: Third class
</P>
<P>
   2:30 p.m.: Gets taped for practice; team meetings
</P>
<P>
   3:30 p.m.: Practice
</P>
<P>
   6:15 p.m.: Showers, media interviews
</P>
<P>
   6:30 p.m.: Eats dinner
</P>
<P>
   7:30 p.m.: Study hall, individual tutoring at McWhorter Hall
dorm
</P>
<P>
   9:30 p.m.: Returns to room, studies
</P>
<P>
   11:30 p.m. - midnight: Goes to sleep
</P>
<P>
   Comment:
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize that I've been given a great opportunity to get my
education and play football at Georgia. I've always been told that
my classes come first, so that's my first priority during the
entire school year. It's tougher during football season, but the
academic people do a good job in teaching us time management and
study skills.''
</P>
