<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USFFSU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seminoles dominate No. 18 USC 30-10
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. -- What Bobby Bowden hoped for Saturday was a
giant leap forward by a Florida State team which still has
aspirations of winning the national championship. What he got in a
30-10 win over No. 18 Southern California was an uncomfortable
reminder: The Seminoles may have all the pieces that make up a
great team, but they have yet to fall into place.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we're gaining some ground but we're still not a team
that really executes well on offense,'' said Bowden, whose No. 10
Seminoles (3-1) should move up in the polls today with a loss by
No. 9 Washington. ''The defense played great. But the offense just
basically played well enough for us to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The final score did not reflect how much Florida State's defense
dominated the game, holding Southern California to only 189 yards
of total offense. Seventy-three of those yards came on one run by
Frank Strong in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On the day, USC completed only 3 of 19 passes for 23 yards. R.
Jay Soward, one of the nation's very best receivers, was held to
only one catch for five yards. Florida State almost doubled
Southern California's time of possession (39:16-20:44).
</P>
<P>
   ''Our defense really put a hurting on that team,'' said
quarterback Chris Weinke. ''It had to be a long ride home for a lot
of the guys on that offense. Our guys really had an attitude about
them today.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State led 13-3 at halftime and 20-3 late in the third
quarter. Southern California's lone touchdown was set up by
Strong's long run but the Seminoles were never really challenged.
Still, long after the game, Bowden remained concerned about an
offense that rolled up enough yards (404 total) but could not take
advantage of several scoring opportunities, including two turnovers
by Southern California inside its own 20-yard line in the second
half. The Seminoles got only three points out of those two Trojan
miscues.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know the offense is going to come around with time,'' he
added. ''I just don't like to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   It was another tough afternoon for Weinke, who completed 13 of
31 passes for 228 yards and two touchdowns. Weinke was one of eight
FSU offensive starters who missed two days of practice with an
intestinal virus this week and at times he looked sluggish. On
several occasions he missed wide open receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really didn't start feeling right until Friday,'' said
Weinke, who did not throw an interception for the second
consecutive game. ''If we just execute, we would have really done
some damage on offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Still there were heroes on the offensive side of the ball for
Florida State:
</P>
<P>
   Wide recevier Peter Warrick, who posted his sixth career
100-yard game with 112 yards receiving and a touchdown. He set up
another touchdown with a 41-yard catch and run.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Jeff Chaney, the No. 3 tailback, who came off the
bench when Travis Minor sprained an ankle and rushed for a
career-high 89 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But Bowden is impatient because his team has no margin for error
since the inexplicable 24-7 loss at N.C. State on Sept. 12. The
Seminoles play three of their next four games on the road and still
have No. 11 Virginia and No. 8 Florida coming to Tallahassee in
November.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now we can't worry about it (the national championship)
because the N.C. State loss put us on the back burner,'' said
Bowden. ''We just have to keeping trying to get better.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
