<HEADLINE>
ANDRADE HAD A SEPTEMBER TO REMEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just a year ago it seemed Billy Andrade was on his way into the
PGA Tour Championship at Champions Golf Club near Houston. The $4
million event was established for the top 30 players on the money
list. Andrade was 30th entering the final week, but Bill Glasson
won in Las Vegas to jump from 54th to 27th and Andrade missed by
$5. Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   The year that followed proved to be a long and difficult one for
Andrade, a native of Bristol, R.I., who now lives outside Atlanta
with wife Jody, son Cameron, and daughter Lelia. The 1998 PGA Tour
Championship seemed out of sight. Just retaining his Tour card
seemed in doubt. Then Andrade finished joint ninth in Milwaukee
(Sept. 6) and pulled out a stunning victory in the Canadian Open
the following week.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Andrade had his first Tour victory since 1991, when he
became the first player in 12 years to win his first two events in
consecutive weeks (he followed a victory at the Kemper Open with a
win at the Buick Classic). Andrade, 34, is sitting this week out
but has risen to 41st on the money list and thinks maybe it's his
turn to knock somebody out of the Tour Championship, which will be
contested at his home course, East Lake GC in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was absolutely fantastic,'' said Andrade. ``It was a big
win. It was huge. I hadn't won in so long. You never really know
when it's going to end. I was having such a poor year for me. Then
I finished ninth in Milwaukee. I played fantastic in Canada. It's a
big deal to win a tournament of that magnitude. It's a national
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven years between victories was a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see it coming,'' said Andrade. ``I was ninth in
Milwaukee. To make a 35-foot putt and get it up and down out of a
sand trap just to get into a playoff made it even more enjoyable.''
</P>
<P>
   After hitting into the water on the 18th hole of the third
round, Andrade began the final round of the Canadian two shots back
of Bob Friend. When Friend bogeyed the eighth Sunday and Andrade
made a birdie, they were all square.
</P>
<P>
   Andrade eventually birdied the 16th and 17th to seize the lead,
but on the par-5 18th, Friend birdied and Andrade found water
again. Andrade proceeded to roll in a 35-foot putt to save par and
force the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Andrade remembered the putt Rhode Islander Dana Quigley had to
make to win a Senior Tour event the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought of him making that putt and jumping up and down,''
said Andrade, who stayed out of the water on the 18th in the
playoff and beat Friend with a sand-save par.
</P>
<P>
   Andrade is bypassing this week's Texas Open but will play the
next four weeks before the Tour Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year has been a huge struggle,'' he said. ``I'm not used
to not doing well. There were months of sporadic play. I couldn't
seem to pinpoint one specific thing. I'd miss putts one week, make
putts the next. I'm going to try to be the player I can be the rest
of the year. I want to be the best player on the Tour for the rest
of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tom Tetrault &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has been head professional at Fall River CC
for two decades, was named New England PGA section pro of the year
in 1990, and won the section's Horton Smith Award this year, will
receive the Bill Strausbaugh Award at the PGA of America's annual
meeting Nov. 5 in New Orleans. There is no higher award on the
national stage, and Tetrault is just the second out of the NEPGA to
win it. The award recognizes someone who excels in club relations
and ``has caused dramatic improvements in employment conditions in
the local PGA sections or at the national level.'' ``He's helped
more clubs in the past 20 years in terms of getting jobs for
professionals than anyone else,'' said NEPGA executive director  &UR; Ed
Carbone &LR; . Tetrault is also a past president of the NEPGA section
... The Ryder Cup continues to occupy center stage on next year's
New England golf landscape. There have been 41,000 applications for
tickets, and just 10,000 will be available in next month's drawing
...  &UR; John Hickson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who won the recent New England Open at The
Quechee Club, heads the field for the NEPGA individual match-play
competition Wednesday and Thursday at Prouts Neck in Scarborough,
Maine. NEPGA sectional champion  &UR; Mike Baker  &LR; of Bangor Municipal GC
is also in the field of 16. The Wogan Award, for the section's top
player, may be determined at this championship. Baker is trailing
Hickson, who has 85 Wogan points, by 5. Rhode Island Open champion
 &UR; Kirk Hanefeld  &LR; of Salem CC has 78.5 points, and defender  &UR; Paul
Parajeckas  &LR; of Woburn CC is fourth with 62. They all made the cut
at the Eastern qualifying for the Eastern regional PGA Club
Professionals Championship, and they earn an additional 10 points
if they finish in the top 32 in the competition, which ends this
weekend. ``It's still up for grabs,'' said Carbone. ``It's the
closest and most exciting it's ever been.'' ...  &UR; Jim Holbrook &LR; , the
veteran out of Indian Ridge, hopes to join  &UR; Tim Holland  &LR; (1966-68)
as the second threepeat Massachusetts Senior champion when the
championship is played Monday and Tuesday at Eastward Ho! Holbrook
won the last two years at Tedesco and Springfield CC. He will be
joined in the field by insurance business partner and Boston
College associate head hockey coach  &UR; Jim Logue &LR; . The field also
includes newcomer and veteran campaigner  &UR; Walter
Sharis &LR; , &UR;  &LR; reinstated amateur and former Nashawtuc CC head pro
 &UR; Charley Volpone &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and 1995 State Amateur champion  &UR; Ed Fletcher &LR; 
... These thoughts from  &UR; Dean Burpee  &LR; of Charles River CC, who lost
on the first hole of a playoff with  &UR; Steve Tasho  &LR; of Thorny Lea in
the State Mid-Amateur last Wednesday at Concord CC: ``It's unusual
for me to be playing after Labor Day. It's disappointing to lose in
a playoff, but it's the old cliche. If someone had told me on
Tuesday morning, `You're going to be in a playoff,' I'd have said
it would be great.''
</P>
