<SLUG> BC-FBC-ONCOLLEGEFOOBALL-BCLOSS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO REASON TO PANIC OVER 3-1 START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ With 1 minute 30 seconds left in the game
Saturday, fans behind the Boston College bench at Papa John's
Cardinal Stadium started what has become a familiar seranade for
losing teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overrated, overrated,'' chanted the Louisville fans, pointing
to a scoreboard that told you all you needed to know about the kind
of day it was for BC.
</P>
<P>
   Louisville 52, Boston College 28.
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. No fluke, either. It was as sound a beating as the
Eagles have received since Notre Dame spanked them last season in
South Bend, Ind., 52-20.
</P>
<P>
   Critics and cynics may say that BC, a team with an impressive
road win over Georgia Tech and home victories over Rutgers and
Temple, was exposed in the midsummer heat Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line is that four games into the 1998 season, the
Eagles are 3-1, which is exactly where most people thought they
would be.
</P>
<P>
   This ``L'' was as unexpected as the ``W'' was against Georgia
Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, with a monumental defensive collapse and such
sloppiness on offense that coach Tom O'Brien removed starting
quarterback Scott Mutryn and starting center Damien Woody
(following a fumbled snap), the Eagles gave back the one win they
need to get into that murky area known as bowl eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, who has done a nice job of bringing this program back
to respectability, was disappointed with the loss, but not stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every week is a reality check,'' said the second-year coach.
``If we're healthy and play as well as we are capable of playing,
we have a chance to stay with anybody. But we have to play perfect.
We don't have much margin for error. We have six or seven key guys
and if they go down, we've got problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday two of those players, nose guard Chris Hovan and free
safety Pedro Cirino, went down with injuries. Add to that the three
lost fumbles and an interception and you have a formula for
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, the way Louisville quarterback Chris Redman was
throwing the ball, BC might have had problems winning even if they
hadn't turned the ball over.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien knows that the journey is going to get tough in 10 days
when unbeaten Virginia Tech comes to the Heights for a Thursday
night ESPN game. He knows it could get tougher nine days after that
when Syracuse comes to Alumni Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows who's good?'' O'Brien said. ``But we're going to
find out in a few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien says it is time to reevaluate, to regroup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to see if we're doing the right things, doing
things right,'' he said. ``We're going to take a few days off and
then by Thursday we'll start concentrating on Virginia Tech.''
</P>
<P>
   What O'Brien and the 38,231 fans saw Saturday was a BC team that
has lots of holes, not a great deal of depth, and a long way to go
before it's ready to move into a viable role as a Big East
contender.
</P>
<P>
   It was clearly a game the Eagles could have won and maybe should
have won. When they trailed, 31-14, at halftime, looking almost
helpless on defense at times, O'Brien tore into them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I chewed on them pretty good at the half, not as much at the
end of the game,'' said O'Brien. ``They know what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   And what they didn't do.
</P>
<P>
   What is different this morning is the perspective or spin that
Eagle fans can put on their team's season.
</P>
<P>
   At 4-0, the Eagles would have been only two wins from being bowl
eligible, three wins from being a bowl lock. And no team _ with the
possible exception of West Virginia at the end of the season _
remaining on the Eagles' schedule looked unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   At 4-0, the Eagles had some wiggle room to overcome a bad game
such as Saturday's effort.
</P>
<P>
   At 4-0, the buildup for Virginia Tech would have been enormous.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that has changed. Now every game, with the exception of
Navy, is a possible loss.
</P>
<P>
   At 3-1, BC looks vulnerable and a little beat up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still 3-1,'' said O'Brien with a wry grin as he went
back into the Eagles' locker room for a quick postgame shower and a
trip back to Boston on the team charter.
</P>
<P>
   So they are. And that really is all that everyone expected at
this point.
</P>
<P>
   The question that has yet to be answered _ and would be the same
even if the Eagles had won Saturday _ is whether the Eagles will
look at themselves a week from Thursday night and find themselves a
very respectable 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Overrated? Hardly. As that football guru from the Jersey
Meadowlands who made a pit stop in Foxborough maintains, ``You are
what you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now BC is 3-1 and that's not bad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
