<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-DONATO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONATO STRATEGY IS DUBIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is hard to know what you would do in someone else's shoes.
Impossible, really. You can speculate, ruminate, criticize, even
scratch or shake your head. But until you're in that spot, who
knows? Bruins forward Ted Donato is doing what he thinks is best by
sitting home on the South Shore, far from training camp, while
awaiting a trade from the only pro team he has ever played for.
</P>
<P>
   Three other players _ Jason Allison, Kyle McLaren, and Anson
Carter _ are also sitting home, but unlike Donato, their reasons
are financial. Donato, whose role diminished significantly as last
season wore on, believes he wouldn't get a legitimate opportunity
to earn back his spot on the club. He doesn't want to be the
Bruins' insurance policy if Allison and Carter are out long-term.
He doesn't want to be relegated to a spare part once they
eventually return.
</P>
<P>
   Donato's stand, while sincere, is beyond puzzling. Coach Pat
Burns and Donato had a meeting at the start of camp. Burns thought
they had cleared the air and that Donato would be there. He wasn't.
Privately, some of Donato's teammates are as baffled as the coach
as to why Do-nato hasn't come in, given it his all, and earned a
job on the roster. If he really shined, they figure, there was no
way a team could not utilize his talent and give him his due ice
time. Donato is one of the more versatile players around. He has
plenty of hockey sense, can play all three forward positions, and
is a joy to have around.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have had no luck in accommodating Donato's trade
request. They don't want to give up a dime for two nickels, and
teams are busy trying to sign their own free agents and assess
their own talent before making any deals. It's easy to understand
the positions of the other three _ it's a matter of money _ but
Donato's stand is more philosophical, more difficult to comprehend.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard-educated Donato is obviously book-smart, and he has
always shown plenty of common sense, too. In this case, though, he
appears wrong. It says here he could end up worse off than he is.
You live long enough, you realize there are no guarantees in life.
Donato could've had his destiny in his own hands had he come into
camp. Now, his destiny is in management's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck, Teddy, because that's not a place I'd want my destiny
to be.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Chances are pretty good that players around the league won't be
flooding  &UR; Darius Kasparaitis's  &LR; home with get-well cards. The
hard-nosed (politically correct terminology for ``dirty'')
Pittsburgh defenseman is expected to be sidelined 4-6 months
because of a torn anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee. He
is scheduled to undergo surgery Wednesday, and he could miss the
entire regular season. Kasparaitis, as everyone remembers, is the
player who ended  &UR; Steve Heinze's  &LR; season after 30 games in 1996-97
when he delivered a hit that caused knee and abdominal injuries.
Last Sunday, Kasparaitis was injured when he tangled up with
Detroit's  &UR; Darryl Laplante  &LR; during an exhibition game. ``If you
play with fire, you're going to get burned,'' said Burns. ``If you
play out of control like that, your career won't last long.'' ...
 &UR; Dino Ciccarelli &LR; , &UR;  &LR; 38, will miss the next week because of a
sprained right ankle suffered in practice. But Panthers coach
 &UR; Terry Murray  &LR; is not worried about it. ``There's no need to take a
look at him in training camp anyway,'' said Murray. ``He's been
around 100 years.'' ...  &UR; Colin Campbell &LR; , the former Rangers coach
who is now the NHL dean of supplemental discipline, levied his
first suspension last Wednesday, sitting down Stars captain  &UR; Derian
Hatcher  &LR; for four exhibition games and fining him $1,000 for
punching and cross-checking St. Louis defenseman  &UR; Chris Pronger
 &LR; ... While Hurricane Georges didn't affect the Bruins' exhibition
against the Panthers tonight in Sunrise, Fla., some members of the
Tampa Bay Lightning were on alert. Assistant GM  &UR; Tony
Esposito &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has a home on St. Petersburg Beach, and forward
 &UR; John Cullen &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has a home on the water at Snell Isle in St.
Pete, had been planning to evacuate the area. ``I've never been
through something like this, none of us have,'' said Cullen. ``A
lot of us were out of town and had no idea what was going on. I
just talked to my wife who said she lined up a place for us to stay
in Orlando. I was like, `Orlando?' That's when I realized this is
serious stuff.'' Team president  &UR; Billy McGeehee &LR;  reportedly passed
out hurricane survival guides to each player. ``I was driving into
the office and saw a building with plywood covering the windows,''
said coach  &UR; Jacques Demers &LR; . ``They had spray paint over the
plywood that said, `We're still open.' When I saw that, I thought,
`Wow.' Then it hit me and now I feel bad for those people who live
near the water or live in mobile homes. I worry for those people.''
The storm had turned west as of Friday night, sparing Tampa, but
the game against Dallas scheduled for last night was canceled ...
Lightning forward  &UR; Stephane Richer  &LR; has had pain and blurred vision
in his left eye after being struck by a stick during practice last
Wednesday but didn't expect to miss any workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Center  &UR; Brent Sutter &LR; , younger brother of former Bruins coach
 &UR; Brian Sutter &LR; , &UR;  &LR; has joined the Blackhawks' scouting staff. He
retired in April after a 17-year playing career ... Everybody in
the league has an opinion about coming from the junior ranks as
opposed to coming from college. Here is Burns, a former junior
coach: ``I think (college players) are surprised at the intensity
of the NHL games. The practice-to-game ratio in junior hockey
compared to college hockey is a lot different. Juniors are almost
like the NHL. The travel schedule, everything, is based on an NHL
schedule. The toughness of the games. Juniors are a little bit
wilder than it is in college hockey. I think a lot of them tend to
not be prepared for that.  &UR; Andre Savage  &LR; (of Michigan Tech) got a
good rap in the ear Wednesday (in Pittsburgh) and wondered if a bus
had hit him. Some of them adapt and some don't.'' ... Burns has
some advice for those Bruins who end up in Providence: break your
back in the AHL and you might be back in the NHL. ``If you can do
it in the minors, you can do it up here,'' said Burns. ``If you
can't do it in the minors, you can't do it up here. Kids sometimes
take it as a setback but if you take it as a challenge ...  &UR; Tim
Taylor  &LR; was cut from the Detroit Red Wings and he won a scoring
championship in Adirondack, that's why he's playing in the NHL
 &UR; today &LR; .  &UR; Stephan Lebeau  &LR; was cut from the Montreal Canadiens and
he went down and won a scoring championship. He won a Stanley Cup
with the Montreal Canadiens.  &UR; Mathieu Schneider &LR; , &UR;  &LR; my first year,
he came in and I said, `You have to go to the minors' and he said,
`I'm better than  &UR; Larry Robinson &LR; ,' and I said, `What? You think
you're better than Larry Robinson?' Larry was still playing. We
sent him down but you have to give him credit. He went down for
30-35 games, worked his ass off, and proved he could be dominant
down there and came up and played.'' Schneider, now with Toronto,
is an unsigned free agent seeking $3 million a year ... Interesting
to see the fortune of center  &UR; Steve Rucchin &LR; . Rucchin, who earned a
paltry $350,000 last season with Anaheim, was rewarded with a huge
raise this year. His claim to fame is playing between stars  &UR; Paul
Kariya  &LR; and  &UR; Teemu Selanne &LR; . ``I cut Steve Rucchin in Toronto,''
said Burns. ``He was a walk-on. I thought, `This guy can't play in
the league.' He went to Anaheim. He's playing with Selanne and
Kariya. My dead grandmother could probably get 15 points a year
with those two. You've got to look at it that way, too. I give
Steve credit, he kept on going, kept on fighting, and made himself
a better player.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Former Bruins center  &UR; Bob Carpenter  &LR; could see his role change
with the Devils this season, if he remains with the Devils, that
is. Carpenter is an obvious choice to be exposed in the Oct. 5
waiver draft. If he isn't plucked, he isn't sure where he fits in
new coach  &UR; Robbie Ftorek's  &LR; plan. ``I feel I can play or I wouldn't
have done all that work over the summer,'' said the 35-year-old
veteran who was a favorite of former coach  &UR; Jacques Lemaire &LR; . ``I'm
at the stage of my career when I just want to play, whatever that
role is. I'm just going to be positive and happy. You don't come
back for your 18th year if it's not fun. You can only worry about
what you can do. Otherwise, you'll have a lot of stress. I'll keep
going until they tell me not to come here, until they tell me to go
home.'' ... Former Bruin defenseman  &UR; Stephane Quintal &LR; , &UR;  &LR; now with
Montreal, came close to losing the sight in his right eye because
of a bizarre infection caused by a tooth extraction in the summer.
After having the tooth pulled, he developed a sinus infection and
was placed on antibiotics. Earlier this month, Quintal had
gastrointestinal problems and began vomiting. After the root of the
tooth was forced into his sinus cavity, he developed another
infection that was very close to his eye; the infection required
surgery to drain. ``Losing the sight in it could have happened if
we had waited too long,'' said Quintal. ``It could have gone up
that far. I'm lucky. Sometimes, because you're a pro athlete, you
think you're invincible.'' Quintal lost 10 pounds while he was sick
and has just recently begun eating food that first goes through a
blender. It's likely he'll miss the season opener ... As if Little
Rock, Ark., didn't get enough bad ink because of our president,
word comes that the first-ever professional hockey game in the
state was an abject disaster. Nashville and Dallas met at Barton
Coliseum for an exhibition game, but overtime had to be canceled
because of rowdy fans. When warned that the game would be stopped
if debris continued to be thrown on the ice, the spectators threw
more paper airplanes and coins. ``I think that was the right
call,'' said Dallas coach  &UR; Ken Hitchcock &LR; . ``You can't have objects
thrown on the ice. Nothing is more dangerous.'' ... 13 days to
opening night.
</P>
</TEXT>
