<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BC-LOUISVILLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERFECTLY AWFUL DAY FOR BC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ They came here looking to punctuate a perfect
September. But instead of putting an exclamation point on a 4-0
start, Boston College affixed a question mark to its first loss of
the season after Saturday's dreadful 52-28 setback to Louisville
before 38,231 at Papa John's Cardinal Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Off to its best start in six years after three consecutive
victories, BC's first loss _ and worst since a 52-20 shellacking at
Notre Dame last year _ gave rise to numerous questions.
</P>
<P>
   How could a BC offense that was so balanced and so efficient
become so turnover-prone (three fumbles, one interception) and so
discombobulated against a Louisville defense that surrendered 801
yards in its opener against Kentucky? How could a BC defense that
was so steely tough in the first three weeks become so Charmin soft
in Week 4 by allowing 52 points and 507 yards total offense?
</P>
<P>
   And, most pressing of all, just how good are these Eagles?
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't take your first five or whatever possessions we
had and fumble the ball twice like we did,'' said BC coach Tom
O'Brien, citing those factors that led to a ruinous afternoon for
the Eagles (3-1). ``Those are opportunities you can't give a decent
team. Maybe they (Louisville) are better than their (2-2) record,
who knows? I keep telling you guys, who knows who's any good in
September? We're going to start finding out here in the next couple
of weeks who's pretty good, but after our performance, we're not
pretty good right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Louisville quarterback Chris Redman made that abundantly and
painfully clear all afternoon after he dissected BC's secondary by
completing 31 of 47 passes for 362 yards and 5 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just clicking,'' surmised junior free safety Pedro
Cirino, who intercepted Redman in the end zone in the first quarter
before sustaining a deep bruise in the second. ``We didn't cover
anyone and we didn't play well, and they executed to perfection.
When you get those two things combined, it can get ugly on the
scoreboard.''
</P>
<P>
   And it did.
</P>
<P>
   Redman, a 6-foot-3-inch junior from Louisville, broke a
single-game school record with his five TDs. He connected twice
with his former high school teammate, Ibn Green, on Louisville's
first and last TDs of the game: an 8-yarder that made it 7-0 with
9:34 left in the first quarter, and a 27-yard TD that gave
Louisville a whopping 52-21 lead with 7:12 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we finally hit on all cylinders,'' said Redman, who
helped snap Louisville's 10-game losing streak with a 35-9 victory
at Illinois last week. ``We've been close a time or two, but I knew
we had this in us. I think this win means a lot because Illinois
was a little bit suspect team, but we knew that (BC) was a really
good ball club that had some talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior quarterback Scott Mutryn, who attempted as many passes as
Redman completed, went 19 of 31 for 230 yards and 2 TDs. He had a
pair of TDs on a 36-yard strike to Dennis Harding that tied the
game, 7-7, with 6:58 left in the first and a 21-yard TD to Anthony
DiCosmo (9 catches, 102 yards) that helped BC pull within 6, 20-14,
with 3:38 to go before intermission.
</P>
<P>
   But that was as close as the Eagles would get after Louisville
capped a 24-point eruption in the second quarter by scoring 10
points in the final 1:30 to take a commanding 31-14 lead at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Redman hit Green with a huge 40-yard strike to set up a 4-yard
TD pass to Rico Williams and then connected with Leroy Collins (27
carries, 97 yards, 2 touchdowns) in the left flat on the 2-point
conversion to make it 28-14.
</P>
<P>
   On BC's next possession, Jermaine Walker committed a costly
turnover when he fumbled for the second time in the game, this time
at the BC 29. It set up Jon Hilbert's 22-yard field goal that gave
Louisville a 17-point cushion at the break.
</P>
<P>
   BC squandered a prime opportunity from the Louisville 3 in the
third quarter when, on third and goal, Mutryn bobbled the snap,
rolled to his right, and tried to force a pass into the end zone
intended for tight end Rob Tardio. The ball was twice tipped by
Cardinal defenders and once by Tardio before Braxton Anderson
intercepted it in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Senior running back Mike Cloud, the nation's No. 2 rusher who
was held well below his average (184.0 yards per game) after
rushing 21 times for 124 yards, helped BC atone for the mistake
with a 27-yard TD in the third that made it 31-21. But Redman
turned up the heat, firing three more TDs _ a 19-yard pass to
Arnold Jackson in the third; a 14-yarder to Charles Sheffield with
13:52 left, and the 27-yarder to Green _ to cap the Louisville
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   After watching Mutryn fumble a snap from center Damian Woody at
midfield, O'Brien benched both his starting quarterback and center
and inserted backup Tim Hasselbeck, who responded by firing a
46-yard TD to Walker with 3:38 left.
</P>
<P>
   But it proved too little too late.
</P>
<P>
   Period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
