</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-YOUNG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG BACK DOING WHAT HE DOES BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Not only is the San Francisco 49ers quarterback named Young,
but he's also acting young.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Young may be 38 years old and one season removed from
several concussions that forced him to seriously consider his
athletic mortality, but none of that has meant a thing to him this
season. Of course, to get to this season he had to first get
through the last one, and to do that Young had to get through a
battery of neurological tests after twice being knocked unconscious
in a matter of days.
</P>
<P>
   After the second concussion, the discussion around Young's
family table was no longer about football futures. It was about
possibly using that law degree he'd earned at Brigham Young while
it still had a future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared I was going to have to quit,'' recalled Young,
``but I came out of my discussions with the neurosurgeons and if
they said, `Steve, you're at risk.' I would have quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I went to the head of neurosurgery at Stanford and he was
a straight shooter. He didn't care about the 49ers. He didn't care
about football. He was a guy who told me he'd wear a helmet driving
a car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through my high school records, my records at BYU and
in the NFL and the numbers (of concussions) weren't what you
thought. Plus, I never suffered an actual knockout blow. I was
never knocked out. This was not a fly-by-night deal. I know I'd
like to be a judge some day and I couldn't be up there with
short-term memory loss. The defense would love that. `So, Your
Honor, you said my client should go scot-free, right?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I considered all that before I came back. This is not like in
boxing. There's a huge difference between helmet injuries and
boxing injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Some, however, feared that Young was merely trying to convince
himself that he could continue even though he seemed at risk for
the kind of permanent damage that retired Al Toon, Merrill Hoge,
Stan Humphries, and several other prominent NFL players in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, if you look long enough you can find a doctor to
tell you anything you'd like to hear, and there were whispers that
perhaps this was what Young was up to because despite his obvious
intelligence, love of sport can play tricks on a man.
</P>
<P>
   It has done so to hundreds of boxers and at least as many
football players, so could Young be any different?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to convince myself,'' Young insisted. ``They
convinced me. After all that testing, the experts said it was up to
me. They said if I wanted to quit it was fine but I needn't do it
because of the concussions.''
</P>
<P>
   That was all Young needed to hear. He never wanted to leave the
game in the first place, and when his battle with sudden darkness
syndrome ended last season, he wanted to do nothing more than go
back to work.
</P>
<P>
   He did, but the 49ers remained careful with him all season. They
ran the ball more than ever and it was 13 weeks before head coach
Steve Mariucci even had a quarterback sneak in the game plan for a
quarterback who needs only three more rushing touchdowns to pass
Jack Kemp and become the all-time leader.
</P>
<P>
   Before the new year began, he lobbied Mariucci hard to expand
his role again. He wanted to run free as he always had. He wanted
to throw short, deep, and often. He wanted, in other words, to
return to being Steve Young.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, Mariucci agreed, and the result after two games has
been remarkable even by Young's Hall of Fame standards. Not only
are the 49ers 2-0 going into Sunday's battle of the unbeatens
against division rival Atlanta, but they are leading the NFL in
total offense, passing offense, and rushing offense. Young has
passed for 666 yards and six touchdowns, the best start of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, this comes as no surprise to him, but it does come with
a pure sense of joy, for few players seem to love the mere act of
playing football more than he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like quarterbacking,'' Young said. ``There are not many
things I could come up with to test my emotions and my wit more.
It's a lab for life. I suggest it for anybody. It tests yourself in
so many ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really the most intriguing career I think I could
find. Playing quarterback in the NFL is like trying to catch a
tiger. You better be careful or it's going to bite you.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes so many years for you to come close to mastering it
that when you do to some degree you don't want to stop. I can
remember talking to Neil Lomax after he had to retire with those
bad hips. He was so frustrated because that came at a time when
he'd just figured out the game and his body quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to sit some years (behind Joe Montana) when I should
have played. I'd like to have those years back as much as I can.
The truth of it is you get hooked on the adrenaline. There's not
too many things you can do that can start the adrenaline pumping
like playing quarterback in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially when you can still play quarterback the way Steve
Young is playing it _ like a young Steve.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Even though Patriots owner  &UR; Bob Kraft  &LR; is a rising power in NFL
circles, some things still amaze him. A recent example is the
decision of Green Bay general manager  &UR; Ron Wolf  &LR; to include a
clause in head coach  &UR; Mike Holmgren's  &LR; contract that allows him to
join another team at the end of this season in return for a
second-round draft choice. What baffles Kraft is that he squeezed
the New York Jets for first-, second-, third-, and fourth-round
choices to allow  &UR; Bill Parcells  &LR; to leave two years ago. ``That
move doesn't get good value for the stockholders,'' Kraft said.
``It gives away shareholder value cheap and I don't understand the
motive. That's the difference between a principal running a team
and a hired gun. I had a Super Bowl losing coach and we got much
more. They've got a back-to-back Super Bowl coach who won one and
they'll settle for a two? I would say that's not in the best
interest of the Green Bay Packers' shareholders. When you're an
owner-operator you look at these things differently from an
employee managing the asset.'' ... Panic seems to be in the air in
Baltimore, and not because  &UR; Jim Harbaugh  &LR; has been benched in favor
of young  &UR; Eric Zeier  &LR; at quarterback. Lame duck coach  &UR; Ted
Marchibroda  &LR; also benched tailbacks  &UR; Errict Rhett  &LR; and  &UR; Jay Graham
 &LR; in favor of untested  &UR; Priest Holmes &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has one carry this
season. Rhett rushed for 92 yards on opening day but has been used
sparingly since then, despite averaging 5.7 yards a carry (24 for
136). Graham replaced Rhett in the starting lineup in Week 2 and
last Sunday he rushed for 67 yards on 20 carries, but that was not
enough either as the Ravens' offense continued to sputter. ``This
has been on my mind for a while,'' Marchibroda said when he made
the move. If so, why'd he play Holmes at flanker last Sunday and
throw him the ball only once? ... New Cleveland Browns operative
 &UR; Carmen Policy  &LR; has said Holmgren is at the top of his list of
potential head coaches despite a clause in the team's expansion
franchise agreement that prohibits it from using draft picks to
compensate a team for hiring away a head coach already under
contract. Policy is planning to petition NFL commissioner  &UR; Paul
Tagliabue  &LR; to overturn the clause, arguing that Carolina and
Jacksonville were not under similar restrictions when they entered
the league three years ago and none of the other franchises faces a
similar restriction. It's a good argument, but insiders say it will
fall upon deaf ears unless Policy and new Browns owner  &UR; Al Lerner
 &LR; are ready to make their first official act a lawsuit, and they
still might not prevail. A league source maintained last week that
the majority of owners are vehemently opposed to allowing head
coaches to break contracts and move from team to team at will.
``Policy wants to have as many options as he can and that's
understandable, but the owners don't want coaches running the
league,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Holmes is not the only shift at running back in the NFL Sunday,
but at least the one in St. Louis was forced upon  &UR; Dick Vermeil
 &LR; after  &UR; Greg Hill  &LR; ended a huge day last week (158 yards) by
breaking his leg. He'll be replaced by rookie  &UR; Robert Holcombe &LR; ,
who found that out in an unusual way. During a Wednesday meeting to
go over pass protection, running backs coach  &UR; Wilbert Montgomery
 &LR; told Holcombe, ``By the way, Robert, you're going to get a lot of
reps this week. As a matter of fact, you're going to be starting,
so I need your undivided attention.'' Considering that Holcombe had
yet to dress for a game this season, it didn't take much to get his
attention. Coincidentally, the start comes against his hometown
team, the Cardinals. Holcombe played his final two seasons of prep
football at Mesa High in Phoenix while living with his aunt and
uncle ...  &UR; Jay Posner  &LR; of the San Diego Union Tribune was verbally
assaulted by Chargers rookie quarterback  &UR; Ryan Leaf  &LR; after Posner
had noted in the paper that the quarterback followed a bad day on
Sunday by cursing out a cameraman who was filming locker room
interviews for the team's weekly TV show. Other reporters said the
incident with Posner began with Leaf throwing a football at him
while he talked with Chargers GM  &UR; Bobby Beathard  &LR; but the ball was
intercepted by team official  &UR; Bill Devaney &LR; . &UR;  &LR; Leaf denied that, and
Posner said he didn't know about it because his back was to Leaf.
If it is true, it would be similar to an incident in Leaf's college
days, when he threw a ball at a Spokane writer while he was at
Washington State. Regardless, Leaf later called Posner to his
locker to complain about the story, claiming the cameraman had
pushed him and was verbally abusive. When Leaf was finished, Posner
said, ``Now let me tell you something,'' and Leaf leaped up and
began screaming and cursing in a diatribe caught by a San Diego TV
cameraman. An hour later, Leaf called Posner to apologize but by
Thursday he had announced that he was no longer talking to the
media. Told of this, his media-friendly agent,  &UR; Leigh Steinberg,
 &LR; replied, ``That won't last long.'' Beathard was angry over Leaf's
announcement, saying, ``We were all hoping this was behind us.
Players have a responsibility to the organization to talk to the
media.'' Beathard said Leaf's approach was only going to make life
harder for him. As for the ball-throwing incident, one wiseguy who
was there said, ``It was Leaf's 15th straight incompletion,''
alluding to the quarterback's poor performance last Sunday against
the Chiefs, when he went 1 for 15 with two interceptions and three
fumbles. Leaf ended his one-day media blackout Friday, answering 8
of 11 questions with either a yes or a no.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   A year ago last Sunday, in college games, the trio of Leaf,
 &UR; Peyton Manning &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Charlie Batch  &LR; went a combined 75 of 127
for 975 yards and 10 touchdowns. This year, they went 41 of 99 for
357 yards, no touchdown passes, six interceptions, and four
fumbles. A year ago they all were winners. Last Sunday they all
were losers. Welcome to the NFL, boys ... Several Dallas insiders
insist that the Cowboys had plans to play  &UR; Deion Sanders  &LR; at
quarterback in short-yardage situations last week against the
Giants. Head coach  &UR; Chan Gailey  &LR; isn't talking about it, but in
Pittsburgh, he came up with similar ones for  &UR; Kordell Stewart
 &LR; before Stewart made the conversion from wide receiver to
quarterback. Sanders did take snaps at quarterback at the end of
the week, but it wasn't necessary for him to play QB because he
killed the Giants at defensive back and as a punt returner. But
don't be surprised to see him under center one of these Sundays.
Sanders, by the way, has the highest interception-return average in
NFL history at 27.4 yards per return (37 picks for 1,012 yards) ...
Carolina linebacker  &UR; Kevin Greene  &LR; leads the NFC with five sacks
and has become football's answer to  &UR; George Foreman &LR; . He now has
more sacks after the age of 30 (75.5 of his 138) than any man in
history. Green Bay's  &UR; Reggie White  &LR; has made 71.5 since turning 30,
and  &UR; Chris Doleman  &LR; (70) and Buffalo's  &UR; Bruce Smith  &LR; (63.50) are
also in the competition ... Greene is one of the bright spots for
the Panthers, who have already lost six players for the season with
injuries ... The Patriots'  &UR; Robert Edwards  &LR; became only the eighth
rookie since 1970 to rush for a touchdown in each of his first
three games. Of the other seven, one was not  &UR; Curtis Martin  &LR; ...
49ers owner  &UR; Eddie DeBartolo  &LR; secretly testified in front of a
federal grand jury Thursday in Baton Rouge that is looking into
charges of bribery involving former Louisiana Gov.  &UR; Edwin Edwards &LR; 
and a riverboat gambling license. Word is DeBartolo accepted an
immunity deal in exchange for his testimony. DeBartolo admits to
making a $400,000 cash payment to Edwards, who claims he was
serving as a lobbyist. The day after delivery of the cash,
DeBartolo's organization received the final available riverboat
gambling license from the state. DeBartolo first appeared before
the grand jury in June 1997 but is believed to have taken the Fifth
Amendment then. Sources say the deal he eventually agreed to will
allow him to pay a fine and avoid jail time by portraying himself
as a victim of Edwards. Since the matter began, DeBartolo turned
over day-to-day control of the 49ers to his sister. When Policy
left in a dispute with DeBartolo,  &UR; Larry Thrailkill &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a DeBartolo
associate, was installed as club president. Tagliabue has mediated
an ongoing dispute over control of the team between DeBartolo and
his sister, who has opposed DeBartolo's plans to build a mall
adjacent to a planned $350 million stadium near 3Com Park. The
conflict has escalated in recent months to a battle for control.
``Where it's going, I don't know,'' said NFL senior vice president
for communication and government affairs  &UR; Joe Browne &LR; . &UR;  &LR;  ``Eddie
does not have an active role in running the team right now. Once we
determine what happened in Louisiana, we'll review it. If he wants
to get back in as the operating head, it will depend on the charges
and how he pleads. We don't have a formula for if you plead X we do
Y. We'll have to wait and see.'' ... The Colts' defense is the only
one in the NFL without a sack and may be forced to play Sunday
without starting ends.  &UR; Dan Footman  &LR; has a bad knee and  &UR; Al
Fontenot  &LR; has a calf injury. Converted linebacker  &UR; Bertrand Berry
 &LR; would replace Footman and be faced with trying to solve Pro Bowl
tackle  &UR; Willie Roaf &LR; , &UR;  &LR; while Fontenot's replacement could be  &UR; Van
Tuinei &LR; , who only signed a week ago ... Meanwhile, up in Buffalo,
quarterback  &UR; Rob Johnson  &LR; has to be happy to have Sunday off. The
Bills have allowed 22 sacks and he has suffered two concussions in
three games.
</P>
</TEXT>
