<HEADER>
A6210 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ORIOLES-REDSOX-BO     09-26 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ORIOLES-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX DON'T SWEAT SETBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And then there was one _ and a postseason. A lengthy postseason,
the Red Sox hope.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game against the Orioles had all the makings of a
controlled scrimmage. If not exactly a Grapefruit League affair,
call it at least a pre-postseason outing.
</P>
<P>
   A parade of Red Sox pitchers each got their prescribed work,
including Dennis Eckersley, who made a record-setting 1,071st
appearance. Every position player save John Valentin made an
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Red Sox didn't have enough to take care of
Baltimore as their four-game win streak ended with a 5-2 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Not a problem.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if the Red Sox wrapped things up with a week or two
to spare and had to worry about whether to rev up or rest up for
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're peaking and playing well at the right time,'' said Mo
Vaughn, who had a hit in his last at-bat and is at .336 in his race
with the Yankees' Bernie Williams for the batting title. ``It's not
like you've got two weeks to go and you try to turn it off and on.
Three or four days and we're back in the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   First, the Red Sox send Pete Schourek to the mound Sunday to
close out the regular season and prepare for his scheduled start in
Game 4 of the first round Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was Bret Saberhagen's turn, and despite giving up a
couple of home runs in his five innings and losing for only the
second time since Aug. 6 to drop to 15-8, he was pleased with his
outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely a good tuneup,'' Saberhagen said. ``That's a
quality team over there. It's probably one of the toughest games
I've had this year, knowing you're going out there to try and get
some work in, but the game does not mean a thing except to get the
work in.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, entering on a pitch count of 60-70, threw 49 strikes
in 74 pitches. He gave up a two-run home run to B.J. Surhoff _
Surhoff's first of two _ in the second inning and then a solo job
to Eric Davis in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``The curve to Davis was not that bad a pitch,'' Saberhagen
said. ``I've been working on two different speed pitches and that
was the slower of the two. It was a first-pitch changeup to Surhoff
and had a little too much of the plate. I'm not concerned with that
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   He was more worried about a pitch that hit Oriole shortstop Mike
Bordick in the head in the second inning. Bordick sprawled face
down near the plate. He suffered a contusion on the left side of
his forehead, was taken for precautionary X-rays, but was back in
the clubhouse and told Saberhagen he was fine by phone before the
game ended.
</P>
<P>
   Quiet through five innings and trailing, 3-0, the Red Sox
finally got something going in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Lewis and Darren Bragg both singled and Vaughn worked a
walk to load the bases with no outs. Nomar Garciaparra then ripped
the first pitch down the third-base line for a double, cutting
Baltimore's lead to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sox would get no more.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanley was hit by a pitch to reload the bases, but Trot
Nixon, batting for Troy O'Leary, flied to short left. And then
Robbie Alomar made a nice diving play to stop a Scott Hatteberg
grounder and start an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you can hit the ball much better than what
Hatteberg did,'' said Sox manager Jimy Williams, who cited a couple
of other Alomar defensive plays.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore got one of those runs back on Alomar's solo homer off
Steve Avery to lead off the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   And the Red Sox threatened again in the bottom of the inning.
Vaughn (1 for 3) singled to lead off the inning and went to second
on a wild pitch. But Lou Merloni and Stanley struck out and the Sox
couldn't take advantage. They went down in order in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Boston actually outhit the Orioles, 7-6, but Baltimore hit four
home runs. Scott Erickson went seven innings and got the win to up
his record to 16-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good fastball for the first five innings,'' Erickson
said. ``Then I ran out of gas. I was tired and got a little wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Lowe, Jim Corsi, Avery, and Eckersley each got an inning
of work. Bragg had two hits.
</P>
<P>
   And now it's down to one game before showtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was kind of like a spring training feeling, getting ready
for the season to get going,'' Saberhagen said. ``I didn't have
that intensity I normally have going out there. It's nothing I'm
concerned with. Going to the postseason, if you can't get up for
that, you can't get up for anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
