<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6213 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-ROSENBLA     09-26 2257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-ROSENBLATT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOUTS OF FATIGUE A CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASHANTUCKET PEQUOT RESERVATION _ In the last four rounds of his
unanimous decision over Terry Norris Friday night, Dana Rosenblatt
looked like a dead man walking. An hour later, he looked like a
dead man, period.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt was so dehydrated that he had to be given an IV after
becoming ill in his locker room and was then carried on a stretcher
into a waiting ambulance that took him to Backus Hospital. He was
rehydrated there and had a small cut on his right eyelid stitched,
but it is neither his eye nor a sore knuckle on his left hand that
should be a concern for trainer Joe Lake.
</P>
<P>
   His worry has to be a developing pattern in which the Malden
middleweight starts fast, looks dominant for about eight rounds,
and then begins to fade like a pair of well-worn jeans until he is
only a shadow in the ring in the final rounds.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened in his previous fight, a victory over
Arthur Allen, and against Norris: Rosenblatt dominates for eight
rounds and then has to hold on for dear life. Allen used that
advantage to turn Rosen-blatt's face into swollen pulp in six
minutes after he'd failed to win 60 seconds of the first eight
rounds, and Friday night Rosen-blatt made Norris look old, slow,
and ready for retirement for eight rounds. His advantage, according
to Compubox's punch stats, was decisive at that point and clear to
the eye as well.
</P>
<P>
   Then, inexplicably, he stood up for Round 9 and looked like he'd
just seen Heartbreak Hill for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly unable to move his hands often enough to sting Norris
with a jab that had already bloodied the former junior middleweight
champion's nose and mouth, he appeared totally exhausted. For 12
minutes he repeatedly held Norris at every opportunity, refusing to
use the jab, while clinching so often that a crowd heavily in his
favor began to boo.
</P>
<P>
   This dance went on for 12 interminable minutes before the fight
ended with Rosenblatt clutching Norris like a man trying to open an
umbrella in a stiff wind.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt had piled up such a big lead that cries of protest
from Norris's cornermen over the unanimous decision were absurd,
but the bigger concern for Lake has to be whether Rosenblatt has a
physical problem. Few fighters have ever made such complete
reversals in one round as Rosenblatt has in his last two fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's his electrolytes or something like that,'' Lake
said. ``He just seemed to hit the wall and had nothing the last two
rounds. He was totally dehydrated when it was over. Same thing last
fight. We don't know what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Evander Holyfield once had a similar problem. It manifested
itself most severely in his odd loss to Michael Moorer when Nevada
doctors thought his exhaustion resulted from a heart problem. Later
it was learned he regularly grew so dehydrated in training that it
was difficult for his body to function.After some testing, a new
approach of rehydration was begun.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps something similar is the source of Rosenblatt's sudden
somnambulent syndrome, but whatever the cause is, it needs to be
found if he hopes to climb the top rungs of the middleweight
division.
</P>
<P>
   Since he weighed in at 158 pounds and probably was 10 pounds
heavier by fight time, his exhaustion should not have been a result
of trying to make weight, as it sometimes was when he was still
battling to fight at 154 pounds. That is no longer a reasonable
weight for him, which is why Lake has rejected plans from promoter
Bob Arum to send Rosenblatt to Europe to fight for one of the
junior middleweight titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does he do with it after he wins it?'' Lake said. ``He
wouldn't be able to defend it because he couldn't make the weight.
What's the point? If he was going to fight Oscar (De La Hoya) at
154 he could do it once for the opportunity. But just to win some
title his body wouldn't let him keep makes no sense. Dana is a
mid-dle-weight.''
</P>
<P>
   It would appear so, but maybe even 160 is taking too much out of
him. Then again, maybe it's not the weight but some other problem
doctors could find after testing. Whatever it is, Rosen-blatt and
Lake need to investigate it and solve it, because if they don't,
one night his lead won't be big enough, or his fatigue will arrive
soon enough, to get him beat.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Promoter  &UR; Don King  &LR; is being threatened with having his Florida
promoter's license suspended or revoked because of allegations
reported here that King paid $100,000 to a charity run by the
Florida State Athletic Commission's executive director,  &UR; Michael
Scionti &LR; . It is the only donation ever made to the organization,
and the charge is that King received special treatment as a result.
Scionti has denied the charges but Arizona Sen.  &UR; John McCain  &LR; has
asked Florida Gov.  &UR; Lawton Chiles  &LR; to look into the allegations of
conflict of interest. Both the governor's office and the state
attorney general's office have begun an investigation. The
allegations first came from lawyers for  &UR; Julio Cesar Chavez &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who
claimed that Scionti, because of the donation, was urging the
commission to recognize exclusive promotional contracts that
prevented a fighter from working for anyone else. Florida
previously had a rule prohibiting such exclusionary contracts but
at Scionti's urgings, it changed that position ... Arum conceded
that despite De La Hoya's popularity, nothing compares with  &UR; Mike
Tyson's &LR; . But he went on to argue that it is for the worst of
reasons. ``People will watch Tyson because he's boxing's version of
`The Truman Show,''' Arum said. ``He's lived his life in a
fishbowl. Oscar will outdraw anyone but Tyson. He's the most
popular guy in the sport.'' ... Mr. Ten Percent, fight manager
 &UR; Shelly Finkel &LR; , &UR;  &LR; showed where his loyalties truly lie when for no
apparent reason he opined, ``When Mike fights Evander again, he
will win.'' Finkel made his reputation, not to mention hundreds of
thousands of dollars, off Holyfield's sweat and heart when he was
his co-manager. Now he's Tyson's 10 percenter, so he's got the
other guy winning. Some guys have no shame ... Before the  &UR; Junior
Jones &LR; - &UR; Erik Morales  &LR; fight two weeks ago, Mexican government
officials claimed that HBO workers neglected to apply and pay for
$250 work permits. They took several to the US-Mexico border on the
eve of the fight and demanded $60,000 in fines to let them stay to
work the telecast. Mexican promoter  &UR; Fernando Beltran  &LR; managed to
``negotiate'' the fines down to $20,000, but HBO executives were
