<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6215 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-SAVAGE-BOS     09-26 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SAVAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVAGE WORKING HARD AND WINGING IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ He might be a rookie in training camp but
Andre Savage's ties to the Bruins were established long before the
23-year-old forward signed with Boston as a free agent last June.
</P>
<P>
   Savage, a native of Ottawa, has former Bruin coach Steve Kasper
as his agent, and Tim Watters, who was an assistant coach under
Kasper in 1995-96, coached Savage for the last two years at
Michigan Tech.
</P>
<P>
   The youngster has made coach Pat Burns take notice, and captain
Ray Bourque said he is impressed with the way Savage goes to the
net. Savage is just hoping to win a spot on the club, somehow, some
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to work hard,'' said Savage, who had a
terrific goal against the Penguins last Wednesday, beating veteran
defenseman Kevin Hatcher before firing a shot past goalie Craig
Hillier. ``I tried to do everything good in every aspect of the
game. I was just trying to give it my best every time. It helps
when you have good players to play with. Since I'm a new guy, the
older guys help me out and that makes it easier to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Savage has had to get used to a new position: left wing. He
spent most of his college career playing center or right wing and
was the second player in school history to lead the team in scoring
three straight seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played center a few times, too, (in camp),'' said Savage,
who had 14 goals and 41 points in 33 games last season. ``I think
Pat is trying to get a feel of where he should play me. I hadn't
played left wing before a whole lot, but I'm getting used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   This training camp has been complicated because there are four
restricted free agents _ Jason Allison, Anson Carter, Kyle McLaren,
and Ted Donato _ sitting out. Workouts resemble episodes of ``Star
Search,'' with a host of young players fighting for available jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just messes up the cards more, that's all,'' said Burns.
``Savage, I thought, played a real strong game (Wednesday) and
worked hard. Peter Nordstrom had a good performance. Landon Wilson
didn't have a good performance so you're weighing it, (with
players) going up and going down. Cameron Mann had a pretty good
game, Joe Thornton played better. Jonathan Girard was so-so. So you
have the ups and downs of selecting a team where you're excited one
day and the next day you're not sure. That's the fun about training
camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Savage hasn't seemed awed by the surroundings. He and Bourque,
both French-speaking natives of Quebec province, have bonded.
Savage said he's soaking up advice like a sponge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray is a really good leader,'' said Savage. ``He always
emphasizes for me to go to the net with the puck. Things will
happen if you go to the net. Guys like him, with all the experience
they have, you know they're saying it for a reason. They know what
they're talking about. It helps when you have guys like that
helping you out.''
</P>
<P>
   Savage is well aware of the free agent situation and he's hoping
to use it to his advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you a little bit more of a chance to prove
yourself,'' he said. ``Nothing is written in stone. You have to
work hard every game and practice. If you give your best, hopefully
good things will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that attitude and his following through on it that have
impressed Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``He works hard in the corners and comes up with the puck,''
said Burns. ``He gets some good chances. He's not an easy skater
but he gets there, he finds a way to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque said Savage reminds him a bit of Steve Heinze. Burns can
see the comparison somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heinze is a little bit better of a skater,'' said Burns, ``but
he's right _ he's got that crouch position and he's got a quick
shot and a good shot and he's a good, hard worker. All those things
are in his favor.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kasper and Savage were shopping around for teams, Boston by
far showed the most interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to the Islanders a little bit and the Rangers a
little bit,'' said Savage. ``But it was nothing really serious.
Boston was really the one who showed a real interest. That's all I
wanted was to get an opportunity, to get my foot in the door and
prove myself and hopefully I can play in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Watters, for one, believes he can.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the offensive skills you just can't teach kids,'' said
Watters. ``His commitment was second to none. He'd do whatever he
could to make himself a better player. Boston has a good reputation
for giving young guys opportunities. I'm really glad for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
