<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS LOSE AGAIN IN OAKLAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ It's a good thing for the Angels their game against
the Oakland A's on Saturday was meaningless. Otherwise, their 4-3
loss would have hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The A's Rickey Henderson _ on Rickey Henderson Day at the
Oakland Coliseum _ singled home Eric Chavez in the bottom of the
ninth to cap a two-run rally off Angels closer Troy Percival before
22,661.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was set up with one out in the ninth by shortstop
Justin Baughman, who fielded Scott Spiezio's grounder cleanly but
threw it away for an error, one of four Anaheim made in the game.
</P>
<P>
   With two out, Chavez tied the game with an RBI single, then
scored the game-winner on Henderson's single.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson was honored before the game for scoring his 2,000th
career run Aug. 31, joining Ty Cobb, Hank Aaron, Babe Ruth, Pete
Rose and Willie Mays as the only players to score 2,000 runs.
</P>
<P>
   Baughman was in at shortstop to give Gary DiSarcina a day off.
Tim Salmon and Darin Erstad also didn't play. But despite giving
some of his players the day off, the loss bothered manager Terry
Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because the lineup changed doesn't mean we didn't try to
win the game,'' he said. ``You play hard and you play to win. They
mean just as much to me every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Steve Sparks got knocked around by the Rangers in
his previous two starts, but on Saturday he regained the form that
helped him win six consecutive decisions during one stretch this
summer. Sparks gave up two runs (one earned) and five hits in seven
innings, helping him ensure an invitation to spring training next
season. He finished the season 9-4 with a 4.34 ERA in 22 games,
including 20 starts.
</P>
<P>
   But before he joins the Angels in Arizona next February, Sparks
will go to his home near Houston to help his wife take care of
their two children and maybe do some substitute teaching at the
local high school.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks didn't teach during the last offseason because he was
recovering from surgeries on his right elbow and left shoulder, but
he usually works in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent my offseasons teaching, waiting tables or playing
winter ball,'' Sparks said. ``You try to make enough money to get
you through to spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   His performance this season is generally regarded as the biggest
surprise of the year for the Angels, but Sparks says he's just
happy to be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very grateful I'm healthy and I'm grateful for the
opportunity these guys gave me,'' he said. ``(General manager) Bill
(Bavasi) made me feel wanted. I called him before spring training
for an opportunity to play, and they, more than any other team,
showed confidence in me.
</P>
<P>
   ``They moved me up from Double-A to Triple-A early on because
they took my word for it when I said I was throwing good,'' he
said. ``I really didn't have any doubts I could pitch. I've always
been confident. Whether that's being naive or not, I don't know.
Sometimes all it takes is an opportunity and a few breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Pritchett (No.2) and Jim Edmonds (No.25) hit solo homers
for the Angels, and Edmonds singled home a run in the eighth for a
3-2 lead. But Percival (2-7), going for his 43rd save, couldn't
hold it. A's reliever T.J. Mathews (7-4) got the victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
