<SLUG> BC-FBC-SMU-MISSISSIPPI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMU BLOWS 22-POINT LEAD IN LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Whit Canning 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ In the aftermath of an amazing mishap at the Cotton
Bowl yesterday, SMU coach Mike Cavan offered a succinct analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing good ever comes of this, and nothing ever will,'' he
said, after watching the Mississippi Rebels (3-1) score 29 late
points to overcome the Mustangs in overtime, 48-41.
</P>
<P>
   Cavan's reference was to the fact that the Mustangs (0-4) once
held a 22-point lead and played maybe their best game of the
season. Problem was, they didn't play it long enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overconfident?'' said Cavan, in reference to one query. ``How
can you be overconfident when you haven't won a game? We just did
it again _ failed to play 60 minutes. We were tired at the end
\Rafter 3 hours, 35 minutes\S, but so were they. We just haven't
learned how to play a complete football game.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Tracy Hart rolled into the end zone from 47 yards away
with an interception to give SMU a 41-19 lead with 9:45 left, it
almost seemed they had done enough.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the Rebels were reeling, having recently coughed
up the ball at the SMU 2-yard line after moving 78 yards _ and
watched SMU roll back down the field with it. Josh McCown, SMU's
freshman quarterback, had thrown three touchdown passes, two to
Albert Johnson, and Rodnick Phillips (119 yards) was ripping huge
chunks out of the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' SMU cornerback Jacoby Rhinehart said, ``I thought
we had the game won in the third quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, the bedeviled Rebels would lose four fumbles, an
interception, and nearly the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Romaro Miller (32-of-51, 351 yards) brought them back with a
scoring pass to Cory Peterson and a two-point conversion _ and then
the game turned.
</P>
<P>
   The Mustangs were soon sitting at the Ole Miss 45 after
recovering an onside kick, but were unable to move _ so Colin
Vadheim drifted a punt toward the right flag.
</P>
<P>
   It never made it. Peterson took it at the 8, tore off to the
right, and sailed 92 yards behind a wall of blue helmets _ and with
5:55 left, it was a game again, with SMU leading 41-34.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kick right!'' Cavan said, ``Kick right! We kept practicing
that, but we just didn't cover. The kicking game killed us again.''
</P>
<P>
   It still seemed like SMU's game with Ole Miss looking at a
fourth-and-seven at its 15 with 1:31 left. But Miller completed a
pass for the first down. Then with 40 seconds left, the Rebs took
their final timeout at the SMU 44.
</P>
<P>
   On the next play, Miller fired a rocket to Grant Heard _ a step
ahead of Hart in the end zone _ and a stunned throng of 22,281
generously laced with Ole Miss fans was looking at overtime.
</P>
<P>
   After throwing repeatedly throughout the afternoon, the Rebs
alternated Deuce McAlister and Joe Gunn on five consecutive rushing
plays in overtime, where teams start a possession at the opponent's
25. McAlister carried 4 yards on the last carry, thrusting his
finger into the air as he turned the corner and swept into the end
zone.
</P>
<P>
   On SMU's first snap, McCown went to the end zone for Johnson,
but the ball was off his fingertips and over the end line. After
two plays lost 6 yards, McCown went to Johnson again, but this one
sailed out of the end zone, and the Mustangs' despair was complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Explain it?'' Cavan said. ``I wish I could.'' \Nsubheds:Extra
points  &LR; body:Mississippi is now 12-0 under coach Tommy Tuberville
in nonconference games. ... The Rebels had plenty of fans on hand
to watch their first game at the Cotton Bowl since losing to Texas
on New Year's Day in 1962.  &LR; tagtop:Whit Canning, (817) 390-7760
</P>
</TEXT>
