</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SOSA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA'S CLUTCH HIT STAYS IN BALLPARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Screaming for Sammy Sequel, the delirious crowd
yesterday at the Astrodome instead got Sammy Scrappy.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Sammy Sosa got his biggest hit of the year, and
20,000 responded with boos and exits.
</P>
<P>
   Needing a homer to keep any hope alive in his Greater Tater Race
with Mark McGwire, Sosa instead shortened his swing and grounded a
single to left field that ignited an eighth-inning rally and
spurred his Chicago Cubs to a crucial 3-2 victory against the
Houston Astros. With McGwire launching two more dingers to reach
68, Sosa stuck on 66 but propelled his team to the brink of the
playoffs with single No. 98.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark's always been ahead, and I didn't think I could catch
him,'' said Sosa, conceding the race for the umpteenth time while
washing down a huge plate of postgame pasta with a
cranberry-rasberry Snapple. ``He'll probably hit 70. It's great for
him. I've always said he was `The Man,' and I'll say it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of Sosa's spark, Gary Gaetti's two-out, two-run double
and closer Rod Beck's controversial game-ending tag-out of Astros
pinch hitter Dave Clark, a Cubs victory today will either clinch
the National League wild-card berth or allow them to play host to a
Monday playoff game at Wrigley Field against the San Francisco
Giants. Both teams enter today's finales with 89-72 records, with
the New York Mets a game back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more interested in the wild card,'' Sosa said. ``If
(McGwire) gets the record and I get the playoffs, then I'll take
that.''
</P>
<P>
   After holding a brief, 45-minute lead with his 66th homer Friday
night, Sosa's edge was Maccuumed-up as he went homerless in his
next six at-bats while McGwire pounded three in a span of two days
out of Busch Stadium 780 miles away to all but clinch the most
glamorous record in American sports.
</P>
<P>
   After fouling out to first baseman Jeff Bagwell in the first on
a 1-0 fastball, Sosa drilled a 1-1 pitch over Shane Reynolds' head
for a line-drive single in the third. Before his next at-bat, Sosa
was again behind McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   The sellout of 51,950 erupted at the video of McGwire's 67th,
then urged Sosa to retie the race. Leading off the sixth, he was
greeted by chants of ``Sam-mee, Sam-mee'' and Reynolds was heartily
booed by his own fans at each pitch out of the strike zone. On a
3-2 count, however, Sosa whiffed at a dipping splitter for his
National League-leading 169th strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   A lock for NL most valuable player, Sosa will become the first
such award winner to also lead the league in strikeouts. He almost
added to his total in a key at-bat leading off the eighth. But
after grazing two two-strike pitches from reliever Jay Powell to
stay alive, Sosa choked up on the bat and golfed a low pitch into
the hole to start a rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thinking home run, I was thinking get on base,'' Sosa
explained. ``I was proud of that'' hit.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Sosa stepped into the on-deck circle in the ninth,
he trailed McGwire by two. Sosa was left there when second baseman
Mickey Morandini grounded out, forcing him to hope for McGwire to
go homerless today in order for him to tie with two against the
Astros, who start left-hander Mike Hampton. Should the Cubs play in
a wild-card playoff game, however, Sosa's statistics will count
toward the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look good, but it ain't over,'' Cubs first baseman
Mark Grace said. ``As we have seen, either one of these guys can go
out and hit two or three in a game. But the reason Sammy is so
great showed today. He did what he had to do to get us a win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
