<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-WASHINGTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEBRASKA BEATS WASHINGTON, 55-7  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. _ One play, one pitch to DeAngelo Evans was all
Bobby Newcombe was wishing for against the Washington Huskies
Saturday. The Nebraska quarterback had sat out the past two games
with a torn knee ligament. Evans, the I-back in the ground-gobbling
Cornhusker option, had been out for 21 months trying to overcome a
medical chart worth of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Newcombe and Evans got a whole lot more than a pitch together,
much to the detriment of No. 9 Washington, which was overwhelmed at
Memorial Stadium by No. 2-ranked Nebraska, 55-7.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 76,372 _ Nebraska's 223rd consecutive sellout _
watched the duo demoralize the Huskies, driving the Cornhuskers to
a 35-7 lead at half-time and never looking back. They combined for
six touchdowns in a performance reminiscent of Nebraska's 1980s
powerhouse pair of Turner Gill and Mike Rozier to hand Washington
its worst loss since a 52-0 shellacking by Alabama in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   They also reasserted something that has been forgotten in the
team's three previous games: that Nebraska is first and foremost a
running team. The Cornhuskers gained 434 yards rushing, nearly
double their average this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a statement as a team,'' said Evans, who carried 13
times for 146 yards and 3 touchdowns. ``This is Nebraska, and we're
going to do what we do _ run the ball at you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cornhuskers did it the slow, grinding way. Newcombe capped
an 11-play, 82-yard opening drive by scampering 3 yards around
right end to begin the rout. They also did it the swift, numbing
way. Newcombe flicked the ball on the option to Evans, who followed
a devastating block by wingback Shervin Wiggins and rambled 60
yards down the sideline. It was his first touchdown since December
1996, in the Big 12 championship game, when he scored 3 touchdowns
and gained 132 yards.
</P>
<P>
   From then until Saturday Evans had been sentenced to the
training room trying to overcome first an abdominal muscle tear
that required surgery, then an ankle sprain and finally cartilage
damage to a knee he injured in Nebraska's spring game.
</P>
<P>
   He had become an inspiration for an injury-riddled Cornhusker
team because of the grace and determination with which he attacked
his long climb back. And finally it was rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Evans displayed the acceleration and sharp cuts that helped him
break the high school rushing record of Barry Sanders, a fellow
Wichita, Kan., native now with the Detroit Lions. He put a
stutter-step move that wobbled the knees of Husky linebacker Lester
Towns and then burst by to complete a 14-yard touchdown run in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   Newcombe, who was back after tearing a ligament in Nebraska's
opener, matched Evans' brilliance play for play. Newcombe, a native
of New Mexico, was attracted to Nebraska after watching Evans on
television throughout the 1996 season, when he gained 776 yards and
ran for 14 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd tell my dad that one day I'd pitch to him,'' Newcombe
said. And on his first opportunity, he pitched behind Evans, nearly
causing a turnover. ``I was so anxious to do it, I almost threw it
away,'' Newcombe said. ``It was great to see him running down the
sideline on that long one after all he's been through.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only Newcombe's second game as Nebraska's quarterback,
and he wore a knee brace, but the sophomore directed the option
like he was wired electronically to the quarterback coach, Gill. He
engineered drives of 82, 90 and 60 yards. He carried the ball 14
times and turned upfield for 79 yards and 3 touchdowns. He was 5 of
8 passing for 84 yards.
</P>
<P>
   On defense Nebraska was just as dominating, holding the Huskies
to 273 total yards. A relentless pass rush forced the quarterback,
the Heisman Trophy hopeful Brock Huard, into two fumbles and two
interceptions before he was removed from the game.
</P>
<P>
   The day's most lasting image of Huard came after Nebraska
defensive tackle Jason Wiltz picked off Huard's batted pass. The
6-foot-4-inch 310-pounder crushed the Husky quarterback on the
return, but somehow Huard hung on to the seat of Wiltz's pants like
a child to drag him down.
</P>
<P>
   The snapshot of Newcombe's and Evans' day was much warmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired,'' Necombe confessed. ``After being out for so long
and with all the worries and pressures I had to deal with, it was
kind of a fairy-tale thing today.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
