<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOJO-FUNERAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2,000 RECALL GRIFFITH JOYNER, TRACK STAR WITH COMMITMENT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMANTHA STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MISSION VIEJO, Calif. _ The little girl had pigtails with pink
ties and diamond earrings. She wore a fluorescent pink dress and
held on to a shaggy teddy bear as she stood with a boy and girl
outside the church doors on Saturday, with relatives and friends
mingling nearby. ``Look,'' she said, as she pointed inside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seven-year-old Mary Ruth Joyner was looking at the shiny,
flower-draped, copper coffin of her 38-year-old mother, Florence
Griffith Joyner. Griffith Joyner, who won three gold medals and a
silver medal in track and field at the 1988 Summer Olympics, was
known not only for her extraordinary speed, but also for her beauty
and humanitarian efforts. She died at her home in Mission Viejo on
Monday morning.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Griffith Joyner's funeral service at Saddleback Community Church
was a celebration of about 2,000 people, some who had never met the
Olympian and others who had watched her from the beginning. It was
a service filled with gospel singing and readings of Scripture.
Many who eulogized Griffith Joyner defended her accomplishments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Kersee, who coached Griffith Joyner, said it was Griffith
Joyner's commitment to the track and field world that first caught
his attention. Kersee _ who is married to Jackie Joyner-Kersee,
whose brother, Al Joyner, was married to Griffith Joyner _ came to
the podium and remembered Griffith Joyner with a spirited sermon
that had the audience laughing, crying, clapping and shouting
``Amen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am blessed to coach her,'' Kersee said as he told those in
the church it was time to tell the truth, alluding to news reports
and rumors that her times at the 1988 Olympics were helped by
performance-enhancing drugs, although she never tested positive for
any illegal substance. ``All of her races have been run with faith
_ not her coach or her shoes. She knew that Jesus was in her heart.
She ran a faithful race. She stopped by today to say all those
jealous, venomous words _ those jealous words can't harm her no
more. Lies can't hurt us anymore. God is protecting her from the
scorpion's bag of reporters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``She ran a race faithfully and won. She was such a good mother,
great wife, excellent daughter, fine sister, and she was a good
friend and had fans everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Mary Ruth went to the podium to be with her father, Al.
Joyner told the mourners that Griffith Joyner had always wanted to
hear her daughter sing, and so Mary Ruth and a young girl friend
took the microphones and sang a song about the wind and Jesus.
Joyner broke down and the Kersees escorted him down the stairs to
the coffin, where he kissed his wife goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   William Hybl, the president of the U.S. Olympic Committee,
spoke. He announced a special exhibit to be opened at the USOC
headquarters in the spring to honor Griffith Joyner's
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 10 years ago, yesterday, that she ran in Seoul,'' said
Andre Phillips, who had won a gold medal in the 400-meter hurdles
there. ```Andre,' she said, `it's your turn tomorrow.' And we both
won gold. I have never been impressed or starstruck by other
athletes. At her race, I was in awe, but not shocked, by how she
performed. She just had it in her.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
