<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAC IS THE MAN, BUT SOSA IS MVP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Eric Karros probably put it best.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Mark McGwire has done is the most important thing to
happen to baseball in the past 20 years,'' the Dodgers first
baseman said. ``But Sammy Sosa is still the MVP.''
</P>
<P>
   Although McGwire moved ahead of Sosa in the single-season home
run record with two on Saturday, he is not the National League Most
Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   That is difficult to say because McGwire has been the pick in
this space most of the season. He has helped bring baseball back to
the fans. He sparked water cooler debates. He spent more time on
the nightly news than Bill Clinton _ and that wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cardinals, projected to win the NL Central, never got
close. It wasn't McGwire's fault the Cardinals pitching staff
disintegrated. No one noticed under McGwire's massive shadow. But
they are noticing now and it's going to cost him.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa hit 66 homers and carried the Chicago Cubs on his back for
an entire season. If you don't think those kinds of guys are
important, then you haven't been watching your Dodgers very closely
the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   The game is about winning. That is why Kevin Malone is with the
Dodgers now. That is why Fox is ready to spend $75 million on next
year's payroll.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs were not a very good team this year. But they got 19
victories from Kevin Tapani and brought up a wunderkind named Kerry
Wood. They got 49 saves out of Rod Beck, who wanted to play for the
Dodgers but couldn't because Peter O'Malley, in one of his final
acts as owner, wouldn't give Fred Claire the money.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that would have mattered without Sosa. In June, he
did much more than hit a major-league record 20 home runs. He gave
the Cubs _ baseball's lovable losers _ a reason to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Three-time batting champion Bill Madlock once said it is easier
to win awards for a winning team because you have winning to take
your mind off the records at hand. From Opening Day, McGwire had
the overwhelming task of chasing Roger Maris.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa also had the wild-card race, which still might not be
decided at the end of today when the regular season is scheduled to
end.
</P>
<P>
   He also made the home run chase fun, lightening up the
often-sullen McGwire. Sosa showed emotion, cried during nearly
every sound bite. He made even non-baseball fans wish this season
never would end.
</P>
<P>
   When this MVP ballot is mailed Monday, it will read Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   This just in: Mike Piazza will re-sign with the Mets if co-owner
Nelson Doubleday has any say in it. And Piazza will get the $100
million contract the Dodgers never offered and looked so remote
just two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have decided to make every effort we can to sign him,''
Doubleday said. ``The way things are going now for Mike here in New
York is better now than it has been. It's really his call. But Lord
knows, I want him to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends on the Dodgers say Piazza has told them he won't return
to New York, but Doubleday knows if the Yankees win the World
Series, he has no choice but to make a big splash regardless of the
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the sublime to the ridiculous, to that extent it's an
issue,'' he said. ``But any numbers we've seen or heard are not
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Piazza is at least sounding like someone who'll
listen to the Mets' postseason offers _ which represents a
startling change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a lot of good experiences here,'' he said.
``I've enjoyed a lot of the guys. I think the fans have treated me
fairly. I've never complained.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was pointed out that the fans at Shea booed Piazza for
much of the summer, he replied: ``There was obviously a time early
on when I wasn't playing very well. I don't think it's been any
different for me than for anybody else who played in any other city
like New York or Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   Across town: Here's what the Yankees' rotation will be in the
division series: David Wells, Andy Pettitte, David Cone and, if
necessary, Orlando Hernandez in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre's decision to go with Pettitte, rather than
Hernandez or Hideki Irabu, comes more from the heart than the head,
especially since the left-hander is only 2-5 with a 6.90 ERA in his
last seven starts. Still, Pettitte is 9-4 this year at home, where
Games 1, 2 and 5 will be played. Pettitte also has pitched well in
past postseasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy's been there, there's no substitute for that. He doesn't
have anything to prove about his heart,'' said Torre, referring to
the 1-0 win over John Smoltz in Game 5 of the 1996 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's no doubt Pettitte hasn't been himself lately; his
ERA has climbed from 3.54 before Aug. 9 to 4.30 now. If Wells were
to lose Game 1, and Pettitte fails to reverse his slump in Game 2,
New York could be an ugly place this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Brown not down: Brant Brown's error in left field Wednesday that
cost the Chicago Cubs a victory in Milwaukee brought back the usual
ghosts from the collapse in 1969 and the grounder through Leon
Durham's legs in the 1984 playoff loss to San Diego. Was it just
one of those Cubs things?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just something that happened,'' Brown said. ``I don't
know how to explain it. It just stopped a little short on me and I
wasn't able to catch it. It was just a routine fly ball, nothing
troubling about that. You can say it was the wind, or the sun, but
those are elements we play with every day. Hopefully it doesn't
cost us that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown has had an interesting year. He became the regular center
fielder after Lance Johnson went on the DL earlier in the year. He
has also filled in at first base and in left field when others were
out. The Cubs think so much about the 27-year-old Brown that they
turned down several trade offers for him. He was among the players
Seattle reportedly asked for when the Cubs inquired about Randy
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, four days from now you can say it wasn't a Cub
thing,'' Rod Beck said after the game. ``Who knows? This just might
bring us even closer together.''
</P>
<P>
   No flash in the pan: Boston's Tom Gordon recorded his 41st
straight save Wednesday night, tying the major-league record set by
Beck and matched by San Diego's Trevor Hoffman earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Gordon got the final five outs for his 40th save,
tying the AL record set by his teammate, Dennis Eckersley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saved 48 of 50 one year (1990) when I was (bleeping) lights
out, I thought,'' Eckersley said. ``And that was pitching in a park
like Oakland. This place is a (bleeping) bandbox.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon hasn't blown a save since April 14. He now has 45 saves
this season, five more than Jeff Reardon saved in 1991 when he set
a Red Sox record.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws strikes,'' Eckersley said. ``What amazes me is his
consistency, velocity-wise. I knew how nasty his curveball was.
He's really been focused. He's just jumped in and hasn't skipped a
beat. It's really been great to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon never dreamed about 41 straight saves. When he came to
spring training in February he didn't know what percentage of games
he'd be saving and what percentage Eckersley would be called upon
to save. Gordon started quickly this spring, Eckersley started
slowly, and Gordon became manager Jimy Williams' main man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm just so excited that I've gotten a chance to
pitch every day,'' Gordon said. ``That's what keeps me motivated.
The important thing is trying to make the playoffs, not that I'm
downplaying (the streak). I know about it because I read about it.
I just try to block as much out as I can and focus on what it takes
to get ready. Those things are not important until Sept. 27, when I
can look in the mirror, see what I've accomplished and that my team
is going to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockie mountain winter: It appears that Colorado general manager
Bob Gebhard will remain in place and manager Don Baylor will be
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry McMorris said a few weeks ago that he still believes
this is the best team in franchise history on paper even though
they never had a leadoff hitter, center fielder or closer, and is
very upset the Rockies didn't play better.
</P>
<P>
   Gebhard has two years remaining on his contract, and Baylor only
one. It's doubtful both will go, leaving three years of salary to
eat. And since Baylor really didn't do much to light a fire under
this team, he could be the fall guy.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor appears worn out after six years of managing half the
time in a place where every game is in doubt until the last out.
His future could hinge on the availability of potential
replacements.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyland is the leading contender if he opts out of his
Marlins contract. Art Howe also is well-liked by McMorris and
Gebhard (read: a company man, not a loose cannon type such as Davey
Johnson). Like the Dodgers, the Rockies are interested in Felipe
Alou, who still has a year left on his Montreal contract. Gebhard
loves him and gave him his first managing job in the Expos'
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Finally: Baltimore manager Ray Miller is projecting that Cal
Ripken will play 145-150 games next year, a figure that Ripken does
not dispute, though he insists he will come back for 1999 with the
same play-all-the-time attitude he has carried into every season
since 1982. ``I've never been closed-minded to the concept of an
off day if I wasn't contributing for whatever reason,'' he said.
``If it goes in that direction and plays out that way, so be it.
But I'm going to continue coming to the ballpark with the same
exact attitude.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOP OF THE ORDER
</P>
<P>
   Pitching wins in the postseason. The Atlanta Braves lead the
majors in ERA (3.27), complete games (24), shutouts (22),
opponents' batting average (.241), strikeouts (1,209) and fewest
home runs allowed (117). The shutout and complete game totals are
the Braves' best since 1992, when they had 24 shutouts and 26
complete games. In round one, John Smoltz will start Game 1, Tom
Glavine Game 2 and Greg Maddux Game 3. &QL; 
ROTISSERIE WATCH
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Drew, the St. Louis Cardinals top draft pick who turned
baseball on its ear last year by demanding $10 million from the
Philadelphia Phillies. In Drew's first 13 games, he has 13 RBI and
five homers. He gives the Cardinals the chance to let Brian Jordan
walk as a free agent and sign a front-line pitcher. Sounds like he
already is worth the money. &QL; 
STAT OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs and New York Mets were last separated by more
than one game on Aug. 7, when the Cubs led the Mets by 1{ games.
There have been 16 lead changes or ties between the two teams since
then. But now the Mets, who lost Saturday, can only get into the
postseason if there is a playoff on Monday. &QL; 
THE BUZZ
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore second baseman Roberto Alomar said this past week he
has fond memories of the time he spent in Toronto and would not
rule out returning as a free agent if the Blue Jays are interested.
``My options are going to be open if I go on the market,'' he said.
``I'll have to wait and see what Baltimore has to say. I'm still
under contract now, but I always had fun in Toronto. There were
some great times and I can't forget that.'' &QL; 
QUOTABLE
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no different than I ever was. It's the players that have
made me look better. The thing is, I was always considered a
players' manager. That was a rap against me. But Davey Johnson was
a players' manager, too, and for him that was a strong point. I
always wondered what the difference was. The difference was the
players.'' &QL; 
_ Yankees Joe Torre, who had losing records managing the Mets,
Braves and Cardinals.
</P>
</TEXT>
