<HEADLINE>
'HUSKERS QUELL DOUBTS WITH CONVINCING WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. _ Harvest time. Time for the farmer to bring in
his crop. And time for college football teams to cultivate their
national championship chances.
</P>
<P>
   There were whispers around here _ and it wasn't just the wind
stirring the cornstalks _ wondering if Nebraska was good enough to
contend for a fourth title in five years. Sure, the 'Huskers were
ranked No. 2, but they had been less than impressive in winning
three games against teams they were supposed to beat.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's game against No. 9 Washington would prove which team
was a fraud. Here's what the Cornhuskers' dominating 55-7 victory
confirmed: Nebraska has a bumper crop, while the Huskies appear to
be all dried up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal was to make a statement,'' said center Josh Heskew,
the only returning veteran on the offensive line. ``We wanted to
come out and dominate. We've been criticized enough. Today, we
played the ninth-ranked team. We played some good ball. If you look
at the whole picture, we did a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington was the unfortunate recipient of Nebraska's wrath and
good health. For the first time this season, the 'Huskers had
quarterback Bobby Newcombe and I-back DeAngelo Evans on the field
together. Add in veteran fullback Joel Mackovicka and Nebraska has
an offense that is again capable of crooked numbers and fat stat
sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Teams that want to run option football should study Nebraska
(are you listening, Oklahoma Sooners coaches?) The 'Huskers
finished with 527 total yards, 434 of that on the ground. Evans
rushed 146 yards and three touchdowns on just 13 carries. Newcombe
had three touchdowns and gained 79 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two are big-play type of guys,'' Nebraska coach Frank
Solich said.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, who rushed for 776 yards as a freshman in 1996, was a
redshirt last season as he recovered from groin surgery. Nebraska's
attack needs an I-back who can gain yards in chunks. Evans has the
speed and moves to do that. His first TD was a 60-yard streak with
an option pitch. On his next two scores, he left defenders grasping
at air.
</P>
<P>
   Newcombe, a sophomore, might be a better quarterback than Tommie
Frazier, the hero of Nebraska's 1994 and 1995 title teams. Newcombe
jump started the 'Huskers' first TD drive with two impressive
scrambles. He has good timing on option pitches and he is a
deceptive runner.
</P>
<P>
   Washington was Newcombe's first ``big game'' as Nebraska's
quarterback. He confessed he was more worried last week about four
tests and a paper that was due Thursday. When you cover 40 yards in
4.4 seconds, you worry about the important things, not about
dodging 240-pound linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   One-game snapshots can be misleading. Florida State, Notre Dame
and Florida all took turns as one-week title contenders. Champions
are judged in the context of a full season.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska's season and championship hopes will be determined Nov.
14 in Manhattan, Kan., against Kansas State. Games with Texas A&AMP;M
(in College Station), Oklahoma State and Missouri should be mere
preludes, if yesterday is any indication.
</P>
<P>
   So now we know. When healthy, the 'Huskers are as talented as
any team in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one game. We're 4-0,'' said Solich, who downplayed any
messages his team sent yesterday. ``The players felt this was a key
game for us. It was. But so were the first three and so is the next
one and the game after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds a lot like Tom Osborne. Looks a lot like the same ol'
Nebraska.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
