r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-WASHINGT     09-26 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-WASHINGTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVANS A HIT, HUARD HIT HARD IN NEBRASKA'S WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. _ DeAngelo Evans couldn't wait to get hit. Brock
Huard couldn't wait for the hitting to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the contrast. Evans made a triumphant return as
Nebraska's I-back, gaining 146 yards and scoring three touchdowns.
With Evans juicing the offense, the second-ranked 'Huskers (4-0)
strolled to a 55-7 victory against ninth-ranked Washington here
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was relaxed but nervous,'' said Evans, a sophomore who sat
out last season with an injury and hadn't played in a game since
Dec. 7, 1996. ``The nerves went away with the first hit. That's
what I had been waiting for.''
</P>
<P>
   Huard, the Huskies' junior quarterback, found himself in the
middle of a redclad stampede. He was sacked three times and
pressured on nearly all of his 32 pass attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was worried about somebody taking his head off,'' Nebraska
defensive end Chad Kelsay said. ``He said, `Stop hitting me.' He
was starting to whine a little bit. You could see he wasn't
comfortable in the pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Huard completed 18 passes for 160 yards and one touchdown before
being relieved in the third quarter. He threw two interceptions and
lost two fumbles. Washington had six turnovers and 12 penalties for
144 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stings, this hurts,'' Huard said of Washington's worst
loss since a 62-13 loss to UCLA in 1973. ``You just want to crawl
into a hole.''
</P>
<P>
   The hole was provided by Nebraska's offense. The 'Huskers' first
touchdown drive was 82 yards (actually 92 after a penalty and a
loss) in 11 plays. The second touchdown was a one-play strike:
Evans 60 yards on an option pitch. After Huard's first
interception, the 'Huskers scored to make it 21-0 late in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at halftime, all of their running backs were averaging
seven yards a carry,'' Washington coach Jim Lambright said. ``We
obviously didn't have very good answers with our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Nebraska gained 384 yards in a 27-14 victory in
Seattle. Yesterday, the 'Huskers had 434 yards rushing, averaging
6.4 yards per attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska coach Frank Solich figured he would have an explosive
offense with sophomore Bobby Newcombe at quarterback and Evans at
I-back. But yesterday was the first game the two had played
together; Newcombe missed the 'Huskers' last two games with a knee
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all happy for DeAngelo, we're delighted to see him play
and play so well,'' Solich said. ``It's been a struggle for him,
and he's come through an awful lot. With DeAngelo and Bobby, it
causes a lot of headaches for the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The 'Huskers hoped that a veteran defense would allow the team's
untested offense time to jell. The jell hardened against
Washington. Evans rushed for 776 yards as a freshman and provides
the I-back speed the 'Huskers' offense requires.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one game, and I don't want to make too much of it,''
Evans said. ``But it was kind of like a fairy tale for me.''
 &LR; tagtop:Wendell Barnhouse, (817) 390-7238
