<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    He looks Young again
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Servic
<TEXT>
<P>
   San Francisco _ Steve Young is back, and for the Atlanta
Falcons, that's not good. Judging by the way the 49ers quarterback
played in his first two games _ passing for more than 300 yards and
throwing three touchdown passes in consecutive games for the first
time _ it looks as if the great-great-great grandson of Brigham
Young is as good as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Or better.
</P>
<P>
   And this is the man who last year tied Sammy Baugh's NFL record
with his sixth NFL passing title and a 104.7 rating.
</P>
<P>
   With no lingering effects from several concussions in a 14-year
pro career, and a healthy throwing elbow for the first time since
1996, Young looks young again.
</P>
<P>
   He sure isn't playing like a man who'll turn 37 two weeks from
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks better than he has for the last three or four
years,'' 49ers line coach Bobb McKittrick told the San Francisco
Chronicle. ``His elbow doesn't hurt. His head doesn't hurt. Now he
has confidence in all his (wide) receivers (Jerry Rice, Terrell
Owens and J.J. Stokes). And he still has that innate ability to
pull it down and make a first down (running).''
</P>
<P>
   When the 49ers thrashed the Redskins 45-10 on Monday Night
Football on Sept. 14, Young took off around end, ran for 20 yards
and got smashed by Washington cornerback Darrell Green. Young
popped up, patted Green on the helmet and ran to the huddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a strong move,'' said Young, who also ran 9 yards for a
TD against Washington. ``It just was not a very good move. It seems
like old times. We're back to where we have the weapons, and we
have the wherewithal and the coach is making the calls.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco coach Steve Mariucci is allowing Young to do more
this year because he's healthy, Owens and Stokes have matured, Rice
has returned and Young has a quality backup in Ty Detmer.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Young has completed 47-of-78 passes for 666 yards, six
TDs and just one interception, for a 108.2 passer rating, second in
the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Young said the offense is still ``ratty'' and can improve. ``We
feel good about it,'' he said. ``But my gosh, we've got to keep
working. You arrive in January; you don't arrive in September.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
