</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RICE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No fade for Rice
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ The irony is such that it causes a man who
has played 13 seasons with ice water coursing through his veins to
well up with uncharacteristic passion. Having long ago secured his
place in NFL history, Jerry Rice now is trying to define his niche
in the San Francisco 49ers wide-receiver corps.
</P>
<P>
   At least for the first two games of the season, Rice conceded
late last week, the quest to fit in with youngsters Terrell Owens
and J.J. Stokes has been more a struggle than he initially
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a major adjustment for me,'' Rice allowed as the
49ers completed their preparations for today's game against the
Atlanta Falcons. ``I had myself convinced that everything was fine.
I thought I had come to grips with everything in my mind. But we
started playing games, and it was obvious I'd been fooling myself
somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of felt like I was the third wheel on the bicycle.
And, yes, it was frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   That frustration manifested itself late in San Francisco's 45-10
victory at Washington two weeks ago. In front of a national
audience for the Monday night game, Rice blew up on the sideline,
complaining to coach Steve Mariucci about not getting the ball
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Rice had a team-high four catches in the game, but did not score
and was dragged down from behind by Redskins cornerback Darrell
Green after a 57-yard reception. Rice also dropped an easy pass
earlier in the game and made some poor route adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, a contrite Rice, labeling his conduct as
``unprofessional,'' apologized to Mariucci, his teammates and even
the media. Rice vowed that such a display will not be repeated, and
he probably will be overly conscious of that promise.
</P>
<P>
   While the tensions have subsided, some questions remain how a
player accustomed to being ``the man'' for his entire career will
react when required to be simply a mortal in an offense loaded with
other big-play performer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still going to look to Jerry in the clutch,''
quarterback Steve Young said. ``But we don't always have to look to
him now. It's a big change for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates and coaches privately acknowledge that even if it has
been difficult for him to share the load with Stokes and Owens,
simply toting the weight of having been the premier playmaker in
NFL history is every bit as burdensome. Stokes and Owens blossomed
as a tandem last year after knee surgery caused Rice to miss all
but two games.
</P>
<P>
   His individual brilliance and the expectations that accompany
it, some veterans noted, might be too much for any 36-year-old
player to live up to. Not surprisingly, Rice doesn't agree that his
past accomplishments represent a now-unattainable benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   If his reputation not only precedes him but also follows him
around like a lost puppy, it won't help him a bit on Sunday
afternoons, Rice insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cornerbacks still know I'm going to bust my rear end to
get open,'' Rice said. ``The work ethic isn't any different. If
anything, the past year made me work harder and has made me
appreciate things a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   The year began with Rice's wife barely surviving a difficult
pregnancy, which caused him to consider retirement seriously. Then
came the knee surgery in September, when he was injured in the
season opener at Tampa Bay. He became the first player to return in
the same calendar year from reconstructive surgery, but the
groundbreaking rehabilitation was ruined when Rice sustained a
broken kneecap in December, and he missed the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months after the second injury, Rice still bristles at
suggestions _ including one by former 49ers coach Bill Walsh _ that
his hasty return was ill-advised. Clearly, though, it was born in
part by Rice's ego. His physical prowess largely overshadows that
ego, but it's still a major part of what motivates Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Once, for example, he complained, with racial overtones, that he
was underappreciated _ after a Super Bowl victory in which he won
MVP honors. Despite his league-record 177 touchdowns, he still begs
for the ball in the ``red zone.'' And while he holds every career
receiving mark, the tantrum in Washington hardly was the first time
he had chafed at not getting the ball enough.
</P>
<P>
   It has to be difficult being just one of the Niners' three
talented wide receivers instead of the player everyone else was
trying to complement. For example, in their breakout '97 season,
Stokes and Owens combined for 118 catches, 1,669 yards and 12
touchdowns; just three years ago, Rice had better numbers by
himself _ 122 receptions for 1,848 yards and 15 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   That he'll neverapproach such gaudy numbers again is the reality
Rice must reconcile himself to. The process, he said, is a work in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I've got to deal with,'' Rice said. ``Some days
I'll get mine, and some days they'll get theirs. For the good of
the team and my own sanity, it's just something I've got to work my
way through.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
