<SLUG> BC-STORM-KEYWEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Houseboat Row may be sunk
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY WEST _ The island's famed Houseboat Row nearly disappeared
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of fighting with city officials who wanted to
condemn the ragtag collection of vessels docked along Roosevelt
Boulevard on the ocean, residents returned Saturday to find all but
four of the 26 boats smashed against the sea wall or each other,
and listing badly. Structurally, these homes suffered the worst of
the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was going to be OK, but after that eye went over
I knew we were in trouble,'' said Dave Tinkler, whose boat, the
Tenacity, survived but took a beating when a neighboring boat blew
loose off its moorings.
</P>
<P>
   As the sky lightened Saturday, residents who sought shelter
during the daylong storm began wandering back.
</P>
<P>
   Even before they reached their boats, the road provided an
ominous warning: Up and down the road, seaweed and sand buried the
pavement. The sea wall crumbled at one point, washing debris and
concrete across four lanes. At the docks, houses barely floated in
a muck of debris. The back half of the My Home dipped underwater
and two boats flattened a sailboat between them. Another's roof was
torn off and dropped on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Brothers Buster and A.C. Busby arrived to find Buster's dinghy
tossed onto the road. They sank his 32-foot Georgia Pearl before
the storm, hoping it would fare better underwater than above.
Because winds and surf continued to pound the shore Saturday, they
will have to wait to assess the damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been there since the 1960s,'' A.C. Busby said. ``Oh heck.
We'll just get it tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Halin, who lives aboard a 22-foot sailboat, parked his van
on the road and holed up inside so he could watch the boat from his
rear-view mirror during the storm. When it tilted up like a rocket,
he suspected trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just blew clear across the street,'' he said, pointing
toward a hotel where his boat sat in the yard.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet, Halin quickly realized his van was only a little
safer than the boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't do it again,'' he said. ``It got pretty hairy. It
tried to come off its wheels.''
</P>
<P>
   While Halin's van won't start, he said his boat looks unharmed
and will probably sail again if he can get a wrecker to carry it
back to Houseboat Row.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if there is a row after Saturday. Some residents
suspect officials will try to condemn the area now and permanently
remove the boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the politicians tried to do in 10 years, the storm did in
an hour,'' Tinkler said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
