</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Andruw focusing on playoffs, not steals
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Unless Andruw Jones finds a way to steal three bases
today, his quest to become baseball's youngest player with 30 home
runs and 30 steals will fall short.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be nice but if it doesn't happen, it doesn't happen,''
Jones said. ``If I had run more early, right now I wouldn't have
this kind of problem. I just got to let it go and look forward to
trying next season.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, whose two-run double with the bases loaded in the sixth
broke open the Braves' 4-0 win, has completed a late push that far
surpassed a bunch of stolen bases. He is hitting .301 with 15
homers and 35 RBIs the last two months. His defense should bring
him his first Gold Glove.
</P>
<P>
   But factoring in his 11 steals in the last 31 games brought his
season an historic tinge. At 21 years and five months, he enters
the final game of the year with 31 homers and 27 steals. The
youngest 30-30 man in baseball history is Seattle's Alex Rodriguez,
who was 23 years, two months when he reached the 30-30 July 19 this
season (and has since reached 42 homers with 45 steals).
</P>
<P>
   Hence, Jones has another shot at Rodriguez's record next year.
He also wants to raise his average. He takes a .274 average into
the last day, a number affected by his 127 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you the truth, I can be a .300 hitter,'' he said.
``It's hard when you start in a slump with such a low batting
average (.196 after 29 games) and try to come all the way up. If I
had started with a huge season, I probably would have kept (his
average) up that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care,'' he said. ``What matters is the World Series.
That's what I want this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Burp
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Norm Charlton gave the club a scare Saturday when
trainer Jeff Porter had to scurry to the mound after one batter in
the ninth. No injury. Just flu. Charlton called to the dugout when
he momentarily thought he was going to get sick on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wouldn't have bothered me either,'' Charlton said with a
shrug. But he had to leave the game suffering from what Porter
called a 24-hour flu. Kerry Ligtenberg came on to finish the game.
Charlton, with one run allowed in his last 12 appearances, remains
in competition with rookie Odalis Perez for a second left-hander's
spot on the postseason roster.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart fine, thank you
</P>
<P>
   Keith Lockhart reported no discomfort in his right hamstring the
morning following his first start in two weeks, and then played the
final three innings Saturday without incident. He tested the injury
twice on fielding plays Friday and quickly allayed some of the
club's fears about his readiness for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some sprint-type stuff but the only way to play it
was aggressively,'' Lockhart said. ``So I ran and just held my
breath and really felt fine. I was happy with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no one in the park was more surprised than he was with
his fifth-inning homer, Lockhart's ninth of the season. It carried
over the 390-foot mark at the Braves bullpen, the deepest point of
right field. The second baseman was more than puzzled when the
homer was announced as 388 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did it hit (right fielder Butch) Huskey in the head and bounce
over? At least give me 390,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael's rib
</P>
<P>
   Mike Cather visited the clubhouse Saturday morning, nearly 2 1/2
weeks after a three-inch section of his first rib was surgically
removed to free a blocked artery that was restricting blood flow to
his right arm. The condition, called thorasic outlet syndrome,
should be corrected to allow Cather, whose 2.39 ERA led all Braves
relievers in 1997, to be ready for spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Shipped to Richmond last July 15 after allowing 13 hits in eight
appearances, Cather began experiencing numbness in his arm lasting
up to 40 minutes after he would pitch. He could not even make a
fist after coming out of games. Tests done last month determined
the first rib placed enough pressure on the artery when he came to
a set position to cut off circulation for three to four seconds to
his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there was a lot of scar tissue around the artery that
had attached to the rib,'' Cather said. ``It was worse than they
thought it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Farm business
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have dropped Eugene (Ore.) as their short-season
Class A farm club and have signed a two-year agreement with the
Jamestown (N.Y.) Jammers of the New York-Penn League. Like Eugene,
Jamestown, an affiliate of the Detroit Tigers for the last five
years, plays a 74-game low-Class A schedule. The Braves had been
affiliated with Eugene since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
