<HEADER>
A6438 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-SIDEBAR27-     09-26 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-SIDEBAR27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It isn't over, even when it's over
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- On the door to the Braves clubhouse at Turner Field,
there is posted a letter on Time Warner stationery.
``Congratulations on winning the National League East Division
Championship,'' it reads. ``I'm proud of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Turner signed it, and it's nearly two weeks old. Now it's
about time for another mash note from the boss, for winning 105
games and setting a new record for all Braves, back through the
days of the Bees, Doves, Beaneaters and all the other monikers
they've gone by. One record they don't want was set in 1935. Those
Braves lost 115 games. The next year they changed their name to
Bees, but the losing went on.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward here to the ninth inning Saturday. Todd Hundley of
the New York Mets, pinch-hitting, swings at a third strike, becomes
the 27th out. The 161st game of the season is over. The Braves have
won, 4-0. Bobby Valentine stands at the dugout railing, transfixed,
looking up at the fireworks belching out of the oversized Coca-Cola
bottle in left field. It had been a day of dry throat, a lot of
nervous swallowing, spitting cotton, for viewing with concern. It
wasn't the official end, but if you peered hard, you could see the
dark at the end of the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   This was no time for a losing streak, but this was the Mets'
fourth in a row. The little manager had gone to his best. His ace,
Al Leiter. Seventeen-game winner, third best earned-run average in
the league. For three innings, he was perfect. By the sixth inning,
he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine kept making moves. By the time shadows fell across the
field, he had used nearly everybody on his side but Jay Horowitz,
the Mets nonathletic media director, but he could change nothing.
The Braves got to Leiter for three runs in the sixth, the Mets
couldn't make a dent in the five pitchers Bobby Cox marched in and
out. It was like spring training, or more likely, a postseason
tryout camp. Cox started his only 20-game winner, Tom Glavine, but
true to the game plan, by the sixth inning, Glavine was gone,
leaving a shutout behind. That's the way it goes with this crazy
game these days. The hell with individual records, call in ``Iron
Mike'' if he can win.
</P>
<P>
   It's some kind of luxury for a manager when he can go to the
bullpen for relief from 17- and 15-game winners, Kevin Millwood and
Denny Neagle. It was pure irony that Neagle should have been the
winning pitcher. For a stretch last summer, try as hard as he
might, he became ``Losing Pitcher'' Neagle. Started 14 times and
lost 10. This time, he walked in from the bullpen, pitched two easy
innings and won his 16th. Sometimes the gods don't make sense.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the Braves offense was the Jones offense. Chipper
knocked in the first run with a neat little single, Andruw knocked
in the next two with a ripping double into the left field corner.
Javier Lopez added the fourth with his 34th home run, and a story
goes with that.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez had come to bat twice with the bases loaded. The first
time, he popped up to John Olerud. The second time, he struck out.
He comes up the last time with nobody on and hits it out. Like I
say, sometimes the gods don't make sense.
</P>
<P>
   That touches on the case of the other catcher, the vaunted Mike
Piazza. This is your pick-up guy in the batting order. When nobody
else can get it done, look to this ``Iron Mike.'' He was as futile
as Lopez. Came to bat with two Mets on and waved weakly at a third
strike. Came up again with the bases loaded. This could have ripped
it, but he punched a little floater to Gerald Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing for the Braves now but a little fun. Well, not so fast
there. ``We've still got a lot to get done,'' said Cox, winner of
105 games in 1998. Some managers are never happy unless they have a
crisis they can create.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
