<SLUG> BC-FBC-CLASSIC27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rattlers survive 5 turnovers to beat Tennessee State 31-23
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The showdown between Florida A&AMP;M and Tennessee State
in the 10th annual Atlanta Football Classic at the Georgia Dome
Saturday evening was characterized by turnovers for one team, and
penalties and missed opportunities by the other.
</P>
<P>
   It also included a total of 89 passes and 980 yards total
offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Rattlers of FAMU (3-1), who turned the ball over five times
in the first half, managed to overcome their mistakes to post their
eighth straight victory over TSU (1-2), this one by a margin of
31-23 before a record Classic crowd of 51,726.
</P>
<P>
   That figure exceeded by 4,323 the number that watched these
teams play in the Classic at Bobby Dodd Stadium in '89.
</P>
<P>
   FAMU was not assured of victory in this fifth meeting in Atlanta
until a pass by Tigers' quarterback Leon Murray was tipped away
from junior receiver Corey Sullivan in the end zone with 31 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   Senior wideout Tariq Qaiyim, who had been in Rattlers coach
Billy Joe's doghouse after he dropped two TDs in FAMU's 21-14
opening loss to Hampton, helped deliver victory with fourth-quarter
touchdown receptions of 26 and 31 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's out of the doghouse now,'' Joe said.
</P>
<P>
   With FAMU ahead 17-10, Qaiyim caught his first TD pass thrown by
game MVP Pat Bonner. After TSU had narrowed the gap to 7 again as a
result of an 85-yard pass from Murray to Sullivan, Qaiyim caught
the clincher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I redeemed myself. It was blessing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   TSU forced five turnovers in the first 25 minutes, but failed to
fully capitalize on them. In large measure, that was because of a
rash of penalties. In all, the Tigers were flagged 21 times for 165
yards. Two penalties were levied against the same player after he
removed his helmet following TSU touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to blame anyone (for all of the penalties),''
Tigers coach L.C. Cole said. ``We've got to look at ourselves. But
I take my hat off to this team because it didn't quit. We're still
building, so we'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe, who called Cole's team ``one of the fastest improving team
in I-AA,'' knew that when the Tigers failed to take advantage of
the Rattlers' mistakes they were in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five turnovers in the first half, we should've been down by 40
points,'' Joe said. ``But instead of being behind, we were leading
at half (14-10). I knew all we had to do was settle down.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the penalties and the subsequent scoring
opportunities that went by the board for TSU, the Tigers had a
chance to tie it. They narrowed the gap to the final margin when
senior receiver Tyrone Butterfield caught a pass that was touched
five times in the end zone with 4:33 remaining,
</P>
<P>
   But Murray's pass to Sullivan in the end zone with less than a
minute left was tipped away.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
