<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    San Francisco poses key test for Falcons
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Don't look at it as a football game, but as a
game of King of the Mountain. That's how the Atlanta Falcons are
approaching today's game against the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   To get to the top of the NFC West, they've got to knock off the
king _ the team that's won 13 of 17 division titles and five Super
Bowls since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   It's great Atlanta has won eight of 10 games since last year's
1-7 start. A first-ever win at Carolina on opening day was
fabulous. The team's first 2-0 start since 1986? That's wonderful,
too.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact the Falcons have beaten three of the other four
teams in their division since Dan Reeves took over as coach last
year, their 5-2 record against New Orleans, St. Louis and Carolina,
nothing is validated until Atlanta slays the big dog _ the 49ers
(2-0).
</P>
<P>
   ``They got something we want,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   And to get it, ``We've got to go through San Francisco,'' said
quarterback Chris Chandler. ``Everyone knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking won't get it done, not against a team averaging 530.5
yards. Not against a team that has beaten the Falcons six straight
times here by an average score of 43-16.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the running game will have get going early. The
Falcons are ranked 27th in the NFL in rushing, averaging 85.5 yards
per game. They're averaging 22.5 yards in the first half. Try that
today, and it may be over by halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll take everything we've got; you've got to concentrate
every single play,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons aren't quite looking at this game as do-or-die. They
know they must beat San Francisco sooner or later. They'll try
today, but if it doesn't work out, the 'Niners come to Atlanta Nov.
15.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win, we've come a long ways,'' Reeves said. ``If we
lose, it's not the end of the season. What I'm looking for is ...to
see if we've closed any ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
