<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Something about Edisto Island
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edisto Island, S.C. _ Don't go to Edisto Beach State Park
looking for amusement parks or people dressed in funny clothing
driving golf carts.
</P>
<P>
   It's a peaceful paradise for stressed-out folks who need a
vacation according to Webster's definition: freedom from any
activity; rest; respite; intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Few vacation destinations offer any of the above these days.
</P>
<P>
   That mouse place in Orlando specializes in long lines. Most
beach resorts come with traffic, mobs on the sand and T-shirt shops
every few steps. Other camping locations usually involve frantic
travel to tourist sites.
</P>
<P>
   Not Edisto. The town doesn't even have a McDonald's because
there aren't enough people around during the offseason to support
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't trip over Edisto,'' said Rob Achenberg,
superintendant of Edisto Beach State Park. ``It's definitely a
destination-point vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   The island, 45 minutes south of Charleston, is roughly 14 miles
by 21 miles, most of it uninhabited, with seven miles of beach.
It's 19 miles from S.C. 174 and another 20 or 30 from I-95.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the 100-plus campsites are booked solid nearly year-round,
and it is one of the few state parks anywhere that is
self-supporting. Edisto's major product is peace and quiet. In some
ways, the state-park beach of more than one mile resembles
Cumberland Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look north, you look south, and you don't see
high-rises,'' Achenberg said. ``Basically, you're alone. Maybe
you'll see some loggerhead turtle tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   A midweek crowd in September numbered about 10 along the park's
beach. A couple could stroll along, look back and see only two
pairs of tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Night beach walks are even better. The pollution-free sky is
ablaze with stars never seen in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Sea shells can be found in piles on the beach and are
intermingled with fossils. It's a collector's heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Anglers love it because of the variety of fish available from
the Atlantic and salt marsh creeks.
</P>
<P>
   One such angler is Tom Thompson, 66, a retired U.S. Army master
sergeant from Aiken, S.C. Thompson spends a lot of time at Edisto,
sometimes with his wife and sometimes ``batching'' it on a fishing
trip.
</P>
<P>
   On this trip, he was catching a lot of shrimp, some sea trout, a
redfish or two, and explaining some of the park's uniqueness.
</P>
<P>
   Being on a barrier island, Edisto's state park isn't
particularly neat and manicured like many inland ones.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of sand and a sparsity of grass. The grass that
does grow looks a lot like what would be weeds back home.
</P>
<P>
   Palmetto fronds litter the ground, which could look sloppy, but
there's a purpose. Cutting firewood is prohibited, and all campers
seem to want a campfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of buying wood at the camp store, why not burn
palmetto fronds?'' Thompson asks.
</P>
<P>
   And enjoy something that is becoming as rare as diamonds rest,
respite and intermission, doing nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
