</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Hamilton in element
</P>
<P>
   By Tom McCollister
</P>
<P>
   STAFF WRITER
</P>
<P>
   MARTINSVILLE, Va. _ If there were a briar patch for race-car
drivers, as there is for B'rer Rabbit, Bobby Hamilton would head
straight for Martinsville Speedway. It's not his favorite track on
the Winston Cup circuit, but he's always felt comfortable there.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton goes to Martinsville believing thatwhen you go to a
track like this one you run well. You're always around at the end
and with a lot of brakes left. Always the sign of a good car and
driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It boosts your confidence level to know you're going there
with that caliber of race car,'' Hamilton said. ``It makes you feel
like things are a little easier.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where he cruised to victory in April's Goody's 500,
starting from the pole and leading 377 of the 500 laps. And it's
where, since 1995, he's finished fourth or better in every race.
</P>
<P>
   Since his perfect run here in April, however, Hamilton hasn't
found another Martinsville. He surprised all with a second-place
finish at Sears Point, but he has no other top-fives in the last 10
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've struggled some in qualifying this year, had some
opportunities to win if we'd qualified better,'' team owner Larry
McClure said. ``We went through a crew-chief change, hiring Charley
Pressley, and we're excited about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby gave us back-to-back top-10s at Richmond (sixth) and
Dover (10th), and I'm looking for us to have some success over the
last seven races. All these race tracks we're going to, Bobby has
won three of them before coming to us, and we've won at the other
two (with Sterling Marlin). I think we're moving in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's immediate goal is to finish in the top 10 in points,
and winning one of the last seven events would be welcome, although
not expected.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton is primed for today's NAPA 500, but he's looking longer
term. A new car has been built for the back-to-back
restrictor-plate races at Talladega and Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like 'em,'' Hamilton said about restrictor plate races.
``That's one of the big reasons I wanted to come to this team. I
knew the success of this race team. I'm labeled a short-track,
flat-track driver, and I hate it. I want to win Daytona and
Talladega. I know that this is the race team that can do it for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get in a pressure standpoint when you're running
back-to-back like that, but it doesn't bother me whatsoever.
Another thing that comes into play is the (Winston Cup) points
deal. It's not going to be like the races were earlier in the
season. I'm hopping it will be a smarter race because of the points
battle and people won't (be) as wild and tear up as much stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But first there's Martinsville, whose points count as much as
those at Daytona and Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be as good at Martinsville as I was last time,'' Hamilton
said. ``But I look for two or three others to be better than they
were. We haven't had a bad year. We haven't had that many top-10s,
but we came close to winning a road course, and we won a race.
We've just got to get it consistent. ``It's important for me for
two reasons,'' he said. ``It's important for all the people on the
race team. They had not a terrible year last year, but it certainly
wasn't the year that caliber race team should have. So, it's
important for me to do that for the guys and everybody that works
on the car and anybody that has anything to do with the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
