<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR Notebook
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTON CUP
</P>
<P>
   Mattei, Bodine split as partners
</P>
<P>
   Jim Mattei and Geoff Bodine have ended their partnership. Mattei
purchased Bodine's remaining ownership in the team, but Bodine
apparently will stick around for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a positive move,'' Mattei said. ``I'm excited about
Geoff being able to focus exclusively on driving and continuing to
achieve the level of performance that he has the past few weeks.
With seven races left, we still have an opportunity to make our
presence felt in the Winston Cup series.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodine views the partnership break as a relief. ``A lot of
things have gone on with this team during the past four-plus years
_ some really good, some not so good,'' Bodine said.
``Relinquishing my ownership of the team helps put the negative
things behind me and will enable me to concentrate on driving and
working with the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodine currently ranks 28th in the Winston Cup driver standings.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Steve Grissom and team owner Larry Hedrick have agreed to split.
David Green will drive the No. 41 Chevrolet today. ... Mike Skinner
has improved 10 places to 25th in the points standings. ... Dale
Earnhardt spoke at Martinsville High School earlier this week,
leaving them with this message: ``I encourage all of you to stay in
school and continue your education beyond high school. I regret to
this day not finishing school.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSCH
</P>
<P>
   Big dividends
</P>
<P>
   Elton Sawyer's late-season charge to fourth in the points race
has brought dividends. Akins-Sutton Motorsports will operate a
two-car team with former rookie of the year Glenn Allen working
with Sawyer, beginning with the season-opening race at Daytona.
Sawyer's team will remain intact with crew chief Eddie Pardue.
Allen will have a new crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great. More is going to be better,'' said Sawyer, who
has been driving for his current team since it was formed in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   The Busch series will resume next week at Charlotte for the All
Pro Bumper To Bumper 300. ... Lysol will end its five-year
sponsorship of Hensley Racing at the end of the season. Casey
Atwood replaces Tracy Leslie as the driver until then. ... Jay Guy
has replaced Bobby Guilbranson as crew chief for Hermie Stadler and
DeWalt Tools. ... Stat of the week: Matt Kenseth, Randy LaJoie and
Buckshot Jones are the only Busch drivers who have been in the top
10 every week since the Daytona season opener. ... Dale Earnhardt
Jr. leads in six of seven statistical categories.
</P>
<P>
   CRAFTSMAN TRUCK
</P>
<P>
   Chasing Sprague
</P>
<P>
   Jack Sprague's fourth-place payoff of $20,450 in last week's Ram
Tough 200 makes the Michigan native the first driver to win more
than $2 million in the Craftsman Truck series. Going into the NAPA
250 at Martinsville, his total earnings were $2,001,588. And he
could have company soon. Ron Hornaday went into Saturday's race
only $39,203 behind Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Racing has released its driver, Cintas rookie Wayne
Anderson, replacing him with Bryan Reffner. Team owner Jim Herrick
says several drivers will get a look-see before a permanent
replacement is named for the 1999 season. ... Three trucks were
impounded by NASCAR after the Ram 200 and transported to the wind
tunnel in Marietta, where ongoing aerodynamic evaluation was to be
held. Trucks selected were those of Jimmy Hensley, Hornaday and Tom
Hubert. ... Greg Biffle and Andy Houston remained 1-2 in Rookie of
the Year race going to Martinsville.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
