</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDS-EXPOS-MCGWIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE STANDS ALONE, FOR THE MOMENT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ While some fans held hands and closed their eyes
like participants in a seance, and others gnawed straws to tatters,
Mark McGwire stepped into the batter's box at Busch Stadium
Saturday as if it were an isolation booth.
</P>
<P>
   Oblivious to the wrecked nerves around him, cut off from a
nation engrossed by every swing of his rapturous home-run race with
the Chicago Cubs' Sammy Sosa, McGwire coolly delivered his 67th
home run of the season in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   And in a surreal encore, McGwire sliced through the pressure
again 90 minutes later for his 68th home run.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire forcefully separated himself from a tie with Sosa, who
remained at 66 after failing to homer in Houston Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Peering through his contact lenses, McGwire tends to lose sight
of his home runs. But once he saw the masses lunge toward each ball
_ one that went 403 feet to left, and one that skyrocketed 435 feet
to center _ McGwire shook his fist.
</P>
<P>
   The lead in the race for home-run immortality was his and his
alone _ at least for now. With just one day remaining in the
regular season, barring a wild-card playoff involving the Cubs, the
redhead with a body as solid as a silo distanced himself from his
good friend Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously this feels nice, but I've got one more day and so
does he,'' McGwire said after the Cardinals lost, 7-6, to the Expos
despite his three runs batted in. ``I think he's got bigger things
on his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The National League wild card is at stake for the Cubs. If the
Cubs are in a tie for that final playoff position after Sunday's
games, Sosa would play one additional game that would count in his
regular season statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing I can do about that,'' McGwire said. ``I'll be
home on the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire cannot wait to dip his toes in the Pacific. Although he
will hold on to this precious season like a loved one, he is
understandably drained. That was visible as McGwire sat before a
table of microphones after the game, and discussed the strain he
and Sosa have had to endure this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure has been unbelievable,'' McGwire said. ``I've yet
to tap into what this season has really been like. I've had to
concentrate harder than I've ever had to concentrate before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people understand how difficult it is to do what
Sammy and I have done. Once we both went to 62, everyone wanted
more. Then it was like, `Well, they've gone two or three days
without a home run. What's wrong with them?'''
</P>
<P>
   The Montreal pitching staff can attest to the fact that there's
nothing amiss with McGwire. He put away his ninth two-homer game of
the season by crushing a first-pitch fastball by Dustin Hermanson
in the fourth inning, and a 1-1 sinker by reliever Kirk Bullinger
in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a good pitch to most human beings,'' Bullinger said.
``But that's why he's a superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   A reluctant one, though. McGwire seemed almost embarrassed when
a horde of fans _ resembling rock-star groupies _ hung over a
railing just above the room where their beloved slugger was
talking. They cried out, ``I love you, Mark,'' and ``Don't let it
end.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday it will end, at least for McGwire. But he has not let
the curtain fall on this season without a rousing finale. It took
McGwire less than 24 hours to one-up and then two-up Sosa. After
being tied at 65 for two days this past week, Sosa hit his 66th on
Friday night, a home run that was followed 45 minutes later by
McGwire's 66th. The synchronized swings were mind-boggling, ``with
no way to explain it,'' McGwire said.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, beneath a cap with a cartoon frog on it, McGwire
just raised his eyebrows and smiled a smile of disbelief. It is the
modesty and down-to-earth nature of both McGwire and Sosa that has
allowed the country to enjoy this unforgettable season with them.
So many people like both men so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you can't go wrong, can you?'' McGwire said. ``I just
want everyone to have fun this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   And so they have. Horns honked, and people cheered in the
streets long after Saturday's game was over. For now, their
resident icon's place in history seems safe with his total at 68,
but they have seen Sosa deliver multiple home runs himself. One
more game remains for McGwire and Sosa, with few believing this
race is over just yet.
</P>
<P>
   That looming unease has created an unsettling thought for some
St. Louis fans: What if it ends and all McGwire has is the video of
him breaking Roger Maris' record, the glorious memories of a
special season, and the '62 Corvette given to him by the team? What
if the history books are engraved with Sosa's name, leaving McGwire
as the celebrated footnote?
</P>
<P>
   Just the thought of it makes Tony La Russa reach for an antacid.
There is no hidden agenda for La Russa, the Cardinals' manager. He
is a homer about homers, and has been brazenly honest about his
feelings regarding McGwire's pursuit of the home-run title: the
most glamorous record in baseball should belong to McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always scary when you want something so bad,'' La Russa
said. ``Because it just means that if it doesn't happen, you get
really disappointed. And I think there's a certain amount of
justice to Mark being the home run king and Sammy being the m.v.p.
Sammy's got enough. But this game is about the lack of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   These kind of visceral reactions have been common as this
home-run chase comes to an end, because each player means so much
to those who know them personally. The swirl around McGwire and
Sosa has not affected either man's focus. As always, McGwire is the
one person who has kept his composure and hung tight to perspective
as the tension has built around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Sammy and I have done, whoever is on top, nobody should
be disappointed,'' McGwire said. ``How can you walk away
disappointed if you walk away one below? You can't. It's
impossible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
