<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PURPLE-HEART-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURPLE HEART WILL SOOTHE A VIETNAM VET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The ceremony may be 28 years late, but at
noon Saturday the United States officially recognized Norman Humes'
sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   The 49-year-old Kansas City man received a Purple Heart medal at
the Vietnam Veterans Memorial. He earned the honor because shrapnel
from a mortar tore into his leg in 1970 during combat.
</P>
<P>
   But, as is the case with so much from the Vietnam War, the story
of Humes' medal isn't a simple one, and the happy ending is tinged
with bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   It's a story that began on a crisp morning in December 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Humes was one of a group of soldiers out trying to shore up
American bunkers with timber along a hill in the demilitarized zone
called Alpha 4.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers thinking more about the need to get the bunkers
patched up before the next attack than when that attack might come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had been pretty quiet that morning,'' he said. But the
morning silence was soon broken.
</P>
<P>
   First he heard ``the `thwump, thwump, thwump' of the mortars
being dropped into the tubes.'' He knew enemy mortars would soon
begin exploding all around him.
</P>
<P>
   Humes began screaming for men to head toward the damaged
bunkers. Still, the mortar fire continued, thwump, thwump, 18 times
in all.
</P>
<P>
   Humes was one of three soldiers who didn't made it to a bunker
before the mortars landed. The jagged piece of metal that tore into
the knee came from one that exploded 50 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me,'' he says now, a slight laugh punctuating the
statement, ``I kept on running. I may have been limping pretty
good, but I planned on making it to that bunker.''
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived, a medic bandaged him and said he'd probably get
a Purple Heart. During the rest of his service, others agreed. His
discharge papers listed a Purple Heart as one of his honors. The
medal is awarded to U.S. service personnel for wounds received in
action against an enemy.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't really worry about picking up the medal until 1990,
when he and a friend were picking through a box of old Army
memories. The friend suggested he consider mounting and framing his
awards. That's when Humes realized he didn't have his Purple Heart.
</P>
<P>
   So Humes sent for his medal. He was surprised when a letter came
back informing him he wasn't due one. He started checking around
and got the same answer, again and again.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, in the endless paperwork from his military
service, a clerk had neglected to check a single box.
</P>
<P>
   He asked for the medal. They denied him. He appealed. They
denied. He appealed again. Denied.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote U.S. senators and representatives asking for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I got back were letters telling how committed they were to
veterans' rights,'' he said. ``They owed this to me, but I couldn't
convince anyone....I was really bitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Then one day he ran into Tom Wyrsch, who runs U.S. Rep. Karen
McCarthy's Independence office.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people had ignored him, but I figured he was coming
to us as a last resort, and I owed it to him to look into his
problem,'' Wyrsch said.
</P>
<P>
   He got Humes' military records. It didn't take much study.
</P>
<P>
   ``I highlighted the records in yellow and sent them back to be
investigated,'' he said. ``It wasn't too long before we heard there
didn't need to be any more review. Norman was owed a Purple
Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   So Humes, whose knee still gives him pain occasionally, returned
to the memorial, 42nd Street and Broadway, Saturday for his medal.
He goes there often anyway, to heal and remember those who died and
suffered and to heal some of his own wounds. Sadly, he says, the
fight for his medal is now one of those wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be glad to get it finally,'' he said Friday. ``But we
were forgotten so often in the past, for so many things. I'm still
bitter that it took so much effort. But I am glad to know that
there are still people around who do care.''
</P>
</TEXT>
