<HEADLINE>
MARCHING BAND TRIES TO SET A RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM BAXTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It began, like so many marches, before dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Backpacks littered the tarmac, supplies were hastily allocated
and innocent faces _ much too young for the grueling ordeal ahead _
looked to their leaders for order in the confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with a prayer, they tuned their instruments and began to
march into the early morning fog. It was 4:21 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   About 18 hours later, the teens in the Maranatha Academy
marching band met their goal: breaking the world's record for the
longest musical march.
</P>
<P>
   A blowhorn sounded about 10:30 p.m., followed by an announcement
that the group had surpassed the previous world record of 50 miles.
They stopped shortly after 11 p.m., having marched for nearly 19
hours and 52 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The 20 remaining marchers from an original cast of 78 were
greeted with a mixture of applause, flashing cameras and waiting
arms as they crossed the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm exhausted and excited,'' said Melissa Bridges, who carried
her school's banner. ``And I _ I can't feel my legs.''
</P>
<P>
   The students had trained for months for the march, completing
22- and 33-mile practice hikes earlier in the year, but Friday
still held a few surprises, including unexpected cloudbursts in the
morning and a deep, muggy heat as the day stretched on.
</P>
<P>
   By 10 a.m. the medics in the first-aid tent had helped the first
few troupers who just couldn't take another step.
</P>
<P>
   The band played on.
</P>
<P>
   Hour after hour they slogged along a three-mile route around the
Great Mall of the Great Plains in Olathe, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine what walking 50 miles is like?'' parent Ed
Hamil said. ``I walked around with them once and I was beat.''
</P>
<P>
   The students didn't carry sheet music, so a short repertoire of
about a half-dozen songs had been memorized, including ``Hot
Shot,'' ``Energize!'' and ``Trailblazer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be groaners the rest of the year,'' band director
Steve Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   For a while during thunderstorms Friday morning, students
marched inside the mall, but when the weather cleared, they were
back in the traffic loops circling the center.
</P>
<P>
   By 4 p.m., heat and injuries had decimated the squad, which had
shrunk from 78 students at the beginning to 27.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen students had to complete the march to set a new record.
</P>
<P>
   The bells students had carried in the morning to break the
monotony were long gone. Students complained the bells were banging
against them and bruising their legs.
</P>
<P>
   The wounded gathered around the first-aid tent, offering support
for the still-walking wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Gabbert, a junior, gave up when swelling in her ankles
became so bad she couldn't go on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still had all the energy in the world,'' she said. ``I
wanted to cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, like sophomore Chris Gharst, just had bad luck. Chris
said he was holding up well until he stepped in a pothole and
twisted his leg.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 27, sunburnt and sweaty, still had 20 miles to go
as they struggled in the late-afternoon heat. Olathe had a high of
88 degrees Friday afternoon. The heat index reached 97.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the band played on.
</P>
<P>
   The record was held by a Pennsylvania high school that marched
50.1 miles in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Maranatha band members had spent months collecting pledges,
hoping to raise $400,000. March organizers said a final pledge
count probably won't be made for a week or two, because pledges are
expected to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Maranatha Academy is a Christian school with campuses in Shawnee
and Kansas City, Kan. The band members were from the Shawnee
campus, and the money would go for new uniforms to replace the
outfits that had been purchased used 18 years ago, for larger band
facilities and for a trip to Washington for the July 4 celebrations
in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, the band director, had broken the record once before he
joined Maranatha seven years ago. In 1988, a Caney, Kan., marching
band he directed logged more than 37 miles and was noted in the
1990 edition of The Guinness Book of Records.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon made a few concessions Friday, dispensing with bass drums
and making other changes to ease the students' load, but Guinness
set most of the rules for the march:
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 students must be playing music throughout the march.
</P>
<P>
   Documentation through logs, mileage sheets, videotape and
testimonial letters must be kept.
</P>
<P>
   Marchers may take one five-minute break for every 60 minutes of
marching and playing.
</P>
<P>
   By 9:30 p.m., the number of marchers had dwindled to 20. They
marched under a half-moon, with cooler temperatures much welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the one time I get to yell,'' said Kelli Jackson, a
trumpet player. She dropped out after 28 miles when her ankles
swelled.
</P>
<P>
   Kelli, 12, cheered along with her father, Warren Jackson, a
doctor who helped give first aid to weary marchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're running on pure adrenalin,'' he said. ``They're going
to have lots of blisters after this.''
</P>
<P>
   One marcher, 13-year-old Philip Bailey, had to be pulled out of
line because his legs kept giving out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to leave,'' said Philip, leaning on a friend.
``I have really, really tired legs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
