<HEADLINE>
INFANT BODY FOUND ON CANAL BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX _ Police are searching for the woman who gave birth to a
baby girl, stuffed her in a plastic bag and left her to die on the
rocky banks of a canal.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A man walking his dog found the infant's body, umbilical cord
attached, amid garbage and broken beer bottles near the muddy water
of the Highline Canal, south of Central Avenue and Baseline Road in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The plastic bag that held her had been flapping open in the
wind. The body lay inside the bag on the rocky sand on the south
side of the canal. Sounds of passing cars drowned out the sound of
the west-running water.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe the baby was born late Friday or early Saturday.
They are investigating whether the baby was born dead, was killed,
or died after her mother left her in the plastic bag.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Officers spent the day talking with neighbors with homes near
the canal, but came no closer to finding the mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anybody around here who's pregnant,'' said Ruben
Lopez, 19, working on his car about 50 yards north of where the
infant was found.
</P>
<P>
   The canal is easily accessible from a neighborhood to the south,
and from a large apartment complex and neighborhood to the north.
</P>
<P>
   Police don't know if the mother walked or drove to the spot
where she left her baby.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fourth baby abandoned in Phoenix this year. She is
the first to die.
</P>
<P>
   The other three were given names by hospital nurses and placed
in the custody of Child Protectives Services or foster care.
</P>
<P>
   Baby Brandi was found in June, wrapped in a blanket under a tree
along the 7200 block of Indian School Road.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Baby Rachael was found in a trash container near
15th Avenue and Taylor Street.
</P>
<P>
   Also in November, Baby Jasmine, who was 2 or 3 days old, was
found inside a cardboard box outside a child-care center near 35th
and Dunlap avenues. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
