<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 U.S. `poor' pretty cozy, analyst says  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The good news this week was that the percentage of
poor Americans declined again last year, continuing a trend that
brought government's poverty and income numbers to their best
levels in almost a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The better news is that the situation for those on the lower
rungs of the ladder is probably better than the reported data
indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rector, senior policy analyst for welfare and poverty
issues at the Heritage Foundation, says the Census Bureau's annual
poverty report is inaccurate because it understates real incomes.
</P>
<P>
   In an analysis in /{The Wall Street Journal/} Rector argued his
case by comparing Census Bureau figures with the Commerce
Department's National Income and Product Accounts data. Rector said
Commerce Department accounting for 1996 shows aggregate national
personal income at $6.8 trillion, which included personal payment
of Social Security taxes. The Census Bureau's official definition
of income, however, showed the total at only $4.8 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Rector contends the Census Bureau missed $2 trillion in income,
which equates to about $20,000 for each household. While he
concedes that much of the ``missing income'' belongs to society's
middle and upper strata, ``a large slice is received by low-income
families as well.'' What's missing most significantly from the
poverty statistics, he says, is $500 billion in government
assistance to low-income and elderly households.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to what the yearly poverty report implies, Rector says,
most Americans defined as poor are generally ``better housed and
better fed and own more personal property than average Americans
throughout much of this century.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the numbers he uses to make his point are worth noting.
More than 40 percent of all poor households own their homes and
about three-quarters of a million of these households own homes
valued at more than $150,000. The average home has three bedrooms,
1 bathrooms, a garage and patio. The average poor American has a
third more living space than the average Japanese person and four
times as much as the average Russian.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of 10 officially poor households own cars and nearly three
in 10 own two cars. Nearly all have color television sets and half
have two color TVs. Three-quarters have video cassette recorders,
two-thirds have air-conditioning and microwave ovens, and half have
stereos.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is to suggest that life at the low end of the food
chain is beer and skittles for all, but rather to put things in
perspective. The very term ``poverty report'' conjures up images of
more than 35 million Americans living a life of struggle and
degradation.
</P>
<P>
   As this analysis emphasizes, however, everything is relative. A
poor person in America, for instance, would be the envy of a poor
person in Bangladesh. For that matter, many Americans officially
defined as poor today would be considered fairly well off by even
lower-middle-class Americans of 50 or 60 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line of Rector's thesis is that U.S. society is ill
served by official exaggerations of material deprivation. Society
should, he said, be focusing more on the behavioral problems
afflicting low-income Americans. If it did, he claims, it would
raise awareness of how increasing dependence on the modern welfare
state encourages dysfunctional and self-destructive behavior among
many low-income Americans.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; txr:/{Jerry Heaster's column appears Wednesday, Friday,
Saturday and Sunday. To share a comment, call/} {(816) 889-7827}
/{and enter/} {2301}. /{Send e-mail, including a telephone number,
to/} {jheaster &LR; kcstar.com}.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-98 2311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
