A6470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-CARIB1STLD-     09-26 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-CARIB </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE DOMINICANS ARE FEARED DEAD AS WATERS RECEDE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
 1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT  
 (SUBS to update and refine)   By JOSEPH B. TREASTER and RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic _ Four days after Hurricane
Georges clobbered the Dominican Republic with shattering force, and
as help arrives from around the world, this Caribbean country is
still counting its dead.
</P>
<P>
   With 200 confirmed deaths, government officials say they fear
that scores more lives may have been lost as blocks of homes were
splintered and the storm's rains flooded towns and villages in an
arc stretching as far as 100 miles from this capital city of 3
million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the flood waters recede, the bodies keep emerging,'' said
Adriano Tejada, the chief spokesman for President Leonel Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Saturday, helicopter rescue teams from the Dominican
military as well as from National Guard units from Puerto Rico
plucked survivors from the rooftops of submerged houses in heavily
flooded areas. Some of the wreckage was also being searched by dogs
specially trained to find bodies. In the capital, bulldozers shoved
broken trees into piles and squads of soldiers loaded debris into
dump trucks.
</P>
<P>
   A 10 p.m. curfew is in effect in the capital and is being
enforced by soldiers armed with rifles.
</P>
<P>
   The gray skies and howling wind of Hurricane Georges gave way
Saturday to the kind of brilliant blue sky flecked with wispy
cotton candy clouds that draws millions of tourists to the
Dominican Republic. But even such a glorious day could not lift the
spirits of many Dominicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dying of thirst,'' said Josefa Osuna, a 73-year-old
woman picking through the wreckage of her home on the east side of
Santo Domingo. ``We've lost everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The government estimates that more than 500,000 homes were
damaged and that more than 500 people were injured. Nearly 300,000
people are living in 700 emergency shelters. Thousands of acres of
sugar cane, coffee and tobacco, the country's main crops, have been
ruined. Clusters of people are camped along some of the main roads,
sharing food and trying to piece together what they can of their
broken homes.
</P>
<P>
   The capital is pocked with damage. Roofs are gone, windows
broken, and huge metal billboards with nothing left but the iron
frames line the roads. But almost magically, many houses and stores
appear to have been virtually untouched. Everywhere, though, trees
and shrubs have been snapped off, shredded and sometimes uprooted.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Ventura, the mayor of Santo Domingo and a popular
merengue singer with a big following among Dominican emigres in the
United States, said it was difficult to put a price on the damage
in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not quantified the damage,'' he said. ``It's
enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   In a flight over one of the most severely battered cities, San
Pedro de Macoris, about 30 miles east of here, clumps of wood and
tin houses looked as if they had been smashed by an angry giant.
Scores of other houses had been turned into what from the air
looked like rows of tiny doll houses with their roofs lifted off.
</P>
<P>
   A huge sugar mill lost all but a few strips of tin from its roof
and at the Tetelo Vargas Stadium, where the Estrellas Orientales
(Oriental Stars) play the nation's favorite pastime, baseball,
racks of spotlights dangled into the bleachers and much of the tin
sun shade was gone.
</P>
<P>
   While rescue teams were trying to reach people in outlying
areas, the streets of the capital were jammed Saturday with cars
and trucks snaking past downed power lines, trees and heaps of
roofing and rubble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first day that people have really been able to
move,'' said Leonardo Luzon, 44, whose house lost its roof and an
outside wall. ``Now people are out looking for building supplies
and food.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the country of eight million people has been without
electricity since the hurricane hit on Tuesday, and with no power
to operate pumps, drinking water has been in short supply. At least
12 men, women and teen-agers were lined up with plastic jugs and
pails at a water hose at one house on the edge of the capital at
midday. Others made their way through the wreckage balancing
buckets of water on their heads.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster stirred human misery and cruelty. Julio Romero, a
handyman whose tiny home on the outskirts of Santo Domingo was
destroyed, had in recent days collected a pile of lumber and cinder
blocks to begin rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   But the other night, as he slept with neighbors who put him up,
thieves made off with the material he had collected.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are evil, but they are clever,'' Romero said. ``They prey
on those of us who are suffering, and that's how they survive.''
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor, Dolores Santos, echoed those thoughts as she
surveyed the heap of wood beams, glass, tables and chairs that was
once her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thieves have taken everything,'' she said screaming. ``They
took TV's, wood, whatever worthwhile that was left. How can people
do this to each other?''
</P>
<P>
   Mothers and children wandered the edges of the capital like
nomads.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica Suna led her 5-year-old son by the hand as they walked
over to survey the damage to their four-room home. Almost in tears,
she looked at the child, who was barefoot and wearing only blue
shorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing left,'' she said. ``Look at my child. How will
I take care of him?''
</P>
<P>
   At Las Americas International Airport here Saturday morning, an
American Airlines passenger jet from Miami had just unloaded a
cargo of food, gasoline-powered generators, lumber and disposable
diapers as another big jet with relief supplies was landing from
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the communications equipment at the airport was knocked
out by the storm, keeping the runways closed until Friday when
jetliners arrived from Panama and Venezuela. Four small
propeller-driven commuter planes flew in with passengers from
nearby Puerto Rico. Saturday morning, several small charter planes
arrived with journalists from Miami and Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of vacationers hunkered down in hotels in the
Dominican Republic as the hurricane ripped through. They were
particularly relieved that the airport had reopened and some of
them were beginning to leave for home Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   At the airport the storm had tossed two big planes together like
broken toys. It also smashed windows at the terminal and flattened
a forest flanking the airfield.
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday morning, the airport was beginning to hum again. In
the main passenger arrivals terminal, broken ceiling tiles still
littered the polished terrazzo floor. But immigration officials
were quietly processing the papers of the new arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   In Haiti, the death toll from Hurricane Georges has increased to
94 as about 60 other people are missing and feared dead, the
interior ministry said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti, which shares the island of Hispaniola with the Dominican
Republic, has been afflicted with extensive flooding, particularly
in the central plateau and the Artibonite Valley, after almost
every river in the country overflowed, officials said. The
hurricane has also left more than 100,000 homeless and seriously
injured dozens as it destroyed at least 6,000 homes and many acres
of crops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
