<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. NEWT CASTS THE FIRST STONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, some ol' boys was gathered around the rock pile back
in Washington, D.C., when a honkin' big chunk a nastiness went
flying over everybody and whacked Billy Boy Clinton upside his
head.
</P>
<P>
   The craggy stone of an insult was hurled by none other than Newt
Gingrich, speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives, who upped
and called the president a ``misogynist.''
</P>
<P>
   With all the smut getting printed in the papers lately, some
folks might figure ``misogyny'' has something to do with spreading
Crisco on your back and getting a rubdown. But, no.
</P>
<P>
   Pure and simple, it means ``woman-hater.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Gingrich called Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of name-calling going on lately, mostly by men who
don't remember the lessons they learned on the schoolyard. For
instance, when some loudmouth starts putting you down, you say,
``I'm rubber and you're glue, whatever you say bounces off me and
sticks on you.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, congressional candidate Newt Gingrich sent
out a flyer about his female Democratic opponent. In it, the
Gingrich camp said if the voters elected a woman, she would have to
break up her family in order to move to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Still, according to Newt, Clinton's the woman-hater. &QL; 
BAD TIMING
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after getting elected to Congress on a platform of
``family values,'' Gingrich decided to divorce his wife of many
years, Jackie, with whom he'd had two daughters. This happened
while Jackie was going through treatment for cancer.
</P>
<P>
   She later told a reporter about a particularly revealing
incident during that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``By September, I went into the hospital for my third surgery,''
she said. ``The two girls came to see me and said, `Daddy is
downstairs. Could he come up?' When he got there, he wanted to
discuss the terms of the divorce while I was recovering from my
surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, it's Clinton who hates women.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe Clinton does.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't treat his wife very well. He uses women and lies
about it. And, according to his grand jury testimony, he believes
in a strange and narrow definition of sex.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, Newt and Bill apparently consult the same
dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   The September 1995 issue of ``Vanity Fair'' magazine featured a
long profile of Gingrich, written by Gail Sheehy. This was a long
time before anyone ever heard of Monica Lewinsky. &QL; 
SOMETHING IN COMMON
</P>
<P>
   In the article, several former associates discussed Gingrich's
extracurricular behavior with the ladies. One woman, Anne Manning,
claimed to be a mistress. She said Gingrich preferred to engage in
the same type of physical intimacy most recently associated with
Clinton and the intern. Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Gingrich) prefers that modus operandi,'' Manning said in
1995, ``because then he can say, `I never slept with her.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds familiar, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   What we've got with Newt and Bill, it turns out, is six of one
and half dozen of the Bubba.
</P>
<P>
   Articles published over the years also have reported that
Gingrich's former wife had to go to court to collect child support
and alimony payments.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gingrich says Clinton is the woman-hater.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's U.S. Sen. John McCain hasn't said much about Clinton.
It's been reported many times that McCain's own first marriage
ended in part because he fooled around. He doesn't like to talk
about it. He shouldn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   No one should.
</P>
<P>
   They will, however, as long as someone like Gingrich keeps
stoking the fire on the impeachment express and calling other
people misogynists.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, in the ``Vanity Fair'' article, Gingrich's second
wife, Marianne, says she once bought her husband a book to help him
understand the kind of person he was. It's ``Men Who Hate Women &AMP;
the Women Who Love Them.'' &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
