<SLUG> BC-BOB-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOB A WINNER WITH DIAMONDBACKS' FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bank One Ballpark is one of the largest buildings in Arizona,
but it spent the past six months under a microscope.
</P>
<P>
   During the Diamondbacks' inaugural season, every creak and
squeak coming from the mammoth ballpark was analyzed, dissected and
discussed. From the pool to the roof to the air conditioning to the
grass, everybody wanted to know: What about BOB?
</P>
<P>
   ``The building has operated probably as well as we ever could
have hoped,'' said Roger Brendecke, an administrator for the
Maricopa County Stadium District. ``We did not have any major roof
problems. We didn't have anything other than . . . problems
normally associated with commissioning a new building.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing has gone smoother and had less problems than some
single-family homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the $355 million ballpark was not without its share of
troubles. The grass never quite took hold. The air conditioning
needed some tweaking, as did the giant, retractable roof. And St.
Louis slugger Mark McGwire hit a rocket that took a chunk out of
the electronic scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Diamondbacks play their last game today, fans say
they're satisfied with BOB's first season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The park itself is fantastic,'' said Mike Nelson, 36, of
Chandler, who attended about 40 games. ``No matter where you sit,
even in the upper deck, you've got a good view.''
</P>
<P>
   And Nelson said he's happy how the expansion Diamondbacks
delivered on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am ecstatic,'' Nelson said. ``They are not going to have a
100-loss season. They guaranteed that (Tuesday) night. That was all
I hoped for.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deems, a 66-year-old season-ticket holder from Scottsdale,
said he likes BOB's cozy atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have spring training tickets to the Cubs, and the (BOB)
outfield seems closer,'' Deems said. ``Even though it's a long ways
out, it just seems compact.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the team's play, Deems said he was pleasantly surprised
by All-Star outfielder Devon White, and disappointed in
third-baseman Matt Williams and shortstop Jay Bell, two high-priced
free agents who had subpar years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to seeing some improvement in the team,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like most fans, Deems said he enjoys the games more when the
roof is open, but he understands why it has to be closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's over 100 degrees outside, I don't think it's ever
going to be open,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For BOB, the closest thing to a crisis came during the intense
heat of July, when the air-conditioning system couldn't seem to
cool the upper deck.
</P>
<P>
   Ballpark officials investigated and discovered large gaps around
the giant outfield doors, which have advertising on the inside and
murals on the outside. After closing the gaps with clear plastic,
they also redirected air around the upper deck, BOB General Manager
Bob Machen said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also experimented with closing the roof at different
times to make sure the stadium is cool at game time. They settled
on 3{ hours before game time.
</P>
<P>
   In June, after McGwire cracked the scoreboard with a batting
practice fly ball, some reports placed the damage at $20,000.
Machen said the real figure was around $500. They didn't fix it
right away, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Texas outfielder) Juan Gonzalez was coming, and we waited to
see if he was going to do any of those things,'' Machen said.
</P>
<P>
   While flying balls were a problem, so were flying bats. In
separate games, two fans were whacked by bats that slipped out of
batters' hands. One received 50 stitches. In the other case, the
bat whizzed right over the head of Jerry Colangelo, the
Diamondbacks managing gen eral partner, and then hit a fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is an inherent problem when you go to a baseball game,''
Machen said, adding, ``You have to watch what's going on on the
field, every pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   For most fans, criticism came in two areas: concessions and
parking, though the game-day gridlock some predicted for downtown
never came true. Still, some said the food was too expensive and
too fatty, and others said paying $10 to park near the stadium is
just too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not impressed (with the food),'' said Pam Wilson, a
season-ticket holder from Mesa. ``I don't think it's anything
special. I don't normally eat at the ballpark because I think it's
expensive and I'm not a hotdog and hamburger person, per se.''
</P>
<P>
   In a public relations move, the team backed away from a
no-cooler policy before the season started. That allowed fans to
bring in their own food and avoid paying ballpark prices.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop BOB's vendor, Restaura, from selling 72 miles
of hot dogs and 20 tons of chicken tenders. They also peddled
25,000 pounds of nacho chips, 2,500 gallons of cheese and 32.5
million ounces of soda.
</P>
<P>
   They sold 160,000 orders of the $5 chicken tenders and fries _
the second-most popular item behind hot dogs, and widely considered
to be the best deal at BOB.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, fans liked BOB's ushers, though they were
charged with enforcing some unpopular rules.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans were rankled when they weren't allowed to move down
into the expensive, field-level seats that opened up in the late
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work very hard to make sure they don't do that,'' Machen
said. ``Because I paid $50 for my seat, I don't want somebody
coming down sitting there who paid $9 for their seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Ushers also kept people from standing along the outfield
concourse and watching the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people that are sitting in front of those people who are
walking, they don't want people breathing down their necks,''
Machen said. ``So that's why (the ushers) are doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bill Muller can be reached at 444-8178 or at bill.muller &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
