<DOCNO> NYT19980926.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6489 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  EGYPTTREASURESBOWINPHOEN     09-26 1640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 EGYPT TREASURES BOW IN PHOENIX  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six Germans and a crew of workers from the Phoenix Art Museum
have plopped down three tons of red granite on the floor of the
Cummings Great Hall.
</P>
<P>
   They have jimmied it into place against a temporary wall built
for the `` Splendors of Ancient Egypt'' show that opens Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   It is the sarcophagus of Kai-em-nofret. It is 4,480 years old
and it hangs a few inches in the air, suspended on both ends by the
steel tongues of pallet jacks, those hand-operated half-forklifts
used to place heavy objects in precise locations.
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps a little late to ask the question, but one of the
Germans, from the museum that owns the sarcophagus, asks almost
distractedly in an accent, ``Is there a right side to this?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, there is. There is an inscription on one side of the
giant stone box, and of course, it is the side up against the wall.
It reads, simply _ if you can say that about hieroglyphic writing _
``The Chamberlain Kai-em-nofret.''
</P>
<P>
   So, they pump the pallet jacks up again, and like piano movers
in an apartment hallway, they try to turn the whole thing around
without dinging up the freshly painted new walls, or the
not-so-fresh speckled granite of the box.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the few miscues as the giant exhibit is being
installed. With more than 200 artifacts from ancient Egypt, the
show is larger and more inclusive than the famous ``Treasures of
Tutankhamen'' show that ushered in the era of museum blockbuster
shows in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The path that brought Kai-em-nofret's intended final resting
place to Phoenix began in 1995, when the museum that owns it, the
Roemer and Pelizaeus Museum of Hildesheim, Germany, decided it
needed to renovate and expand its facilities.
</P>
<P>
   That museum was founded in 1870. But dust collects, paint peels
and leaky plumbing stains ceilings and floors, so, when they needed
to renovate the old place, they thought, well, we can either put
all our collection in storage while we work, or we can send it
around the world to be seen elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Which they did. Its American tour has taken it to St.
Petersburg, Fla.; Houston; Detroit; and Portland, Ore., before
coming to Phoenix. And by art museum standards, the Egypt show
happened in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   Museum Director Jim Ballinger saw the show in Houston in the
spring of 1997, at the Museum of Fine Arts there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had goose bumps when I saw it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, in November, Ballinger flew to Germany for
an official contract-signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   It's a monster show, covering three-fifths of the time
civilization has existed on the planet. The oldest pieces, from the
time of the Pyramids, are roughly 5,000 years old; the most recent
are from the time of the Roman Empire. Three thousand years are
covered, with sculpture, painting, pottery, jewelry and a mummy.
</P>
<P>
   So much stuff, in fact, that it took two Allied Van Lines
semitrailers and six Germans, to say nothing of a van-line
specialist, the normal staff of the museum, and that forklift.
</P>
<P>
   And those were just the final steps. In the beginning, money had
to be raised, plans had to be made. The museum prefers not to say
how much the exhibit will cost, but Ballinger did say that it is
``higher than the entire operating budget of the museum 10 years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the museum's budget was approximately $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   US West immediately agreed to be the major corporate sponsor for
the show. The museum got additional support from the Flinn
Foundation, the Kemper and Ethel Marley Foundation, Bashas',
Dillard's and Bank of America. But even with money and corporate
sponsorship, there was still the problem of where to put the show.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, the exhibit ate up 20,000 square feet; in Portland,
it took 18,000.
</P>
<P>
   The standard space for changing shows at the Phoenix Art Museum
was only 9,100 feet. And the museum was already backed up with its
regularly scheduled shows _ the Cowboy Artists of America show in
October and `` Copper as Canvas'' show in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also a long show, up for 5{ months, much longer than most
museum shows, '' Ballinger said.
</P>
<P>
   So he and the museum staff had to decide where it could put the
Egyptian exhibit. They decided on the Cummings Great Hall, which is
normally a meeting and banquet hall and was not designed to display
art. It could be combined, however, with its surrounding galleries
to add up to 18,000 square feet. But making it happen would take a
major commitment of time and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it would be a big undertaking,'' Ballinger said, ``and
we cannot pretend to have a staff curator with the credentials in
Egyptology to move the show along, so we knew we had to have
someone on staff to marshal this thing along.''
</P>
<P>
   So they hired Jim Rhone, retired special projects manager for
Phoenix, as Egypt project manager, and University of Arizona
Egyptologist Richard Wilkinson as a consultant. But that still left
them without an on-site curator _ the person who normally decides
what goes where in a show, and how the pieces are best displayed.
</P>
<P>
   That work fell to Exhibit Designer David Restad and Kathryn
Blake, associate curator for education. Brought into the process in
October 1997, Restad and Blake had a year to plan and execute the
exhibition, in addition to their regular jobs at the museum.
</P>
<P>
   They began with a visit to the Detroit exhibit in October to see
what they were dealing with. They discovered a huge show spread out
over an even huger space.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not like anything we've experienced before,'' Restad
said. `` I ran into something like writer's block. I can't just
pull it out of a hat. It's a new space where I've never worked
before _ and I was just getting a handle on the Steele Gallery.''
</P>
<P>
   The Steele Gallery is the changing exhibit space in the enlarged
portion of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   But Restad let things percolate for a while. He also visited the
Portland Art Museum in April when the show went there. He was
accompanied by Rhone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave David a second chance to see the exhibit in a
different venue and gave me a chance to talk with a number of
people in Portland with their experience on the staff side, with
marketing people, the volunteer coordinator and operations
director,'' Rhone said.
</P>
<P>
   When they returned, Restad began cutting out little squares of
cardboard representing the separate exhibit pieces and moving them
around on a graph-paper floor plan, trying to figure out how best
to lay out the show. He had to take into account the number of
pieces in the show, their chronological organization and just how
many stops there would be on the audiotape tour that museum
visitors would be given.
</P>
<P>
   He also had to plan where to build walls in the Great Hall to
subdivide it into smaller, more intimate galleries. He wound up
making a foamcore model of the exhibit space and using small wooden
blocks to represent the exhibit cases. Then, when he had the show
planned out in general, he went full-scale, putting tape and
cardboard squares down on the floor of the Great Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a jigsaw puzzle,'' he said. ``You find the right
piece and it takes you to the next piece and once that gets going,
it turns into a pinball game and you shoot people this way and then
over that way.''
</P>
<P>
   He also had the museum staff walk through the space to see how
the traffic might flow in real terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, I was getting more comfortable,'' Restad said.
</P>
<P>
   All this was just the physical side of the exhibit, though.
Blake and Rhone had another set of concerns to take care of _
marketing, education, ticketing, security _ all on a grander scale
than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to begin reaching out to the public schools,'' Rhone
said. ``Our education department mailed out a notice to each and
every schoolteacher in the state, so they got in their mailboxes
the information they needed to book their schoolchildren on
tours.''
</P>
<P>
   They have already booked 70,000 students from throughout Arizona
and have a waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has been a mammoth task,'' Rhone said.
</P>
<P>
   Ticketing was mammoth as well. Rhone soon decided it would be
too much for the museum staff, so they went with Dillard's.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, obviously, since we have added so much extra exhibit
space, that requires more security personnel,'' he said. ``We'll be
open more hours than usual, so the museum finds itself open 61
hours a week.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the museum has added about 24 full-time positions for the
Egypt show, plus an additional 10 security positions. That's not
counting the volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just blown away with the response,'' Rhone said.
``Over 2,000 people called in and volunteered.''
</P>
<P>
   Deadlines came sooner than a museum staff is accustomed to. For
most shows, even the largest, full installation is possible in
about six weeks. But this had to be completely ready before the
trucks arrived from Portland with the show pieces. And opening date
was Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided we needed to close the Cummings Great Hall July
6,'' Rhone said.
</P>
<P>
   The walls were up by July 10; the cases were in place by Aug.
15. And when the trucks showed up on Aug. 26, the hall was ready to
go.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the museum's own preparators install the objects into
their places, but for this show came a crew of six specialists from
Germany. Two women were curators from the Pelizaeus Museum and four
men were employees of Hasenkamp, the German company that crates,
couriers and installs shows for museums. They handled the whole
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done this so many times for so many museums, they know
exactly what it will take,'' Restad said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, except perhaps for that almost-backward sarcophagus. But
he'll never know the difference. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-98 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980926.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6491 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  EGYPTTREASURESBOWINPHOEN     09-26 1640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 EGYPT TREASURES BOW IN PHOENIX  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six Germans and a crew of workers from the Phoenix Art Museum
have plopped down three tons of red granite on the floor of the
Cummings Great Hall.
</P>
<P>
   They have jimmied it into place against a temporary wall built
for the `` Splendors of Ancient Egypt'' show that opens Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   It is the sarcophagus of Kai-em-nofret. It is 4,480 years old
and it hangs a few inches in the air, suspended on both ends by the
steel tongues of pallet jacks, those hand-operated half-forklifts
used to place heavy objects in precise locations.
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps a little late to ask the question, but one of the
Germans, from the museum that owns the sarcophagus, asks almost
distractedly in an accent, ``Is there a right side to this?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, there is. There is an inscription on one side of the
giant stone box, and of course, it is the side up against the wall.
It reads, simply _ if you can say that about hieroglyphic writing _
``The Chamberlain Kai-em-nofret.''
</P>
<P>
   So, they pump the pallet jacks up again, and like piano movers
in an apartment hallway, they try to turn the whole thing around
without dinging up the freshly painted new walls, or the
not-so-fresh speckled granite of the box.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the few miscues as the giant exhibit is being
installed. With more than 200 artifacts from ancient Egypt, the
show is larger and more inclusive than the famous ``Treasures of
Tutankhamen'' show that ushered in the era of museum blockbuster
shows in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The path that brought Kai-em-nofret's intended final resting
place to Phoenix began in 1995, when the museum that owns it, the
Roemer and Pelizaeus Museum of Hildesheim, Germany, decided it
needed to renovate and expand its facilities.
</P>
<P>
   That museum was founded in 1870. But dust collects, paint peels
and leaky plumbing stains ceilings and floors, so, when they needed
to renovate the old place, they thought, well, we can either put
all our collection in storage while we work, or we can send it
around the world to be seen elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Which they did. Its American tour has taken it to St.
Petersburg, Fla.; Houston; Detroit; and Portland, Ore., before
coming to Phoenix. And by art museum standards, the Egypt show
happened in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   Museum Director Jim Ballinger saw the show in Houston in the
spring of 1997, at the Museum of Fine Arts there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had goose bumps when I saw it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, in November, Ballinger flew to Germany for
an official contract-signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   It's a monster show, covering three-fifths of the time
civilization has existed on the planet. The oldest pieces, from the
time of the Pyramids, are roughly 5,000 years old; the most recent
are from the time of the Roman Empire. Three thousand years are
covered, with sculpture, painting, pottery, jewelry and a mummy.
</P>
<P>
   So much stuff, in fact, that it took two Allied Van Lines
semitrailers and six Germans, to say nothing of a van-line
specialist, the normal staff of the museum, and that forklift.
</P>
<P>
   And those were just the final steps. In the beginning, money had
to be raised, plans had to be made. The museum prefers not to say
how much the exhibit will cost, but Ballinger did say that it is
``higher than the entire operating budget of the museum 10 years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the museum's budget was approximately $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   US West immediately agreed to be the major corporate sponsor for
the show. The museum got additional support from the Flinn
Foundation, the Kemper and Ethel Marley Foundation, Bashas',
Dillard's and Bank of America. But even with money and corporate
sponsorship, there was still the problem of where to put the show.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, the exhibit ate up 20,000 square feet; in Portland,
it took 18,000.
</P>
<P>
   The standard space for changing shows at the Phoenix Art Museum
was only 9,100 feet. And the museum was already backed up with its
regularly scheduled shows _ the Cowboy Artists of America show in
October and `` Copper as Canvas'' show in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also a long show, up for 5{ months, much longer than most
museum shows, '' Ballinger said.
</P>
<P>
   So he and the museum staff had to decide where it could put the
Egyptian exhibit. They decided on the Cummings Great Hall, which is
normally a meeting and banquet hall and was not designed to display
art. It could be combined, however, with its surrounding galleries
to add up to 18,000 square feet. But making it happen would take a
major commitment of time and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it would be a big undertaking,'' Ballinger said, ``and
we cannot pretend to have a staff curator with the credentials in
Egyptology to move the show along, so we knew we had to have
someone on staff to marshal this thing along.''
</P>
<P>
   So they hired Jim Rhone, retired special projects manager for
Phoenix, as Egypt project manager, and University of Arizona
Egyptologist Richard Wilkinson as a consultant. But that still left
them without an on-site curator _ the person who normally decides
what goes where in a show, and how the pieces are best displayed.
</P>
<P>
   That work fell to Exhibit Designer David Restad and Kathryn
Blake, associate curator for education. Brought into the process in
October 1997, Restad and Blake had a year to plan and execute the
exhibition, in addition to their regular jobs at the museum.
</P>
<P>
   They began with a visit to the Detroit exhibit in October to see
what they were dealing with. They discovered a huge show spread out
over an even huger space.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not like anything we've experienced before,'' Restad
said. `` I ran into something like writer's block. I can't just
pull it out of a hat. It's a new space where I've never worked
before _ and I was just getting a handle on the Steele Gallery.''
</P>
<P>
   The Steele Gallery is the changing exhibit space in the enlarged
portion of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   But Restad let things percolate for a while. He also visited the
Portland Art Museum in April when the show went there. He was
accompanied by Rhone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave David a second chance to see the exhibit in a
different venue and gave me a chance to talk with a number of
people in Portland with their experience on the staff side, with
marketing people, the volunteer coordinator and operations
director,'' Rhone said.
</P>
<P>
   When they returned, Restad began cutting out little squares of
cardboard representing the separate exhibit pieces and moving them
around on a graph-paper floor plan, trying to figure out how best
to lay out the show. He had to take into account the number of
pieces in the show, their chronological organization and just how
many stops there would be on the audiotape tour that museum
visitors would be given.
</P>
<P>
   He also had to plan where to build walls in the Great Hall to
subdivide it into smaller, more intimate galleries. He wound up
making a foamcore model of the exhibit space and using small wooden
blocks to represent the exhibit cases. Then, when he had the show
planned out in general, he went full-scale, putting tape and
cardboard squares down on the floor of the Great Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a jigsaw puzzle,'' he said. ``You find the right
piece and it takes you to the next piece and once that gets going,
it turns into a pinball game and you shoot people this way and then
over that way.''
</P>
<P>
   He also had the museum staff walk through the space to see how
the traffic might flow in real terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, I was getting more comfortable,'' Restad said.
</P>
<P>
   All this was just the physical side of the exhibit, though.
Blake and Rhone had another set of concerns to take care of _
marketing, education, ticketing, security _ all on a grander scale
than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to begin reaching out to the public schools,'' Rhone
said. ``Our education department mailed out a notice to each and
every schoolteacher in the state, so they got in their mailboxes
the information they needed to book their schoolchildren on
tours.''
</P>
<P>
   They have already booked 70,000 students from throughout Arizona
and have a waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has been a mammoth task,'' Rhone said.
</P>
<P>
   Ticketing was mammoth as well. Rhone soon decided it would be
too much for the museum staff, so they went with Dillard's.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, obviously, since we have added so much extra exhibit
space, that requires more security personnel,'' he said. ``We'll be
open more hours than usual, so the museum finds itself open 61
hours a week.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the museum has added about 24 full-time positions for the
Egypt show, plus an additional 10 security positions. That's not
counting the volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just blown away with the response,'' Rhone said.
``Over 2,000 people called in and volunteered.''
</P>
<P>
   Deadlines came sooner than a museum staff is accustomed to. For
most shows, even the largest, full installation is possible in
about six weeks. But this had to be completely ready before the
trucks arrived from Portland with the show pieces. And opening date
was Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided we needed to close the Cummings Great Hall July
6,'' Rhone said.
</P>
<P>
   The walls were up by July 10; the cases were in place by Aug.
15. And when the trucks showed up on Aug. 26, the hall was ready to
go.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the museum's own preparators install the objects into
their places, but for this show came a crew of six specialists from
Germany. Two women were curators from the Pelizaeus Museum and four
men were employees of Hasenkamp, the German company that crates,
couriers and installs shows for museums. They handled the whole
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done this so many times for so many museums, they know
exactly what it will take,'' Restad said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, except perhaps for that almost-backward sarcophagus. But
he'll never know the difference. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
